[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction "]
[Result "*"]

{ Welcome to the Chessable course Lifetime Repertoires: Sicilian Kan! To avoid any confusion, we have to state that there are two authors of the course - Grandmasters Igor Kovalenko and Arturs Neiksans. Igor is the mastermind, or the so-called 'brains of the course', spending an incredible amount of hours on mind-boggling analytical sessions.  Arturs is the moderator, expanding and polishing Igor's ideas, thus delivering the product of Igor's highly-regarded analytical mind in the Russian-speaking community to the English-speaking audience. We hope that you will find the course to be instructive and easy to understand, essentially building a fighting repertoire against White's 1.e4, playing for the win. This is also what we will play at the Grandmaster level! }
1. e4 c5
{ The Sicilian Defense has long been a main weapon to fight against 1.e4 at any level. The fashion to play other openings @@StartBracket@@Caro-Kann, Ruy Lopez Berlin, Petroff@@EndBracket@@ comes and goes, but the Sicilian Defense always remains. It has the ideal formula - you can get very aggressive and aim for a lot of dynamics, sometimes ignoring a few positional rules. Then there are also 'quiet Sicilians', where both opponents maneuver for a long time @@StartBracket@@this was preferred by players like Karpov and Anand@@EndBracket@@. Our Sicilian Kan / Taimanov structures hold the balance of the aforementioned elements. }
2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways to pressure White's center. }
5. c4
{ Because of this exact continuation, the Kan system was a rare choice for many years until players started to change their evaluation of the typical 'Hedgehog' positions, which at some point were believed to be bad.   5.g3!?  Unbelievable but this continuation was already being used in the middle of the 19th century by one of the best players in the world! After about 170 years, it's back, and is being played at the highest level.  5...Bc5?!  6.Nb3  Ba7  While here it's not too great, you might recognize this idea later in the course.  7.Bg2  Ne7  8.Bf4  Nbc6  9.Bd6  White firmly occupied the weak d6 square in Staunton, H. - NN /London 1852.   5.Be2  Qc7   5...Nf6  6.Qd3  This concept, discovered some 150 years ago, was waiting for its moment to shine for a very, very long time. Only with the arrival of the modern Stockfish did White start to research more variations with delaying the development of the queenside knight. Meitner, P. - Anderssen, A. /Vienna 1873.  6.O-O  Nf6  7.Bf3  Not a great plan for White.  7...Nc6  8.g3  Bc5  Black brings out the dark-squared bishop before playing ...d6.  9.c3  O-O  10.Bg2  d6  11.Nb3  Ba7  Since their opponents at the time were not familiar with the system @@StartBracket@@despite being strong players@@EndBracket@@, both Paulsens would often get out of the opening with great chances. Blackburne, J. - Paulsen, W. Dresden, 1892.   5.Nc3  Qc7  6.g3  Bb4  One of the typical ideas of the system, like many things, was discovered in the 19th century.  7.Qd3  Nc6  8.Nxc6  bxc6  9.Bg2  a5!  This type of play was ahead of its time.  10.Bf4  e5  11.Bd2  Ba6  12.Qf3  Nf6  13.a3  Be7  Black was already better in Von Gottschall, H. - Paulsen, W. Hamburg 1885.   5.Bd3  The concept of being very flexible against Black's breakthrough in the center with ...d5 was one of the most popular ideas a long time ago.  5...Qc7  This early development of the queen was used pretty much against any of White's responses.  6.O-O  Nf6  7.Be3  Bc5  This modern idea is more than 100 years old.  8.Nc3  O-O  9.Qd2  b5  Black didn't have any problems in Porges,  M. - Paulsen, W. Dresden 1892. }
5... Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7
{ Black deals with the e5 threat - the Maroczy Bind setup against the Sicilian Kan here is a huge crossroads. White can seek some off-beat continuations to catch the opponent off-guard or play the classical a3 to prevent Black from playing ...Bb4. Before the age of Stockfish and the likes, it was unanimously considered as 'the only way to fight for the advantage'.  Time passed and practice proved that Black has many practical options, and the position itself is not so simple to give conclusions about. Then came the modern Be2 and, with the help of modern engines, it became clear that White can allow the ...Bb4 maneuver and that focusing on development with plans to grab a space advantage or go for a direct attack is much more important than the integrity of the pawn structure. But let's not get ahead of ourselves. }
7. a3
{ This 'old continuation' remains popular even today. White's game seems to be more positional and harmonious, while  7.Be2  is very aggressive, ignoring some positional concepts but quickly charging forward. }
7... b6
{ First, Black fianchettoes the bishop on b7 and keeps his eyes open, waiting to see what White will choose next. }
8. Be3 Bb7 9. f3
{ So, White has set up the Maroczy Bind - the position which has been tested for decades. Where to go? There are two plans. The first one is to commit to ...d6, aiming for the traditional Hedgehog, however, today it's considered to be very dangerous because White has several plans. Among them: either push the a-pawn as far as a5, or push the kingside pawns @@StartBracket@@and it does not matter where the White king stands@@EndBracket@@.   The second plan for Black was resurrected at the end of the 90's by one of the most creative players in the Chess circuit, Alexander Morozevich - Black plays ...Nc6 with mainly two ideas. First, trade the knights on d4 and continue with ...Bd6 and ...h5, enjoying good counterplay because of the dark squares. Second, reposition the knight on g6 via the e5 square, push the h-pawn as far as h4, and continue with either ...Bd6 or ...d5. The only downsides are a lack of flexibility, and the weak pawn on b6. }
9... Nc6
{ Although this move was known before, it would once again emerge at the dawn of the new Millenium.   9...Be7  10.Rc1  d6  Some time ago both sides did not understand the strength of White's g4-g5 push.  11.Be2  11...O-O  12.O-O  Nbd7  This is the classical Hedgehog system from Black's perspective that we will keep referring to throughout the course.  13.Qd2  Rac8  14.b4  Qb8  15.Kh1  Rfe8  16.Rfd1  h5  Of course, this idea is typical for the Kan system but best to make it when White's dark-squared bishop is already on g1, or if the black knight already stands on g6.  17.Bg5  Ne5  18.Na4  McShane, L. @@StartBracket@@2688@@EndBracket@@ - Grandelius, N.  @@StartBracket@@2691@@EndBracket@@ Eskilstuna, 2019  18...Bc6!?  An interesting idea - Black invites the white knight from a4 to jump back, before retreating with the bishop to a8.   18...Ba8  19.Qe3  This was played in the game.  19.Nxc6  Rxc6  Black has good counterplay against the c4-pawn.  20.Rc3  Rec8  21.Rdc1  h4!  22.Be3  Bd8   22...h3  23.gxh3  Qb7  This also looks interesting.  23.Bf2  Qb7  This entire variation is not included in the course since White had several options to play something stronger. However, the arising position in the middlegame is quite important since sometimes we will see something similar. }
10. Rc1 Nxd4
{ 10...Be7  is a very serious alternative but that's already the domain of strong chess engines. }
11. Bxd4
{ Only later White would find a very precise order of the moves that give White better chances.  11.Qxd4!  11...Bc5  12.Qd2  Bxe3  13.Qxe3  Qc5  Black tries to dominate the dark squares.  14.Qxc5  bxc5  15.e5!  The first precise move for White.  15...Nh5  16.Na4!  The second - White inevitably pushes b4.  16...Rc8  17.b4  cxb4  18.axb4  White is better but the advantage is far from critical. }
11... Bd6 12. g3 h5 { Black has at least sufficient counterplay. } *

