[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Closed Sicilian 2.Nc3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 e6 3. Nge2
{ This venomous move itself doesn't reveal much - White might still play both g3 and d4. White's knight on e2 is a little more passive than on f3 but on the other hand, it doesn't close the light-squared bishop's gaze on g2, and at the same time, a potential pin with Black's ...Bg4 doesn't seem so annoying anymore. }
3... a6 4. g3
{ We will analyze the idea which involves delaying the d4 push. Otherwise, after White's d4, Black takes the pawn, and we simply transpose to other chapters . }
4... b5
{ Black wants to position his light-squared bishop on b7 as quickly as possible, applying pressure against White's center. Again, if White plays d4, Black is ready to transpose to other chapters. }
5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O Nc6
{ This is a typical idea in the Sicilian Kan, and exactly with this order of moves so that Black can capture the white knight on d4, rather than allowing White to take the black knight on c6. }
7. d4 { White transposes to the Open Sicilian. } 7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nxd4
{ Black's principle in general for such kinds of positions is - if possible, take on d4 yourself. The white queen on d4 may feel active but it will be subject for you to win some tempi. }
9. Qxd4 Rc8
{ A multi-purpose move - Black still wants to play ...Ne7 but would like to see what White will do first. Because Black managed to play ...Nxd4 earlier and thus keep the bishop on b7, in many variations White's Nd5 will be less dangerous. Perhaps in some lesser variations, you might be threatening to win the c2-pawn but you can't choose it over development. Here White has several potential ideas. }
10. Bf4
{ White is waving a red flag - Qa7 next is incoming! Because of the White bishop on f4, Black can't play ...Qc7. In some variations, White might be fighting for the d6-square but it's not so important as he can't capitalize on it. If White could trade the dark-squared bishops and position his knight on d6, that would be a dominating position but we don't see how White can achieve it. }
10... Rc4
{ Black with a tempo frees the c8-square for the black queen and thus solves the problem of Qa7. }
11. Qd3
{ 11.Qa7?!  not a huge mistake but it's not clear what White is going to do next  11...Qc8  12.Be3?  that's just being stubborn  12...Ne7  . }
11... Qc8
{ A smart move - Black strengthens control of the queenside first before finishing development of the kingside which still is very flexible. White also has to understand if Black's ...b4 is a threat or not. }
12. Rfe1 { White is back at the Nd5 ideas - be alert. } 12... Bc5
{ This maneuver is meant only against White's Rfe1 and Nd5 plan and can't be applied against anything else, otherwise, the Black rook on c4 can get into trouble. }
13. a4 { The only ambitious choice that White has. } 13... b4
{ The rook on c4 is indirectly defended because of a discovered check threat. }
14. Nd5 exd5 15. exd5+ Kd8
{ The game can get very sharp but Black's chances most certainly are not worse. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black " Closed Sicilian 2.Nc3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 e6 3. g3
{ The start of the Closed Sicilian. White wants to fianchetto the light-squared bishop on g2 and then decide what to do next. He might play in the spirit of King's Indian attack, playing d3 next and organizing a kingside initiative or switch to an Open Sicilian with d4. }
3... d5
{ If you can solve your problems right away, do it. First, this approach is very similar to what we proposed to play in Chapter 6 @@StartBracket@@the only difference is that instead of Nc3 White had Nf3@@EndBracket@@ and it's a very good idea to have the same battle plan against several similar setups. Second, with an open center, it's easier to find simpler @@StartBracket@@if not the strongest@@EndBracket@@ decisions. }
4. exd5
{ Seemingly a necessary move for White as the alternatives give many choices for Black. }
4... exd5
{ Now there's a fair chance that the position will transpose to one of the variations of Chapter 6. }
5. d4
{ Pushing the d-pawn forward must be the critical choice, otherwise Black will play an early ...d4 himself, thus having a lot of space for the pieces and avoiding a position with an isolated pawn. }
5... cxd4
{ If we're inevitably going to get an isolated pawn on d5, it's best to have the white queen on d4 as it can be used to win tempi. }
6. Qxd4 Nf6
{ Black wants to play ...Nc6 again thus White has to react quickly. } 7. Bg5
{ The most principled choice - White has created a pin and wants to castle long to win the pawn on d5. We're undecided what to offer you as both continuations look fun but decided to leave the most played continuation as the main suggestion as it's easier to learn and might save you some time. }
7... Be7
{ This must be the simplest continuation - Black directly defends from the Bxf6 threat as the pawn on d5 afterward can't be taken, at least not right away. However, if you're looking for some crazy solutions, check the alternative! }
8. O-O-O O-O
{ This continuation, however, is less explored. Now the question that should be bugging White is: what to do with the d5-pawn? It was the goal to win it, right? But Black is giving it away voluntarily with no resistance! }
9. Nxd5 { The most obvious choice can be backed with a basic calculation. }
9... Nxd5 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. Qxd5 Nc6
{ White has won a pawn, but how much was the pawn worth? White is slightly behind in development and the king on the queenside is not feeling very secure. }
12. Qd6 Qe4 { Of course, White would love to trade queens. } 13. f3
{ The only way for White to continue the fight, otherwise, the position will repeat. }
13... Qe3+ 14. Qd2 Qb6
{ Black's play on the queenside is very easy to set up. It's White who constantly needs to look behind his shoulder. }
15. Bd3 Be6 16. a3 Rfd8 17. Ne2 Bf5
{ The position is balanced - White won't be able to hold the extra pawn for long, or Black's threats will become serious. For more details, see the relevant chapter. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
