[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Anti-Sicilian 2.Nf3 e6 3.g3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3
{ We will examine various setups from White's perspective that involve fianchettoing the light-squared bishop to g2. There are a lot of ideas behind positioning the bishop on g2 - in many cases, White will be defending the pawn on e4 with the bishop, which can easily become the strongest piece on the board should the h1-a8 diagonal open up.  This particular order of the moves doesn't have an official title, though sometimes it's referred to as the Adams variation, for reasons that are not particularly clear. A few years ago, one of the authors of this course, Arturs Neiksans, published a database from White's perspective, analyzing 3.g3 as part of his Anti-Sicilian trilogy against ...e6 setups in depth. Since this setup has been employed by many players from the Baltic states, we'll be referring to the line as the Baltic variation. }
3... d5
{ There's more than one continuation from Black - this one is the most direct and gives Black an easy development. In most cases, it will create an isolated pawn on d5 but Black should be able to compensate it with a lot of activity. }
4. exd5
{ The main idea behind the g3 setup - White wants to trade pawns to push d4 next. }
4... exd5 5. d4 Nf6
{ We propose to start with your kingside development and hold off on the natural ...Nc6 - there's a good reason for this. }
6. Bg2 Be7 7. O-O O-O
{ Now White has a choice - take on c5 himself and start to attack the isolated pawn or look for better circumstances. }
8. Nc3 { Let's treat this as the main move in the position. } 8... Nc6
{ Now that the White knight has made it to c3, the queenside knight goes to c6, ready to attack the center. White once again has a choice. }
9. dxc5 Bxc5
{ On most occasions you will reach exactly this position, but the order of the moves may vary. }
10. a3
{ The trickiest idea of the variation - White is preparing to play b4 next, and depending on how Black will respond, continue with either Bb2 or Bg5. }
10... Re8 { A smart waiting move - Black is not revealing all his cards. } 11.
b4 d4
{ Black was waiting for this counter-punch. Depending on where the knight retreats to, Black can choose his continuation accordingly. }
12. Na4
{ This is the critical continuation at White's disposal - now Black can retreat his dark-squared bishop far away from the white knight's range. }
12... Bf8 13. Bb2
{ Now it's Black who has a choice - you can either take the equalizing path, or be a little more ambitious. You choose! }
13... Bg4
{ For the sake of simplicity, we'll offer this continuation as the main  @@StartBracket@@  13...Qc7  is the alternative@@EndBracket@@ -  now, with accurate play Black should get a solid endgame. Black wants to play ...Qd7 next, stopping White's h3 and also indirectly targeting the white knight on a4. }
14. h3
{ White doesn't have a choice as it's difficult to imagine that White will want to endure the pin. }
14... Bh5 15. g4 Bg6 16. Nxd4 Nxd4
{ All of these moves are more or less forced. } 17. Bxd4
{ Taking with the bishop looks a little scary - Black will gain control over a very important diagonal, targeting the white king. }
17... Bxc2 18. Qxc2
{ Note that  18.Bxf6  doesn't work in view of  18...Qxd1  19.Raxd1  Bxa4  ,  winning material since both the rook on d1 and the bishop on f6 are under attack. }
18... Qxd4 19. Bxb7 Rab8
{ White has won the pawn, but Black's ...Qf4 is looming, followed by ...Bd6. }
