[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black " Anti-Sicilian 2.Nf3 e6 3.Qe2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. Qe2
{ This awkward-looking move has its perks if White is aiming for a closed French setup - assuming that Black at some point pushes forward the traditional ...d5. Then White's queenside knight is not heading to the traditional d2-square to defend the e4-pawn, giving White more options. White's light-squared bishop is still going to g2. }
3... Nc6 4. g3
{ Probably the most flexible move in the position - White fianchettoes the light-squared bishop on g2 and keeps all options open in the center. }
4... g6
{ If White can't respond to this maneuver with an immediate d4 push or prepare it in a near future, then go for it - Black's dark-squared bishop stands best on g7. Here the white queen is already on e2. }
5. Bg2 Bg7 6. O-O Nge7 7. c3
{ White doesn't have a big choice here - he could start with  7.d3  but most likely it would just transpose to one of the lines. }
7... e5
{ A good moment to close the center, making White's life considerably more difficult. Keep the d-pawn on d7 for the moment as you could have a pleasant choice to play either ...d6 or ...d5 in one go. If you play  7...d5  immediately, White could march past it with  8.e5  and achieve exactly what he wanted - an easy initiative on the kingside, using the dark squares. }
8. d3
{ This must be the main move in the position, which can be reached with a different move order as well. }
8... O-O 9. a3
{ White's main idea in the position - he's preparing to play b4 next and should Black try to stop it with ...a5, then the a4 push could be annoying, fixing some eternal light-squared weaknesses on c4 and b5. }
9... d6 { We did not analyze it but  9...d5  is a serious alternative here. }
10. b4 { White wants to play b5 next and push away the black knight. } 10... a6
11. Be3
{ White is trying to apply some pressure against the c5-pawn. Don't take the pawn on b4, otherwise, after axb4 White has won the battle for the center and opened the a-file for his rook. }
11... b6 12. Qd2
{ This motif in the arising positions seems to be quite common - White is threatening with both Bh6 and d4 push. The last threat does not seem very dangerous, since the White rook stands on a1, directly under the gaze of Black's dark-squared bishop. }
12... Be6 13. Bh6
{ Yudasin, L. @@StartBracket@@2522@@EndBracket@@ - Yang, D. @@StartBracket@@2432@@EndBracket@@ World op 2011. }
13... b5
{ Black prepares to play ...Qb6 and position both rooks on the d-file and c-file. White is not ready to play d4. }
14. d4 cxd4 15. cxd4 Bg4 { Black wins the fight for the d4-square. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Anti-Sicilian 2.Nf3 e6 3.d3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d3
{ We will explain to you what to do if White plays some sort of King's Indian attack or closed French position, involving g3, Bg2 and not going for the immediate d4 push. We decided to offer you dynamic positions which usually won't involve an early ...d5 push.  The reason for this is that after either White's Nbd2 or Qe2 and fianchettoing the light-squared bishop on g2, White would eventually close the center with e5, and enjoy an easy build-up and initiative on the kingside, with Black struggling for counterplay on the queenside.  The freshest example in this regard is the 2021 World Cup's quarterfinal game 3 between Sergey Karjakin and Sam Shankland. Engines like Black's position, but for humans it's a little more difficult. }
3... Nc6 4. g3 d6
{ Black takes care of the e5-square and prepares to play ...Nf6 next. If something happens and White includes moves like Nbd2 or Qe2 next, Black might still consider playing ...g6 and fianchetto the dark-squared bishop on g7, as for White it will be much more difficult to grab the center with the d4 push. }
5. Bg2 Nf6 6. O-O Be7
{ Let's just keep it simple, the bishop stands fine on e7. Now White has some choices, but for Black, it's pretty straightforward - just castle short, aggressively push forward the queenside pawns and watch out for what White does in the center. }
7. c4
{ White could try to set up some sort of Maroczy Bind, planning to play Nc3 and d4 next. }
7... O-O 8. Nc3 Rb8 { Black is looking for his counterplay. } 9. d4
{ If White does this right away, Black has an unusual counterstrike in the center. }
9... e5
{ Both sides gain complete control over the d4 and d5-squares respectively. It's possible to also take on d4 but Black won't be able to make a breakthrough with ...b5 in time, thus you will have to play a typical Hedgehog position in a slightly cramped position. }
10. dxc5 dxc5 11. Be3 b6
{ The position is about equal. Black ultimately wants to land his knight on d4, but remember this - if White does the same and plays Nd5 while his pawn on e4 is protected, you are not obliged to take the knight on d5 right away. Pick the right moment, and then block the newly formed passed pawn on d5 with a light piece on d6. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Kan 5.Nc3 b5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ Continuing the setups with g3 and fianchettoing White's light-squared bishop to g2 - we will examine what to do if White plays an Open Sicilian with the g3 setup, including Nc3. }
2... e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways to pressure White's center. }
5. Nc3
{ It's time to move to the Open Sicilian Nc3 setups if White doesn't fianchetto the bishop on g2, but plays some central-based moves. We will examine some of the lesser-played moves, before moving to the main continuation. }
5... b5
{ Black stays true to the spirit of the Kan - play ...b5 once the white knight stands on c3 so that the pawn on e4 is under early pressure. }
6. g3
{ It's possible to reach this position also with a different order of moves. This system is quite tricky - White positions his light-squared bishop to oppose Black's bishop on b7 and one of the most dangerous motifs that you will have to be aware of is the incoming e5 threat and the following intermezzo captures on f6 since the bishop on b7 will be under attack. }
6... Nf6
{ Black plays a little trick - you can start also with  6...Bb7  , it doesn't matter much. }
7. Bg2 Bb7
{ Now White has several continuations but all of them are more or less harmless. Black's idea is to avoid playing ...d6 as this would lead to some typical Sicilian Najdorf setups. That means - more lines to study and more unnecessary things to remember. Our task is not to overload your memory! }
8. O-O
{ This continuation at the highest level has only been played in blitz. Even at the club level, it should not be too difficult to understand the important nuances at the board. }
8... b4
{ Black goes after the pawn - the difference to one of the informational lines is that White has already committed himself to castling kingside. }
9. Nd5
{ This aggressive continuation is typical but compared to other lines it doesn't seem so dangerous, as here the queenside is still closed. White is taking big risks. }
9... exd5 10. exd5 Bc5
{ The only continuation but still rather obvious, after which White will have to cook up something to get compensation for the missing piece. }
11. Re1+ Kf8 12. a3
{ Naturally, White is seeking ways to open the queenside and bring into the game as many pieces, as fast as he can. }
12... a5 { It's best to keep the position closed, if possible. } 13. Nb3 Bb6
{ Black sticks to the same approach. The same position can be reached with a different order of the moves as well. We'll just mention here that it's also interesting to explore  13...Bd6  , with an unclear position. }
14. axb4 axb4 15. Rxa8 Bxa8
{ With the queenside rook gone, White's initiative doesn't seem strong anymore. Probably White will win another pawn due to the lead in the development, but Black should be safe. }
16. Bd2 Na6 17. Qe2 Bb7 18. Qb5 d6 19. Ra1 Nd7
{ White still needs to prove what exactly he has for the sacrificed material - Black's position looks under control. }
