[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Kan 5.Nc3 b5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ Continuing the setups with g3 and fianchettoing White's light-squared bishop to g2 - we will examine what to do if White plays an Open Sicilian with the g3 setup, including Nc3. }
2... e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways to pressure White's center. }
5. Nc3
{ It's time to move to the Open Sicilian Nc3 setups if White doesn't fianchetto the bishop on g2, but plays some central-based moves. We will examine some of the lesser-played moves, before moving to the main continuation. }
5... b5
{ Black stays true to the spirit of the Kan - play ...b5 once the white knight stands on c3 so that the pawn on e4 is under early pressure. }
6. g3
{ It's possible to reach this position also with a different order of moves. This system is quite tricky - White positions his light-squared bishop to oppose Black's bishop on b7 and one of the most dangerous motifs that you will have to be aware of is the incoming e5 threat and the following intermezzo captures on f6 since the bishop on b7 will be under attack. }
6... Nf6
{ Black plays a little trick - you can start also with  6...Bb7  , it doesn't matter much. }
7. Bg2 Bb7
{ Now White has several continuations but all of them are more or less harmless. Black's idea is to avoid playing ...d6 as this would lead to some typical Sicilian Najdorf setups. That means - more lines to study and more unnecessary things to remember. Our task is not to overload your memory! }
8. Qe2
{ Since castling kingside and giving up the pawn is harmless, we'll treat this queen move as the main. White is thinking about early Nd5 ideas, or at the right moment pushing e5. }
8... Nc6
{ The simplest choice - again Black declines to play ...d6 which is not necessary. The arising variations might lead to drawish or at least peaceful lines, thus if you are looking for something much sharper, we do have an alternative! }
9. Nxc6
{ White has to take. If he tries to protect the knight with  9.Be3  , Black can immediately go bother the bishop with ...Ne5-c4 ideas. If White retreats with the knight to b3, it's really passive there and Black can safely switch to a perfect Sicilian Najdorf / Scheveningen structure, and can consider playing ...d6. }
9... Bxc6 10. Nd5
{ Nice way to complicate matters but Black doesn't have to take the knight.   10.O-O?!  Due to the placement of the white queen, castling short can unexpectedly backfire.  10...b4!  The white knight can't retreat, otherwise White loses an exchange.  11.e5  White has no choice but to go here and give up a pawn instead.  11...Bxg2  12.Kxg2  bxc3  13.exf6  Qxf6  . De la Villa Garcia, J. @@StartBracket@@2470@@EndBracket@@ - Strikovic, A. @@StartBracket@@2495@@EndBracket@@ San Sebastian op 1994. White has no compensation for the missing pawn. }
10... Be7 11. Nxe7 Qxe7
{ There was a time when reaching positions like this was treated as a success for White. However, time passes and it has been proven that Black organizes good counterplay using the light squares and that the dark-squared bishop has nothing better than a trade for the knight. }
12. O-O O-O 13. Bg5
{ White wants to trade his bishop for the knight and push forward the e-pawn, creating a weakness on d6. }
13... h6 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. e5 Qf5
{ White has a small edge, due to the weakened pawn on d7, but not enough to be something serious. }
16. Rad1 { Here's how the game could continue. } 16... Bxg2 17. Kxg2 b4
{ A very nice idea - Black gives up the pawn on d7 to stop White from playing d3. Focus on your piece activity. }
18. Rxd7 Rfc8 19. Rc1 Rab8
{ Black should have enough compensation for the missing pawn. For instance, after  20.Rd4  Rb5  21.Re4  a5  ,  it's not clear how White is going to untangle the rook from c1. }
*

