5. Nc3
{ It's time to move to the Open Sicilian Nc3 setups if White doesn't fianchetto the bishop on g2, but plays some central-based moves. We will examine some of the lesser-played moves, before moving to the main continuation. }
5... b5
{ Black stays true to the spirit of the Kan - play ...b5 once the white knight stands on c3 so that the pawn on e4 is under early pressure. }
6. Bd3
{ By a big margin, this is the main move in the position, directed against Black's chosen setup. The bishop on d3 overprotects the pawn on e4 and this means that White most likely won't have to include a3, defending against the ...b4 push. White is quite flexible with his ideas on the kingside, but with the light-squared bishop standing on the b1-h7 diagonal, it's safe to assume that White will be thinking either about an e5 push or an Nd5 motif, using the open e-file. }
6... Bb7 7. O-O Nc6
{ As you probably remember - we have mentioned this a couple of times already - trading a pair of knights usually favors Black. Black is also flexible with his ideas - there's no need to rush with ...d6 and thus close the dark-squared bishop. The kingside knight might be developed to f6, but an alternative is also ...Ne7-g6. }
8. Nxc6
{ This move is usually played in a heartbeat - the alternatives look somewhat less appealing. If the knight retreats somewhere, then Black has nothing to worry about so the only reasonable alternative seems to be defending it. }
8... Bxc6 9. Re1
{ This is the only move that gives White some hope for an opening advantage. }
9... Qb8
{ This is a classic multi-purpose move. Not only does it create counterplay on the b8-h2 diagonal, but in addition, Black evades the Nd5 threat with a tempo, which is why this move looks better than the traditional ...Qc7. White has many ways to continue here, but Black's response almost always remains the same. Let's have a look at them. }
10. Nd5
{ White is shooting into thin air - this is the exact reason for ...Qb8. }
10... Bd6 11. Qh5
{ The most aggressive response - anything else does not pose any problems for Black. To this day, it remains a technical novelty to be played, albeit quite a logical one. The maneuver itself has been tested at least several times, with White having included a4 vs. ...b4. }
11... Ne7 { Black continues with traditional development. } 12. Nxe7 Bxe7 13.
e5
{ White makes sure that there's no easy way for Black to take his king out of the center by castling kingside, by annoyingly delaying it. }
13... h6
{ To muddy the waters, Black can be quite creative and stop White from trading the dark-squared bishops and thus getting an easy game. At the same time, Black is also planning for spme queenside expansion with ...b4, ...a5-a4, and eventually ...Ra5.  The engines tend to overestimate this position in White's favor. Black's game is very straightforward, while White has to navigate through a million nuances. The immediate light-squared bishop trade poses Black no problems. }
14. Qg4
{ The strongest move - White provokes some weaknesses in Black's camp. } 14...
g5
{ The idea of this move is to keep an option to play aggressively on the kingside with ...h5-h4. Now White's Be4 is also off the table as the e5-pawn hangs. }
15. Qh5 { White remains alert to Black's intentions. } 15... b4 16. Bd2 a5 17.
Rad1 a4
{ Even if White made it this far, this part of Black's plan is very straightforward, while White still has to figure out what the best setup is. }
18. Be4 { It makes sense to trade the light-squared bishops. } 18... Qb7 19.
Qf3 a3 { Black creates a potential target for the future! } 20. b3 Ra5
{ Suddenly, Black has his own threats. This is how the game could continue:  21.Bxc6  dxc6  22.c4  bxc3  23.Bxc3  Rd5  White is already forced to make some big decisions - the game for him is certainly not risk-free. }
