6... Bb7 7. O-O Nc6
{ As you probably remember - we have mentioned this a couple of times already - trading a pair of knights usually favors Black. Black is also flexible with his ideas - there's no need to rush with ...d6 and thus close the dark-squared bishop. The kingside knight might be developed to f6, but an alternative is also ...Ne7-g6. }
8. Nxc6
{ This move is usually played in a heartbeat - the alternatives look somewhat less appealing. If the knight retreats somewhere, then Black has nothing to worry about so the only reasonable alternative seems to be defending it. }
8... Bxc6 9. Re1
{ This is the only move that gives White some hope for an opening advantage. }
9... Qb8
{ This is a classic multi-purpose move. Not only does it create counterplay on the b8-h2 diagonal, but in addition, Black evades the Nd5 threat with a tempo, which is why this move looks better than the traditional ...Qc7. White has many ways to continue here, but Black's response almost always remains the same. Let's have a look at them. }
10. a4
{ White may want to include this move before shoving the queenside knight to d5 for better prospects - this continuation in practice has been White's top choice so far. }
10... bxa4 { Black diverts White's attention from the Nd5 maneuver. } 11. Nxa4
Bd6
{ Although this is a typical way of developing pieces, the arising position is very fresh. Indian GM Praggnanandhaa has played this position twice already. }
12. h3 { A human response - the pawn on h2 needs protection. } 12... Ne7
{ Black is preparing to play ...Bf4 at the right moment to trade off White's strong dark-squared bishop. }
13. Be3 { White is aiming at Nb6 tricks, attacking the black rook on a8. }
13... Bh2+
{ Before playing ...Bf4 and thus trading off the dark-squared bishops, Black gives this intermezzo check to weaken the control of the f2-pawn. }
14. Kh1 Bf4 15. Bd4
{ If White is forced to trade the dark-squared bishops, Black easily holds together the queenside. Thus, it's understandable that White wants to dodge the trade, at least for the time being. However, now the game becomes highly tactical and it's easy to miss one shot if you are not careful. }
15... O-O
{ Don't forget about your development - hunting White's dark-squared bishop can wait. }
16. e5
{ White avoids the dark-squared bishop trade by pushing forward the e-pawn, but the consequences are difficult to evaluate. }
16... Ng6 17. Nb6
{ Once again White's Nb6 can face consequences, this time there's a different trick. }
17... Qb7 { It's so easy to miss this move! } 18. f3
{ 18.Bf1  Nh4  19.Qg4  g5!  this leads to a big mess. } 18... Bxe5
{ Black uses the fact that the white knight on b6 is not well protected and grabs the e5-pawn. The following moves make the most sense. }
19. Nxa8 Bxd4 20. Bxg6 Bf6
{ Black will inevitably capture the knight on a8, while White has very weak dark squares around the king. }
21. Be4 d5 22. Bd3 Rxa8
{ Black has full compensation for the sacrificed material, and it's not much - just an exchange for a pawn. }
