[Black "Kan 5.Bd3 Bc5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways to pressure White's center. }
5. Bd3
{ One of the main continuations that has been around for decades. White develops the kingside first with a fast short castle and is very flexible with the ideas on the queenside, where the knight is not always developed to c3. Thus the approach of ...b5, which worked so well against White's Nc3, won't be a good idea here as now it's not creating any threats, but only weaknesses. }
5... Bc5
{ Against the Bd3 systems in particular, this move has always been one of the most popular continuations, and the true drawback of White's plan. Otherwise, everybody would just play 5.Bd3 with all the flexibility perks and not bother learning the other sidelines. Due to the bishop's early placement on d3, the white knight on d4 is unprotected, so Black's goal is to push it away from the center. }
6. Nb3
{ White retreats with a tempo, so logically this is the top choice for White. There are two lesser-known alternatives. }
6... Ba7
{ There's an ongoing debate about which is stronger for Black - retreating with the bishop to a7 or e7, now that the White knight has been kicked from the center. We think the bishop is more active on a7 where it applies more pressure on White. In other words - it's more fun! }
7. Qg4
{ One of the main ideas for White is to try to exploit the fact that Black's dark-squared bishop is no longer defending the g7-pawn, so there are some dark-square weaknesses. }
7... Nf6 { Black solves the problems with a tactical solution. } 8. Qg3
{ White keeps the option of taking on g7 for later but at the moment the e5 push is a bigger threat to worry about. }
8... d6
{ With the bishop on a7, it's important to take care of the e5-square.   8...Nc6?  9.e5!  Now Black doesn't have a satisfactory continuation.  9...Nh5  10.Qh3  g6  11.g4  Ng7  12.Qh6  Black's position - and control of the dark squares - is terrible. }
9. Nc3 Nc6
{ With the white king still in the center, the Qxg7 threat is always parried with the ...Rg8 and ...Bxf2+ idea. }
10. O-O
{ After castling kingside, White renews the threat to take on g7 since the f2 and g2-pawns are protected. This is a risky strategy for White. }
10... b5
{ You could also just castle short and meet White's Bh6 with ...Ne8, but why talk White out of complications if they favor you? The option to castle short can be revisited later. Here Black is threatening to challenge the pawn on e4. }
11. Kh1
{ Removing the king from the annoying pin looks reasonable. White could play  11.Be3  but it begs the question, why it was necessary to invest two tempi for Qg4-g3 to play it when Qe2 could have achieved it in one move? }
11... Ne5
{ The pawn on g7 still can't be taken as it would transpose to Smirin's game. }
12. f4 Nxd3 13. cxd3 O-O
{ With this tricky play, Black has established a bishop pair advantage and healthy development. The white knight on b3 has no good prospects of getting into the game. }
14. e5
{ Without the light-squared bishop, this push can't be great, however, Black has only one good response here. }
14... Ne8
{ You don't have to take on e5 and thus open White's dark-squared bishop. This is not checkers! }
15. Ne4 f5
{ The position is inevitably opening and Black is taking over the game. } *

