{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways to pressure White's center. }
5. Bd3
{ One of the main continuations that has been around for decades. White develops the kingside first with a fast short castle and is very flexible with the ideas on the queenside, where the knight is not always developed to c3. Thus the approach of ...b5, which worked so well against White's Nc3, won't be a good idea here as now it's not creating any threats, but only weaknesses. }
5... Bc5
{ Against the Bd3 systems in particular, this move has always been one of the most popular continuations, and the true drawback of White's plan. Otherwise, everybody would just play 5.Bd3 with all the flexibility perks and not bother learning the other sidelines. Due to the bishop's early placement on d3, the white knight on d4 is unprotected, so Black's goal is to push it away from the center. }
6. Nb3
{ White retreats with a tempo, so logically this is the top choice for White. There are two lesser-known alternatives. }
6... Ba7
{ There's an ongoing debate about which is stronger for Black - retreating with the bishop to a7 or e7, now that the White knight has been kicked from the center. We think the bishop is more active on a7 where it applies more pressure on White. In other words - it's more fun! }
7. O-O
{ White castling short immediately before committing to Qg4 has an important nuance. }
7... Nc6 { Black has to take care of the e5-square first. } 8. Qg4 Qf6
{ Some time ago the popular belief was that in this line White easily obtains an advantage, which was also published in several opening books @@StartBracket@@i.e., Parimarjan Negi's acclaimed Sicilian opening books for White@@EndBracket@@.  However, opening theory moves on and it is becoming apparent that not only does Black have good chances to equalize, he also has chances to take over the game - the fight will take place across the entire board.  It was no accident that Georgian grandmasters were pushing for this line in some high-level official tournaments in 2018, getting excellent chances to play for the win with the black pieces. }
9. Nc3 Nge7
{ Black keeps the option to play either ...d6 or ...d5, depending on the situation. White has several ways to fight for the initiative, but none leads to the goal. }
10. Kh1
{ A logical and popular move that prepares f4, however, Black has a good answer which has already been tested in practice. }
10... Ne5
{ Black switches from the aggressive ...h5 plans to a positional approach to equalize the game. Here, the idea is to push away the white queen and most likely take the White bishop on d3. }
11. Qg3
{ Normally, White wants to play either f4 or Be3 next, aiming for a positional game. If Black is not careful, then Bg5 can unexpectedly drop material. }
11... Nxd3
{ It's best to clarify White's intentions right away - Black simplifies the position and White now has to make a big committal decision. }
12. cxd3
{ This is probably what most players will do - capture with the pawn and aim for a more solid pawn structure. Now Black has a choice. }
12... d5
{ Solid and good - Black eventually equalizes the game. Now White's Kh1 feels like a waste of time and the f4-pawn push is shooting at thin air. }
13. Bf4 { White is ambitious and continues to fight for the dark squares. }
13... Qg6
{ To increase the power of the two bishops, Black wants to take on e4 but the queen on f6 is under a potential tempo if White captures the pawn with the knight. If Black manages to trade off the queens, the position is very safe as the black king in the center feels quite comfortable. }
14. Qh4
{ White keeps the queens on the board - the black king will have to stay in the center for a couple of moves. }
14... dxe4
{ Now that the queen has been removed from the f6-square, it's time to take on e4. After all, White might adjust his strategy and start threatening to take on d5, opening the e-file. }
15. Nxe4
{ White spoils his pawn structure but there's the annoying Nd6 check incoming. }
15... e5 { A shocking resource! } 16. Bxe5 Nf5 17. Qf4 O-O
{ Black sacrifices a pawn to finish development, and the power of the two bishops grants Black very good compensation for the pawn. }
