{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways to pressure White's center. }
5. Bd3 Bc5 6. Nb3 Ba7 7. Qe2
{ Instead of the more aggressive Qg4, White tries to play more positionally and immediately trade the dark-squared bishops. White keeps the option to castle both ways, So we're interested in having as flexible a setup as possible. }
7... Ne7
{ Black wants to castle short as quickly as possible and prepares against a potential Maroczy Bind setup. }
8. Be3
{ A multi-purpose move as White doesn't reveal anything yet. That's why we want to remain flexible and be able to react to White's chosen setups in the best possible way.  As a general rule of thumb, Black seldom takes on e3 himself, unless there's something immediately after it. After all, why would you want to take it and give up the g1-a7 diagonal? The black rook on a7 stands just fine.  If White is looking for a big fight and is an aggressive player, he should castle long and focus on the kingside attack with a quick pawn push.  This, however, will give Black enough counter-chances on the queenside, so it's all about the move order. If White is a positional player and prefers to castle short, Black is quite flexible with his development on the queenside. }
8... O-O
{ It's strange but this is quite a rare order of the moves. Black wants to save time on ...Nbc6 and ...d6 so that it's possible to meet the Maroczy Bind with ...d5. }
9. Nc3
{ As soon as the White knight lands on c3, push ...b5 to challenge its position. Please notice that Black has not yet committed to ....Nbc6 which might not be necessary here. }
9... b5 10. Bxa7
{ About here it should start to become apparent to White that Black is not going to take on e3 himself, so seeking some clarity in the position is an understandable idea. }
10... Rxa7 11. Qe3 Rb7
{ A paradoxical idea - the black rook stands pretty well here! Black returns to the ...b4 push ideas which might be combined with a later ...d5 push as well. White can no longer castle long and go for a kingside attack. }
12. h4
{ White could try to be smart and start the kingside attack without defining the placement of the king. }
12... d6
{ Black also can be quite flexible and wait until White castles long. The ...b4 threat is always in the air. }
13. h5 h6 14. g4 f6 15. f4 Nd7
{ Black's defensive capabilities are not worse. At the moment, Black is thinking of pushing ...e5 to control all the dark squares on the kingside, effectively stopping the attack.   Here's how the game could continue if White proceeds with his plan:  16.g5  fxg5  17.fxg5  hxg5  .  As soon as White pushes h6, Black can play ...g6 and hide the king on the h-file.  18.Qxg5  Ne5  19.O-O-O  N7c6  Black's defense looks rock-solid, while the attacking chances on the queenside might still be there. }
