[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Maroczy Bind 5.c4 − 7.f4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways to pressure White's center. }
5. c4
{ This is it - White goes for the Maroczy Bind once again, this time with more favorable circumstances. We will continue to examine the less played lines before moving to the top-notch theory. Black's strategy, in general, is to avoid playing ...d6 and the arising Hedgehog structure @@StartBracket@@pawns on d6, e6, knights of f6, d7, and light-squared bishop on b7@@EndBracket@@ as long as you can and go for much more dynamic lines instead.  If White is ready to invest a lot of energy to force Black to play ...d6 and switch to the Hedgehog, we can do it as White will have lost some time. We will explain this concept in more detail later. }
5... Nf6
{ Let's start by challenging the center to see how well-prepared White is. The white pawn on e4 is under attack. }
6. Nc3
{ This is White's main response, also renewing the e5 threat.   6.e5?  is a typical mistake - there's almost no chance that your opponent will miss it, otherwise he would never go for this aggressive setup.  6...Qa5+  . }
6... Qc7
{ Black deals with the e5 threat - the Maroczy Bind setup against the Sicilian Kan here is a huge crossroads. White can seek some off-beat continuations to catch the opponent off-guard or play the classical a3 to prevent Black from playing ...Bb4. Before the age of Stockfish and the likes, it was unanimously considered as 'the only way to fight for the advantage'.  Time passed and practice proved that Black has many practical options, and the position is not so simple to give conclusions about. Then came the modern Be2 and, with the help of modern engines, it became clear that White can allow the ...Bb4 maneuver. Focusing on development with plans to grab space or go for a direct attack is much more important than the integrity of the pawn structure. But let's not get ahead of ourselves. }
7. f4
{ This is an interesting idea and, once again, it's important to understand what White is aiming for - it's not only the e5 push. If you quickly close the center with ...d6 and go for the Hedgehog, White will be able to build up the perfect system against it and take the space advantage. Every variation that requires aggressive measures is of paramount importance. }
7... Bb4 8. Bd3 b5
{ If White defends the e4-pawn, now it's the time to go for one of the most thematic breakthroughs. }
9. e5 { White doesn't have anything better - now starts a forced sequence. }
9... bxc4 10. exf6 cxd3 11. fxg7 Rg8 12. Qxd3
{ Technically, White could castle short and then take the pawn, it does not matter. }
12... Rxg7 13. O-O Bb7
{ Despite the weakened position of the king, Black's chances are not worse due to the very powerful bishops. The position is double-edged. }
