1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways to pressure White's center. }
5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7
{ Black deals with the e5 threat - the Maroczy Bind setup against the Sicilian Kan here is a huge crossroads. White can seek some off-beat continuations to catch the opponent off-guard or play the classical a3 to prevent Black from playing ...Bb4. Before the age of Stockfish and the likes, it was unanimously considered as 'the only way to fight for the advantage'.  Time passed and practice proved that Black has many practical options, and the position is not so simple to give conclusions about. Then came the modern Be2 and, with the help of modern engines, it became clear that White can allow the ...Bb4 maneuver. Focusing on development with plans to grab space or go for a direct attack is much more important than the integrity of the pawn structure. But let's not get ahead of ourselves. }
7. a3
{ This 'old continuation' remains popular even today. White's game seems to be more positional and harmonious, while  7.Be2  is very aggressive, ignoring some positional concepts but quickly charging forward. }
7... b6
{ First, Black fianchettoes the bishop on b7 and waits to see what White will do next. }
8. Be3 Bb7 9. f3
{ So, White has set up the Maroczy Bind - the position which has been tested for decades. Where to go? There are two plans. The first one is to commit to ...d6, aiming for the traditional Hedgehog, however, today it's considered to be very dangerous because White has several plans. Among them: either push the a-pawn as far as a5, or push forward the kingside pawns.  The second plan for Black was resurrected at the end of the 90's by one of the most creative players in the chess circuit, Alexander Morozevich - Black plays ...Nc6 with two main ideas. First, trade the knights on d4 and continue with ...Bd6 and ...h5, enjoying good counterplay because of the dark squares. The second, reposition the knight on g6 via the e5 square, push the h-pawn as far as h4, and continue with either ...Bd6 or ...d5. The only minus - a lack of flexibility and the weak pawn on b6. }
9... Nc6
{ With this move Black's idea is to escape the two aforementioned dangerous plans. Let's remind you what they are - White either pushing forward the a-pawn as far as a5 or storming forward with the pawns on the kingside @@StartBracket@@g4-g5 and h4@@EndBracket@@, when Black will be dreaming about getting a draw.  With the knight on c6, these plans are impossible. Black's task is to get as complex a Hedgehog as possible, delaying the ...d6 move as long as possible since you might want to include your dark-squared bishop in the game via the d6-square. If White pushes the h-pawn, Black will be able to create counterplay. }
10. Na4
{ First, we need to familiarize ourselves with this simple move - White goes after the b6-pawn and tries to exploit the obvious drawback of Black's last move. Although it's not the most popular move at the moment, it feels like a stand-alone continuation, which can't be put into the same basket as other a3 continuations.  The other continuations like b4, Qd2, Rc1, or Be2 look very similar and on most occasions will just transpose from one line to another. This plan is a favorite of Stockfish and it makes sense. }
10... Rb8
{ Everything so far is logical. We are attacked and there comes the defense. Now White faces some choices.   10...Ne5?!  Unfortunately, this typical maneuver is not so great here.  11.Nb3  Bc6  12.Nxb6  Rb8  13.c5  d5  . This idea we've seen before, but White emerges on top from these complications.  14.Na5  dxe4  15.Nxc6  Qxc6  16.Qd4  White's domination of the queenside, backed with two bishops seems to be too strong. }
11. Rc1
{ A multi-purpose move that might be the favorite choice of an experienced player. }
11... Nxd4
{ Black forces matters in the center and is more practical.  11...Be7  also is very interesting but we decided that it requires Black to remember too many computerized lines and calculate a lot while White has several interesting continuations.   11...Bd6?  12.Ne2!  now Black suddenly has real problems defending the b6-pawn as the dark-squared bishop is hanging as well.  12...Ba8  13.Nxb6  White wins something. }
12. Qxd4 { The principled choice. } 12... Bc6
{ Black solves the problem of the b6-pawn with a tactical trick. } 13. c5
{ Only this move can create Black any problems. } 13... b5
{ Black has to close the queenside, otherwise, those weaknesses will be critical. Now White has to make a big choice - jump forward or retreat. }
14. Nc3
{ The human choice - the knight on c3 feels more flexible than on b6 but then again it allows Black to operate more freely in his camp. You can't have it both ways. }
14... Be7 15. g3
{ White is threatening Bf4 which is the best way for White to fight for something. Now Black has a choice - fight for equality or a chance to take over the game. }
15... O-O
{ Black sacrifices an exchange to dominate the dark squares while at the same time White is behind in development. If White manages to find all the best moves, he keeps an advantage, but we have big doubts that even then it will be enough to win.  Continuing the thought - if White makes even one mistake, Black's counterplay will explode like a volcano. Be warned - the complications can be mind-boggling! This makes this a perfect continuation for blitz or rapid at the least, even at the highest level! }
16. Bf4 Qa7
{ Compared with  16...Qa5  , this continuation is much simpler to play and gives Black some temporary initiative, so we decided to offer this line to study and keep the crazy lines as informational. It's important to note - Black's game may be simpler here but it's also simpler to find the moves for White. }
17. Bxb8 Rxb8
{ Black not only is threatening to grab the pawn but also push ...d6. } 18. Ne2
b4
{ One of the thematic ideas of the position - Black needs to quickly open the position, otherwise, he has nothing for the exchange. }
19. axb4 a5 20. Ra1 { Creating the pin is very logical and tempting. } 20...
Qc7 21. Rxa5 d6
{ White is up an exchange and a pawn but the initiative belongs to Black. Check the relevant chapter for in-depth analysis. }
