{ Black must remember this exact setup. White can change the move order @@StartBracket@@except bothering the b6-pawn@@EndBracket@@ but Black's maneuvers are always the same. }
13. O-O Ng6
{ Remove the knight from the center before White can play f4! Now White's center is a little static and Black can focus on his plans. Black wants to play ...Bd6 and fight for the dark squares, so White's next move will be directed against this. }
14. Kh1
{ Now Black's ...Bd6 is impossible - there will be an Nb5 trick and the pawn on h2 can't be taken with a check. Also, White wants to play Na4 and attack the b6-pawn, perhaps linked together with the c5 push. }
14... d6
{ It's time to switch to the classical Hedgehog - this is one of the rare moments in the entire course that we have to do this. }
15. Qe1 { White is going after the b6-pawn. } 15... Rab8 16. Qf2 Rfc8
{ Black is looking for ways to attack the c4-pawn but doesn't have to hurry. }
17. Rfd1 Ba8 18. Nb3 h6
{ There's no need to rush - you can wait for White to define his structure first. Black is thinking about ...Ne5 and ...g5 ideas in the distant future, but a lot can happen on the road. }
