[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Maroczy Bind 5.c4 − 7.Be2 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways to pressure White's center. }
5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7
{ Black deals with the e5 threat - the Maroczy Bind setup against the Sicilian Kan here is a huge crossroads. White can seek some off-beat continuations to catch the opponent off-guard or play the classical a3 to prevent Black from playing ...Bb4. Before the age of Stockfish and the likes, it was unanimously considered as 'the only way to fight for the advantage'.  Time passed and practice proved that Black has many practical options, and the position is not so simple to give conclusions about. Then came the modern Be2 and, with the help of modern engines, it became clear that White can allow the ...Bb4 maneuver. Focusing on development with plans to grab space or go for a direct attack is much more important than the integrity of the pawn structure. But let's not get ahead of ourselves. }
7. Be2 Bb4
{ In the final chapter of the course we are going to examine the Nc2 setups if White retreats with the d4-knight to challenge Black's dark-squared bishop. Sometimes the arising positions will seem similar to previous chapters, but not always. }
8. Nc2
{ A strong move that has recently gained popularity, especially among young players who are working with modern engines. White immediately tries to clarify the situation with the pinned knight. }
8... Bd6
{ This seems to be a more solid continuation and a safer alternative to  8...Bxc3  and is also in the spirit of the Sicilian Kan. Black slows down White's short castle and wants to reposition the dark-squared bishop on e5. }
9. Be3
{ A serious move - White plans to play Qd2 next and bother the black bishop on d6. After all, White can play h3 later, if he wants, right? }
9... O-O 10. Qd2 Be5
{ Solak, D. @@StartBracket@@2593@@EndBracket@@ - Sadikhov, U. @@StartBracket@@2500@@EndBracket@@ TUR-chT 1st League 2019. Black is back to the idea of bothering the white pawn on e4, this time via the e5-square. White has a few ways to deal with the threat. }
11. Rd1
{ If White plays Rd1 early without committing to Nd4, that means he's ready to sacrifice the e4-pawn for great activity on the dark squares. }
11... b5
{ However, you don't have to take it - it's more appealing to play active than sitting on the defensive with an extra pawn. This is also one of the drawbacks of the white knight retreating to c2 - it's not controlling the b5-square anymore. }
12. cxb5 axb5 13. Bd4
{ It makes sense for White to reject the pawn and first solidify the control of the center, otherwise, his entire queenside and the pawn on e4 will be hanging. }
13... Nc6
{ Now the black queen has a retreat square to b8, if necessary. White will have to be very careful to avoid trouble. }
14. Bxe5 Qxe5 15. f4 Qc5 16. e5
{ If you say A, be ready to say B as well - White is fighting for control of the center. }
16... b4
{ Once again, the typical Sicilian counter-strike goes through. There's a fight for the control of the e4 and d5-squares, with the question being which knights will occupy them. }
17. Nxb4 { Here's how the game could continue. } 17... Nxb4 18. exf6 Bb7
{ Very powerful - instead of counting the pawns, Black focuses on piece activity. }
19. a3 Nd5 20. Nxd5 Bxd5 21. f5 gxf6
{ In the end, the position is balanced, but White had to make a lot of uneasy moves to get here. }
