9... O-O 10. Qd2 Be5
{ Solak, D. @@StartBracket@@2593@@EndBracket@@ - Sadikhov, U. @@StartBracket@@2500@@EndBracket@@ TUR-chT 1st League 2019. Black is back to the idea of bothering the white pawn on e4, this time via the e5-square. White has a few ways to deal with the threat. }
11. Bd4
{ An interesting maneuver - White wants to trade the dark-squared bishops and reposition his knight to e3 for better control of the center. }
11... d6
{ Another famous Sicilian idea - Black doesn't mind the creation of the doubled pawns if it hands him the d4-square. If White does nothing, Black will play ...Nc6 and take on d4 with the knight.   11...Nc6?!  If White allows the bishop trade and gains nothing in return, it won't be fun.  12.Bxe5  Nxe5  13.Ne3  White controls the center and has a considerable space advantage, while Black has no good pawn breakthroughs. }
12. Bxe5 dxe5 13. O-O
{ This is simple and logical - White castles short and relies on his pawn majority on the queenside. Black should try to seize control of the dark squares. }
13... Rd8 14. Qe3 Bd7
{ Black takes control of b5 and a4-squares and prepares to push ...a5 and ...Na6. If necessary, the black knight is ready to jump to c6 as well. }
15. Rfd1 a5 16. Rac1 Na6 17. b3 Nc5
{ Black has achieved the perfect setup and is very solid. } *

