1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways to pressure White's center. }
5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7
{ Black deals with the e5 threat - the Maroczy Bind setup against the Sicilian Kan here is a huge crossroads. White can seek some off-beat continuations to catch the opponent off-guard or play the classical a3 to prevent Black from playing ...Bb4. Before the age of Stockfish and the likes, it was unanimously considered as 'the only way to fight for the advantage'.  Time passed and practice proved that Black has many practical options, and the position is not so simple to give conclusions about. Then came the modern Be2 and, with the help of modern engines, it became clear that White can allow the ...Bb4 maneuver. Focusing on development with plans to grab space or go for a direct attack is much more important than the integrity of the pawn structure. But let's not get ahead of ourselves. }
7. Be2
{ White is aiming for fast development, underlining that the ...Bb4 threat does not concern him. If Black doesn't play ...Bb4, then White has simply won a tempo by not committing to a3. In addition, White has two chances to fool his opponent, but both of these have their weak sides as well. }
7... Bb4
{ Black should only bring out the bishop after the inclusion of the moves ...Qc7/Be2. The ...Bb4 move itself is just developing a piece and nothing else, while ...Qc7 sets up the creation of the Qc7-Bd6 battery, attacks the pawn on c4, and also dodges a potential pin with Bg5.  We will examine positions where White goes for fast development, often not minding to sacrifice a pawn. We will examine all the possible scenarios related to the very popular Nc2 retreat in the final chapter of the course. }
8. Qd3
{ In most cases, White can't ignore what's happening with the e4-pawn and has to respond in some way. The white queen feels awkward on d3 but, it covers many important squares and can be rerouted to g3. }
8... O-O 9. O-O Nc6
{ The strongest move - you'll see that the alternatives don't even come close. Black is once again fighting for the d4-square, but might also consider the ...Ne5 jump if the circumstances are right. White has quite a few choices here. }
10. Bg5
{ If we were to move the white pawn from c4 to c2, we would likely reach similar positions to the ones seen in Chapter 13, where White plays the very tricky 5.Be2. On the one hand, White has more space and he can try to squeeze Black. On the other, the weakness on d4 will be a key element for Black to get a good game in some variations, and the 'lost' tempo for c4 could also be important. }
10... Be7
{ Black retreats with the bishop to consolidate the position, and once again threatens the typical ...Ng4, forcing White to give up the dark-squared bishop. }
11. Bh4
{ The most logical move, which also serves as prophylaxis against Black's ...Ng4 maneuver. }
11... Ne5
{ Black dodges the potential knight trade for the foreseeable future, and pressures the white pawn on c4. White still needs to decide whether to try to keep it or not. There are three queen retreats that make sense. }
12. Qc2 { A novelty to be played, but it's both natural and strong. } 12... d6
{ Black should focus on development. } 13. b3 Bd7
{ In order not to give White a free hand by grabbing space with moves like f4 and Bf3, Black has to remind White that he has some counter-attacking ideas on the queenside. Positioning the bishop on b7 would be too slow here. }
14. Rfd1 Rfd8
{ The kingside rook will have to be positioned here sooner or later so let's do it right away. }
15. Rac1 Rac8
{ Black can already think of going for complications with ...b5. However, this is the type of position where the threat is stronger than its execution - don't rush. The lines here are rarely forced, there's a lot of maneuvering when White needs to be ready for either ...b5 or ...d5 breakthroughs, while the dark-squared bishop on h4 is sort of disconnected from other pieces.   Here's how the game could continue:  16.a4  h6  17.Bg3  Qa5  18.Qb1  Qb4  . This blockade for the Hedgehog is typical, and for White, it's not easy to get rid of it. The threats of breakthroughs are always around.  19.Bf4  Nc6  20.Be3  Nxd4  21.Bxd4  Bc6  . In the end, we get a classical Hedgehog with a lot of maneuvering. }
