{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways to pressure White's center. }
5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7
{ Black deals with the e5 threat - the Maroczy Bind setup against the Sicilian Kan here is a huge crossroads. White can seek some off-beat continuations to catch the opponent off-guard or play the classical a3 to prevent Black from playing ...Bb4. Before the age of Stockfish and the likes, it was unanimously considered as 'the only way to fight for the advantage'.  Time passed and practice proved that Black has many practical options, and the position is not so simple to give conclusions about. Then came the modern Be2 and, with the help of modern engines, it became clear that White can allow the ...Bb4 maneuver. Focusing on development with plans to grab space or go for a direct attack is much more important than the integrity of the pawn structure. But let's not get ahead of ourselves. }
7. Be2 Bb4
{ In the final chapter of the course we are going to examine the Nc2 setups if White retreats with the d4-knight to challenge Black's dark-squared bishop. Sometimes the arising positions will seem similar to previous chapters, but not always. }
8. Qd3
{ As we explained, the White queen feels awkward on d3, but it covers many important squares and can be rerouted to g3. This is the main move. }
8... O-O 9. Nc2
{ While not so popular, this continuation is quite a dangerous weapon. Black will have to know precisely what he can use to create sufficient counterplay. The only choice here is really between the typical Kan's ...Bd6, or take on c3 as after ...Be7 Black is forced to enter the classical Hedgehog, when White's position is close to optimal, with a big space advantage. }
9... Bd6
{ We already learned that the dark-squared bishop stands almost perfectly here, at least temporarily. It slows down White's intentions to castle short and also stops the f4 push. This will give Black enough time to prepare for what's coming next. }
10. Be3
{ The most natural move that White has, improving the control of the dark squares. Castling can wait for the moment, plus it can still theoretically happen both ways. Of course, castling long caries an extra risk due to the ...b5 push. }
10... Nc6
{ Black continues with the general plan of the Sicilian Kan. Now White has some choices to make. }
11. Rd1
{ White forces the bishop to retreat to e7. It might seem like a loss of time and that White has managed to include a useful developing move, but the white rook on d1 makes it easier for Black to carry out the counterstrike ...b5! }
11... Be7
{ Now White has to make a big decision: how to play the game: as a positional squeeze or a fight to the death? White's current setup is not ideal. }
12. a4
{ A standard prophylactic move that starts a positional fight. Apart from the extra protection against the ...b5 push, it also has some downsides - the weakness of the b3-pawn and the b4-square could play a role later. }
12... Ne5
{ We concluded that the most practical thing that Black can do is switch to the classical Hedgehog. White's setup is not perfect to meet it. }
13. Qd4 d6 14. O-O Ned7
{ It looks like White has won a couple of tempi but what exactly has been gained? The knight on c2 does not stand well, but the commitment to the a4 push with Rad1 and the queen on d4 should not be dangerous for Black. }
15. f4
{ White could choose this setup sooner or later - just make sure you are ready to meet it. Remember, don't fall under White's classical g4-g5 space grabbing threat without having a proper counterstrike in the center. Evaluate the awkward placement of the white queen - it might be the reason why this plan is so difficult to make work for White.   If White ever tries to grab more space on the queenside with  15.b4  , he will feel the downside of the a4 push.  15...a5!  Black wins back access to the c5-square. }
15... b6 16. Bf2 Bb7 17. Qe3
{ White is rearranging his pieces but so is Black. } 17... Rfe8
{ If White is considering an early g-pawn push, he'll need to reckon with the ...d5 counterstrike. }
18. Nd4 Bf8
{ After a few moves, Black will be ready for a pawn breakthrough in the center. White has some space advantage, but he constantly needs to watch out for both the breakthroughs in the center, as well as what's happening on the weakened queenside. The position remains double-edged - exactly what Black was aiming for. For more details, see the corresponding chapter. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1) Early b4 Ideas"]
[Black "Wing Gambit 2.b4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ In the first chapter of the course we're going to explain everything about the b4-pawn push - the Wing gambit. White sacrifices a pawn to accelerate his development, fight for the center, and open the a-file. This continuation is usually employed as a surprise weapon or in accelerated time control games when the short-term initiative is important.If Black is accurate, such an approach is considered not to be dangerous, and perhaps even dubious. White can opt for this plan at several moments - they can push b4 right away or after a preparation move, a3 or Nf3.Our suggested approach will be as follows: if White plays it without including a3, take the free pawn, but don't hold onto it at the expense of your development, as this is exactly what White wants. Instead, continue standard development in the spirit of the Sicilian Kan, but try to maintain some flexibility in the center. This means not simply closing it at the first opportunity. If White plays a3 first, your response may vary depending on the situation, but in general, you can just decline the pawn as White has wasted a tempo on a3. The bottom line: don't despair, but be happy as White is dodging far more critical lines of the Sicilian Kan! }
2. b4
{ The most direct approach, which also gives Black some freedom to react. }
2... cxb4 { Free pawn! } 3. d4
{ White could grab the center right away, but now the arising positions will be very similar to the Alapin variation. }
3... e6 4. a3 Nf6
{ You don't want to take the pawn on a3 - this would only accelerate White's development. Offer White to take on b4 himself. }
5. Bd3
{ This seems to be almost necessary. If White plays  5.e5  , then after  5...Nd5  Black keeps flexibility in the center, with an option to make a breakthrough with ...d6. When White sacrifices the b-pawn, he is usually aiming for a closed center to focus on the kingside. }
5... Nc6
{ Now Black is ready to recapture on b4 with the knight and, if possible, eliminate White's light-squared bishop. }
6. Ne2
{ A necessity - after  6.Nf3  Black has  6...d5  7.e5  Ne4!  With the white knight on e2, Black can't do this as the knight on e4 would be under attack after f3. }
6... d6
{ It's worth considering also playing  6...Be7  , keeping the center flexible. Which it still is! }
7. O-O Be7 8. Bd2
{ White loses a tempo, forcing Black to take on a3, otherwise Black will never do it himself. }
8... bxa3 9. Nxa3 O-O
{ Black has an extra pawn and healthy development - it's not clear if White's center compensates for the missing pawn. Now  10.f4  can be answered with  10...d5  , and the black knight is heading to e4.   If White tries to grab the center with  10.c4  , then  10...Nd7  looks very good, preparing to play ...e5 next, and fight for control of the dark squares. If White is slow, Black finishes development on the queenside. }
*

