1. e4 c5
{ In the first chapter of the course we're going to explain everything about the b4-pawn push - the Wing gambit. White sacrifices a pawn to accelerate his development, fight for the center, and open the a-file. This continuation is usually employed as a surprise weapon or in accelerated time control games when the short-term initiative is important.If Black is accurate, such an approach is considered not to be dangerous, and perhaps even dubious. White can opt for this plan at several moments - they can push b4 right away or after a preparation move, a3 or Nf3.Our suggested approach will be as follows: if White plays it without including a3, take the free pawn, but don't hold onto it at the expense of your development, as this is exactly what White wants. Instead, continue standard development in the spirit of the Sicilian Kan, but try to maintain some flexibility in the center. This means not simply closing it at the first opportunity. If White plays a3 first, your response may vary depending on the situation, but in general, you can just decline the pawn as White has wasted a tempo on a3. The bottom line: don't despair, but be happy as White is dodging far more critical lines of the Sicilian Kan! }
2. b4
{ The most direct approach, which also gives Black some freedom to react. }
2... cxb4 { Free pawn! } 3. a3
{ As a rule of thumb, you never want to take on a3, unless White's making a major concession to force you to do it. }
3... e5
{ This seems to be the most energetic move, with a direct resemblance to @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  e5  and White has done something weird on the queenside. On a serious note, the pawn on e5 doesn't allow White to grab the pawn center with the d4 push, and it also closes up the long-range capabilities of White's bishop once it comes to b2.   3...e6  is also playable, but since the white knight isn't standing on f3 just yet, White gets access to an early Qg4 maneuver.  4.axb4  Bxb4  5.c3  A common idea for White is to push away the bishop and take the center.  5...Be7  6.d4  Nf6  7.e5  Nd5  8.Qg4  .  The position is just unclear - unfortunately, Black can't castle right away due to the Bh6 threat. }
4. Nf3 { Or  4.Bb2  Nc6  and the position inevitably should transpose. } 4...
Nc6
{ Now we're going to see some familiar ideas from the 1. e4 e5 repertoire - it depends on how White continues here. }
5. axb4 Bxb4 6. c3 Ba5
{ But this position has some direct resemblance to the Evans gambit! The dark-squared bishop on a5 slows down White's intention to push d4. Black will have to be a little careful of the weakened a3-f8 diagonal, but White can't exploit it. }
7. Bb5
{ White's trying to win back the pawn on e5. Black has quite a few good continuations here, but this one makes the most sense. }
7... Nge7 8. Ba3 d6 9. d4
{ White doesn't have too much time, and needs to show something for the missing pawn. }
9... exd4
{ The simplest approach - Black gives up the extra pawn to finish development. You can also consider  9...a6  . }
10. Qxd4 O-O 11. Qxd6 Bc7 12. Qxd8 Rxd8
{ Black's pieces look more active, and there is also an outside passed pawn on the queenside. }
