1. e4 c5
{ In the first chapter of the course we're going to explain everything about the b4-pawn push - the Wing gambit. White sacrifices a pawn to accelerate his development, fight for the center, and open the a-file. This continuation is usually employed as a surprise weapon or in accelerated time control games when the short-term initiative is important.If Black is accurate, such an approach is considered not to be dangerous, and perhaps even dubious. White can opt for this plan at several moments - they can push b4 right away or after a preparation move, a3 or Nf3.Our suggested approach will be as follows: if White plays it without including a3, take the free pawn, but don't hold onto it at the expense of your development, as this is exactly what White wants. Instead, continue standard development in the spirit of the Sicilian Kan, but try to maintain some flexibility in the center. This means not simply closing it at the first opportunity. If White plays a3 first, your response may vary depending on the situation, but in general, you can just decline the pawn as White has wasted a tempo on a3. The bottom line: don't despair, but be happy as White is dodging far more critical lines of the Sicilian Kan! }
2. a3
{ White prepares to play b4 next. We suggest playing in the Sicilian Kan spirit and first seeing what happens. }
2... e6 3. b4 { Or  3.Nf3  Nc6  , transposing to a later covered line. } 3...
b6
{ The best move - White essentially has wasted a tempo on a3 to play b4, so it's a good idea to decline the pawn and focus on normal development, White will be struggling to keep equality. If you are feeling adventurous, you can always accept the pawn. Just be ready, as White will have compensation for it, including access to the early Qg4 maneuver. }
4. Nf3 Bb7
{ After this simple move, White has some issues protecting the pawn on e4. If White plays either  5.Bd3  or  5.d3  to protect the pawn, Black can take the b-pawn. Now White's attempts to grab the pawn center will feel like a clear concession, compared to similar lines. Black already has the light-squared bishop on b7. }
5. bxc5 bxc5 6. Nc3 Nc6
{ It's best to start with this move so that Rb1 can be answered with ...Rb8. }
7. Rb1 Rb8
{ White has protected the pawn on e4, but now he can't do anything active in the center as the d4 push would create numerous weaknesses on the queenside. }
8. Bc4
{ Gelman, A. @@StartBracket@@2460@@EndBracket@@ - Vokarev, S. @@StartBracket@@2594@@EndBracket@@ chess.com Titled Tuesday 2020. Here Black has several ways to continue with normal development, but the following continuation looks particularly good. }
8... Ba8 { The idea is to fight for control of the e5-square right away. } 9.
Rxb8 Qxb8 10. O-O Nf6 11. Re1 Bd6
{ Black has control over the central squares.   12.Nb5  Be7  13.e5  Nd5  the knight on b5 doesn't do much. }
