{ In the first chapter of the course we're going to explain everything about the b4-pawn push - the Wing gambit. White sacrifices a pawn to accelerate his development, fight for the center, and open the a-file. This continuation is usually employed as a surprise weapon or in accelerated time control games when the short-term initiative is important.If Black is accurate, such an approach is considered not to be dangerous, and perhaps even dubious. White can opt for this plan at several moments - they can push b4 right away or after a preparation move, a3 or Nf3.Our suggested approach will be as follows: if White plays it without including a3, take the free pawn, but don't hold onto it at the expense of your development, as this is exactly what White wants. Instead, continue standard development in the spirit of the Sicilian Kan, but try to maintain some flexibility in the center. This means not simply closing it at the first opportunity. If White plays a3 first, your response may vary depending on the situation, but in general, you can just decline the pawn as White has wasted a tempo on a3. The bottom line: don't despair, but be happy as White is dodging far more critical lines of the Sicilian Kan! }
2. Nf3 e6 3. b4
{ It's time to revisit if White can push b4 again. Some things are slightly different now - the white knight on f3 blocks an early queen jump on g4, but Black has committed himself to putting the e-pawn on e6. }
3... cxb4
{ The white pawn is not on a3 yet, so take the pawn. Just remember: you don't have to hold onto it at all costs. One of the hidden perks of having extra material is that you can choose the right moment to sell it back for the right price! Now White has a choice - either to play a3 right away or first take the center. }
4. a3
{ For White, it's not very obvious if he should include this move before pushing forward the central d-pawn, as Black can immediately challenge the center. }
4... Nf6
{ 4...d5  5.e5  Black doesn't have any real problems here, with accurate play, he probably can get better chances. White still has a long-term initiative. We think that playing such a position from the Black perspective is not much fun, especially in accelerated time control games. If we compare this position to some of the previous lines, when Black had the knight on e4 there were chances to trade it for some positional benefits and more ways for White to misplay the position. }
5. e5
{ What else? The white pawn on e4 is under attack, but playing  5.Bd3  without including d4 would be just weird. }
5... Nd5 { Black's plan is simple - play ...Nc6, ...d6 and castle short. } 6.
axb4
{ White doesn't have a great choice here - he has to eliminate the black pawn on b4 and take the center as quickly as possible, otherwise Black will respond to White's c4 by taking it en passant. }
6... Bxb4
{ Now the only question for White is whether to play c4 with or without first pushing away the black bishop from b4. }
7. c4 Ne7
{ Now the black knight takes the e7 square and leaves the b4 outpost for the dark-squared bishop. }
8. Na3
{ White was going after Black's dark-squared bishop in the game Sipila, V. @@StartBracket@@2231@@EndBracket@@ - Zagorskis, D. @@StartBracket@@2497@@EndBracket@@ Khanty-Mansiysk Olympiad 2010. While it's possible to try to keep it and get a complicated game, we're offering something simpler. }
8... Nbc6 9. Nc2 d5 10. Nxb4 { White doesn't have a huge choice. } 10... Nxb4
11. Ba3 Nbc6
{ Black will have to be a little accurate about the weakened a3-f8 diagonal, but the fact that the center is dynamic and about to open helps Black. For comparison, this would be a terrible position if the white pawn was standing on c3, with White about to play d4. }
12. Bd6
{ In general, it's a good idea not to miss your opponent's ideas. Here, White wants to play c5 and ensure that the bishop on d6 or the pawn after the trade is well protected. }
12... dxc4 13. Bxc4 Nf5 14. Ba3 { It didn't hold on d6 for long. } 14... a6
{ Black is about to take complete control over the light squares, while White is struggling to prove what exactly he has for the missing pawn. }
15. O-O b5 16. Ba2 Bb7 17. Bc5 Nce7
{ Black is inevitably castling short and essentially has two connected passed pawns on the queenside. }
