[White "1) Early b4 Ideas"]
[Black " Delayed Wing Gambit 3.b4 #10 | Informational 4...d5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ In the first chapter of the course we're going to explain everything about the b4-pawn push - the Wing gambit. White sacrifices a pawn to accelerate his development, fight for the center, and open the a-file. This continuation is usually employed as a surprise weapon or in accelerated time control games when the short-term initiative is important.If Black is accurate, such an approach is considered not to be dangerous, and perhaps even dubious. White can opt for this plan at several moments - they can push b4 right away or after a preparation move, a3 or Nf3.Our suggested approach will be as follows: if White plays it without including a3, take the free pawn, but don't hold onto it at the expense of your development, as this is exactly what White wants. Instead, continue standard development in the spirit of the Sicilian Kan, but try to maintain some flexibility in the center. This means not simply closing it at the first opportunity. If White plays a3 first, your response may vary depending on the situation, but in general, you can just decline the pawn as White has wasted a tempo on a3. The bottom line: don't despair, but be happy as White is dodging far more critical lines of the Sicilian Kan! }
2. Nf3 e6 3. b4
{ It's time to revisit if White can push b4 again. Some things are slightly different now - the white knight on f3 blocks an early queen jump on g4, but Black has committed himself to putting the e-pawn on e6. }
3... cxb4
{ The white pawn is not on a3 yet, so take the pawn. Just remember: you don't have to hold onto it at all costs. One of the hidden perks of having extra material is that you can choose the right moment to sell it back for the right price! Now White has a choice - either to play a3 right away or first take the center. }
4. d4 d5
{ This is also a possibility, although we think that it's a little riskier. Now White will try to close the center and hope to organize a kingside attack. }
5. e5 Bd7
{ Quite a usual idea, borrowed from the French Defense - Black wants to trade the light-squared bishop first, otherwise, White's bishop on d3 could become an instrumental piece to develop a strong kingside attack. }
6. a3
{ White wants to play this move anyway, but at the same time, he's fighting against the light-squared bishop trade.   6.Bd3  This response is too soft - now Black gets exactly what he wanted.  6...Qa5!?  7.O-O   7.Qe2  a6  unfortunately for White, it doesn't stop the bishop trade.  7...Bb5  8.Bxb5+  Qxb5  Although Black is a little behind in development, the position is closed and it's difficult for White to organize a successful kingside attack without the light-squared bishop. Black is just better. }
6... bxa3
{ 6...Qa5  here the direct light-squared bishop trade, unfortunately, doesn't work.  7.Bd2  Bb5?  Black can get into huge trouble, although it might not be obvious from afar.  8.axb4  a double attack on the queen!  8...Qxa1  9.Bxb5+  Nc6  10.c4!  Redolfi, A. - Bazan, O. Cordoba Open 1967. After this powerful move, the black queen is in danger.  10...dxc4  11.Bc3  Qa2  12.Nfd2!  Black is losing a lot of things. }
7. c3
{ 7.Bd3!?  Black could probably get easily confused with the move order and how White could try to play this out, and this move is one of them. }
7... Qa5
{ Literally forcing White to take on a3, otherwise Black could have some problems developing the kingside knight. }
8. Bxa3 Bxa3 9. Rxa3 Qc7
{ It's not clear if the dark-squared bishop trade for White was a success - it could have been used for an attack on the c1-h6 diagonal. Now the black knight can be comfortably developed on e7. }
10. Bd3 Nc6 11. Nbd2 Nge7 12. O-O h6
{ There's no need to find out if after castling short the thematic Bxh7+ and Ng5+ with Qg4 or Qh5 next work here - the last move is a useful addition anyway. }
13. Qe2 O-O 14. Bb1 f6 15. exf6 Rxf6
{ Black should be fine and hold while still keeping the extra pawn. } 16. Qd3
{ White's direct attack doesn't go through. } 16... Ng6 17. Re1 Be8 18. h3 Nf8
{ The knight on f8 protects the h7-square, and Black is ready to trade the light-squared bishops via the g6-square. White has no compensation for the missing pawn. If you do all of this, the arising position is great, but it might be a little tricky to get there. }
*

