[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ In the first chapter of the course we're going to explain everything about the b4-pawn push - the Wing gambit. White sacrifices a pawn to accelerate his development, fight for the center, and open the a-file. This continuation is usually employed as a surprise weapon or in accelerated time control games when the short-term initiative is important.If Black is accurate, such an approach is considered not to be dangerous, and perhaps even dubious. White can opt for this plan at several moments - they can push b4 right away or after a preparation move, a3 or Nf3.Our suggested approach will be as follows: if White plays it without including a3, take the free pawn, but don't hold onto it at the expense of your development, as this is exactly what White wants. Instead, continue standard development in the spirit of the Sicilian Kan, but try to maintain some flexibility in the center. This means not simply closing it at the first opportunity. If White plays a3 first, your response may vary depending on the situation, but in general, you can just decline the pawn as White has wasted a tempo on a3. The bottom line: don't despair, but be happy as White is dodging far more critical lines of the Sicilian Kan! }
2. Nf3 e6 3. b4
{ It's time to revisit if White can push b4 again. Some things are slightly different now - the white knight on f3 blocks an early queen jump on g4, but Black has committed himself to putting the e-pawn on e6. }
3... cxb4
{ The white pawn is not on a3 yet, so take the pawn. Just remember: you don't have to hold onto it at all costs. One of the hidden perks of having extra material is that you can choose the right moment to sell it back for the right price! Now White has a choice - either to play a3 right away or first take the center. }
4. d4 Nf6
{ This move probably is more consistent with the entire approach of not closing the center too early, although that should be possible as well. }
5. Bd3 Nc6 6. O-O d5
{ Without this move, it's probably going to be difficult to find an active plan. }
7. e5 Ne4
{ However, now there's a major difference - comparing with the informative line which starts with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pp1p1ppp/4p3/8/1p2P3/5N2/P1PP1PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 0 4@@EndFEN@@  4.d4  d5  ,  Black's kingside knight has managed to find a way on the e4 square which must feel like an improvement! Now Black can simply finish development at the kingside and if necessary, after the trades give up a pawn on e4, Thus Black eliminates White's light-squared bishop and opens diagonals to activate his own. }
8. a3 a5
{ Before finishing development, Black's idea is not to waste a tempo on ...Be7 as Black will have to recapture on b4 with the bishop anyway and slow down White's typical c3, which strengthens the center. As you will see, in all the following lines, Black will give up the extra pawn to fight for better prospects. }
9. Re1 { Another way to threaten to win back the pawn. } 9... Rb8
{ Black shouldn't mind giving up the pawn as long as the light-squared bishop gets activated. }
10. axb4 Bxb4 11. Nfd2 Nxd2
{ This inclusion here is necessary first and only then comes the planned ...b5. }
12. Bxd2 b5
{ Black now needs to make sure that a direct attack on the kingside doesn't go through. }
13. Qg4 g6 { Of course not castling, which would allow Bh6. } 14. Bg5 Be7
{ Around here, it should start to become apparent that White doesn't have any real compensation for the pawn as Black is rock solid. }
15. Bxe7
{ 15.Bh6  Qb6  16.c3  b4  this also can't cause any problems for Black. On the contrary, the d4-pawn is targeted. }
15... Qxe7 16. Nd2 O-O 17. Nf3 Bd7
{ Black has finished his development while White's attack on the kingside is only in its starting phase. }
18. h4 a4 19. c3 b4
{ Black should keep a cool head on the kingside, make sure no immediate tactics work, and simply push forward the passed pawn on the queenside. }
