1. e4 c5
{ In the first chapter of the course we're going to explain everything about the b4-pawn push - the Wing gambit. White sacrifices a pawn to accelerate his development, fight for the center, and open the a-file. This continuation is usually employed as a surprise weapon or in accelerated time control games when the short-term initiative is important.If Black is accurate, such an approach is considered not to be dangerous, and perhaps even dubious. White can opt for this plan at several moments - they can push b4 right away or after a preparation move, a3 or Nf3.Our suggested approach will be as follows: if White plays it without including a3, take the free pawn, but don't hold onto it at the expense of your development, as this is exactly what White wants. Instead, continue standard development in the spirit of the Sicilian Kan, but try to maintain some flexibility in the center. This means not simply closing it at the first opportunity. If White plays a3 first, your response may vary depending on the situation, but in general, you can just decline the pawn as White has wasted a tempo on a3. The bottom line: don't despair, but be happy as White is dodging far more critical lines of the Sicilian Kan! }
2. Nf3 e6 3. b4
{ It's time to revisit if White can push b4 again. Some things are slightly different now - the white knight on f3 blocks an early queen jump on g4, but Black has committed himself to putting the e-pawn on e6. }
3... d5
{ Of course, this is playable, but now it feels like a concession to one of the earlier variations, as White has not spent a tempo to push b4. Choose yourself! }
4. exd5 exd5 5. Bb5+ Nc6 6. O-O
{ White very quickly finishes his development, and it's quite apparent that Black is lagging. Since ...Be7 move most certainly will be met with bxc5 and Black's dark-squared bishop will be forced to move again, it's best to take the pawn immediately. }
6... cxb4 7. Bb2 Nf6 8. Re1+ Be6
{ 8...Be7  9.Bxf6  gxf6  this looks like a risky strategical decision. The black king is vulnerable no matter where it goes. }
9. Nd4 Qd7 { White can't exploit his lead in development. } 10. a3 Be7
{ You don't want to allow White to bring rook into the game so quickly. } 11.
Nxe6 fxe6 12. axb4 O-O 13. Qe2 e5 { The game is pretty sharp. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2)  Early b3 Plans"]
[Black "Snyder Variation 2.b3 − 4.Bxf6"]
[Result "*"]

{  } 1. e4 c5
{ This chapter will be devoted to the setups with White playing an early b3. The idea behind this move is mainly to improvise with fianchettoing the dark-squared bishop on b2 and thus avoid mainstream theory. }
2. b3
{ If White does this as early as the second move, Black does not have to play the ...e6 setups anymore and has more flexibility. }
2... g6
{ This is our suggestion: position the dark-squared bishop on the same diagonal as the white bishop to negate its activity. }
3. Bb2 Nf6
{ Of course, the knight has to be developed first. This is the simplest approach - Black continues development on the kingside and starts to pressure the white pawn on e4. Now White has some choices, but none of them promise an advantage. }
4. Bxf6
{ This motif to voluntarily give up the strong bishop and conquer the d5 square is known from other theoretical variations, but here Black will easily get rid of the doubled pawn and get an active dark-squared bishop. }
4... exf6 5. Nc3 Bg7
{ Black's ...f5 will inevitably happen. If White goes to incredible lengths to stop it, this will seriously damage the harmony of his pieces. }
6. g3 Nc6 7. Bg2 O-O 8. Nge2 d6
{ White does enjoy the temporary control of the d5 square, but it's not clear what the exact benefits of this are. }
9. O-O f5 10. exf5 Bxf5 11. Rc1
{ Petenyi, T. @@StartBracket@@2444@@EndBracket@@ - Khalifman, A. @@StartBracket@@2617@@EndBracket@@ European Club Cup 2018. }
11... h5
{ Black's bishops are very active, and promise Black at least an equal game. }
