[White "2)  Early b3 Plans"]
[Black "Snyder Variation 2.b3 − 4.c4"]
[Result "*"]

{  } 1. e4 c5
{ This chapter will be devoted to the setups with White playing an early b3. The idea behind this move is mainly to improvise with fianchettoing the dark-squared bishop on b2 and thus avoid mainstream theory. }
2. b3
{ If White does this as early as the second move, Black does not have to play the ...e6 setups anymore and has more flexibility. }
2... g6
{ This is our suggestion: position the dark-squared bishop on the same diagonal as the white bishop to negate its activity. }
3. Bb2 Nf6
{ Of course, the knight has to be developed first. This is the simplest approach - Black continues development on the kingside and starts to pressure the white pawn on e4. Now White has some choices, but none of them promise an advantage. }
4. c4
{ One of the popular themes in any opening is the Maroczy Bind setup - White plays e4 and c4 to restrict the opponent's active plans. Here, however, with the dark-squared bishop on b2, it looks a little strange. }
4... d6
{ Black stops the incoming e5 threat and keeps an option to play ...e5 himself and close the center for good whenever necessary. For example, if White were to play Nf3 next before trying to make d4 happen. }
5. g3 Bg7 6. Bg2 Nc6 7. Ne2 e5
{ Huynh Mai Phuong, D. @@StartBracket@@2146@@EndBracket@@ - Le, K. @@StartBracket@@2338@@EndBracket@@ Vietnamese Women Team championships 2004. Now that White is threatening d4 and the creation of the Maroczy Bind, it's a good idea to close the center. Now White's bishop on b2 is useless - the initiative should pass to Black soon. }
