{  } 1. e4 c5
{ This chapter will be devoted to the setups with White playing an early b3. The idea behind this move is mainly to improvise with fianchettoing the dark-squared bishop on b2 and thus avoid mainstream theory. }
2. Nf3 e6 3. b3
{ This is an interesting continuation that is not as harmless as it may seem. Black has already committed himself to ...e6 thus the options will be a little limited, compared with the total freedom after 2.b3. }
3... d5
{ Although making a breakthrough with the d-pawn or b-pawn is one of the main motives in any Sicilian variation, here it helps White as he's ahead in development. }
4. exd5 exd5 5. Bb5+
{ White is about to castle short very quickly, while Black is seriously underdeveloped. }
5... Bd7 6. Qe2+ Qe7
{ The only move, otherwise, after White's Bb2 there will be problems with the long diagonal. }
7. Bxd7+ Nxd7 8. Nc3 { Now starts an almost forced sequence. } 8... Ngf6 9. O-O
Qxe2 10. Nxe2 Be7 11. d4
{ White has a solid advantage - he will establish an isolated pawn for Black on d5 and an outpost on d4, while the Black knight on d7 for these kinds of positions is misplaced and should be on c6. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2)  Early b3 Plans"]
[Black "3.b3 b6 4.d4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

{  } 1. e4 c5
{ This chapter will be devoted to the setups with White playing an early b3. The idea behind this move is mainly to improvise with fianchettoing the dark-squared bishop on b2 and thus avoid mainstream theory. }
2. Nf3 e6 3. b3
{ This is an interesting continuation that is not as harmless as it may seem. Black has already committed himself to ...e6 thus the options will be a little limited, compared with the total freedom after 2.b3. }
3... b6
{ The simplest continuation of all choices - Black wants to apply immediate pressure to the white pawn on e4. At the same time, we're not just thinking about equalizing, but fighting for the initiative and taking over the game. We'll show you a couple of alternative variations which to illustrate ideas for both sides in this setup.   A@@EndBracket@@  3...a6  Black could consider going for this Kan and Hedgehog setup, but it looks a little strange to play the ...a6 move before the white knight has landed on d4 as White might have other plans.  4.c4  Qc7  5.Bb2  b6  6.g3  one of Black's ideas in the Kan is to restrict the white knight's movements once it's on d4. Here, White is doing something else.  6...Bb7  7.Qe2  Nf6  8.e5  Ng4  9.Bg2  White's position looks more pleasant - it's not very easy to get rid of the white pawn on e5.   B@@EndBracket@@  3...Nf6  allows White to immediately win some tempi and seize space advantage.  4.e5  Nd5  5.c4  Ne7  6.Bb2  Nbc6  7.Nc3  the white knight on e4 will be a formidable force as it's not easy to push forward the d-pawn due to the hanging pawn on g7. }
4. d4
{ One of the most popular continuations in the position is switch to the Open Sicilian. }
4... cxd4
{ Of course, it goes without saying that Black has to take the pawn, otherwise, White will push d5 and claim a considerable space advantage. }
5. Nxd4 Bb7
{ White does not manage to setup the Maroczy Bind with optimal coordination of the pieces, as Black immediately attacks the pawn on e4. }
6. Bd3 Bc5
{ Black uses the fact that the white knight on d4 is unprotected to win a tempo, and will have several great ideas to choose from. The knight is not going to f6 as White could benefit from pushing e5, forcing the black knight to move again. The f6-square is not the only place to put the knight. }
7. Be3
{ It's paradoxical to play b3 and continue with Be3 but White does not have a great alternative. If White plays  7.c3  , the dark-squared bishop looks terrible on b2 anyway. This move at least develops a piece.   7.Bb2  this natural move can actually cause White some serious headaches after  7...Qf6!  and suddenly, the knight on d4 is under serious pressure as it can't leave - the bishop on b2 is undefended, plus there's a potential Scholar's Mate on f2.  8.c3  Nc6  White will struggle to stay in the game. }
7... Ne7
{ There's no need to force matters here - White's piece coordination looks quite strange. Black has many interesting ideas here - put the knight on g6, maybe the queen on f6 later, and at some point push d5 to activate the light-squared bishop. }
8. c4
{ If White returns to the Maroczy Bind ideas to justify the inclusion of the earlier b3, Black will nicely use the dark squares. }
8... Ng6 9. Qd2 { This does not solve White's problems. } 9... Qf6 10. Nc2 Bxe3
11. Qxe3 Na6
{ Please notice this move - the knights aren't always developed to their standard squares. The black knight is heading to c5 to attack the e4-pawn, where it doesn't close the light-squared bishop. }
12. Nd2 Nc5 13. Be2
{ White's got no choice as Black's already thinking about ...Qc3.   13.O-O??  Qc3  White unexpectedly drops a piece. }
13... O-O 14. O-O d5
{ Once the position opens, Black's pieces are better positioned and coordinated. }
*

