{ White is threatening to play b4 and cut off the black knight on a6 from the game. }
10... e5 11. Qe2 Nc7 12. Nf5 Bxe3 13. Nxe3 Ne6
{ The position is dynamic equality - Black can think about pushing forward the d-pawn, but there's no reason to rush with it. Consider playing slower moves like ...Qc7, ...d6, ...Rac8, and position one of the knights on c5. White's light-squared bishop is not impressive. }
