16... Qe7 17. Qxe7+ Kxe7 18. Ne5 Nh6
{ We did not analyze this position very far but if you're feeling adventurous and this position does happen in your game, you can consider playing  18...Rf8  and keep the exchange. Be warned though - due to the initiative, White's chances will not be worse.   The game could continue with  19.Nc6+  Kd6  20.e5+  Kc7  21.Nxd8  Rxd8  22.e4  .  Because of the stranded knight on h6 and the slightly vulnerable black king, the position is equal, although those doubled white pawns look very weak. }
