{ White defends the pawn on e4. Of course,  6.Nc3  would make no sense as White would immediately lose a pawn due to  6...Bb4  . }
6... Nf6
{ Black continues to press the pawn on e4, at the same time setting a nice trap. }
7. e5
{ It makes a lot of sense for White to solve the problem and push forward the e-pawn with a tempo, but there's a little problem with the plan. }
7... Qc7
{ This should come as a total shock for White - Black is threatening with both ...Qe5 and ...Qc3. Please note that it would not be possible, had White played @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pb1p1ppp/1p2p3/8/3NP3/1P6/P1P2PPP/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Bd3  and not  6.Nd2  - then the knight on f6 would be lost for nothing as after ...Qe5+ White could cover from the check with the bishop, protecting the knight on d4 with the queen. Major difference! }
8. Nc4
{ This is pretty much the only way to deal with both threats.   8.exf6  Qe5+  9.Be2  Qxd4  Black wins back the piece and something extra. }
8... Ne4 9. a3 a6 10. Bb2 b5
{ White loses the pawn on e5 for no compensation. } *

