6... Nf6
{ Black continues to press the pawn on e4, at the same time setting a nice trap. }
7. Bd3 d5
{ Probably the simplest choice that Black has which leads to a French Defense setup. If you are looking for more variety and unusual dynamics, consider  7...Na6!?  . }
8. e5 Qc7
{ An important resource! White can't take the knight due to the ...Qe5 check and has to give up the e4 square. }
9. N2f3 Ne4 10. O-O a6 { Black's position looks very solid. } 11. Bb2
{ Let us illustrate a sample line of what happens if White tries to open the queenside very quickly. }
11... Nd7 12. c4 Ndc5 13. Rc1 Nxd3 14. Qxd3 dxc4 15. Rxc4 Qd7
{ If White doesn't crash through immediately, then Black is left with the powerful light-squared bishop on b7. }
16. Rfc1 Nc5 17. Qe3 Bd5 18. R4c3 Be7 19. b4 Na4 20. Rc7 Qd8 21. Ba1 O-O
{ Black is taking over the game. } *

