{  } 1. e4 c5
{ This chapter will be devoted to the setups with White playing an early b3. The idea behind this move is mainly to improvise with fianchettoing the dark-squared bishop on b2 and thus avoid mainstream theory. }
2. Nf3 e6 3. b3
{ This is an interesting continuation that is not as harmless as it may seem. Black has already committed himself to ...e6 thus the options will be a little limited, compared with the total freedom after 2.b3. }
3... b6
{ The simplest continuation of all choices - Black wants to apply immediate pressure to the white pawn on e4. At the same time, we're not just thinking about equalizing, but fighting for the initiative and taking over the game. We'll show you a couple of alternative variations which to illustrate ideas for both sides in this setup.   A@@EndBracket@@  3...a6  Black could consider going for this Kan and Hedgehog setup, but it looks a little strange to play the ...a6 move before the white knight has landed on d4 as White might have other plans.  4.c4  Qc7  5.Bb2  b6  6.g3  one of Black's ideas in the Kan is to restrict the white knight's movements once it's on d4. Here, White is doing something else.  6...Bb7  7.Qe2  Nf6  8.e5  Ng4  9.Bg2  White's position looks more pleasant - it's not very easy to get rid of the white pawn on e5.   B@@EndBracket@@  3...Nf6  allows White to immediately win some tempi and seize space advantage.  4.e5  Nd5  5.c4  Ne7  6.Bb2  Nbc6  7.Nc3  the white knight on e4 will be a formidable force as it's not easy to push forward the d-pawn due to the hanging pawn on g7. }
4. Bb2
{ White finishes the fianchettoing the dark-squared bishop while keeping a lot of options open. }
4... Bb7
{ Now White has to find a way to protect the e4-pawn. Something like  5.d3  would be extremely passive and without ambition. }
5. Qe2
{ The idea of this move is mainly to play g3 and fianchetto the light-squared bishop on g2, while keeping some flexibility in the center, but it doesn't mean that White can't switch to Nc3, long castle, and d4 plans.   5.Bd3?!  with the inclusion of 4.Bb2, now White has no easy way to parry Black's ...Nc6-b4 positional threat, as he won't be able to put the rook on e1, allowing the bishop to escape to f1. An easy mix-up for White.  5...Nc6  6.c3  if White allows the trade of his light-squared bishop for the knight, the center becomes static and it will be difficult to achieve any serious pawn breakthroughs.  6...d5  Black's position looks even better due to better piece placement and a strong center. }
5... Nc6 6. Nc3
{ This is a good indication that White is aiming to castle long and push d4. }
6... a6
{ Black prepares for the immediate counterstrike on the queenside and gains space, while putting kingside development on hold. The main reason for this is that you still don't have a complete picture of where this game is heading. There might be moments when you will want to develop the kingside knight to e7. }
7. O-O-O b5 8. Kb1
{ Antipov, M. @@StartBracket@@2529@@EndBracket@@ - Potkin, V. @@StartBracket@@2605@@EndBracket@@ Moscow Aeroflot op-A 14th 2015, this would allow Black to stop White's activities in the center. }
8... Qb6 { Now there's no more d4. } *

