{ The White bishop on b2 seems to be misplaced for this type of position - it belongs on the c1-h6 diagonal. Now White needs to understand whether the pawn on e4 is in danger.   7...a6?!  If Black were to try to switch to a similar setup with ...b5 and wait for a better moment to take on d4, unfortunately, White can do it himself first.  8.Nxc6  Bxc6  Tsydypov, Z. @@StartBracket@@2553@@EndBracket@@ - Papin, V. @@StartBracket@@2481@@EndBracket@@ Russian Blitz championship 2019.  9.Qd2  Nf6  10.Bd3  Bc5  11.O-O-O  White's chances look better. }
8. Be2
{ If White continues with quiet development, Black can play in the spirit of Sicilian Kan/Taimanov.   8.Ndb5  White can't be allowed to trade Black's dark-squared bishop for the knight - then Black would lose the battle for the central dark squares.  8...Qb8!  White can't improve on the threat and will be forced to retreat, losing time. }
8... Qc7 9. O-O a6
{ Black takes control of the b5-square - this doesn't necessarily mean that Black will push forward ...b5. Another reason to do it is to prepare ...Bd6, making sure that White can't respond with Nb5. }
10. Nxc6 Bxc6
{ 10...dxc6  should also be good, but here Black maintains the pressure on the e4-pawn. }
11. Bf3 Bd6 12. g3 Be5
{ One of the most famous bishop maneuvers of Sicilian Kan/Taimanov. Black's dark-squared bishop on e5 feels like a king! }
