{ Black maintains the tension in the center and keeps attacking the white pawn on e4. If White pushes e5, then Black is ready to respond with ...Ne4. After the bishop trade, Black's light-squared bishop can find a new home on g6, not allowing White an easy long castle.   8...dxc6?!  here taking with the d-pawn doesn't seem to be an option as, compared with other sidelines, the arising position feels like a major concession  9.e5  Nd5  10.Ne4  White has a fantastic position with a great knight on e4. }
9. Bd3 Bb4
{ Black continues to press on the White pawn on e4 and sets another devilish trap. This also pretty much forces White to castle short - if he were allowed to castle long, the potential pawn mass on the kingside should give White better chances for a successful attack, as Black's counter-attempts on the queenside will be slow. That's also the reason why we don't suggest the immediate ...Bd6.   9...d5?!  although pushing the d-pawn looks logical, it also opens White's now perfectly-placed bishops on b2 and d3.  10.exd5  Nxd5  11.Be4  Black had created an annoying pin in Li, R. @@StartBracket@@2569@@EndBracket@@ - Kavutskiy, K. @@StartBracket@@2369@@EndBracket@@ North American op 27th 2017.  11...Bb4  12.Qd4  Bxc3+  13.Bxc3  f6  14.O-O-O  White's advantage is obvious - the bishop pair, an open position, and slightly better development. }
10. Qf3
{ Antipov, M. @@StartBracket@@2619@@EndBracket@@ - Morovic Fernandez, I. @@StartBracket@@2510@@EndBracket@@ FIDE chess.com Grand Swiss 2021. This move is quite typical for many Sicilian positions. The white queen on f3 not only protects the pawn on e4, but also indirectly the knight on c3, and often it is moved to g3. }
10... Rc8 11. O-O Bd6
{ Now that the white queen blocks the f-pawn, Black is in time to position his dark-squared bishop on e5 for a great blockade. }
12. Rae1 Be5 13. Qh3 O-O
{ Black should remain tactically alert to White's possibilities at all times.  13...g5?!  Playing in the spirit of the main line is interesting - Black keeps the bishop on e5 and makes sure that the f4 push is never happening. However, the positional drawbacks are quite obvious.  14.Nd1  d6  ,  Black can't keep control of the e5-square and is forced to replace it with a pawn, thus losing a lot of dynamics.  15.Bxe5  dxe5  16.Qg3  Nd7  . Probably, Black now wishes he could go back with the g-pawn to fix the position. }
14. f4 Bd4+ 15. Kh1 e5
{ Just in time, Black stops the white pawn on e4 and effectively prevents the light-squared bishop on d3 from attacking the black king. The pawn on e5 can be fortified with ...d6, with Black focusing on queenside counterplay. }
16. fxe5
{ White has some crazy tactical possibilities at his disposal but Black's chances are not worse. Here is a sample line. }
16... Bxe5 17. Nd5 Bxb2 18. Nxf6+ Bxf6 19. e5 Bh4
{ This is where most human beings would just stop the calculation as the attack seemingly has stopped but the Silicon beast would like to continue. }
20. Rf4 Qg5 { Due to the ...Bxg2+ threat White can't take the bishop on h4. }
21. Bxh7+ Kh8 22. Rxh4 Bxg2+ 23. Qxg2 Qxh4 { White's attack is over. } *

