{ This chapter will be devoted to the setups with White playing an early b3. The idea behind this move is mainly to improvise with fianchettoing the dark-squared bishop on b2 and thus avoid mainstream theory. }
2. Nf3 e6 3. b3
{ This is an interesting continuation that is not as harmless as it may seem. Black has already committed himself to ...e6 thus the options will be a little limited, compared with the total freedom after 2.b3. }
3... b6
{ The simplest continuation of all choices - Black wants to apply immediate pressure to the white pawn on e4. At the same time, we're not just thinking about equalizing, but fighting for the initiative and taking over the game. We'll show you a couple of alternative variations which to illustrate ideas for both sides in this setup.   A@@EndBracket@@  3...a6  Black could consider going for this Kan and Hedgehog setup, but it looks a little strange to play the ...a6 move before the white knight has landed on d4 as White might have other plans.  4.c4  Qc7  5.Bb2  b6  6.g3  one of Black's ideas in the Kan is to restrict the white knight's movements once it's on d4. Here, White is doing something else.  6...Bb7  7.Qe2  Nf6  8.e5  Ng4  9.Bg2  White's position looks more pleasant - it's not very easy to get rid of the white pawn on e5.   B@@EndBracket@@  3...Nf6  allows White to immediately win some tempi and seize space advantage.  4.e5  Nd5  5.c4  Ne7  6.Bb2  Nbc6  7.Nc3  the white knight on e4 will be a formidable force as it's not easy to push forward the d-pawn due to the hanging pawn on g7. }
4. Bb2
{ White finishes the fianchettoing the dark-squared bishop while keeping a lot of options open. }
4... Bb7
{ Now White has to find a way to protect the e4-pawn. Something like  5.d3  would be extremely passive and without ambition. }
5. Nc3 Nc6
{ Black finishes development on the queenside first and fights for control of the d4-square. }
6. d4 cxd4 7. Nxd4 Nf6
{ The White bishop on b2 seems to be misplaced for this type of position - it belongs on the c1-h6 diagonal. Now White needs to understand whether the pawn on e4 is in danger.   7...a6?!  If Black were to try to switch to a similar setup with ...b5 and wait for a better moment to take on d4, unfortunately, White can do it himself first.  8.Nxc6  Bxc6  Tsydypov, Z. @@StartBracket@@2553@@EndBracket@@ - Papin, V. @@StartBracket@@2481@@EndBracket@@ Russian Blitz championship 2019.  9.Qd2  Nf6  10.Bd3  Bc5  11.O-O-O  White's chances look better. }
8. Nxc6 Bxc6
{ Black maintains the tension in the center and keeps attacking the white pawn on e4. If White pushes e5, then Black is ready to respond with ...Ne4. After the bishop trade, Black's light-squared bishop can find a new home on g6, not allowing White an easy long castle.   8...dxc6?!  here taking with the d-pawn doesn't seem to be an option as, compared with other sidelines, the arising position feels like a major concession  9.e5  Nd5  10.Ne4  White has a fantastic position with a great knight on e4. }
9. Bd3 Bb4
{ Black continues to press on the White pawn on e4 and sets another devilish trap. This also pretty much forces White to castle short - if he were allowed to castle long, the potential pawn mass on the kingside should give White better chances for a successful attack, as Black's counter-attempts on the queenside will be slow. That's also the reason why we don't suggest the immediate ...Bd6.   9...d5?!  although pushing the d-pawn looks logical, it also opens White's now perfectly-placed bishops on b2 and d3.  10.exd5  Nxd5  11.Be4  Black had created an annoying pin in Li, R. @@StartBracket@@2569@@EndBracket@@ - Kavutskiy, K. @@StartBracket@@2369@@EndBracket@@ North American op 27th 2017.  11...Bb4  12.Qd4  Bxc3+  13.Bxc3  f6  14.O-O-O  White's advantage is obvious - the bishop pair, an open position, and slightly better development. }
10. Qf3
{ Antipov, M. @@StartBracket@@2619@@EndBracket@@ - Morovic Fernandez, I. @@StartBracket@@2510@@EndBracket@@ FIDE chess.com Grand Swiss 2021. This move is quite typical for many Sicilian positions. The white queen on f3 not only protects the pawn on e4, but also indirectly the knight on c3, and often it is moved to g3. }
10... Rc8 11. O-O Bd6
{ Now that the white queen blocks the f-pawn, Black is in time to position his dark-squared bishop on e5 for a great blockade. }
12. Rae1 Be5 13. Qh3 O-O
{ Black should remain tactically alert to White's possibilities at all times.  13...g5?!  Playing in the spirit of the main line is interesting - Black keeps the bishop on e5 and makes sure that the f4 push is never happening. However, the positional drawbacks are quite obvious.  14.Nd1  d6  ,  Black can't keep control of the e5-square and is forced to replace it with a pawn, thus losing a lot of dynamics.  15.Bxe5  dxe5  16.Qg3  Nd7  . Probably, Black now wishes he could go back with the g-pawn to fix the position. }
14. f4 Bd4+ 15. Kh1 e5
{ Just in time, Black stops the white pawn on e4 and effectively prevents the light-squared bishop on d3 from attacking the black king. The pawn on e5 can be fortified with ...d6, with Black focusing on queenside counterplay. }
16. fxe5
{ White has some crazy tactical possibilities at his disposal but Black's chances are not worse. Here is a sample line. }
16... Bxe5 17. Nd5 Bxb2 18. Nxf6+ Bxf6 19. e5 Bh4
{ This is where most human beings would just stop the calculation as the attack seemingly has stopped but the Silicon beast would like to continue. }
20. Rf6 { Very pretty but Black's defenses are holding. } 20... gxf6 21. Qf5
Bxg2+
{ Exposing the white king for checks and freeing the c6-square for a potential escape route later. }
22. Kxg2 Re8 23. Qxh7+ Kf8
{ White doesn't have more than equality, sometimes a forced perpetual check. }
24. Qh6+ Ke7 25. Qxh4 Rg8+ 26. Kf1 Qc7 27. Bh7 Rgf8
{ Now starts a forced line. } 28. Qxf6+ Ke8 29. e6 dxe6 30. Bg6 Rg8 31. Rxe6+
Kf8 { White's attack essentially is over. } 32. Rc6 Rxg6 33. Qh8+ Ke7 34. Rxc7+
Rxc7
{ The arising endgame is drawish as White will have to force a perpetual check. Of course, you don't have to memorize this line, it's just a sample variation to show how Black can keep his position together. It also requires quite a bit of imagination from White. }
*

