9. Bd3 Bb4
{ Black continues to press on the White pawn on e4 and sets another devilish trap. This also pretty much forces White to castle short - if he were allowed to castle long, the potential pawn mass on the kingside should give White better chances for a successful attack, as Black's counter-attempts on the queenside will be slow. That's also the reason why we don't suggest the immediate ...Bd6.   9...d5?!  although pushing the d-pawn looks logical, it also opens White's now perfectly-placed bishops on b2 and d3.  10.exd5  Nxd5  11.Be4  Black had created an annoying pin in Li, R. @@StartBracket@@2569@@EndBracket@@ - Kavutskiy, K. @@StartBracket@@2369@@EndBracket@@ North American op 27th 2017.  11...Bb4  12.Qd4  Bxc3+  13.Bxc3  f6  14.O-O-O  White's advantage is obvious - the bishop pair, an open position, and slightly better development. }
10. a3
{ This forces Black's hand and leads both players to a position with opposite-color bishops. Black's chances at least are not worse, if not better. }
10... Bxc3+ 11. Bxc3 Nxe4 { The forced sequence continues. } 12. Bxe4 Bxe4 13.
Qg4
{ Putting the queen on d4 is not possible.   13.Qd4  Qf6!  A very important resource! Note that this is possible only if the White king is still in the center, otherwise, Qxe4 kills the game. }
13... Bg6
{ A new spot for the light-squared bishop, at the same time protecting the black king. }
14. Bxg7 Rg8 15. Bb2 Qc7
{ For some reason after castling long the black king always feels safer than the white king, no matter which side it castles. In either case, Black has the open file for future operations. }
