8. Nxc6 Bxc6
{ Black maintains the tension in the center and keeps attacking the white pawn on e4. If White pushes e5, then Black is ready to respond with ...Ne4. After the bishop trade, Black's light-squared bishop can find a new home on g6, not allowing White an easy long castle.   8...dxc6?!  here taking with the d-pawn doesn't seem to be an option as, compared with other sidelines, the arising position feels like a major concession  9.e5  Nd5  10.Ne4  White has a fantastic position with a great knight on e4. }
9. Bd3 Bb4
{ Black continues to press on the White pawn on e4 and sets another devilish trap. This also pretty much forces White to castle short - if he were allowed to castle long, the potential pawn mass on the kingside should give White better chances for a successful attack, as Black's counter-attempts on the queenside will be slow. That's also the reason why we don't suggest the immediate ...Bd6.   9...d5?!  although pushing the d-pawn looks logical, it also opens White's now perfectly-placed bishops on b2 and d3.  10.exd5  Nxd5  11.Be4  Black had created an annoying pin in Li, R. @@StartBracket@@2569@@EndBracket@@ - Kavutskiy, K. @@StartBracket@@2369@@EndBracket@@ North American op 27th 2017.  11...Bb4  12.Qd4  Bxc3+  13.Bxc3  f6  14.O-O-O  White's advantage is obvious - the bishop pair, an open position, and slightly better development. }
10. O-O
{ Krejci, J. @@StartBracket@@2578@@EndBracket@@ - Videnova, I. @@StartBracket@@2369@@EndBracket@@ Biel MTO op 51st 2018. This move makes the most sense from White's perspective, finishing development and removing the pin. At the same time, White is castling on the same side as the black king, so any immediate pawn push on the kingside won't feel so dangerous anymore.   10.Qe2?  The most logical move here is a mistake!  10...Bxe4!  11.Bxe4  Rc8  White loses quite a bit! }
10... Qc7
{ Black starts to eye the e5-square again, stopping White's potential e-pawn push. At the same time, Black is ready to renew the ...Bxc3 and ...Nxe4 threat as castling long is now available in one move.   10...Bxc3?  Now that White has castled short, going after the pawn on e4 is very risky.  11.Bxc3  Nxe4?  12.Bxe4  Bxe4  13.Qd4!  Now Black has no ...Qf6 here.  13...Bg6  14.Qxg7  Rf8  15.Bb4  Black's position collapses. }
11. Nb5 { White renews the e5 threat, so Black must act quickly. } 11... Bxb5
12. Bxb5 Bc3 13. Bxc3
{ 13.Ba3?  He who digs a pit can fall into it himself! White could offer an exchange sacrifice for a strong attack, but there's a very nice refutation  13...Qe5!  White will take the exchange, but also force the queen trade! }
13... Qxc3 { Without the dark-squared bishops, White has no attack. } 14. Qd6
Qc5 15. Qxc5 bxc5
{ The position is equal, but we like the prospects of a knight that can be much more unpredictable and resourceful than the bishop. }
16. e5 Nd5 17. Rfd1 a6 { Pushing the bishop away from the annoying pin. } 18.
Bc4 Nb4
{ Black has nothing to worry about and would like to keep the knight on the board, if possible. }
