[White "3) Morra Gambit & Alapin"]
[Black "2.d4 cxd4 3.Qxd4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ In this chapter, we are mainly going to examine the Alapin system, which involves c3 to prepare the d4 push, but we will also briefly have a look at the Smith-Morra Gambit if White plays 2.d4 right away. }
2. d4
{ The start of the Smith-Morra Gambit! In general, it's not very dangerous, but you have to know a few original ideas to properly combat it. It's mainly employed in accelerated time control games, mostly online, where temporary initiative is more important. }
2... cxd4 3. Qxd4
{ This can't be very dangerous and gives Black plenty of freedom on how to continue.  3.Nf3  e6  4.c3  dxc3  . If White wants to play the Smith-Morra, this is a different move order and just transposes to the same lines. }
3... Nc6 { To start with, Black develops the queenside knight with a tempo. }
4. Qd3
{ 4.Qe3  Nf6  5.Nc3  d5  looks even simpler but Black can freely choose anything else as well. }
4... Nf6 5. Nc3 e6
{ As one of many choices, Black can opt for something that has a resemblance to the Sicilian Kan. }
6. Bf4 a6 7. Nf3 b5
{ This idea will be present for similar structures later in the course. } 8. e5
Qc7 9. Be2 Nb4 10. Qd2 Nfd5
{ Black is doing great but please understand that this is just a sample line - you're free to improvise! }
