[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ In this chapter, we are mainly going to examine the Alapin system, which involves c3 to prepare the d4 push, but we will also briefly have a look at the Smith-Morra Gambit if White plays 2.d4 right away. }
2. d4
{ The start of the Smith-Morra Gambit! In general, it's not very dangerous, but you have to know a few original ideas to properly combat it. It's mainly employed in accelerated time control games, mostly online, where temporary initiative is more important. }
2... cxd4 3. c3
{ White sacrifices a pawn to accelerate development, which is the main theme of the Smith-Morra Gambit.  3.Nf3  e6  4.c3  dxc3  . If White wants to play the Smith-Morra, this is a different move order and just transposes to the same lines. }
3... dxc3
{ The best choice is to accept the pawn. There might be moments later when you can give it back for the right price. }
4. Nxc3 Nc6 5. Nf3 e6
{ The good news is that our Sicilian Kan/Taimanov systems fit like a glove against the Smith-Morra, so you won't have to learn much out of the ordinary. }
6. Bc4 { By far the most played move. } 6... a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! The black pawns on e6 and a6 clearly limit the active possibilities of White's pieces. }
7. O-O b5
{ Black's task is to get rid of White's light-squared bishop from the a2-g8 diagonal as quickly as possible. }
8. Bb3 Na5
{ Very precise. Now White has to make a big decision - either give up one of his most important attacking pieces, retreat, or go completely nuts with a suspicious attack.   8...Bb7  Including this logical move first can unexpectedly backfire.  9.Re1  Na5  10.Bd5!  Now Black can't capture on d5 as it will open the e-file with deadly force. }
9. Re1
{ White might give up the light-squared bishop to bring more pieces in the action. }
9... Nxb3 10. Qxb3 Bb7
{ Now that White's light-squared bishop is gone, you can safely develop the light-squared bishop to b7. The only question now is: how will White execute the Nd5 jump, with or without including a4? }
11. a4 { It makes sense for White to include the pawn push first. } 11... b4
12. Nd5 Bd6
{ Black's response is exactly the same, with or without White including a4. Black is either threatening to take the knight and retreat with the king to f8 or just finish development with ...Ne7. }
13. Bg5 { White should probably push everything forward aggressively. } 13...
f6
{ This is bold, but that's what the strongest moves often look like! Black could have just played  13...Ne7  as well. }
14. Bh4 Ne7
{ Black is about to finish development, and White may become desperate trying to find where exactly his initiative lies. }
15. Bxf6
{ Going all in makes sense. This is the moment when Black needs to remain cool. }
15... exd5 16. e5
{ If White takes with the bishop on e7, it's best to capture it with the king and leave the bishop on d6 as a blockade. White is running out of attacking pieces. }
16... Bc5 17. Rac1 gxf6 18. exf6 O-O { White is down a piece for nothing. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Morra Gambit & Alapin"]
[Black "Alapin 2.c3 d5  "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 { This is a transposition analyzed later in the chapter. } 2...
d5 3. exd5 Qxd5
{ Black aims to create an isolated queen's pawn for White on d4 with hopes of exploiting it later. }
4. d4 Nf6 5. Nf3 e6
{ This position transposes to the main line. When it comes to strategy in the Sicilian Alapin, a good player has to keep the following things in mind:1.@@EndBracket@@ How to save time by studying fewer lines and still get good positions.2.@@EndBracket@@ How complex the game is, and how to take over the initiative. 3.@@EndBracket@@ How solid it is @@StartBracket@@against stronger opponents and when you're not in shape.@@EndBracket@@ 4.@@EndBracket@@ The strategic soundness of the lines, so that you're not changing the repertoire if somebody comes at you with a stronger engine and the previously analyzed lines don't hold anymore. In the Sicilian Alapin, it's not so simple to do, as every single move has several good responses and it's easy to mix up things. We hope we have managed to explain things at the correct level, and that you don't mix anything up! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Morra Gambit & Alapin"]
[Black "Alapin 2.Nf3 e6 3.c3 d5 4.e5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White starts with typical development of the kingside, but there are still many ways to continue here. }
2... e6 3. c3
{ The Sicilian Alapin - while it's not as popular as other Sicilian variations, it has a pace of its own and is quite interesting. For starters, White just wants to grab the center with d4 so Black must do something about it. Compared with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.c3  a move earlier, Black has already committed himself to play ...e6 and has limited options to respond. That's the reason why we're offering a setup that will inevitably transpose, making your life a lot easier, with fewer lines to learn.   3.d4  White can also try to switch to the Smith-Morra with this odd move order.  3...cxd4  4.c3  dxc3  . If you are looking for ways to switch to Alapin lines, this will come with concessions for Black.  5.Nxc3  Nc6  transposes to the Smith-Morra lines. }
3... d5 4. e5
{ White could try offering to switch to the French Defense Advance variation. }
4... d4
{ There's no need to play the French Defense Advance variation, which could arise from  4...Nc6  5.d4  , but if you're a big fan, it's up to you! In the arising positions, both sides have their structural advantages, and often it depends if you can make 'the right trade' to leave the opponent without 'the attackers'.  With the last move, Black makes sure that White can't strengthen the center with the natural d4. }
5. Na3
{ A fashionable move - before developing the light-squared bishop, White is inviting Black to play the natural ...Nc6, which has been considered not to be the best setup for Black for quite some time. After all, it would become rather challenging to activate Black's light-squared bishop. }
5... Bd7
{ Black's response remains the same - bring out the light-squared bishop to c6 first. The pawn on d4 very often is sacrificed to accelerate Black's development.   5...Nc6  We will illustrate how quickly things can go wrong for Black if playing natural developing moves:  6.Bd3  Nge7  7.O-O  Ng6  8.Re1  Black's position is already starting to look cramped - there's not much space to show activity but the pawn on d4 can become vulnerable.  8...Be7  9.Nc4  O-O  10.Be4  The typical maneuver for White - he might want to take the knight on c6 and establish an excellent outpost on c4 for the knight. Although, the bishop is pretty strong on e4 anyway.  10...Qc7  11.cxd4  cxd4  12.d3  Sadzikowski, D. @@StartBracket@@2287@@EndBracket@@ - Butkiewicz, L. @@StartBracket@@2369@@EndBracket@@ Wroclaw, WSB GM 2010. Black can't take on e5 due to Bxh7+ tricks while White can be active on both kingside and queenside. }
6. cxd4
{ A@@EndBracket@@  6.d3  as is typical for this structure, Black doesn't mind taking on c3 when White has already played d3.  6...dxc3  7.bxc3  Bc6  White might find himself in a difficult situation with the pawn structure in the center d4 and cxd4 will allow Black to establish a very strong outpost on d5, or White will create a weak c-pawn. Important to note that after White's d4, Black is not obliged to take right away.   B@@EndBracket@@  6.Nc4  If White puts the knight on the cozy c4-square, it's best to get rid of it right away, before White plays a4.  6...b5  7.Na3  Giving a check on d6 is tempting, but it will cost White a pawn.  7...Qb6  White has wasted two tempi on Nc4-a3. Black wants to strengthen the pawn on b5 with ...a6 and then decide whichever maneuver suits best - ...Bc6 and ...Nd7 or just the ...Nc6. In the latter case, Black has at least gained considerable space on the queenside. }
6... cxd4
{ Now the question is - when and how White will pick up the d-pawn? Black will use the time to get a lead in development. }
7. Nc2 Nc6 8. Bd3
{ White might decide to focus on his development first and for the time being ignore the d4-pawn. }
8... Qc7
{ Also, the immediate  8...g5  with ideas to play ...Bg7 next looks very interesting - this maneuver is quite typical for the variation. }
9. Qe2 g5 10. h3 Bg7
{ White inevitably will have to go to a position with an isolated queen's pawn. Black has very active pieces. }
*

