8. bxa3 Ne7 9. h4
{ A good idea for White is to seek some improvised counterplay on the kingside, resembling a typical French Defense approach, otherwise he has a risky strategic position. White can easily stay behind in development with a bad bishop and then have to fight for a long time for the draw. }
9... Qa5
{ Black is attacking the white pawn on e5 and pinning the d-pawn - an important factor to fight for the initiative.   9...Nbc6  If Black starts with the knight move in hopes to bring out the light-squared bishop to c6, White does not have to trade the knights.  10.Nf3  Na5  11.Rh3!  White's potential initiative on the kingside looks interesting, giving White better chances. }
10. Qe2
{ White protects the pawn on e5, but now the light-squared bishop is blocked and the king remains in the center. After  10.Qh5  , Black's approach would be the same. }
10... Nbc6 11. Nf3 Nf5
{ Black wants to take complete control of the light squares with moves like ...Nce7, ...Bc6, and ...h5 to fix the outpost of the black knight on f5. The extra pawn for White feels meaningless. }
12. Bb2 h5 13. Qe4 Nce7 { Black has wonderful coordination of his pieces. } 14.
Qxb7
{ White might win another pawn, but it's a doubled pawn. Black wins time to regroup his pieces. }
14... Bc6 15. Qa6 Qxa6 16. Bxa6 Bxf3 17. gxf3 Rb8 18. Bc3 Nd5
{ Black's position is very easy to play, while the same can't be said about White. }
