1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White starts with typical development of the kingside, but there are still many ways to continue here. }
2... e6 3. c3
{ The Sicilian Alapin - while it's not as popular as other Sicilian variations, it has a pace of its own and is quite interesting. For starters, White just wants to grab the center with d4 so Black must do something about it. Compared with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.c3  a move earlier, Black has already committed himself to play ...e6 and has limited options to respond. That's the reason why we're offering a setup that will inevitably transpose, making your life a lot easier, with fewer lines to learn.   3.d4  White can also try to switch to the Smith-Morra with this odd move order.  3...cxd4  4.c3  dxc3  . If you are looking for ways to switch to Alapin lines, this will come with concessions for Black.  5.Nxc3  Nc6  transposes to the Smith-Morra lines. }
3... d5 4. e5
{ White could try offering to switch to the French Defense Advance variation. }
4... d4
{ There's no need to play the French Defense Advance variation, which could arise from  4...Nc6  5.d4  , but if you're a big fan, it's up to you! In the arising positions, both sides have their structural advantages, and often it depends if you can make 'the right trade' to leave the opponent without 'the attackers'.  With the last move, Black makes sure that White can't strengthen the center with the natural d4. }
5. g3
{ An alternative way for White to continue development. Now that the Black d-pawn stands on d4, the long h1-a8 diagonal is open and can be fought for. }
5... Bd7 { Black again brings out the light-squared bishop first. } 6. Bg2
{ Not very careful! } 6... d3
{ Now that the White bishop is gone, this maneuver is possible. The pawn on d3 essentially splits White's position into two halves.   6...Bc6?!  this was played in Lagarde, M. @@StartBracket@@2657@@EndBracket@@ - Svidler, P. @@StartBracket@@2723@@EndBracket@@ chess24 Banter Blitz Cup Qual-H 2020. Although this is a standard maneuver, if Black does this right away, he might experience problems with normal development.  7.d3!  Ne7  8.O-O  Ng6  . Compared with a similar line in one of the sidelines, Black didn't play ...dxc3 with ...Bb5-c6 to provoke some useful weaknesses. The bishop already stands on c6.   9.Qe2  Nd7  10.Nbd2  Be7  11.h4!  A very strong move, posing Black some annoying problems.  11...h5  12.cxd4  cxd4  13.b3  It's not even the pawn on d4 that should worry Black; as we already discussed, often Black doesn't mind giving it away to accelerate his development. It's the piece activity that counts - for example, it's not clear what the black knight is doing on g6. White is better here. }
7. O-O Bc6 8. Ne1
{ If White tries to go after the d3-pawn right away, Black can start an initiative on the kingside. }
8... h5
{ The threat of ...h4 and opening the h-file is quite strong. Black's position should be preferred. }
