{ An alternative way for White to continue development. Now that the Black d-pawn stands on d4, the long h1-a8 diagonal is open and can be fought for. }
5... Bd7 { Black again brings out the light-squared bishop first. } 6. cxd4 Bc6
{ By the way, there shouldn't be anything wrong with the simple pawn take as well, continuing with ...Nc6 later. This move simply feels more energetic. }
7. dxc5 Bxc5 8. Bg2 Qd3
{ This forces the position a little - the queen on d3 is very annoying.   8...Ne7  Black can also avoid forcing things and aim for long-term compensation.  9.O-O  Nf5  10.Nc3  O-O  Motylev, A. @@StartBracket@@2651@@EndBracket@@ - Grachev, B. @@StartBracket@@2621@@EndBracket@@ Moscow blitz 73rd 2019. Black has good compensation for the pawn. }
9. Qe2 Qxe2+ 10. Kxe2 Nd7 { White can't keep his extra pawn. } 11. d4
{ Here begins a forced variation. } 11... Bxd4 12. Nxd4 Bxg2 13. Rg1 Bd5 14. f4
f6 { Black looks just fine. } *

