[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White starts with typical development of the kingside, but there are still many ways to continue here. }
2... e6 3. c3
{ The Sicilian Alapin - while it's not as popular as other Sicilian variations, it has a pace of its own and is quite interesting. For starters, White just wants to grab the center with d4 so Black must do something about it. Compared with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.c3  a move earlier, Black has already committed himself to play ...e6 and has limited options to respond. That's the reason why we're offering a setup that will inevitably transpose, making your life a lot easier, with fewer lines to learn.   3.d4  White can also try to switch to the Smith-Morra with this odd move order.  3...cxd4  4.c3  dxc3  . If you are looking for ways to switch to Alapin lines, this will come with concessions for Black.  5.Nxc3  Nc6  transposes to the Smith-Morra lines. }
3... d5 4. e5
{ White could try offering to switch to the French Defense Advance variation. }
4... d4
{ There's no need to play the French Defense Advance variation, which could arise from  4...Nc6  5.d4  , but if you're a big fan, it's up to you! In the arising positions, both sides have their structural advantages, and often it depends if you can make 'the right trade' to leave the opponent without 'the attackers'.  With the last move, Black makes sure that White can't strengthen the center with the natural d4. }
5. cxd4
{ If this trade happens early, there's a good chance that White is going after the d4-pawn. }
5... cxd4 6. Bb5+ Bd7
{ Black's response remains universal against all White's continuations - Black happily gives up the d4-pawn to gain time. }
7. Nxd4
{ If White doesn't take the pawn, it's not very clear why he went for the bishop trade. Black can trade the bishops, put the knight on c6, and enjoy the full comfort that the position provides. The last move starts a forced sequence. }
7... Bxb5 8. Nxb5 a6
{ The d6-square is defended and not yet covered by the kingside knight. } 9.
N5c3 Nc6 10. O-O
{ A strong response - White is not interested in playing f4 yet to keep the pawn on e5, as it would seriously weaken all of the light squares in the position, giving Black a lot more than just compensation. At the same time, White offers to return the pawn on e5... }
10... Nge7
{ The e5-pawn is not going anywhere! Even if it does, Black will always get something out of it. Now White faces an uneasy decision - try to keep the pawn or ready himself to play an isolated queen's pawn position with no obvious advantages for it.   10...Nxe5?  This is a big mistake - White's continuation should be obvious.  11.d4  Nc6  12.d5  The position opens up, and Black is hopelessly behind in development. }
11. f4
{ If White decides to keep the pawn, Black's initiative develops very quickly. }
11... Nf5 12. d3 Qd4+ 13. Kh1 O-O-O
{ It's not even about the pawn on d3 - the plan of ...h5-h4 and ...Ng3+ looks extremely unpleasant for White. }
