{ The Sicilian Alapin - while it's not as popular as other Sicilian variations, it has a pace of its own and is quite interesting. For starters, White just wants to grab the center with d4 so Black must do something about it. Compared with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.c3  a move earlier, Black has already committed himself to play ...e6 and has limited options to respond. That's the reason why we're offering a setup that will inevitably transpose, making your life a lot easier, with fewer lines to learn.   3.d4  White can also try to switch to the Smith-Morra with this odd move order.  3...cxd4  4.c3  dxc3  . If you are looking for ways to switch to Alapin lines, this will come with concessions for Black.  5.Nxc3  Nc6  transposes to the Smith-Morra lines. }
3... d5 4. e5
{ White could try offering to switch to the French Defense Advance variation. }
4... d4
{ There's no need to play the French Defense Advance variation, which could arise from  4...Nc6  5.d4  , but if you're a big fan, it's up to you! In the arising positions, both sides have their structural advantages, and often it depends if you can make 'the right trade' to leave the opponent without 'the attackers'.  With the last move, Black makes sure that White can't strengthen the center with the natural d4. }
