3... d5 4. e5
{ White could try offering to switch to the French Defense Advance variation. }
4... d4
{ There's no need to play the French Defense Advance variation, which could arise from  4...Nc6  5.d4  , but if you're a big fan, it's up to you! In the arising positions, both sides have their structural advantages, and often it depends if you can make 'the right trade' to leave the opponent without 'the attackers'.  With the last move, Black makes sure that White can't strengthen the center with the natural d4. }
5. Bd3
{ This awkward-looking move is the most popular move in the position - White continues development, intending to castle short. The bishop is often rerouted to e4 to target the black knight on c6  @@StartBracket@@assuming it's there@@EndBracket@@ and then to pressure the black pawn on d4. }
5... Bd7
{ The universal response against every setup that White chooses! Black brings out the light-squared bishop to c6, otherwise, that bishop may never see the daylight. }
6. O-O Bc6
{ Black positions the bishop on c6 and is waiting for White to define his setup. }
7. Na3
{ The critical move at White's disposal - White keeps open all options, including going after the d4-pawn. }
7... Ne7 8. Re1
{ Now that Black doesn't have access to ...g5 move anymore, this is the best moment to develop the rook. We also have to check what happens if White goes for the d4 pawn. }
8... Ng6
{ Not only is Black looking to complete his development, but he might also have ideas for an early ...Nf4 as well. }
9. Be4
{ White is aiming for the position where the light-squared bishops are traded and the rook is very active on e4, possibly lifting it to g4 and some h4-h5 ideas.   9.Nc4  the knight won't hold on c4 as long as you won't allow White to play a4 and protect the new outpost.  9...b5  Either the knight goes back from where it came, or White plays a dubious gambit with Nd6+. }
9... Be7
{ There's no need to rush with the bishop trade - you can do it later when the moment is right. Now comes an important moment, what White is going to do with the c-pawn. }
10. cxd4
{ If the pawn trade happens, this means that White still hopes to win the pawn on d4. However, now Black will have enough counterplay at the queenside. }
10... cxd4 11. d3 Bxe4
{ It's possible to also castle short but here Black wants to get his knight on c6 as quickly as possible to hold the center. }
12. Rxe4 Nc6
{ Black has managed to equalize the game and should focus on the queenside. White can't win the pawn on d4 due to the already known ...Nxe5 tactical trick. }
13. Nc4 b5 14. Ncd2 O-O { Black's plan is quite straightforward. } 15. Nb3 a5
16. a4 bxa4 17. Nbxd4 Ngxe5 { Do you remember this trick? It works again! } *

