[White "3) Morra Gambit & Alapin"]
[Black "Alapin 2.Nf3 e6 3.c3 d5 4.exd5 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White starts with typical development of the kingside, but there are still many ways to continue here. }
2... e6 3. c3
{ The Sicilian Alapin - while it's not as popular as other Sicilian variations, it has a pace of its own and is quite interesting. For starters, White just wants to grab the center with d4 so Black must do something about it. Compared with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.c3  a move earlier, Black has already committed himself to play ...e6 and has limited options to respond. That's the reason why we're offering a setup that will inevitably transpose, making your life a lot easier, with fewer lines to learn.   3.d4  White can also try to switch to the Smith-Morra with this odd move order.  3...cxd4  4.c3  dxc3  . If you are looking for ways to switch to Alapin lines, this will come with concessions for Black.  5.Nxc3  Nc6  transposes to the Smith-Morra lines. }
3... d5 4. exd5 Qxd5
{ The black queen on d5 feels rather well and applies some serious pressure against the center. Capturing with the pawn would not be very ambitious. }
5. d4
{ What you have to know about the position is that White very often is willing to recapture on d4 with a pawn, entering an isolated queen's pawn structure, later organizing a kingside attack. There's no reason to rush with this. }
5... Nf6 { Now White has several choices. } 6. Be2
{ White rushes to castle short. } 6... Nc6
{ It's best to include this move sooner than later to stop White's c4 and Nc3 plans. Black also wants to take on d4 next and create an isolated pawn on d4 - taking it early is possible but allows White to play an interesting gambit with Nxd4, sacrificing the pawn on g2.   6...Be7?!  this move might feel flexible for Black but it doesn't pressure White's center.  7.c4!  Now, this is quite strong - White is just in time to play Nc3 and fight for the central squares.  7...Qd7  We'll illustrate, the difference with including both Be2 and ...Be7.  8.Nc3  cxd4  9.Qxd4  Nc6  10.Qf4!  Now Black doesn't have ...e5 as the e-file is closed, but  10...Nb4  can be easily parried with White castling short. Thus White simply enjoys some space advantage. }
7. O-O cxd4
{ It's time to clarify the situation in the center.   7...Be7?!  again, Black needs to stay alert of the c4 plan.  8.c4  Qd8  9.dxc5  this idea would not be possible if White had not castled short - now he's ready to recapture on d1 with the rook.  9...O-O  10.Nc3  Bxc5  11.a3  White's position should be preferred as he enjoys some space advantage. }
8. cxd4
{ The principal choice - we're entering the realm of IQP @@StartBracket@@isolated queen's pawn structure@@EndBracket@@. White is aiming for a potential kingside attack, Black hopes to exploit the weak sides of having an isolated pawn on d4. }
8... Be7 9. Nc3 Qd6
{ The most popular continuation - here the black queen stands quite well. It's not allowing White to play Bf4 and after castling short can immediately apply pressure against the d4-pawn with ...Rd8. Black should not be afraid of Nb5. }
10. Be3 O-O 11. Rc1 Bd7
{ Black finishes development - White's attack has not started yet. It's interesting to explore also  11...b6  , trying to develop the light-squared bishop to b7 but this is a whole extra tempo. }
12. Ne5
{ Paichadze, L. @@StartBracket@@2568@@EndBracket@@ - Lupulescu, C. @@StartBracket@@2631@@EndBracket@@ EU-ch 18th 2017. }
12... Rad8
{ 12...Nxe5??  Unfortunately, the pawn can't be taken  13.dxe5  Qxe5  14.Bd4  Black is losing material as the bishop on d7 hangs. }
13. Nb5 Qd5
{ The Black queen is back on d5 looking for other ways to exit the scene. Retreating with  13...Qb8  is possible, but it allows White to increase pressure with  14.Bf4  . }
14. Bc4 Qe4 15. Nc3 Qh4 16. Nf3 Qh5
{ The Black queen on h5 slows down any kingside hostilities from White. At some point later it can be rerouted to a5 if there's a need. }
