[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White starts with typical development of the kingside, but there are still many ways to continue here. }
2... e6 3. c3
{ The Sicilian Alapin - while it's not as popular as other Sicilian variations, it has a pace of its own and is quite interesting. For starters, White just wants to grab the center with d4 so Black must do something about it. Compared with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.c3  a move earlier, Black has already committed himself to play ...e6 and has limited options to respond. That's the reason why we're offering a setup that will inevitably transpose, making your life a lot easier, with fewer lines to learn.   3.d4  White can also try to switch to the Smith-Morra with this odd move order.  3...cxd4  4.c3  dxc3  . If you are looking for ways to switch to Alapin lines, this will come with concessions for Black.  5.Nxc3  Nc6  transposes to the Smith-Morra lines. }
3... d5 4. exd5 Qxd5
{ The black queen on d5 feels rather well and applies some serious pressure against the center. Capturing with the pawn would not be very ambitious. }
5. d4
{ What you have to know about the position is that White very often is willing to recapture on d4 with a pawn, entering an isolated queen's pawn structure, later organizing a kingside attack. There's no reason to rush with this. }
5... Nf6 { Now White has several choices. } 6. Bd3
{ With the light-squared bishop on d3 the threat of c4 considerably loses power, thus there's no reason to rush with ...Nc6. }
6... Be7 7. O-O O-O
{ What has essentially happened here is that Black did not commit himself to take on d4, thus making the c3-square available for the white knight and opening the c-file for the white rook. Depending on what White will do, it's still possible but it also can be a good idea to keep more pressure in the center. Perhaps at the right time, Black is ready to play ...b6 and ...Ba6, trading off White's strong light-squared bishop? }
8. c4 Qd7
{ This maneuver should already be quite familiar to you! An alternative square for the black queen is h5. }
9. dxc5 Rd8 10. Ne5 Qd4
{ After the following almost forced sequence Black easily equalizes the game. }
11. Qe2 Nbd7 { The White pawn on c5 is not going anywhere. } 12. Nxd7 Bxd7 13.
Be3 Qe5
{ White can't keep the pawn as trying to do so would make things only worse. }
14. Nc3 Bxc5
{ Tzermiadianos, A. @@StartBracket@@2215@@EndBracket@@ - Kotronias, V. @@StartBracket@@2520@@EndBracket@@ GRE-ch 1991, with a balanced position. }
*

