[White "3) Morra Gambit & Alapin"]
[Black "Alapin 2.Nf3 e6 3.c3 d5 4.exd5 #18"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White starts with typical development of the kingside, but there are still many ways to continue here. }
2... e6 3. c3
{ The Sicilian Alapin - while it's not as popular as other Sicilian variations, it has a pace of its own and is quite interesting. For starters, White just wants to grab the center with d4 so Black must do something about it. Compared with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.c3  a move earlier, Black has already committed himself to play ...e6 and has limited options to respond. That's the reason why we're offering a setup that will inevitably transpose, making your life a lot easier, with fewer lines to learn.   3.d4  White can also try to switch to the Smith-Morra with this odd move order.  3...cxd4  4.c3  dxc3  . If you are looking for ways to switch to Alapin lines, this will come with concessions for Black.  5.Nxc3  Nc6  transposes to the Smith-Morra lines. }
3... d5 4. exd5 Qxd5
{ The black queen on d5 feels rather well and applies some serious pressure against the center. Capturing with the pawn would not be very ambitious. }
5. d4
{ What you have to know about the position is that White very often is willing to recapture on d4 with a pawn, entering an isolated queen's pawn structure, later organizing a kingside attack. There's no reason to rush with this. }
5... Nf6 { Now White has several choices. } 6. c4
{ If White tries to push away the black queen right away, there's an important nuance. }
6... Qd7
{ Apparently, this strange move is the best retreat square. Black wants to continue with ...cxd4 but having the queen on the awkward d7-square allows Black to avoid taking the queen on d4. }
7. Nc3 { White wants to push d5 - this must be stopped. } 7... cxd4 8. Qxd4
{ Taking with the knight doesn't apply any pressure for Black. } 8... Nc6
{ And there's the difference - for the queen trade the d7-square feels quite good. }
9. Qxd7+ Bxd7 10. a3
{ Terao, J. @@StartBracket@@1992@@EndBracket@@ - Han Wong, I. Pan American-ch U16 Girls 2004. Here Black could have improved the game with a more natural continuation. }
10... Bc5 11. b4 Nd4
{ Due to the fork threat on c2, Black solves all his opening problems. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3) Morra Gambit & Alapin"]
[Black "Alapin 2.Nf3 e6 3.c3 d5 4.exd5 #19"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ White starts with typical development of the kingside, but there are still many ways to continue here. }
2... e6 3. c3
{ The Sicilian Alapin - while it's not as popular as other Sicilian variations, it has a pace of its own and is quite interesting. For starters, White just wants to grab the center with d4 so Black must do something about it. Compared with @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1@@EndFEN@@  1.e4  c5  2.c3  a move earlier, Black has already committed himself to play ...e6 and has limited options to respond. That's the reason why we're offering a setup that will inevitably transpose, making your life a lot easier, with fewer lines to learn.   3.d4  White can also try to switch to the Smith-Morra with this odd move order.  3...cxd4  4.c3  dxc3  . If you are looking for ways to switch to Alapin lines, this will come with concessions for Black.  5.Nxc3  Nc6  transposes to the Smith-Morra lines. }
3... d5 4. exd5 Qxd5
{ The black queen on d5 feels rather well and applies some serious pressure against the center. Capturing with the pawn would not be very ambitious. }
5. d4
{ What you have to know about the position is that White very often is willing to recapture on d4 with a pawn, entering an isolated queen's pawn structure, later organizing a kingside attack. There's no reason to rush with this. }
5... Nf6 { Now White has several choices. } 6. Na3
{ The latest trend in the position which has gained quite a popularity - White is quite flexible with his plans but the knight on a3 often is useful. }
6... a6
{ Our proposal for this position - Black takes over the control of the b5-square. Please note that it doesn't mean that Black automatically will play ...b5 - you might push it under the right circumstances but that's not always your goal.   6...Nc6  this move is leading to a solid position but has no ambition. }
7. Nc4 Nbd7
{ This position has been reached several times at the highest level. We believe that compared to other alternatives, Black here has the potential to take over the game. }
8. a4
{ From White's perspective it makes perfect sense to secure the knight's outpost on c4 and try to establish a potential weakness on b6. Black here has a choice - try to equalize the game or go for a big fight. }
8... b6
{ This is a little more aggressive and leads to a lively position with all of the pieces still in play. Some may find this continuation even to be simpler. }
9. Be2 Bb7 10. Be3
{ With this move White signals that he wants to take the pawn on c5 in the next couple of moves, and thus tries to provoke Black to take on d4. }
10... Rd8
{ A good solid move - in case White will take the pawn on c5, Black will recapture it with the bishop in one go, not wasting a tempo. }
11. O-O Qc6 { Black keeps queens on board. } 12. Qb3 Be7 13. dxc5 Bxc5
{ White has won the tempo, but the gains are unclear. Black has a lot of chances for a successful kingside attack. }
*

