[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) f4 Without d4"]
[Black "Grand Prix Attack 2.f4 #1 | Informational 2...e6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ In this chapter we are going to explore several setups where White can try to fight for the center with the f4-push, without including d4. They can be tricky, but if armed with proper preparation, such continuations are harmless. }
2. f4
{ The immediate f4-push without any kind of preparation is rather rare, but still, it's important to know what to do against it. }
2... e6
{ If we continue in the Sicilian Kan manner, White's idea becomes obvious quickly. }
3. Nf3 d5 4. Bb5+
{ This is some kind of Sicilian Rossolimo/Moscow Variation, with White including a useful f4. Typical for the variation, Black can cover from the check with ...Bd7, ...Nd7, or ...Nc6. The latter would leave Black with a shattered pawn structure on the queenside. }
4... Bd7
{ Seemingly the solid approach.   4...Nd7  this is a little more aggressive, intending to play ...a6 and get the bishop pair advantage, but Black doesn't have the time to hold the center together.  5.Nc3  dxe4  6.Nxe4  Be7  7.Qe2  White's game is very easy, and the inclusion of f4 really helps.  7...a6  8.Bxd7+  Bxd7  9.b3  Black got his bishop pair advantage, but White's piece coordination is very harmonious.  9...Nf6  10.Nxf6+  Bxf6  11.Ne5  White can even castle long. Maybe it's not much for White, but this is what he's aiming for. }
5. Bxd7+ Qxd7 6. Ne5
{ An annoying intermezzo move, forcing the black queen to move again. } 6...
Qd6 7. Nc3 Nc6 8. Nb5 Qd8 9. Qh5
{ White can develop an unorthodox attack quite quickly. } 9... g6 10. Nxc6 gxh5
{ There's no choice. } 11. Nxd8 Rxd8 12. d3
{ Black has a shattered pawn structure on the kingside. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) f4 Without d4"]
[Black "Grand Prix Attack 2.f4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ In this chapter we are going to explore several setups where White can try to fight for the center with the f4-push, without including d4. They can be tricky, but if armed with proper preparation, such continuations are harmless. }
2. f4
{ The immediate f4-push without any kind of preparation is rather rare, but still, it's important to know what to do against it. }
2... d5
{ By far the strongest continuation and probably the reason why 2.f4 remains a rarity. }
3. exd5
{ White doesn't have much of a choice - anything else looks worse. Here White is at least hoping to win some tempos with Nc3, should Black capture on d5 with the queen.   3.Bb5+  the difference here is that White won't have the  follow-up of Ne5 after the bishop trade, as seen in a similar line.  3...Bd7  4.Bxd7+  Qxd7  Black has solid control over the center. }
3... Nf6
{ The strongest response - there's no need to gift White some extra tempi by capturing with the queen, Black wants to take on d5 with the knight. If White tries to hold on to the pawn, it will cost him time, while the inclusion of the f4 move will be a serious flaw in White's setup. }
4. c4
{ Now White will be left with a terrible light-squared bishop.   4.Nc3  is not very ambitious - White immediately acknowledges that the chosen setup is a failure.  4...Nxd5  5.Nf3  e6  Black will first develop the kingside, castle short and only then decide when to play ...Nc6. The reason is the incoming Bb5, which threatens to ruin Black's pawn structure. }
4... e6
{ It's time to gambit - Black sacrifices a pawn to accelerate his development. }
5. dxe6 Bxe6
{ Looking at White's position, it's not clear what he's been doing in the past moves. }
6. Nf3 Nc6 7. Be2 g6
{ Black's initiative will develop quickly - the compensation for the missing pawn is more than enough. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
