[White "4) f4 Without d4"]
[Black "Grand Prix Attack 2.f4 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ In this chapter we are going to explore several setups where White can try to fight for the center with the f4-push, without including d4. They can be tricky, but if armed with proper preparation, such continuations are harmless. }
2. f4
{ The immediate f4-push without any kind of preparation is rather rare, but still, it's important to know what to do against it. }
2... d5
{ By far the strongest continuation and probably the reason why 2.f4 remains a rarity. }
3. exd5
{ White doesn't have much of a choice - anything else looks worse. Here White is at least hoping to win some tempos with Nc3, should Black capture on d5 with the queen.   3.Bb5+  the difference here is that White won't have the  follow-up of Ne5 after the bishop trade, as seen in a similar line.  3...Bd7  4.Bxd7+  Qxd7  Black has solid control over the center. }
3... Nf6
{ The strongest response - there's no need to gift White some extra tempi by capturing with the queen, Black wants to take on d5 with the knight. If White tries to hold on to the pawn, it will cost him time, while the inclusion of the f4 move will be a serious flaw in White's setup. }
4. Bb5+
{ White wants to keep the pawn on d5, but to do that, he needs to trade the light-squared bishop first. }
4... Bd7 5. Bxd7+ Qxd7 6. c4
{ Otherwise, the entire approach loses any purpose and Black simply takes on d5 with the knight. }
6... e6
{ Now White has some choices, but in all of them Black has an excellent gambit. }
7. Nf3
{ White could try to give up the extra pawn and go for an unexpected counter-attack. With the inclusion of moves like f4 and c4, it looks a little strange. }
7... exd5 8. Ne5 Qe6
{ The most ambitious move - a quieter alternative should be the retreat to c7. }
9. O-O Bd6 10. cxd5 Qxd5
{ Taking with the knight is also possible, but then Black needs to be ready for the incoming f5 push and the knight on e5 can't be taken. Not that it's dangerous anyway, but the following line is simpler. }
11. Nc3 Qd4+ 12. Kh1 O-O { The king is safe now. } 13. Nb5 Qd5
{ Black has a better pawn structure. } *

