{ The strongest response - there's no need to gift White some extra tempi by capturing with the queen, Black wants to take on d5 with the knight. If White tries to hold on to the pawn, it will cost him time, while the inclusion of the f4 move will be a serious flaw in White's setup. }
4. Bb5+
{ White wants to keep the pawn on d5, but to do that, he needs to trade the light-squared bishop first. }
4... Bd7 5. Bxd7+ Qxd7 6. c4
{ Otherwise, the entire approach loses any purpose and Black simply takes on d5 with the knight. }
6... e6
{ Now White has some choices, but in all of them Black has an excellent gambit. }
