[White "4) f4 Without d4"]
[Black "Delayed GP-Attack 2.Be2 Nc6 3.f4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ In this chapter we are going to explore several setups where White can try to fight for the center with the f4-push, without including d4. They can be tricky, but if armed with proper preparation, such continuations are harmless. }
2. Be2
{ This is an interesting idea - White is playing some of known Black's setups but has an extra tempo. }
2... Nc6
{ A slightly more precise order of the moves before committing to ...e6, as White has not committed himself to the f4 setup just yet, although with the early Be2 the chances are high. }
3. f4
{ 3.Nf3  If White tries to trick you and switches to an Open Sicilian, the inclusion of Be2 is not critical.  3...Nf6  4.Nc3  d5  Black should be able to equalize the game quickly - notice that there might be no need to play ...e6 anymore. }
3... d5
{ It's possible to start with  3...e6  to prepare ...d5, but this move feels the most natural. If White will choose something else than d3, you might have committed to ...e6 a little early. }
4. d3
{ White doesn't mind trading the queens early - that's why the bishop is on e2! }
4... e6
{ 4...dxe4  We'll illustrate what happens if Black trades queens.  5.dxe4  Qxd1+  6.Bxd1  b6  because of the advanced pawn on c5, Black can't afford to make active moves in the center like ...e5 as it would forever weaken the d5 square.  7.Nf3  e6  8.Be3  Bb7  9.c3  White is just better with an easy plan. }
5. Nf3 Bd6
{ Instead of developing the knight on the traditional f6 square, there's an alternative way. }
6. O-O Nge7 7. c3
{ White is trying to be flexible with his plans in the center - he might consider pushing e5 and strengthening the center with d4 or moving the queen to h4 for a kingside assault. }
7... f6
{ The simplest setup for Black - it's simple, reliable, and has no strategic risk. Black's next move is castling short and then - keep your eyes open. One idea might be ...b6 and ...Bb7, ... Qd7 and stay flexible in the center, another idea is going for the ...e5 push. }
