9... Nf6 10. e5 dxe5 11. fxe5
{ Black is solidly worse - White will hold the initiative on the kingside. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4) f4 Without d4"]
[Black "GP-Attack 2.Nc3 e6 3.f4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ In this chapter we are going to explore several setups where White can try to fight for the center with the f4-push, without including d4. They can be tricky, but if armed with proper preparation, such continuations are harmless. }
2. Nc3
{ Usually, this starts the Closed Sicilian, but in this chapter, we will examine if White is playing this move to prepare f4. }
2... e6 3. f4 d5
{ Sometimes it's best to ask your opponent to define his plan sooner than later. Now White has to make a committal choice. }
4. Bb5+
{ If this move comes out early, there's a fair chance that White simply wants to trade the light-squared bishop first before playing d3. }
4... Bd7
{ 4...Nc6?!  We strongly advise you to avoid creating the arising pawn structure - you might find it not very attractive.  5.Bxc6+  bxc6  6.d3  Although Black has a strong pawn center, the doubled c-pawns will cause some serious headaches. White's plan at some point later is to play b3, Na4, and Ba3, bothering the pawn on c5. }
5. Bxd7+ Qxd7 6. d3
{ There, White just did it - he's planning to play Nf3 and O-O next, without the need to worry about the placement of the light-squared bishop. }
6... Nc6
{ It's best to start with this move, revealing the chosen setup as late as possible. }
7. Nf3 Nge7
{ Obviously, this is not the only plan in the position, but our suggestion is to go for a known idea in a very similar setup. Unfortunately, Black can't include ...Bd6 to play ...Nge7 later as the pawn on d5 would be lost. The dark-squared bishop on f8 can remain there for the time being. }
8. O-O f6
{ Black takes care of the e5 and g5-squares and is about to castle long. Watch out for White's potential gambit approach with an a3-b4 pawn push - you can simply ignore the pawn. }
9. Qe1 Nd4
{ A good moment to include the knight trade, freeing the c6 square for the other knight. There's nothing wrong with castling long as well. }
10. Qf2 Nxf3+ 11. Qxf3 O-O-O 12. Qf2 Nc6 { The chances are balanced. } *

