1. e4 c5
{ In this chapter we are going to explore several setups where White can try to fight for the center with the f4-push, without including d4. They can be tricky, but if armed with proper preparation, such continuations are harmless. }
2. Nc3
{ Usually, this starts the Closed Sicilian, but in this chapter, we will examine if White is playing this move to prepare f4. }
2... e6 3. f4 d5
{ Sometimes it's best to ask your opponent to define his plan sooner than later. Now White has to make a committal choice. }
4. exd5
{ With the inclusion of f4, this looks a little dubious, but there's a trick. }
4... exd5 5. Bb5+ Nc6
{ Black remains tactically alert. With the e-pawns traded, now White's Bxc6 plan to get to the c5-pawn can backfire as the center is open and Black will be able to conduct a strong attack quickly.   5...Bd7?  don't fall into this trap - with the e-pawns traded, White has an unexpected resource.  6.Qe2+!  Black drops the pawn on d5. }
6. Nf3 Nf6 7. O-O Bd7
{ Black will carefully bring out the pieces and castle short. The pawn on f4 considerably impacts White's options to be active in the center, as the e4-square is weak. }
