[Black "Kan 5.f4 #1 | Informational 5...Nf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. f4
{ This early pawn push comes with an idea to avoid the typical Sicilian Kan setups and our proposed ...b5 plan when the white knight already stands on c3. It could be a potential repertoire for White for blitz. }
5... Nf6
{ This is a logical developing move for Black but it also accelerates White's development. }
6. e5 Ne4
{ On d5 the knight would be subject to lose tempi as well - here, Black might want to back up the wanderer with ...d5. }
7. Qf3 d5 8. exd6
{ Now if Black takes on d6 with the knight, White plays moves like Be3, Nc3, and castles long with a strong initiative as the black knight on d6 for the action is misplaced. }
8... Qa5+
{ Black could try to provoke c3 so that positioning the knight on c3 and castling long no longer is an option. }
9. b4 Qd5 { The only move.   9...Qxb4+??  10.c3  Black loses a piece. } 10. Bb2
Nf6 11. a3
{ Inevitably White takes more space and eventually will have more active pieces. }
11... Bxd6 12. g3 Qxf3 13. Nxf3 b6
{ Even though queens have left the board, Black's position is quite difficult. }
14. Nbd2 Bb7 15. O-O-O
{ White's pieces are dominating the board while Black has some weaknesses to attend on the queenside. }
*

