[White "5) Open Sicilian With f4"]
[Black "Kan 5.f4 #2 | Informational 5...b5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. f4 b5
{ This idea works only with the white knight on c3  - Black plays ...b5 and ...Bb7 to target the pawn on e4 with ...b4 ideas.  Since the white knight is still on b1, the black pawn on b5 can easily become a  target. }
6. Be3 Bb7 7. Nd2
{ The queenside knight defends the central pawn from the d2-square and the a4 push is incoming, making the black pawn on b5 vulnerable. }
7... Nf6 8. Bd3 d6
{ Black would like to play ...Nbd7-c5 but he's out of time. } 9. a4 bxa4
{ 9...b4  is no better - the b-pawn is a weakness and White can establish a great outpost on b6. }
10. Rxa4 Be7 11. O-O Nbd7 12. N4b3
{ White counters the incoming ...Nc5 threat and will pressure the weakness on a6. }
*

