1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. f4
{ This early pawn push comes with an idea to avoid the typical Sicilian Kan setups and our proposed ...b5 plan when the white knight already stands on c3. It could be a potential repertoire for White for blitz. }
5... Nc6
{ This is playable but it resembles more with the Sicilian Taimanov approach. White could play  6.Nc3  and transpose to some of the mainlines of the Taimanov which are not common in the Kan. But there's a simpler way for White to get a good game. }
6. Nxc6 bxc6 7. Be3
{ This setup for White is very easy to play and should be counted as a success. }
7... d5 8. Nd2 Nf6 9. Bd3
{ White has easy ways to build up the initiative on the kingside. } *

