[White "5) Open Sicilian With f4"]
[Black "Kan 5.f4 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. f4
{ This early pawn push comes with an idea to avoid the typical Sicilian Kan setups and our proposed ...b5 plan when the white knight already stands on c3. It could be a potential repertoire for White for blitz. }
5... d5
{ Black should clarify the situation in the center as soon as possible to take away from White some improvisation options. We've also illustrated the other continuations and why they are not so appealing. }
6. e5
{ White establishes a potential outpost on d4 for his knight but relieves any pressure from the center. While this position resembles French Defense Steinitz variation, the difference is that Black has not lost tempi for ...Nf6-d7 and thus is more flexible with development. }
6... Nc6
{ It makes sense to start with this move and see, what happens next. Black is thinking to develop the queenside with a move like ...Bd7, ...Rc8, and ...Qb6 which are characteristic of the French Defense. The kingside knight might be developed to f5. }
7. Be3
{ If White will get to play Nd2-f3, he can even fight for an opening advantage as the White knights would firmly control some of the most important central squares. }
7... Qb6
{ That's why it's a good idea to stop White's plan! At the moment Black is threatening to win a pawn on b2. }
8. Nc3 Qxb2 { This starts a forced sequence. } 9. Na4 Qa3
{ 9...Qb4+??  the wrong way to retreat.  10.c3  Qa5  11.Nxc6  bxc6  12.Bb6  Black loses his queen. }
10. c3 { A sad necessity. } 10... Nxd4 11. Bxd4 b5 12. Nb6 Rb8
{ The forced sequence is almost over - White has nothing to show for the missing pawn.   Here's how the game could continue:  13.Qb3  Qa5  14.Nxc8  Rxc8  15.Bd3  Bc5  White has no compensation for the missing pawn. }
*

