[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. f4
{ This early pawn push comes with an idea to avoid the typical Sicilian Kan setups and our proposed ...b5 plan when the white knight already stands on c3. It could be a potential repertoire for White for blitz. }
5... d5
{ Black should clarify the situation in the center as soon as possible to take away from White some improvisation options. We've also illustrated the other continuations and why they are not so appealing. }
6. e5
{ White establishes a potential outpost on d4 for his knight but relieves any pressure from the center. While this position resembles French defense Steinitz variation, the difference is that Black has not lost tempos for ...Nf6-d7 and thus is more flexible with the development. }
6... Nc6
{ It makes sense to start with this move and see, what happens next. Black is thinking to develop the queenside with a move like ...Bd7, ...Rc8, and ...Qb6 which are characteristic of the French Defense. The kingside knight might be developed to f5. }
7. Nc3 Nge7
{ Unlike in the Steinitz variation, the black knight on e7 is feeling more flexible than on d7. Black wants to trade the knights on d4 and bring the other knight to c6. }
8. Be3 Nxd4 9. Bxd4 Bd7
{ Black is not revealing his cards - maybe the knight will go to c6, maybe f5. It's quite clear that the light-squared bishop belongs to d7, opening the c8-square for the rook. On d7 it's also more defensive against potential incoming f5-pawn attack. It is interesting to consider also the typical French pawn push  9...g5  with interesting complications. }
10. Bd3 Nc6 11. Bf2 g5
{ Now this works like a charm as Black is ready to trade the g-pawn for White's central pawn. }
12. Qd2 Qc7
{ White's center is quite vulnerable. The Black king for the time being can remain in the center - there's no need to rush with castling long, focus on positioning the pieces on the most active squares. If White takes the pawn on g5,  Black's dark-squared bishop feels good on g7. }
*

