1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. f4
{ This early pawn push comes with an idea to avoid the typical Sicilian Kan setups and our proposed ...b5 plan when the white knight already stands on c3. It could be a potential repertoire for White for blitz. }
5... d5
{ Black should clarify the situation in the center as soon as possible to take away from White some improvisation options. We've also illustrated the other continuations and why they are not so appealing. }
6. Nc3
{ The main move, in the spirit of the French Defense where Nc3 also is one of the critical continuations. }
6... dxe4
{ It's possible to explore also  6...Bb4  for a more complex game and perhaps it will be more appreciated by true French defense fans, but this continuation is simpler and works just fine. }
7. Nxe4 Nd7
{ The arising position resembles one of the variations from the French Defense with 3.Nd2. Here the inclusion of f4 and ...a6  favors Black. Black prepares to play ...Ngf6 so that it's possible to recapture with the knight, thus fighting for the central squares. Also with the knight on d7 Black is ready to bother White's light-squared bishop via the c5-square as it's usually placed on d3 to start a potential kingside attack. }
8. Be3 Ngf6 9. Bd3 Be7
{ Black remains flexible with the placement of the queen. } 10. Qf3
{ The most aggressive move, preparing to castle long and thinking about future g4-g5 ideas. }
10... Qc7
{ 10...Nxe4?!  being too flexible sometimes can backfire - don't miss the following trick  11.Bxe4  Nc5?  12.Nc6!  Black can't take the knight and will be forced to give up the important dark-squared bishop, losing control of many important dark squares. }
11. Nxf6+
{ Quite smart - White is aware of Black's plan and includes the knight trade before castling long.   11.O-O-O  If White plays the most obvious move, Black proceeds with his plan.  11...Nxe4  12.Bxe4  Nc5  13.g4  Bd7  However, the trick here is that Black can postpone castling short and can castle long instead. Whichever you like, is up to you! }
11... Nxf6 12. O-O-O Bd7
{ Black is flexible with his plans - castling short is an obvious choice but going the other way might be interesting as well, pretty much negating White's planned kingside attack. }
13. Kb1 Rd8
{ A tricky order of moves - Black prepares to play ...Bc5 and will be threatening with both ... Bxd4 and ...Bc6, or ...Nd5, applying serious pressure against White's centered pieces.   13...Bc5  is a preparatory move for the long castle, making sure that White doesn't play Nb3, thus winning control of many squares on the queenside.  14.Rhe1  O-O-O  Black's  next moves might be ...Kb8 and ...Nd5, enjoying a good middlegame.  15.c3  Ba4  16.Rc1  Nd5  17.Bd2  Kb8  followed by ...Rhe8 and Black is doing alright. }
14. g4 Bc5
{ Black makes sure that White can't play g5 right away and is planning to continue with ...Nd5.   14...O-O?!  15.g5  Nd5  16.Bc1  this position looks dangerous for Black - White's attack on the kingside is about to start. }
15. g5 { Tactically this doesn't work. } 15... Bxd4 16. Bxd4 Bc6 17. Qe3
{ White might be happy to sacrifice the exchange to accelerate his attack but there's more - the bishop on d4 requires to be defended. }
17... Ng4 18. Qg1 Qxf4
{ The White rook is not going anywhere - White is busted. } *

