1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. f4
{ This early pawn push comes with an idea to avoid the typical Sicilian Kan setups and our proposed ...b5 plan when the white knight already stands on c3. It could be a potential repertoire for White for blitz. }
5... d5
{ Black should clarify the situation in the center as soon as possible to take away from White some improvisation options. We've also illustrated the other continuations and why they are not so appealing. }
6. Nc3
{ The main move, in the spirit of the French Defense where Nc3 also is one of the critical continuations. }
6... dxe4
{ It's possible to explore also  6...Bb4  for a more complex game and perhaps it will be more appreciated by true French defense fans, but this continuation is simpler and works just fine. }
