{ The arising position resembles one of the variations from the French Defense with 3.Nd2. Here the inclusion of f4 and ...a6  favors Black. Black prepares to play ...Ngf6 so that it's possible to recapture with the knight, thus fighting for the central squares. Also with the knight on d7 Black is ready to bother White's light-squared bishop via the c5-square as it's usually placed on d3 to start a potential kingside attack. }
8. Be3 Ngf6 9. Bd3 Qc7
{ It's possible to start also with this move, this time being a little more flexible with the placement of the dark-squared bishop. Black also is preparing to play ...Nxe4 and ...Nc5, trading off White's light-squared bishop. }
10. Qf3 Nxe4 11. Bxe4 Nc5
{ Black is a little behind in development so the next couple of moves needs to be played out carefully. }
12. O-O-O Be7
{ The White bishop is not going anywhere - focus on your king's safety first. }
13. Rhe1 O-O 14. Nb3 Nxe4 15. Qxe4 a5
{ Black's initiative at the queenside looks a little more real than whatever White is planning at the kingside. It's a good idea to keep queens on the board. }
