[White "6) 2.Nf3, 3.g3"]
[Black "Anti-Sicilian 3.g3  d5 4.e5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3
{ We will examine various setups from White's perspective, that involve fianchettoing the light-squared bishop to g2. Positioning the bishop on g2 has a lot of perspectives - in many cases, White will be defending the pawn on e4 with the bishop which can easily become the strongest piece on the board, should the diagonal h1-a8 open up.  This particular order of the moves doesn't have an official title and sometimes it's referred to as the Adams variation, for reasons not particularly clear. One of the authors of the course, Arturs Neiksans, a few years ago published a database from White's perspective, in-depth analyzing 3.g3 as part of his Anti-Sicilian trilogy against ...e6 setups. Since this setup has been employed by many players from the Baltic states, we'll keep referring to the line as the Baltic variation. }
3... d5
{ There's more than one continuation from Black - this one is the most direct and gives Black an easy development. In most cases, it will create an isolated pawn on d5 but Black should be able to compensate it with a lot of activity. }
4. e5
{ White can try to close the center and return to French Defense Advance Variation ideas - this is quite a rare continuation. }
4... Nc6
{ Black is trying to apply immediate pressure against the center.   4...Bd7  You could try to transpose to one of the Chapter 3 lines. If White would play  5.c3  next - then  5...d4  works great, bringing out the bishop to c6. @@StartFEN@@rn1qkbnr/pp1b1ppp/4p3/2ppP3/8/5NP1/PPPP1P1P/RNBQKB1R w KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5.Bg2  However, White is not obliged to do it, which begs the question if the early development of the bishop on d7 was such a good idea. }
5. c3
{ Unfortunately, this is not so great here - you might remember our reservations from Chapter 3 in the Sicilian Alapin. One of Black's ideas was to early play ...Bd7 and bring it to c6. }
5... f6
{ Black wants to eliminate the white pawn from e5 to win the battle for the center.   5...d4  6.d3  Nge7  7.Bg2  Ng6  8.Qe2  Qc7  9.Na3  Black is a little worse due to the passive light-squared bishop. }
6. d4 cxd4 7. cxd4 fxe5
{ Black should play it out aggressively - White is a little slow with the execution of the Bg2 setup. }
8. dxe5 { Here White is risking getting a worse position. } 8... Bc5 9. Bd3
Nge7
{ Black will castle short with a nice pressure at the f-file. Think about moving your light-squared bishop to e8 and then either g6 or h5. }
