[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) 2.Nf3, 3.g3"]
[Black "Anti-Sicilian 3.g3  d5 4.d3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3
{ We will examine various setups from White's perspective, that involve fianchettoing the light-squared bishop to g2. Positioning the bishop on g2 has a lot of perspectives - in many cases, White will be defending the pawn on e4 with the bishop which can easily become the strongest piece on the board, should the diagonal h1-a8 open up.  This particular order of the moves doesn't have an official title and sometimes it's referred to as the Adams variation, for reasons not particularly clear. One of the authors of the course, Arturs Neiksans, a few years ago published a database from White's perspective, in-depth analyzing 3.g3 as part of his Anti-Sicilian trilogy against ...e6 setups. Since this setup has been employed by many players from the Baltic states, we'll keep referring to the line as the Baltic variation. }
3... d5
{ There's more than one continuation from Black - this one is the most direct and gives Black an easy development. In most cases, it will create an isolated pawn on d5 but Black should be able to compensate it with a lot of activity. }
4. d3
{ White invites to switch to French King's Indian attack with plans to play either Nbd2 or Qe2 next. We're going to talk about it more in Chapter 8 but in general, we advise avoiding the arising positions where Black has played ...d5, White closes up the center and starts active operations in the kingside. Thus, herewith the given order of moves we recommend to take on e4 - the arising endgame is quite safe. }
4... dxe4 5. dxe4 Qxd1+ 6. Kxd1
{ Black's setup is not ideal - we wish that the c-pawn was not standing on c5. But also White's not perfect - the kings' location needs fixing. }
6... Nc6 7. Bb5
{ The most aggressive continuation - the fact that White has played g3, doesn't mean that he can't adapt to changes of the position. }
7... Bd7 8. Nbd2
{ White wants to play c3 next and fight for the central squares. We found that the following setup for Black is solid. }
8... Nf6 9. Ke2 Bd6
{ The bishop will be rerouted to c7 for a more active role, but the kingside knight is heading to the e5 square, possibly via g4. After that, ...f5 might be an interesting way to get a more active game. Just don't blunder any incoming e5 fork, which would start with trading your knight on c6. }
*

