[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6) 2.Nf3, 3.g3"]
[Black "Anti-Sicilian 3.g3  d5 4.exd5 #2 | Informational 5...Nc6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3
{ We will examine various setups from White's perspective, that involve fianchettoing the light-squared bishop to g2. Positioning the bishop on g2 has a lot of perspectives - in many cases, White will be defending the pawn on e4 with the bishop which can easily become the strongest piece on the board, should the diagonal h1-a8 open up.  This particular order of the moves doesn't have an official title and sometimes it's referred to as the Adams variation, for reasons not particularly clear. One of the authors of the course, Arturs Neiksans, a few years ago published a database from White's perspective, in-depth analyzing 3.g3 as part of his Anti-Sicilian trilogy against ...e6 setups. Since this setup has been employed by many players from the Baltic states, we'll keep referring to the line as the Baltic variation. }
3... d5
{ There's more than one continuation from Black - this one is the most direct and gives Black an easy development. In most cases, it will create an isolated pawn on d5 but Black should be able to compensate it with a lot of activity. }
4. exd5
{ The main idea behind the g3 setup - White wants to trade pawns to push d4 next. }
4... exd5 5. d4 Nc6 { This logical move is not the most precise. } 6. Bg2 Nf6
{ Now Black continues the standard development - the inclusion of ...Nc6 can backfire but not for the reasons that you think.   6...Bg4  If Black starts to apply pressure against the white pawn on d4, unfortunately, White doesn't have to react. If White would be forced to take on c5, Black would get a great position.  7.O-O!  Nxd4  8.Qe1+  White evades the pin.  8...Be7  Retreating with the knight on e6 is bad as the diagonal h1-a8 will open with a great effect.  9.Nxd4  cxd4  10.Qe5  Nf6  11.Qxd4  The difference here is that White has managed to create an isolated pawn on d5 and the black knight is missing from c6 to apply more pressure on the center. Black is worse. }
7. O-O Be7 8. dxc5 Bxc5
{ The Black bishop is moving twice and seemingly there's a deadly check at the e-file but actually, that one is harmless. The problem is that White has not committed himself to Nc3. }
9. a3 O-O 10. b4
{ You might not realize it yet but now Black doesn't have the typical counter-resource ...d4, attacking the knight on c3 which will be explained in the mainline. The white knight will jump to c3 later - this is a big difference. }
10... Be7 11. Nc3 Be6 12. Bb2
{ White got exactly the position that he wanted - the queen typically goes to d3 and the pawn on d5 will be under some serious fire very soon. }
