12. Re1 Rc8
{ Black has a lot of good and solid moves to make - White enjoys a temporary outpost on d4 but it's not much to work with. }
13. a3
{ White prepares the knight to jump to d4, otherwise after the bishop retreat White needs to deal with ...Bb4 consequences, ruining White's pawn structure at the queenside. }
13... Re8 14. Be3
{ Jovanovic, Z. @@StartBracket@@2536@@EndBracket@@ - Schlosser, P. @@StartBracket@@2610@@EndBracket@@ AUT-chT 1314 2014. White is a little slow with his rearranging so Black can do something in the meantime. Activating the pieces is a good start. }
14... Qd7
{ The pawn on h3 is under attack. If White will protect it with Kh2, then Black can activate his light-squared bishop. }
15. Ng5
{ Obviously, this is something that Black always should be ready for but the consequences of the trade are not so clear. }
15... h6 16. Nxe6 fxe6
{ Black's pawn on d5 now is well defended, the pawn on e6 is not in danger and Black can focus on improving his pieces. The bishop belongs to d6 while the queenside knight might be rearranged to c4 in a near future. Don't push forward the central pawns, unless there's a real gain from it. }
