1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. g3
{ We will examine various setups from White's perspective, that involve fianchettoing the light-squared bishop to g2. Positioning the bishop on g2 has a lot of perspectives - in many cases, White will be defending the pawn on e4 with the bishop which can easily become the strongest piece on the board, should the diagonal h1-a8 open up.  This particular order of the moves doesn't have an official title and sometimes it's referred to as the Adams variation, for reasons not particularly clear. One of the authors of the course, Arturs Neiksans, a few years ago published a database from White's perspective, in-depth analyzing 3.g3 as part of his Anti-Sicilian trilogy against ...e6 setups. Since this setup has been employed by many players from the Baltic states, we'll keep referring to the line as the Baltic variation. }
3... d5
{ There's more than one continuation from Black - this one is the most direct and gives Black an easy development. In most cases, it will create an isolated pawn on d5 but Black should be able to compensate it with a lot of activity. }
4. exd5
{ The main idea behind the g3 setup - White wants to trade pawns to push d4 next. }
4... exd5 5. d4 Nf6
{ We propose to start with the kingside development and wait with the natural ...Nc6 - there's a good reason to do it.   5...Qe7+?  now the queen check doesn't work.  6.Be3  the Black queen on e7 slows down development. }
6. Bg2 Be7 7. O-O O-O
{ Now White has a choice - take on c5 himself and start to attack the isolated pawn or look for better circumstances. }
8. Nc3 { Let's treat this as the main move in the position. } 8... Nc6
{ Now that the white knight has made it to c3, the queenside knight goes to c6, ready to attack the center. White once again has a choice.   8...h6  is too slow, unfortunately, Black has no time for prophylactic moves here.  9.Be3  If White manages to force Black to take on d4, White's chances should be preferred.  9...Ng4  Unfortunately Black here is not ready for this kind of action.  10.dxc5  Nxe3  11.fxe3  Bxc5  12.Nxd5  Black may win back the pawn on e3 but White's position will be much better. }
9. dxc5 Bxc5
{ On most occasions you will reach exactly this position, but the order of the moves may vary. }
10. a3
{ The trickiest idea of the variation - White is preparing to play b4 next, and depending on what Black will respond, continue with either Bb2 or Bg5. }
10... Re8 { A smart waiting move - Black is not revealing all his cards. } 11.
b4 d4
{ For this counter-punch Black was waiting for. Depending on where the knight will retreat, Black will choose his continuation accordingly. }
12. Ne2
{ This retreat is linked with an idea to win the pawn on d4 on the spot, but tactically it doesn't work. }
12... Bb6 13. b5
{ White trying to win the pawn on d4 right away has a nice refutation which makes this a nice trap. }
13... Ne5 14. Nfxd4
{ If White captures with the other knight, Black's response is the same. This continuation feels more human as White can seemingly defend the knight on d4 with both c3 and f3 maneuvers. The problem is - both of them are bad. }
14... Bg4 { The freshly created pin dooms White. } 15. f3 Nxf3+ 16. Bxf3 Bxf3
17. Rxf3 Rxe2 { Black's idea becomes apparent - White's position is in ruins. }
