{ The trickiest idea of the variation - White is preparing to play b4 next, and depending on what Black will respond, continue with either Bb2 or Bg5. }
10... Re8 { A smart waiting move - Black is not revealing all his cards. } 11.
b4 d4
{ For this counter-punch Black was waiting for. Depending on where the knight will retreat, Black will choose his continuation accordingly. }
12. Na4
{ This is the critical continuation at White's disposal - now Black can retreat with his dark-squared bishop far away from the white knight's range. }
12... Bf8 13. c4
{ Albeit White wants to establish a pawn majority at the queenside and block the Black pawn on d3, this does not look impressive at all as Black can just trade the pawns, having a great piece activity. }
13... dxc3
{ Simple and good, but Black can explore also the slightly more ambitious  13...d3!?  The arising question would be - is the Black pawn on d3 a strength or a weakness? Probably it depends on how you play it out! }
14. Nxc3 Bg4 15. Be3 Qc8
{ Black has equalized the game and can safely look into the future. } 16. Qb3
{ The only game in this line so far followed like this. } 16... Be6 17. Qb2 Bh3
18. Rfd1 Bxg2 19. Kxg2 Qf5
{ Black has traded off the most active White's piece and is seeking ways to take over the game. }
20. h3 Rac8 21. Qb3 Rxe3
{ For the bravery, it deserves an exclamation mark! Practically Black gets a lasting initiative, while engines are not impressed. }
22. fxe3 Ne5 23. Nxe5 Qxe5
{ White was forced to find a lot of difficult defensive moves in McShane, L. @@StartBracket@@2688@@EndBracket@@ - Smirin, I. @@StartBracket@@2594@@EndBracket@@ Netanya Masters 2019. }
