{ The main idea behind the g3 setup - White wants to trade pawns to push d4 next. }
4... exd5 5. d4 Nf6
{ We propose to start with the kingside development and wait with the natural ...Nc6 - there's a good reason to do it.   5...Qe7+?  now the queen check doesn't work.  6.Be3  the Black queen on e7 slows down development. }
6. Bg2 Be7 7. O-O O-O
{ Now White has a choice - take on c5 himself and start to attack the isolated pawn or look for better circumstances. }
8. Nc3 { Let's treat this as the main move in the position. } 8... Nc6
{ Now that the white knight has made it to c3, the queenside knight goes to c6, ready to attack the center. White once again has a choice.   8...h6  is too slow, unfortunately, Black has no time for prophylactic moves here.  9.Be3  If White manages to force Black to take on d4, White's chances should be preferred.  9...Ng4  Unfortunately Black here is not ready for this kind of action.  10.dxc5  Nxe3  11.fxe3  Bxc5  12.Nxd5  Black may win back the pawn on e3 but White's position will be much better. }
9. dxc5 Bxc5
{ On most occasions you will reach exactly this position, but the order of the moves may vary. }
10. a3
{ The trickiest idea of the variation - White is preparing to play b4 next, and depending on what Black will respond, continue with either Bb2 or Bg5. }
10... Re8 { A smart waiting move - Black is not revealing all his cards. } 11.
b4 d4
{ For this counter-punch Black was waiting for. Depending on where the knight will retreat, Black will choose his continuation accordingly. }
12. Na4
{ This is the critical continuation at White's disposal - now Black can retreat with his dark-squared bishop far away from the white knight's range. }
12... Bf8 13. Bb2
{ Now it's Black who has a choice - you can either go the equalizing path or be a little more ambitious. You choose! }
13... Bg4
{ For the sake of simplicity, we'll offer this continuation as the main  @@StartBracket@@  13...Qc7  is the alternative@@EndBracket@@ -  now with accurate play Black should get a solid endgame. Black wants to play next ...Qd7, stopping White's h3 and also indirectly targeting the white knight on a4. }
14. h3
{ White doesn't have a choice as it's difficult to imagine that White will want to endure the pin. }
14... Bh5 15. g4 Bg6 16. Nxd4 Nxd4
{ All of these moves are more or less forced. } 17. Bxd4
{ Taking with the bishop looks a little scary - Black will gain control over a very important diagonal, targeting the white king. }
17... Bxc2 18. Qxc2
{ Note that  18.Bxf6  doesn't work in view of  18...Qxd1  19.Raxd1  Bxa4  ,  winning material since both the rook on d1 and the bishop on f6 are under attack. }
18... Qxd4 19. Bxb7 Rab8
{ White has won the pawn, but Black's ...Qf4 is looming in the air, followed by ...Bd6.   The game could follow like this: @@StartFEN@@1r2rbk1/pB3ppp/5n2/8/NP1q2P1/P6P/2Q2P2/R4RK1 w - - 1 20@@EndFEN@@  20.Bg2  a5!  @@StartBracket@@The immediate  20...Qf4  is not so good due to  21.Qc1  .@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@1r2rbk1/5ppp/5n2/p7/NP1q2P1/P6P/2Q2PB1/R4RK1 w - - 0 21@@EndFEN@@  21.bxa5  Rec8  White is forced to defend the knight on a4.  22.Qd1  Qf4  and here comes the big threat -  23.Nb6  Rc5  24.a6  Ra5  Black's attack on the kingside looks very real - the pawn on a6 will have to be eliminated first though. }
