b4 d4
{ For this counter-punch Black was waiting for. Depending on where the knight will retreat, Black will choose his continuation accordingly. }
12. Na4
{ This is the critical continuation at White's disposal - now Black can retreat with his dark-squared bishop far away from the white knight's range. }
12... Bf8 13. Bb2
{ Now it's Black who has a choice - you can either go the equalizing path or be a little more ambitious. You choose! }
13... Qc7
{ However, this continuation is for those who are unhappy with just an equal game after  13...Bg4  ,  and are seeking thrill in every game! It's a little gambling - be ready for a very sharp game. Black sacrifices the pawn on d4 for long-term compensation. We won't present you lengthy lines which might never actually happen in the game - just a few ideas for your knowledge. }
14. c3
{ White can try to bow out and decline the thrown challenge but it looks a little strange, especially taking into account that winning the pawn on d4 was White's idea all along. }
14... dxc3 15. Bxc3
{ The most ambitious option in the unambitious line.   If White is threatening Nb5 and the subsequent capture on f6, be alert.  15.Nxc3  Bg4  poses no problems, neither for White or Black - the position is just equal.  16.Nb5?!  Qb6!  17.Bxf6  Qxb5  . There's Black's idea - White has created himself some problems as the light-squared bishop's pin is quite annoying. }
15... Ne4 16. b5 Nxc3 17. Nxc3 Na5
{ Retreating on e5 is also possible but this continuation keeps on the board as many pieces as possible, plus the Black knight is eyeing for the c4-square. }
18. Ng5 { Nice try! } 18... Bf5
{ 18...Qxc3??  Recognize a gift, when you see one.  19.Qh5  . } 19. Qf3 Re5
{ Despite the equal material and the symmetrical pawn structure, the game can become quite sharp and is double-edged. }
