b4 d4
{ For this counter-punch Black was waiting for. Depending on where the knight will retreat, Black will choose his continuation accordingly. }
12. Na4
{ This is the critical continuation at White's disposal - now Black can retreat with his dark-squared bishop far away from the white knight's range. }
12... Bf8 13. Bb2
{ Now it's Black who has a choice - you can either go the equalizing path or be a little more ambitious. You choose! }
13... Qc7
{ However, this continuation is for those who are unhappy with just an equal game after  13...Bg4  ,  and are seeking thrill in every game! It's a little gambling - be ready for a very sharp game. Black sacrifices the pawn on d4 for long-term compensation. We won't present you lengthy lines which might never actually happen in the game - just a few ideas for your knowledge. }
14. Nxd4 { Challenge accepted! } 14... Bg4 15. Qc1 Ne5
{ Black is about to land with his knight on c4 - the White knight on a4 looks just terrible. }
16. Re1
{ 16.c4  is quite a human choice - White may want to simplify the position, as it involves a queen trade.  16...Qxc4  17.Qxc4  Nxc4  18.Bxb7  Rad8  . White has kept his extra pawn but Black is incredibly active.  19.Nb3  Nxb2  20.Nxb2  g6  . At first glance, it seems that White has a healthy extra pawn and that everything is alright. However, if you look at the position more closely, you'll realize that White's position is quite difficult to play. Black has all the easy moves, while White is struggling to understand, where to place his knights. He might coordinate the knights to place one of them on c5 and that's it - they're stuck. }
16... Nc4
{ Black's pieces are more active and White will have to make a lot of uneasy moves. }
17. Bc3 Rxe1+ 18. Qxe1 Re8 19. Qf1 Ne4
{ We can probably stop the analysis around here and conclude that for the pawn Black holds a very interesting initiative. }
20. Nb5
{ Another way how White could continue.  20.Re1??  simply drops a lot of material  20...Ned2  . }
20... Qc8 21. Nxa7 Qf5 22. f3 Nxc3 23. Nxc3 Ne3
{ The arising complications are quite big. } 24. Qf2 Qf6 25. Nab5 Bd7 26. Re1
{ If White has picked up all of these moves, then what awaits us is a drawn endgame. }
26... Nxc2 27. Rxe8 Bxe8 28. Qxc2 Bxb5 29. Nxb5 Qb6+
{ A small trick - Black wins back the piece. } 30. Kh1 Qxb5 31. f4 g6
{ Because of opposite color bishops and the slightly weakened king, White has no chances to win the game - Black should hold this comfortably. }
