21. Nxb5 Qe5 { Now White has a choice, which knight to move to c3. } 22. Nbc3
{ White needs a couple of moves to solidify.   22.Nac3  Nxc3  23.Nxc3  Nxa3!  Black wins back one pawn but remains very active.  24.Rxa3  Qxe1  25.Nd5!  Qd2  26.Ra1  Qxc2  The position inevitably liquidates into a drawn endgame.  27.Ne3  Qe2  28.Rxa7  Bxb4  29.Nxg4  Qxg4  30.Bd5  Rf8  Players can happily shake hands as also 30 moves have been played. }
22... Ned2
{ Suddenly Black has some ...Qxe1 threats, should the white queen retreat to d3. }
23. Bxd2 Nxd2 24. f4 Nxf1 25. fxe5 Ne3
{ White has two extra pawns in an endgame, but nothing is clear. } 26. Be4 Nc4
27. Nb5 Rxe5 { One pawn is back! } 28. Bd3 Nd2 29. Kf2
{ 29.Nxa7  Rh5  30.Kg2  Bf3+  31.Kg1  Bg4  if Black has it enough, there is a draw by repetition. }
29... Rh5 30. h4 g5 { The game still continues - it's a complete mess. } 31.
Rh1
{ 31.hxg5  this looks quite risky for White.  31...Be7  32.Nd4  Bxg5  . The white king is potentially in a mating net - at least it looks pretty scary to have so many Black pieces around the monarch. }
31... Bf3 32. Rg1 Bc6 33. Nc5
{ After several more difficult moves, the position finally simplifies. } 33...
Bxb5 34. Bxb5 g4 35. Bd3 Bxc5+ 36. bxc5 Rxc5 37. Ke3 Nf3
{ Black's initiative is over but so are White's extra two pawns. The logical outcome here is a draw. Luckily you don't have to learn these lines - they're illustrative for some thinking outside the box. }
