[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Closed Sicilian"]
[Black "2.Nc3 e6 3.Nge2 a6 #1 | Informational 6...Nf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 e6 3. Nge2
{ This venomous move itself doesn't reveal much - White might still play both g3 and d4. The white knight on e2 is a little more passive than on f3 but on the other hand, it doesn't close the light-squared bishop's gaze on g2, and at the same time, a potential pin with Black's ...Bg4 doesn't seem so annoying anymore. }
3... a6 4. g3
{ We will analyze the idea which involves delaying the d4 push, otherwise after White's d4, Black takes the pawn, and we simply transpose to other chapters . }
4... b5
{ Black wants to position his light-squared bishop on b7 as quickly as possible, applying pressure against White's center. Again, if White plays d4, Black is ready to transpose to other chapters.   4...d5?!  this is not quite the same as in Chapter 6.  5.exd5  exd5  6.d4  the inclusion of Nge2 and ...a6 favors White, plus the white bishop on g2 will be immediately applying pressure against the black pawn on d5. }
5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O {  } 6... Nf6
{ The main continuation in the position but Black almost by force can land into a strategically dangerous position. }
7. Re1 { A rare but at the same time very strong move! } 7... b4
{ Black has to accept the challenge, otherwise, he's worse.   7...d6?!  Our reservations about ...d6 setup are more explained in Chapter 9. In general, we suggest avoiding playing ...d6 as there are many tactical ideas at White's disposal that can make Black's life miserable.   7...Nc6?  this idea now, unfortunately, does not work.  8.e5!  Ng4  9.d4  Black is not ready for this kind of action in the center.  9...cxd4  10.Nxd4  Ngxe5  11.Rxe5  Nxe5  12.Bxb7  Black is busted as White has both material advantage and a lead in development.  8.d4⩲  cxd4?!  9.Nxd4  White has dangerous ideas to push e5 and shove Nd5, perhaps with including a4 earlier. Try to avoid this setup. }
8. Nd5
{ The idea is very common. With the sacrifice, White opens the e-file and the black king is still in the center. }
8... exd5 9. exd5 d6
{ 9...Be7  10.d6  White wins back the piece and has a much better position. }
10. Nd4+
{ 10.d4?  White wants to play Nd4 with all the comfort but the refutation is simple.  10...c4  White had no compensation for the sacrificed piece in Prudlo, S. @@StartBracket@@2128@@EndBracket@@ - Hunold, R. @@StartBracket@@2119@@EndBracket@@ NRW Class1 Germany 2003. }
10... Kd7
{ Covering with the bishop on e7 is impossible due to Nf5. It does not matter, where the white knight will retreat to - it's quite clear that Black will have to play very accurately not to get mated on the queenside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Closed Sicilian"]
[Black "2.Nc3 e6 3.Nge2 a6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 e6 3. Nge2
{ This venomous move itself doesn't reveal much - White might still play both g3 and d4. The white knight on e2 is a little more passive than on f3 but on the other hand, it doesn't close the light-squared bishop's gaze on g2, and at the same time, a potential pin with Black's ...Bg4 doesn't seem so annoying anymore. }
3... a6 4. g3
{ We will analyze the idea which involves delaying the d4 push, otherwise after White's d4, Black takes the pawn, and we simply transpose to other chapters . }
4... b5
{ Black wants to position his light-squared bishop on b7 as quickly as possible, applying pressure against White's center. Again, if White plays d4, Black is ready to transpose to other chapters.   4...d5?!  this is not quite the same as in Chapter 6.  5.exd5  exd5  6.d4  the inclusion of Nge2 and ...a6 favors White, plus the white bishop on g2 will be immediately applying pressure against the black pawn on d5. }
5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O { 6.d4  cxd4  7.Nxd4  Nf6  this transposes to Chapter 9. }
6... Nc6
{ This is a typical idea in the Sicilian Kan, and exactly with this order of the moves so that Black can capture the white knight on d4 and not White on c6. }
7. Re1
{ White is smart and plays it out in a tricky way. After this move, Black once again has to be careful with the incoming threats - develop the queenside first. }
7... Rc8
{ A good move, remaining alert of White's tactical ideas. If White keeps toying with the ideas too much with some slow preparation moves, Black eventually will bring out the kingside pieces. Think about this order of the moves - ...Be7, ...d6, ...Nf6 and castle short. }
8. a4
{ The inclusion of the a-pawn push usually is linked with the idea to play Nd5 next, so Black has weakened some squares at the queenside.   8.Nf4  If White wants to play e5 or Nd5, you can stop both threats at the same time.  8...d6  Now White's Nd5 is not a threat anymore, the d4 push is impossible so Black will bring out the remaining kingside pieces, probably starting with the bishop. }
8... b4 9. Nd5 Na5
{ Of course, don't take the knight, as opening the e-file so early will lead to a disaster. With this odd knight jump to the edge of the board, Black is already thinking about taking the knight on d5 as the Black knight on a5 defends the bishop on b7 against the d6 tactical tricks. All of this pretty much forces the intruder knight to retreat.  As an alternative, you can consider playing  9...Bd6  but then after the knight retreats to e3 and later to c4 you might experience some minor annoyances with the active white knight. }
10. Ne3
{ 10.d4?!  Is tempting, but White would be making very big risks.  10...exd5  11.exd5  Be7  12.Nf4  Kf8  13.dxc5  Bxc5  It's not very clear how White is going to continue the attack - the piece is missing after all. }
10... Nf6 11. d3 d6
{ Black has a fine position and will castle short in a moment. The black knight on a5 is also controlling the c4-square where the white knight might be heading. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Closed Sicilian"]
[Black "2.Nc3 e6 3.Nge2 a6 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 e6 3. Nge2
{ This venomous move itself doesn't reveal much - White might still play both g3 and d4. The white knight on e2 is a little more passive than on f3 but on the other hand, it doesn't close the light-squared bishop's gaze on g2, and at the same time, a potential pin with Black's ...Bg4 doesn't seem so annoying anymore. }
3... a6 4. g3
{ We will analyze the idea which involves delaying the d4 push, otherwise after White's d4, Black takes the pawn, and we simply transpose to other chapters . }
4... b5
{ Black wants to position his light-squared bishop on b7 as quickly as possible, applying pressure against White's center. Again, if White plays d4, Black is ready to transpose to other chapters.   4...d5?!  this is not quite the same as in Chapter 6.  5.exd5  exd5  6.d4  the inclusion of Nge2 and ...a6 favors White, plus the white bishop on g2 will be immediately applying pressure against the black pawn on d5. }
5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O { 6.d4  cxd4  7.Nxd4  Nf6  this transposes to Chapter 9. }
6... Nc6
{ This is a typical idea in the Sicilian Kan, and exactly with this order of the moves so that Black can capture the white knight on d4 and not White on c6. }
7. Re1
{ White is smart and plays it out in a tricky way. After this move, Black once again has to be careful with the incoming threats - develop the queenside first. }
7... Rc8
{ A good move, remaining alert of White's tactical ideas. If White keeps toying with the ideas too much with some slow preparation moves, Black eventually will bring out the kingside pieces. Think about this order of the moves - ...Be7, ...d6, ...Nf6 and castle short. }
8. Nd5
{ A standard sacrifice - you don't have to take the knight as White is not threatening with anything. This is also the reason why Black is developing the queenside first, being a little flexible with the kingside development.   8.d4  simply transposes to a covered line with a different move order.  8...cxd4  9.Nxd4  Nxd4  10.Qxd4  f6  , with all the non-traditional ideas after it! }
8... Bd6
{ Capturing the knight already is a threat as White will lose access to his typical d6 thrust.   8...Na5?!  with the a4-pawn push not having included, the Black knight on a5 can be a subject of an important tempo. Here's a sample line of the gambit approach that White can take.  9.d4!  exd5  10.exd5  Be7  . Although the knight on a5 protects the bishop on b7 and thus the immediate d6 push does not work, White can improve the threat.  11.Nf4  Kf8  12.Bd2  . The difference here is that the black pawn does not stand on b4, protecting the knight. Despite the material advantage, suddenly Black has to lead a difficult defense. }
9. Ne3 Nf6
{ If you are concerned, what is your bishop doing on d6, ask the same question to the white knight on e3. }
10. f4 Be7
{ It's ok to accept a loss of the tempo - White did the same with his knight. }
11. d3 { 11.e5  Ng8  is quite a strange setup for White. } 11... O-O
{ Black will create a counterplay at the queenside. Don't be intimidated by aggressive white pawn pushes at the kingside and simply ask yourself - can your opponent checkmate you with just 3 pawns? Don't touch the kingside pawns and focus on the queenside. }
