[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Closed Sicilian"]
[Black "2.Nc3 e6 3.Nge2 a6 #4 | Informational 9...Ne7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 e6 3. Nge2
{ This venomous move itself doesn't reveal much - White might still play both g3 and d4. The white knight on e2 is a little more passive than on f3 but on the other hand, it doesn't close the light-squared bishop's gaze on g2, and at the same time, a potential pin with Black's ...Bg4 doesn't seem so annoying anymore. }
3... a6 4. g3
{ We will analyze the idea which involves delaying the d4 push, otherwise after White's d4, Black takes the pawn, and we simply transpose to other chapters . }
4... b5
{ Black wants to position his light-squared bishop on b7 as quickly as possible, applying pressure against White's center. Again, if White plays d4, Black is ready to transpose to other chapters.   4...d5?!  this is not quite the same as in Chapter 6.  5.exd5  exd5  6.d4  the inclusion of Nge2 and ...a6 favors White, plus the white bishop on g2 will be immediately applying pressure against the black pawn on d5. }
5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O { 6.d4  cxd4  7.Nxd4  Nf6  this transposes to Chapter 9. }
6... Nc6
{ This is a typical idea in the Sicilian Kan, and exactly with this order of the moves so that Black can capture the white knight on d4 and not White on c6. }
7. d4 { White transposes to the Open Sicilian. } 7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nxd4
{ Black's principle in general for such kinds of positions is - if possible, take on d4 yourself. The white queen on d4 may feel active but it will be subject for you to win some tempi. }
9. Qxd4 Ne7
{ This is the most played move in the position so far and quite typical for Sicilian Kan / Paulsen setups, transporting the knight to c6, thus getting rid of the queen from d4 and finishing the development at the kingside. There's something that we don't like about it and we have a feeling that it's played a little too early. }
10. a4 { White starts to force matters. } 10... Nc6 11. Qd1
{ Retreating with the queen to e3 is a decent alternative, preparing the Nd5 threat and thus controlling the c5 and b6-squares. }
11... b4 12. Nd5 Bc5
{ Again, Black can't take the knight as the opened e-file will deliver bad news. }
13. Qg4 { Suddenly Black has difficulties protecting the pawn on g7. } 13... h5
{ A typical trick in the Sicilian - Black offers the pawn on g7 'for free'.   13...O-O  14.Bh6  Bd4  with this extravagant move, Black protects the g7-pawn.   An alternative is  14...g6  , giving up an exchange for very unclear compensation.  15.c3  bxc3  16.bxc3  Be5  This was played in Firouzja, A. @@StartBracket@@2728@@EndBracket@@ - Artemiev, V. @@StartBracket@@2716@@EndBracket@@ Nations Cup Online Prelim 2020. White's game can be improved.  17.Rab1!  Rb8  18.f4  This is what Firouzja played in the game, but not including Rb1.  18...Bf6  19.Nb6  White is dominating the board and the e5-pawn push looks very menacing. }
14. Qxg7 Bd4
{ Because the white knight on d5 is still under attack, this line is quite forced. }
15. Qg5 Qxg5 16. Bxg5 exd5 17. exd5
{ It's not clear where the black knight should retreat, to d8 or a7, but White will play Re1+ next and with a small trick collect the third pawn for the piece. }
17... Na7 18. Rfe1+ Kf8 19. Be7+ Kg7 20. Bxb4
{ Since White has three pawns, more space, and Black's minor pieces on the queenside look weird, White's position should be preferred. }
