{ A multi-purpose move - Black still wants to play ...Ne7 but would like to see what White will do first. Because Black managed to play ...Nxd4 earlier and thus keep the bishop on b7, in many variations White's Nd5 will be less dangerous. Perhaps in some lesser variations, you might be threatening to win the c2-pawn but you can't choose it over development. Here White has several potential ideas. }
10. Re1
{ This move can be very annoying - clearly White is thinking about playing Nd5 next, also after  10...Ne7  . Black's  10...Nf6  will be met with  11.e5  , forcing Black to go into a defense early on. There's a way to get some excitement here with an unusual plan. }
10... f6
{ You saw it right! Black wants to play ...Bc5 next and only then develop the knight as the pawn on g7 now is protected. Despite the awkward nature of the move, White can't exploit it as also the planned Nd5 loses power due to more escape routes for the black king. }
11. Be3
{ It seems that White has to include this move and combat the active black bishop on c5. If White will try to open the queenside with a4, close it with ...b4. }
11... Bc5 12. Qd2 Bxe3 13. Qxe3 Nh6
{ It's possible to develop the knight on e7 as well. If White will double the rooks at the d-file to bother Black's pawn on d7, the black bishop easily defends it on c6-square. }
14. a4 O-O
{ Normally we'd like to respond with ...b4, but here the black pawn on b4 will be weaker than b5. }
15. axb5 axb5
{ The position is double-edged. White's open a-file doesn't give him an advantage. }
