1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 e6 3. Nge2
{ This venomous move itself doesn't reveal much - White might still play both g3 and d4. The white knight on e2 is a little more passive than on f3 but on the other hand, it doesn't close the light-squared bishop's gaze on g2, and at the same time, a potential pin with Black's ...Bg4 doesn't seem so annoying anymore. }
3... a6 4. g3
{ We will analyze the idea which involves delaying the d4 push, otherwise after White's d4, Black takes the pawn, and we simply transpose to other chapters . }
4... b5
{ Black wants to position his light-squared bishop on b7 as quickly as possible, applying pressure against White's center. Again, if White plays d4, Black is ready to transpose to other chapters.   4...d5?!  this is not quite the same as in Chapter 6.  5.exd5  exd5  6.d4  the inclusion of Nge2 and ...a6 favors White, plus the white bishop on g2 will be immediately applying pressure against the black pawn on d5. }
5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O { 6.d4  cxd4  7.Nxd4  Nf6  this transposes to Chapter 9. }
6... Nc6
{ This is a typical idea in the Sicilian Kan, and exactly with this order of the moves so that Black can capture the white knight on d4 and not White on c6. }
7. d4 { White transposes to the Open Sicilian. } 7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nxd4
{ Black's principle in general for such kinds of positions is - if possible, take on d4 yourself. The white queen on d4 may feel active but it will be subject for you to win some tempi. }
9. Qxd4 Rc8
{ A multi-purpose move - Black still wants to play ...Ne7 but would like to see what White will do first. Because Black managed to play ...Nxd4 earlier and thus keep the bishop on b7, in many variations White's Nd5 will be less dangerous. Perhaps in some lesser variations, you might be threatening to win the c2-pawn but you can't choose it over development. Here White has several potential ideas. }
10. Be3
{ If White continues development by this natural move, it also closes the e-file and makes any potential sacrifices with Nd5 less likely to happen. This probably also means that he's preparing to play a4 next, trying to open the queenside. }
10... Ne7 11. a4
{ Or  11.Qd2  Nc6  12.a4  - it's the same but with different order of moves. }
11... Nc6
{ Black pushes away the white queen from the d4-square but there are two retreats - b6 or d2. }
12. Qd2 { A more logical retreat than  12.Qb6  . } 12... b4
{ Obviously, Black wants to keep the queenside closed. } 13. Na2 Ne5
{ Black is going after White's dark-squared bishop thus he doesn't have much of a choice. }
14. b3 a5
{ It's a good idea to keep an eye on White's c3 idea to free the 'imprisoned' knight on a2. Here, it's risky as Black could just take the pawn and continue with ...Bb4. }
15. Rfd1 Rc6
{ A very ambitious move! Black prepares a battery to target the c2-pawn and also takes extra care of the d6-square. }
16. Bd4 Rd6 { Black frees the c6-square for the knight. } 17. c3 Nc6
{ Black finally achieves what he wanted - eliminate White's dark-squared bishop. }
18. Qe2 Nxd4 19. cxd4 Qb6
{ Here we can stop the analysis - Black has a nice position with no visible weaknesses while the white knight is stuck on a2.   Here's how the game might continue:  20.d5  Be7  21.e5  White temporarily wins an exchange.  21...Rxd5  22.Bxd5  Bxd5  23.Rxd5  is a good and practical choice, otherwise, that light-squared bishop will create White a lot of problems in the long term.  23...exd5  24.Rd1  O-O  25.Rxd5  Rc8  26.Qd1  Bc5  .  As long as Black focuses on active plans and doesn't worry too much about some simple things like a weak pawn on d7, you are on the right path. }
