5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O { 6.d4  cxd4  7.Nxd4  Nf6  this transposes to Chapter 9. }
6... Nc6
{ This is a typical idea in the Sicilian Kan, and exactly with this order of the moves so that Black can capture the white knight on d4 and not White on c6. }
7. d4 { White transposes to the Open Sicilian. } 7... cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nxd4
{ Black's principle in general for such kinds of positions is - if possible, take on d4 yourself. The white queen on d4 may feel active but it will be subject for you to win some tempi. }
9. Qxd4 Rc8
{ A multi-purpose move - Black still wants to play ...Ne7 but would like to see what White will do first. Because Black managed to play ...Nxd4 earlier and thus keep the bishop on b7, in many variations White's Nd5 will be less dangerous. Perhaps in some lesser variations, you might be threatening to win the c2-pawn but you can't choose it over development. Here White has several potential ideas. }
