9. Qxd4 Rc8
{ A multi-purpose move - Black still wants to play ...Ne7 but would like to see what White will do first. Because Black managed to play ...Nxd4 earlier and thus keep the bishop on b7, in many variations White's Nd5 will be less dangerous. Perhaps in some lesser variations, you might be threatening to win the c2-pawn but you can't choose it over development. Here White has several potential ideas. }
10. Bf4
{ White is waving a red flag - Qa7 next is incoming! Because of the White bishop on f4, Black can't play ...Qc7. In some variations, White might be fighting for the d6-square but it's not so important as he can't capitalize on it. If White could trade the dark-squared bishops and position his knight on d6, that would be a dominating position but we don't see how White can achieve it. }
10... Rc4
{ Black with a tempo frees the c8-square for the black queen and thus solves the problem of Qa7. }
11. Qd3
{ 11.Qa7?!  not a huge mistake but it's not clear what White is going to do next  11...Qc8  12.Be3?  that's just being stubborn  12...Ne7  . }
11... Qc8
{ A smart move - Black strengthens control of the queenside first before finishing development of the kingside which still is very flexible. White also has to understand if Black's ...b4 is a threat or not. }
12. a4
{ Opening of the queenside for White seems to be principled, even if it seemingly costs a pawn. After all, White is ahead in development. After anything else less ambitious like  12.Rad1  Black can just continue development of the kingside with moves ...Ne7-g6 or perhaps ...Nf6 right away, keeping an eye on White's e5. }
12... b4 13. Nb1
{ White is clearly not ready to play Nd5 this time but that doesn't mean that the fight is over. With the last retreat White is preparing to play Nd2 and b3 next, fighting for the weakened dark squares in Black's position. }
13... Ne7
{ It's time to develop the kingside.   13...Rxc2?  there have to be moments when your intuition says - alright, this is too much. This doesn't mean that you can't speculate with the pawn grab at some point but be very careful. Also, White will have to understand if it even works!  14.Nc3  Rxb2  15.Nb5!  axb5  16.Rfc1  It does not even feel that Black has an extra piece - White is about to crush Black. That's why you develop in the opening!  16...Bc5  17.Be3  d6  18.Bd4  Nf6  19.Bxb2  Black is lost. }
14. Nd2 Rc6
{ Again, taking the pawn on c2 is extremely risky as it opens the c-file. } 15.
Be5
{ An experienced player would probably understand that the d6 square is not going to hold, so he would try to slow down Black's development. }
15... Ng6 16. Bd4 f6
{ Black protects the g7 square wants to play ...Ne5 and is still pressing the c2 square. Quite a lot for White to think about. }
17. a5
{ Probably White should go until the end and give up the pawn, otherwise, he starts reacting against Black's threats. }
17... Ne5 18. Qe3 Rxc2
{ Remember when we said that at some point you might grab the pawn after all? This is the moment! Again, it's important to understand - it can't be your goal to win the pawn at the start, however, it's nice to pressure it and keep your opponent guessing, what to choose or when you will take it. Black could also ignore the pawn for longer and simply continue development. }
