{ 11.Qa7?!  not a huge mistake but it's not clear what White is going to do next  11...Qc8  12.Be3?  that's just being stubborn  12...Ne7  . }
11... Qc8
{ A smart move - Black strengthens control of the queenside first before finishing development of the kingside which still is very flexible. White also has to understand if Black's ...b4 is a threat or not. }
12. a4
{ Opening of the queenside for White seems to be principled, even if it seemingly costs a pawn. After all, White is ahead in development. After anything else less ambitious like  12.Rad1  Black can just continue development of the kingside with moves ...Ne7-g6 or perhaps ...Nf6 right away, keeping an eye on White's e5. }
12... b4 13. Nb1
{ White is clearly not ready to play Nd5 this time but that doesn't mean that the fight is over. With the last retreat White is preparing to play Nd2 and b3 next, fighting for the weakened dark squares in Black's position. }
13... Ne7
{ It's time to develop the kingside.   13...Rxc2?  there have to be moments when your intuition says - alright, this is too much. This doesn't mean that you can't speculate with the pawn grab at some point but be very careful. Also, White will have to understand if it even works!  14.Nc3  Rxb2  15.Nb5!  axb5  16.Rfc1  It does not even feel that Black has an extra piece - White is about to crush Black. That's why you develop in the opening!  16...Bc5  17.Be3  d6  18.Bd4  Nf6  19.Bxb2  Black is lost. }
14. Nd2 Rc6
{ Again, taking the pawn on c2 is extremely risky as it opens the c-file. } 15.
Bd6
{ The obvious choice - White wants to control the d6 square but it's only temporary. }
15... Ng6 16. Bxf8 Rxf8
{ Not a bad trade for you - White made three tempos to make it happen while Black's dark-squared bishop did not make any move at all. Loss of the castling option is insignificant as White is unable to exploit it. }
17. Rac1 f6
{ Black is considering making an artificial castle but keeping the king on e7 might work as well. }
18. Qd4 a5 19. Nb3 Qc7 20. f4 Ke7
{ White is simply unable to open the position in a way to endanger the Black king. Black's chances in the middlegame are just as good as White's. If possible, trade queens to make White's weaknesses more vulnerable, most notably, on c2.   20...Kf7?  Removing the king from the center makes the d-pawn more vulnerable, and then there's a tactic.  21.Nxa5!  Qxa5  22.Qxd7+  . Don't miss it! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Closed Sicilian"]
[Black "2.Nc3 e6 3.Nge2 a6  #19"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 e6 3. Nge2
{ This venomous move itself doesn't reveal much - White might still play both g3 and d4. The white knight on e2 is a little more passive than on f3 but on the other hand, it doesn't close the light-squared bishop's gaze on g2, and at the same time, a potential pin with Black's ...Bg4 doesn't seem so annoying anymore. }
3... a6 4. g3
{ We will analyze the idea which involves delaying the d4 push, otherwise after White's d4, Black takes the pawn, and we simply transpose to other chapters . }
4... b5
{ Black wants to position his light-squared bishop on b7 as quickly as possible, applying pressure against White's center. Again, if White plays d4, Black is ready to transpose to other chapters.   4...d5?!  this is not quite the same as in Chapter 6.  5.exd5  exd5  6.d4  the inclusion of Nge2 and ...a6 favors White, plus the white bishop on g2 will be immediately applying pressure against the black pawn on d5. }
5. Bg2 Bb7 6. O-O { 6.d4  cxd4  7.Nxd4  Nf6  this transposes to Chapter 9. }
6... Nc6 7. d3
{ White might insist on the Closed Sicilian but then the knight on e2, in general, is not placed well. }
7... Qc7
{ First, Black sends some additional help for the central squares and then carefully brings out the kingside pieces. White still might change his mind and push d4. }
8. f4 g6
{ An interesting idea - Black wants to play ...f5 and slow down White's expansion on the kingside. Castling long is definitely an option if White gets carried away on the kingside. }
9. f5
{ White might push forward the f-pawn but Black can carefully continue development. }
9... Bg7 10. Qe1 Nf6
{ The white knight on e2 is clearly misplaced for this kind of action. } *

