[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Closed Sicilian"]
[Black "3.Nf3 a6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 e6 3. Nf3
{ White could try to be tricky and toy with the ideas of switching to Open Sicilian with d4. It's a good idea to avoid wandering into unfamiliar positions but reach something that you've studied in the course. }
3... a6 { If White will play d4, we will get the Sicilian Kan positions. } 4.
g3
{ An interesting move order to go for the Closed Sicilian. This is not necessarily great for White as the knight blocks the advancement of the f-pawn.  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  b5  transposes to variations we covered later on. }
4... b5 5. Bg2 Bb7
{ Black already is threatening to play ...b4 and grab the pawn. } 6. O-O
{ White can try to sacrifice the pawn on  e4  to accelerate his initiative. The way we played out the opening, we have to take the pawn.  6.d4  cxd4  7.Nxd4  Nf6  transposes to Chapter 9. }
6... b4 7. Na4 Bxe4 8. d4
{ Naturally, White is opening the position to use the lead in development. }
8... cxd4 9. Qxd4 Nf6 10. Bg5
{ Here, Black has several ways how to continue but the next move seems to be the simplest. }
10... Bb7
{ Black wants to play ...Nc6 and ...Qa5 to challenge the knight on a4. And, if possible, ...Be7 and castle short next. }
11. Rfd1 { White is going after the pawn on d7. } 11... Nc6 12. Qe3
{ The only way to keep the Nb6 threat alive. } 12... Qa5
{ White's attack stops as there is no Nb6 anymore. } *

