[Black "3.Nf3 a6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 e6 3. Nf3
{ White could try to be tricky and toy with the ideas of switching to Open Sicilian with d4. It's a good idea to avoid wandering into unfamiliar positions but reach something that you've studied in the course. }
3... a6 { If White will play d4, we will get the Sicilian Kan positions. } 4.
g3
{ An interesting move order to go for the Closed Sicilian. This is not necessarily great for White as the knight blocks the advancement of the f-pawn.  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  b5  transposes to variations we covered later on. }
4... b5 5. Bg2 Bb7
{ Black already is threatening to play ...b4 and grab the pawn. } 6. d3
{ For the sake of Closed Sicilian and a potential King's Indian attack, White has to play this move sooner or later. The other real option is only open Sicilian.  6.d4  cxd4  7.Nxd4  Nf6  transposes to Chapter 9. }
6... d6
{ Black prepares to play ...Nf6 next, so that White can't push away the knight with e5. }
7. O-O Nf6
{ White has some choices but all of them are linked with pushing the kingside pawns. }
8. Nh4
{ This is an alternate way to free the way for the f-pawn but the white knight on h4 doesn't participate in the attack and will have to go back sooner or later. }
8... Nc6 9. f4 Be7
{ Black should calmly develop his pieces and look for the best moment to castle short. After all, White can't just checkmate you with a couple of pawns. }
10. f5 O-O 11. Ne2 { One way how White might want to get to the e6-pawn. }
11... e5 12. Nc3 c4
{ White is losing time to establish an outpost on d5. Black is very active on the queenside. }
