[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7) Closed Sicilian"]
[Black "3.g3 d5 4.Bg2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 e6 3. g3
{ The start of the Closed Sicilian. White wants to fianchetto the light-squared bishop on g2 and then decide, what to do next. He might play in the spirit of King's Indian attack, playing next d3 and organizing a kingside initiative or switch to an Open Sicilian with d4. }
3... d5
{ If you can solve your problems right away, do it. First, this approach is very similar to what we proposed to play in Chapter 6 @@StartBracket@@the only difference is that instead of Nc3 White had Nf3@@EndBracket@@ and it's a very good idea to have the same battle plan against several similar setups. Second, with an open center, it's easier to find simpler @@StartBracket@@if not the strongest@@EndBracket@@ decisions. }
4. Bg2 Nf6
{ For the sake of simplicity, we suggest you transpose to the main line. However, if you feel ambitious, nobody's stopping you to explore  4...d4  , with an idea to play ...e5 next and King's Indian with colors reversed and following moves like ...Nc6, ...Bd6 and ...Nge7. }
5. e5
{ White can close the center and focus on the kingside initiative but this is relatively harmless.   5.exd5  can also transpose to some of the covered lines with different move orders.  5...exd5  6.d3  d4  7.Ne4  Nxe4  and so on. }
5... Nfd7 6. f4 Nc6 7. Nf3
{ For this type of position, one can't dodge the feeling that the white knight on c3 has been developed too early. }
7... Be7 8. O-O Rb8
{ Black organizes an offensive on the queenside while White is trying to build something on the kingside. }
9. a4 O-O
{ It's possible to postpone castling and focus on the queenside but there's nothing wrong with the move. }
10. d4
{ Not mandatory, White can also opt for  10.d3  but Black's response will be the same. }
10... a6 11. Ne2 b5 12. axb5 axb5
{ As long as Black is keeping an eye on the incoming f5 threat, there will be no surprises. }
13. Kh1 b4 14. Be3 Bb7
{ White has not yet created anything on the kingside while the queenside is wide open and Black is about to create his first serious threats. Don't touch your kingside pawns as that will only accelerate White's plan and create new targets. }
*

