[Black "3.g3 d5 4.Bg2 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 e6 3. g3
{ The start of the Closed Sicilian. White wants to fianchetto the light-squared bishop on g2 and then decide, what to do next. He might play in the spirit of King's Indian attack, playing next d3 and organizing a kingside initiative or switch to an Open Sicilian with d4. }
3... d5
{ If you can solve your problems right away, do it. First, this approach is very similar to what we proposed to play in Chapter 6 @@StartBracket@@the only difference is that instead of Nc3 White had Nf3@@EndBracket@@ and it's a very good idea to have the same battle plan against several similar setups. Second, with an open center, it's easier to find simpler @@StartBracket@@if not the strongest@@EndBracket@@ decisions. }
4. Bg2 Nf6
{ For the sake of simplicity, we suggest you transpose to the main line. However, if you feel ambitious, nobody's stopping you to explore  4...d4  , with an idea to play ...e5 next and King's Indian with colors reversed and following moves like ...Nc6, ...Bd6 and ...Nge7. }
5. d3 { Too slow and with no ambition. } 5... dxe4
{ Simple and good. A more complex and perhaps also ambitious approach would be  5...d4  and the arising King's Indian structure with colors reversed. }
6. Nxe4 Nxe4 7. Bxe4 Be7
{ Unless Black will seriously misplay it, he can never get a worse position after the opening. The pawn structure dictates that White should do something about the d4-square, otherwise Black eventually will get there a knight. Once White plays c3, this weakens the d3-pawn. Black should just slightly carefully develop the pieces and avoid unnecessary complications like playing an early ...Nc6 and allowing White to give up his strong light-squared bishop but forever damaging Black's pawn structure. }
8. Ne2
{ There's no actual theory here and we will just illustrate a potential follow-up. }
8... Qb6 9. O-O O-O 10. Nf4 Bd7
{ Black is toying with ideas to bring on c6 the bishop first so that it's not passive on d7. The problem - once on c6, White is not obliged to take it, and Black is not interested to take on e4. }
11. Qh5 h6 12. Qe2 Nc6 13. c3 Rad8 14. Be3 Qa6
{ Black would like to establish some pressure on the weakened pawn on d3. The bishop on d7 is only temporarily passive. The position remains equal but there is something to work with. }
