{ If White plays this logical move first, this pretty much means that he's missed his best opportunity to go after the d4-pawn push. }
5... Nf6
{ Before pushing forward the d-pawn, Black first fights for the d5 and e4-squares. }
6. d3 { A little modest but what else? } 6... d4
{ Good timing! Black is not going to wait for White to play Bg5. Now thanks to the inclusion of ...Nf6, the white knight can't occupy the d5 square and has to settle for less. }
7. Ne4 Nxe4 8. dxe4
{ A more ambitious approach to organizing a pawn majority at the kingside but White is seriously risking getting a worse position. Black has no weaknesses, has a healthy development, and has grabbed the center. }
8... Nc6 9. Ne2 Bd6
{ Black already is playing the position 'as White' - seeking an advantage. }
10. O-O O-O 11. f4
{ Seemingly an aggressive continuation, this only creates more problems at White's camp. White's army is not coordinated well and this comes at the wrong moment. }
11... Be6 12. e5 Bc7
{ Thanks to the very unfortunate knight on e2 and the passive bishop on c1, White is much worse. Black will make a well-timed ...f6 breakthrough to open the position and claim a big advantage. }
*

