[White "7) Closed Sicilian"]
[Black "5.d4 cxd4 6.Qxd4 #8 | Alternative 7...Nc6 *1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 e6 3. g3
{ The start of the Closed Sicilian. White wants to fianchetto the light-squared bishop on g2 and then decide, what to do next. He might play in the spirit of King's Indian attack, playing next d3 and organizing a kingside initiative or switch to an Open Sicilian with d4. }
3... d5
{ If you can solve your problems right away, do it. First, this approach is very similar to what we proposed to play in Chapter 6 @@StartBracket@@the only difference is that instead of Nc3 White had Nf3@@EndBracket@@ and it's a very good idea to have the same battle plan against several similar setups. Second, with an open center, it's easier to find simpler @@StartBracket@@if not the strongest@@EndBracket@@ decisions. }
4. exd5
{ Seemingly a necessary move for White as the alternatives give many choices for Black. }
4... exd5
{ Now there's a fair chance that the position will transpose to one of the variations of Chapter 6. }
5. d4
{ Pushing forward the d-pawn must be the critical choice, otherwise Black will play an early ...d4 himself, thus having a lot of space for the pieces and avoiding a position with an isolated pawn. }
5... cxd4
{ If we're inevitably going to get an isolated pawn on d5, it's best to have the White queen on d4 as it can be used to win tempi.   5...Nc6  If Black once again tries to transpose to the lines of Chapter 6, this time due to the specific order of the moves, it won't work.  6.Be3!  The strongest move for White - now the arising positions are not the same. What has options to vary between Bg2 and Nge2-Nf3 plans.  6...cxd4  7.Bxd4  Nge7  8.Bg2  Nf5  9.Nf3  White has an advantage. }
6. Qxd4 Nf6
{ Black wants to play ...Nc6 again thus White has to react quickly. } 7. Bg5
{ The most principled choice - White has created a pin and wants to castle long to win the pawn on d5. We're undecided what to offer you as both continuations look fun but decided to leave the most played continuation as the main suggestion as it's easier to learn and might save you some time. }
7... Nc6
{ This continuation is less explored and the lines tend to be more complex and longer, albeit we already reduced them to a normal length just to illustrate some ideas. How practical it's to learn them, judge yourself! White has several responses here. }
8. Bb5 { This pin together with an earlier g3 makes a strange impression. }
8... Be7 9. Bxf6
{ 9.O-O-O  is a risky choice.  9...O-O  10.Qa4  Be6  11.Nf3  h6  The white king is more vulnerable and the queen is stuck on a4. Black will be faster with creating real threats. }
9... Bxf6 10. Qc5
{ White does not allow the black king to castle and still is pressuring the d5-pawn. There's more than one good continuation for Black, but the following is the simplest. }
10... Bxc3+ 11. bxc3 Qe7+ 12. Qxe7+ Kxe7 { The position is equal. } *

