[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) 3.Qe2 & 3.d3"]
[Black "Anti-Sicilian 3.Qe2 Nc6 4.c3 e5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. Qe2
{ This awkward-looking move has its perks if White is aiming for a closed French setup - assuming that Black at some point pushes forward the traditional ...d5. Then the white queenside knight is not heading to the traditional d2-square to defend the e4-pawn, giving White more options. White's light-squared bishop is still going to g2. }
3... Nc6 4. c3
{ White wants to grab the center with d4 - probably it's possible to play this but with the current move order and the white queen on e2, it looks just a little weird. }
4... e5
{ Given the fact that the white queen is already on e2, this move makes the most sense. If White will try to play a gambit with early d4 thrust, just accept the pawn. }
5. Qe3
{ Or  5.g3  g6  , followed by ...Bg7, ...d6, and the typical setup for Black. With this rare move, White is hinting at the d4 thrust, however, he might reconsider developing the light-squared bishop on c4, since the d5-square now is weakened.   5.Na3  White might try to improvise, applying some pressure against the pawn on e5 and a potential weak square on d6, but it's easy to defend.  5...g6  6.Nc4  d6  The only thing to watch out for here is if Black will play ...Bg7 a little too early - then Qd3 could be annoying, pressuring the pawn on d6. Instead, Black can start with ...Nf6. In some extreme circumstances, the king can go to e7 - it feels pretty well here, which can't be said about the white queen on d3. }
5... Nf6
{ 5...g6  Hoping to deliver a little trap after White's  6.d4  Bh6  is not a good idea.   6.Bc4  now Ng5 threat could be a little problem. }
6. d4 { Tactically, it doesn't work. } 6... cxd4 7. cxd4 exd4
{ Black's weakened pawn structure doesn't play a role here. } 8. Nxd4 Bc5 9.
Nxc6 Bxe3 10. Nxd8 Bxc1 { White loses material. } *

