[White "8) 3.Qe2 & 3.d3"]
[Black "Anti-Sicilian 3.Qe2 Nc6 4.b3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. Qe2
{ This awkward-looking move has its perks if White is aiming for a closed French setup - assuming that Black at some point pushes forward the traditional ...d5. Then the white queenside knight is not heading to the traditional d2-square to defend the e4-pawn, giving White more options. White's light-squared bishop is still going to g2. }
3... Nc6 4. b3
{ White wants to fianchetto both of his bishops. Since this is too slow, it can't cause Black any problems. }
4... d6 5. Bb2 e5
{ Black closes the long diagonal for the white bishop and will fianchetto his bishop on g7. }
6. g3 g6 7. Bg2 Bg7 8. O-O Nge7
{ Black's chances to make a successful breakthrough in the center are more real. }
9. c3 O-O 10. Na3
{ Cicak, S. @@StartBracket@@2537@@EndBracket@@ - Hillarp Persson, T. @@StartBracket@@2460@@EndBracket@@ Swedish Championship 2002. }
10... d5
{ A logical improvement over  10...f5  - then  11.Qc4+  and  --  12.Ng5  could become a problem. Black is just better due to better piece coordination and control of the center. If allowed, Black can close the center with ...d4, claiming some space advantage and a typical King's Indian position with colors reversed. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) 3.Qe2 & 3.d3"]
[Black "Anti-Sicilian 3.Qe2 Nc6 4.g3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. Qe2
{ This awkward-looking move has its perks if White is aiming for a closed French setup - assuming that Black at some point pushes forward the traditional ...d5. Then the white queenside knight is not heading to the traditional d2-square to defend the e4-pawn, giving White more options. White's light-squared bishop is still going to g2. }
3... Nc6 4. g3
{ Probably the most flexible move in the position - White fianchettoes the light-squared bishop on g2 and keeps all options open in the center. }
4... g6
{ If White can't respond to this maneuver with an immediate d4 push or prepare it in a near future, then go for it - Black's dark-squared bishop best stands on g7. Here the white queen already is on e2. }
5. h4
{ In some games White has tried this unusual move. The obvious idea is to open the h-file, activating the White rook right away. However, the real trick lies if Black would respond with the 'automatic'  5...h5  - then the weakness on g5 at some point could become critical. }
5... h6
{ Now Black is ready to respond to h5 push with ...g5, effectively closing the kingside. }
6. Bg2 Bg7 7. O-O e5
{ Black's setup remains the same - close the center and play ...Nge7. Notice that here it's White who has made himself a weakness on g4. }
8. a3 Nge7 9. c3
{ Morris, J. @@StartBracket@@2407@@EndBracket@@ - Smirnov, A. @@StartBracket@@2463@@EndBracket@@ Australasian Masters 2015. }
9... O-O { This feels like a natural improvement over the game. } 10. b4 d6
{ White should be already regretting having included h4 - Black can start active operations on the kingside while the center has been secured. }
*

