[Round "?"]
[White "8) 3.Qe2 & 3.d3"]
[Black "Anti-Sicilian 3.Qe2 Nc6 4.g3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. Qe2
{ This awkward-looking move has its perks if White is aiming for a closed French setup - assuming that Black at some point pushes forward the traditional ...d5. Then the white queenside knight is not heading to the traditional d2-square to defend the e4-pawn, giving White more options. White's light-squared bishop is still going to g2. }
3... Nc6 4. g3
{ Probably the most flexible move in the position - White fianchettoes the light-squared bishop on g2 and keeps all options open in the center. }
4... g6
{ If White can't respond to this maneuver with an immediate d4 push or prepare it in a near future, then go for it - Black's dark-squared bishop best stands on g7. Here the white queen already is on e2. }
5. Na3 { This early move changes nothing in Black's approach. } 5... Bg7 6. Nb5
{ Or  6.Nc4  - Black's response would be the same. } 6... d6 7. Qd3 Bf8
{ This move may feel awkward but the white knight will be pushed back from b5 and after that, the black bishop can return to g7. It is possible to play also  7...d5  but that involves sacrificing the pawn on d5 for some decent compensation. }
8. Bg2 a6 9. Na3 Bg7 { Things are back to normal for Black. } 10. O-O
{ If White would play  10.Nc4  , then  10...d5  is very strong. } 10... Nge7
11. Qe2 O-O 12. c3
{ Brustkern, J. @@StartBracket@@2227@@EndBracket@@ - Hirsch, A. @@StartBracket@@2069@@EndBracket@@ Vienna Open 2003. Here Black could have continued with the traditional plan. }
12... e5 13. d3 h6
{ Black gains control of the g5-square and is thinking about moves like ...Be6 and ...f5 next, with an active plan on the kingside. }
