{ Probably the most flexible move in the position - White fianchettoes the light-squared bishop on g2 and keeps all options open in the center. }
4... g6
{ If White can't respond to this maneuver with an immediate d4 push or prepare it in a near future, then go for it - Black's dark-squared bishop best stands on g7. Here the white queen already is on e2. }
5. Bg2 Bg7 6. O-O Nge7 7. d3 O-O 8. Nc3
{ This standard setup doesn't have any ambition to fight for the central squares. }
8... d6 9. Be3 Rb8
{ Black's setup is very common like in many closed Sicilian structures - aim for a queenside initiative. Probably it's ok also to immediately play ...e5 and pursue the traditional plan but with the white knight on c3 it feels a little awkward, albeit the weakness on d5 is rather insignificant. We suggest treating it like this - you can play ...e5 later whenever you feel, that the moment is right. For example, White is threatening to open the center with d4. }
10. a4 a6
{ When executing this move to prepare the ...b5 push, make sure that White can't play a5 which would stop the plan. }
11. Qd2
{ White not only is threatening to trade the dark-squared bishops but also push forward the d-pawn. }
11... e5
{ A good moment to close the center, plus Black should mind trading the dark-squared bishop. }
12. Bh6
{ Salinnikov, D. @@StartBracket@@2484@@EndBracket@@ - Kalashnikov, K. @@StartBracket@@2393@@EndBracket@@ Russian Cup 1999. }
12... f6
{ This is a logical improvement - Black is preparing to trade the dark-squared bishops and also secure the g5-square to play ...Be6 next. }
13. Bxg7 Kxg7
{ Black controls the game - he can resume the original idea of the ...b5 push or first take care of the kingside. Moves like ...Be6 and ... Qd7 make a lot of sense here. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) 3.Qe2 & 3.d3"]
[Black "Anti-Sicilian 3.Qe2 Nc6 4.g3 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. Qe2
{ This awkward-looking move has its perks if White is aiming for a closed French setup - assuming that Black at some point pushes forward the traditional ...d5. Then the white queenside knight is not heading to the traditional d2-square to defend the e4-pawn, giving White more options. White's light-squared bishop is still going to g2. }
3... Nc6 4. g3
{ Probably the most flexible move in the position - White fianchettoes the light-squared bishop on g2 and keeps all options open in the center. }
4... g6
{ If White can't respond to this maneuver with an immediate d4 push or prepare it in a near future, then go for it - Black's dark-squared bishop best stands on g7. Here the white queen already is on e2. }
5. Bg2 Bg7 6. O-O Nge7 7. e5
{ White could try to include this move before Black does it and sort of fight for the d6 and f6 squares, however, it doesn't pose any serious problems as the pawn on e5 won't stay. }
7... d6 { Eliminate the pawn, before White can strengthen it with c3-d4. } 8.
exd6 Qxd6 9. d3 O-O
{ Here the game is less forced - Black has several options at his disposal. One idea is to prepare ...b6 and ...Bb7 and a nice control of the central squares. }
10. Nbd2 Qc7 11. c3
{ Odinokov, N. @@StartBracket@@2349@@EndBracket@@ - Ulybin, M. @@StartBracket@@2562@@EndBracket@@ Russian Team Championship 2003. }
11... b6
{ Black will play next ...Bb7, ...Rad8 and try to pressure the d3 pawn. Any Nc4 moves with the incoming Bf4 threat can be answered with ...Nd5 while White's h4 push - with ...h6. }
