[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) 3.Qe2 & 3.d3"]
[Black "Anti-Sicilian 3.Qe2 Nc6 4.g3 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. Qe2
{ This awkward-looking move has its perks if White is aiming for a closed French setup - assuming that Black at some point pushes forward the traditional ...d5. Then the white queenside knight is not heading to the traditional d2-square to defend the e4-pawn, giving White more options. White's light-squared bishop is still going to g2. }
3... Nc6 4. g3
{ Probably the most flexible move in the position - White fianchettoes the light-squared bishop on g2 and keeps all options open in the center. }
4... g6
{ If White can't respond to this maneuver with an immediate d4 push or prepare it in a near future, then go for it - Black's dark-squared bishop best stands on g7. Here the white queen already is on e2. }
5. Bg2 Bg7 6. O-O Nge7 7. c3
{ White doesn't have a big choice here - he could start with  7.d3  but most likely it would just transpose to one of the lines. }
7... e5
{ A good moment to close the center, making White's life considerably more difficult. Keep the d-pawn on d7 for the moment as you could have a pleasant choice to play either ...d6 or ...d5 in one go. If you would play  7...d5  immediately, White could march past it with  8.e5  and achieve exactly what he wanted - an easy initiative on the kingside, using the dark squares. }
8. Na3
{ White could hurry with the knight's placement on c4 and strengthen it with a4. }
8... O-O
{ Keeping all options open - now after  9.Rd1  and some plans to go for the d4 pawn push, Black's  9...d5  would look like a perfect moment to counter-strike. }
9. Nc4 d6 10. a4
{ White has achieved what he wanted but Black has won the battle for the center.  10.Qd3  would be a mistake as after  10...b5  White can't take the pawn on d6 due to ...c4 threat and the knight is lost. }
10... h6 11. d3
{ Now again  11.Qd3  does not work, this time because of  11...Be6  and the same idea. }
11... Be6
{ The g5-square is secured so the bishop can go to e6. Black can prepare either ...f5 push or think about going for ...d5. }
