[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) 3.Qe2 & 3.d3"]
[Black "Anti-Sicilian 3.d3 Nc6 4.Nbd2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d3
{ We will explain to you what to do if White plays some sort of King's Indian attack or closed French position, involving g3, Bg2 and not going for the immediate d4 push. We decided to offer you dynamic positions which usually won't involve early ...d5 push.  The reason - after either White's Nbd2 or Qe2 and fianchettoing the light-squared bishop on g2, White eventually would close the center with e5 and enjoy an easy build-up and initiative on the kingside, with Black struggling for counterplay on the queenside.  The freshest example in this regard is the 2021 World Cup's quarterfinal game 3 between Sergey Karjakin and Sam Shankland. Engines like Black's position while for humans it's a little more difficult. }
3... Nc6 4. Nbd2
{ If the white knight goes to d2 early, this allows Black to fianchetto the dark-squared bishop on g7. Go for it if White can't counter-strike in the center with d4 and prepare it for execution in the next few moves. }
4... g6 5. g3
{ Here  5.Nc4  can't be good as Black can respond with the strong  5...d5  . }
5... Bg7 6. Bg2 Nge7 7. O-O O-O
{ The arising position is very similar, should White have played Qe2 earlier. }
8. Re1 d6 9. c3
{ It makes a lot of sense for White to fight for the center and use the queen on d1 which still can support the d4 pawn push. }
9... e5
{ Better earlier than later, otherwise White might consider playing a gambit with d4. }
10. a4
{ This would secure the white knight's outpost on c4 but make the center static. }
10... h6 11. Nc4 Be6
{ Black is feeling very comfortable, preparing the ...f5 push. } *

