[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "8) 3.Qe2 & 3.d3"]
[Black "Anti-Sicilian 3.d3 Nc6 4.g3 #1 | Informational 4...g6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d3
{ We will explain to you what to do if White plays some sort of King's Indian attack or closed French position, involving g3, Bg2 and not going for the immediate d4 push. We decided to offer you dynamic positions which usually won't involve early ...d5 push.  The reason - after either White's Nbd2 or Qe2 and fianchettoing the light-squared bishop on g2, White eventually would close the center with e5 and enjoy an easy build-up and initiative on the kingside, with Black struggling for counterplay on the queenside.  The freshest example in this regard is the 2021 World Cup's quarterfinal game 3 between Sergey Karjakin and Sam Shankland. Engines like Black's position while for humans it's a little more difficult. }
3... Nc6 4. g3 g6
{ Here's the nuance - The white queen still stands on d1 and the queenside knight has not yet been developed to d2. Thus after fianchettoing the bishop on g7, you will have to expect an early White's challenge for the center. }
5. Bg2 Bg7 6. O-O Nge7 { Black is trying to apply the same setup, as usual. }
7. c3
{ White can make the typical breakthrough in the center happen faster than usual. }
7... e5
{ Black stays true to the original plan.   7...d5   7...O-O  this position should lead to some kind of French structure with some dark-squares weaknesses around the black king.  8.d4  cxd4  9.cxd4  d5  10.e5  Although Black has opened the queenside to generate some counterplay, eventually, you will have to play ...f6 to break the center, further weakening the king. White's position seems to be preferable.  8.Qe2  White at some point later will push e5 and enjoy an easy game on the kingside - this type of position we recommend to avoid. }
8. a3 d6 9. b4
{ Remember White's positional threat to play b5? It also works here. } 9... a6
10. Be3 b6 11. Ra2
{ White is fast to push d4 and reposition his rook on d2 thus his position should be treated as better. }
