1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d3
{ We will explain to you what to do if White plays some sort of King's Indian attack or closed French position, involving g3, Bg2 and not going for the immediate d4 push. We decided to offer you dynamic positions which usually won't involve early ...d5 push.  The reason - after either White's Nbd2 or Qe2 and fianchettoing the light-squared bishop on g2, White eventually would close the center with e5 and enjoy an easy build-up and initiative on the kingside, with Black struggling for counterplay on the queenside.  The freshest example in this regard is the 2021 World Cup's quarterfinal game 3 between Sergey Karjakin and Sam Shankland. Engines like Black's position while for humans it's a little more difficult. }
3... Nc6 4. g3 d6
{ Black takes care of the e5-square and prepares to play ...Nf6 next. If something happens and White includes moves like Nbd2 or Qe2 next, Black might still consider playing ...g6 and fianchetto the dark-squared bishop on g7, as for White it will be much more difficult to grab the center with the d4 push. }
5. Bg2 Nf6 6. O-O Be7
{ Let's just keep it simple, the bishop stands on e7 fine as well. Now White has some choices but for Black, it's pretty straightforward - just castle short, aggressively push forward the queenside pawns and watch out what White is doing with the center.   6...g6  The problem with this move is that White can prepare to push d4 quickly, and Black can't stop it.  7.Nc3  Bg7   7...e5  would stop the d4 push threat, but now after  8.Nd2  , followed by moves like Nc4-e3 and f4, White's position looks great.  8.d4  cxd4  9.Nxd4  White has wasted a tempo on the d-pawn push but Black does have a weakness on d6. }
7. Re1
{ The most popular way how White protects the e4-pawn, preparing to play c3 and d4 next. Here the white queen on d1 supports the d-pawn push. }
7... O-O 8. Nbd2
{ This looks rather strange and can't cause Black any problems. The white knight is heading to c4. }
8... Rb8 9. a4 a6 10. e5 dxe5 11. Nxe5 Nxe5 12. Rxe5 b6
{ This is also equal - Black will trade the light-squared bishops. } *

