{ This can't be dangerous for Black - you have a healthy development and even if the position is inevitably leading to IQP @@StartBracket@@isolated queen's pawn position@@EndBracket@@, White's setup to meet it is not the best. The white pawn already stands on c3, not allowing White to increase pressure against the d5 pawn with Nc3. }
11. dxc5 Bxc5 12. Be3
{ White's dream position is to occupy the d4-square with a light piece and pressure the d5-pawn but that plan is difficult to make happen. }
12... Bxe3 13. Rxe3 Bf5
{ The main rule for Black - don't trade too many pieces and focus on active moves. If White plays Nd4, don't take on d4 yourself - allow White to take the knight on c6, which will fortify your central pawns position. After all, the black d-pawn is the only central pawn in the game. The position is just equal. }
