[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Open g3 With Nc3"]
[Black "Kan-Wing Attack 5.Nc3 b5 6.g3 #1 | Informational 6...Bb7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ Continuing to look at the setups with g3 and fianchettoing White's light-squared bishop to g2 - we will examine what to do if White plays Open Sicilian with the g3 setup, including Nc3. }
2... e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knights' potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways to pressure White's center. }
5. Nc3
{ It's time to move to the Open Sicilian Nc3 setups if White doesn't fianchetto the bishop on g2 but plays some central-based moves. We will examine some of the less-played moves before moving to the main continuation. }
5... b5
{ Black stays true to the spirit of the Kan - play ...b5 once the white knight stands on c3 so that the pawn on e4 is under early pressure. }
6. g3
{ It's also possible to reach this position with a different order of moves. This system is quite tricky - White positions his light-squared bishop to oppose Black's bishop on b7 and one of the most dangerous motifs that you will have to be aware of is the incoming e5 threat and the following intermezzo captures on f6 since the bishop on b7 will be under attack. }
6... Bb7
{ We would like to show you what happens if Black decides to press on the e4-pawn right away. }
7. Bg2 b4 8. Na4 Nf6
{ It seems very logical - the white pawn on e4 is under attack, and then there's the ...Qa5 threat, maybe Black can soon push ...d5. }
9. c4
{ Unfortunately for Black, White doesn't have to focus on protecting the pawn - welcome to modern chess! }
9... Bxe4
{ Otherwise, Black agrees to play a worse version of the Hedgehog, with the black pawn clearly weakened on b4, as it should have been on b6. }
10. Bxe4 Nxe4 11. Qf3 f5 12. g4
{ White develops a strong initiative very quickly. } 12... Qf6 13. Be3 g6 14.
O-O-O
{ White had a powerful attack in Yeletsky, I. @@StartBracket@@2422@@EndBracket@@ - Iljiushenok, I. @@StartBracket@@2534@@EndBracket@@ Nezhmetdinov Memorial 41st 2019. It's difficult to imagine where the black king will feel safe. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Open g3 With Nc3"]
[Black "Kan-Wing Attack 5.Nc3 b5 6.g3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ Continuing to look at the setups with g3 and fianchettoing White's light-squared bishop to g2 - we will examine what to do if White plays Open Sicilian with the g3 setup, including Nc3. }
2... e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knights' potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways to pressure White's center. }
5. Nc3
{ It's time to move to the Open Sicilian Nc3 setups if White doesn't fianchetto the bishop on g2 but plays some central-based moves. We will examine some of the less-played moves before moving to the main continuation. }
5... b5
{ Black stays true to the spirit of the Kan - play ...b5 once the white knight stands on c3 so that the pawn on e4 is under early pressure. }
6. g3
{ It's also possible to reach this position with a different order of moves. This system is quite tricky - White positions his light-squared bishop to oppose Black's bishop on b7 and one of the most dangerous motifs that you will have to be aware of is the incoming e5 threat and the following intermezzo captures on f6 since the bishop on b7 will be under attack. }
6... Nf6
{ Black plays a little trick - you can start also with  6...Bb7  , it doesn't matter much. }
7. e5
{ The trick is revealed in this line: White can push forward the central pawn, and the black knight has seemingly nowhere to go. }
7... Bb7 { First intermezzo move. } 8. Rg1 b4
{ And the second intermezzo move - this motif is very common for Sicilian Kan and Taimanov systems. Black pushes away the white knight to get access to the d5-square, avoiding the white knight landing on e4. }
9. exf6 { Seems to be principled. } 9... bxc3 10. fxg7 Bxg7 11. bxc3 Qc7
{ White has won a  pawn, but it's doubled and quite weak. Black will have it easier to bring the king to safety and then fight for the center. }
