[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ Continuing to look at the setups with g3 and fianchettoing White's light-squared bishop to g2 - we will examine what to do if White plays Open Sicilian with the g3 setup, including Nc3. }
2... e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knights' potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways to pressure White's center. }
5. Nc3
{ It's time to move to the Open Sicilian Nc3 setups if White doesn't fianchetto the bishop on g2 but plays some central-based moves. We will examine some of the less-played moves before moving to the main continuation. }
5... b5
{ Black stays true to the spirit of the Kan - play ...b5 once the white knight stands on c3 so that the pawn on e4 is under early pressure. }
6. g3
{ It's also possible to reach this position with a different order of moves. This system is quite tricky - White positions his light-squared bishop to oppose Black's bishop on b7 and one of the most dangerous motifs that you will have to be aware of is the incoming e5 threat and the following intermezzo captures on f6 since the bishop on b7 will be under attack. }
6... Nf6
{ Black plays a little trick - you can start also with  6...Bb7  , it doesn't matter much. }
7. Bg2 Bb7
{ Now White has several continuations but all of them are more or less harmless. Black's idea is to avoid playing ...d6 as this would lead to some typical Sicilian Najdorf setups. That means - more lines to study and more unnecessary things to remember. Our task is not to overload your memory! }
8. a3
{ White makes sure that Black's ...b4 is stopped, keeping the e4-pawn safe. }
8... d6
{ The classical continuation requires a lot of knowledge and good calculation capabilities. It's not very practical for Black to go to this line as White has several ideas on how to test Black with forced lines or lead you to tricky setups. We'll briefly show you some of the variations. }
9. O-O Qc7
{ Black protects the bishop on b7.   9...Be7??  Black keeps falling into this trap all the time.  10.e5!  Bxg2     10...dxe5  is not better as  11.Bxb7  Ra7  12.Bc6+  White is crushing.  11.exf6!  the intermezzo move.  11...Bxf1  12.fxe7  Qxe7  13.Qxf1  White has two minor pieces for the rook and should be technically winning. }
10. Re1
{ With the rook at the e-file White is thinking about combinational Nd5 and Nf5 ideas. }
10... Nbd7
{ Another accurate move, making sure that White's a4 is met accordingly.   10...Be7?!  Now White can suddenly change the course of the game.  11.a4!  b4  The alternative is to take on  a4  and accept a lasting pressure against the pawn on a6.  12.Na2  Topalov V. - Short N. Dortmund SuperGM 25th 1997. The problem is that Black has problems protecting the pawn on b4.  12...a5?  13.Nb5  Now White controls the b5-square and can target the d6-pawn. Also, White's c3 is a very typical pawn push, bringing the a2-knight back into the game. }
11. a4
{ On top of the alternatives, White can push the a-pawn, combining it with the typical knight sacrifice on d5.   11.Bf4  This maneuver comes with the threat of sacrificing a knight on b5 for many pawns.   11.Bg5  An interesting continuation that starts big complications, not necessarily in favor of Black.  11...Be7  12.a4  A typical intermezzo move for White, to open the queenside first.  12...bxa4  13.Nd5!  You might think that this is a very beautiful move - it is, but it's a standard for these kinds of positions that usually nobody today is surprised to meet one.  13...exd5  14.exd5  Black's king is under some heavy fire.  14...h6  15.Bxf6  gxf6  16.Rxa4  From a practical point of view, it's much easier to play with White - he's attacking. Black might be fine, but the position is quite unpleasant.   11...Ne5   11...Be7  Black can try to ignore it.  12.Ndxb5  axb5  13.Nxb5  Qc6  14.Nxd6+  Bxd6  15.Qxd6  the forced line ends - White has three connected passed pawns on the queenside for the sacrificed knight, which are backed by two strong bishops. White's chances should be better.  12.a4  White comes back to the alternative idea to provoke some weaknesses on the queenside.  12...bxa4   If  12...b4  is played,  13.Na2  still is very unpleasant.  13.Nxa4  Be7  14.c4  O-O  15.Rc1  White's threats on the queenside look very real - Black is on the defensive early on. }
11... b4
{ 11...bxa4?  opening the queenside almost loses by force.  12.Nd5!  exd5  13.exd5+  Ne5  the only move as the king can't wander to the queenside - thanks to the previous move it's wide open.  14.c4!  Nd7  15.f4  Be7  16.fxe5  dxe5  17.Nc6  White is dominating. There are more lines than this sample but the bottom line is - don't go here. }
12. Na2
{ This time the Nd5 maneuver doesn't do any good for White as quite similar to a previous line, Black will accept the piece, play ...Ne5 and castle long - with the Black pawn on b4, the queenside is sort of closed. Sort of. }
12... Nc5 { Black counter-attacks the pawn on e4. } 13. Bf4
{ White has to go for radical solutions to get to the black king. This involves sacrifices and thus very sharp lines. }
13... Ncxe4 14. Nxb4
{ Some mind-boggling variations are only about to start. As you can see, this entire variation for Black is not very practical - you need to remember more than White will. }
