{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knights' potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways to pressure White's center. }
5. Nc3
{ It's time to move to the Open Sicilian Nc3 setups if White doesn't fianchetto the bishop on g2 but plays some central-based moves. We will examine some of the less-played moves before moving to the main continuation. }
5... b5
{ Black stays true to the spirit of the Kan - play ...b5 once the white knight stands on c3 so that the pawn on e4 is under early pressure. }
6. g3
{ It's also possible to reach this position with a different order of moves. This system is quite tricky - White positions his light-squared bishop to oppose Black's bishop on b7 and one of the most dangerous motifs that you will have to be aware of is the incoming e5 threat and the following intermezzo captures on f6 since the bishop on b7 will be under attack. }
6... Nf6
{ Black plays a little trick - you can start also with  6...Bb7  , it doesn't matter much. }
7. Bg2 Bb7
{ Now White has several continuations but all of them are more or less harmless. Black's idea is to avoid playing ...d6 as this would lead to some typical Sicilian Najdorf setups. That means - more lines to study and more unnecessary things to remember. Our task is not to overload your memory! }
8. O-O
{ This continuation at the highest level has only been played in blitz. Even at the club level, it should not be too difficult to understand the important nuances over the board. }
8... b4
{ Black goes after the pawn - the difference to one of the informational lines is that White has already committed himself to castling kingside. }
9. Nd5
{ This aggressive continuation is typical, but compared to other lines, here it doesn't seem so dangerous as the queenside is still closed. White is taking big risks. }
9... exd5 10. exd5 Bc5
{ The only continuation, but still rather obvious, after which White will have to cook up something to get compensation for the missing piece. }
11. Re1+ Kf8 12. a3
{ Naturally, White is seeking ways to open the queenside and bring as many pieces into the game as soon as possible.   12.Nb3  Bb6  13.a3  a5  transposes. }
12... a5
{ It's best to keep the position closed, if possible.   12...bxa3  this brave move might create too much excitement than you are looking for.  13.b4!  Bxb4  14.c3  Bc5  taking another pawn on c3 seems too much already.  15.Qb3  Ra7  16.Bxa3  although Black is up a full piece, White is attacking with full force. In such a situation it's easy to make a mistake.  16...d6  17.Bxc5  dxc5  18.Qc4!  Nbd7  19.Nc6  Bxc6  20.dxc6  and there you go, Black is already forced to give up the extra piece.  20...g6  21.cxd7  Qxd7  22.Qxc5+  Kg7  Black has some problems reaching full equality but maybe with an accurate play, this still is a draw. }
13. Nb3 Bb6
{ Black sticks to the same approach as the same position can be reached with a different order of the moves as well. We'll just mention that it's interesting to explore also  13...Bd6  , with an unclear position. }
14. axb4 axb4 15. Rxa8 Bxa8
{ With the queenside rook gone, White's initiative doesn't seem strong anymore. Due to the lead in the development, White will probably win another pawn, but Black should be safe. }
16. Bd2 Na6 17. Qe2 Bb7 18. Qb5 d6 19. Ra1 {  } 19... Nd7
{ White still needs to prove what exactly he has for the sacrificed material - Black's position looks under control.   This is how the game would have continued:  20.h4  h5  21.Na5  Bxa5  22.Rxa5  Ndc5  the position is inevitably simplifying.  23.Bxb4  Nxb4  24.Qxb4  g5!  25.hxg5  Qxg5  , now White gets to collect back some material, but Black appears to be pushing.  26.Rxc5  dxc5  27.Qxb7  Kg7  . Black is not risking anything here, and White will have to fight for the draw, which is probably the most likely result with the perfect play. }
