{ Black stays true to the spirit of the Kan - play ...b5 once the white knight stands on c3 so that the pawn on e4 is under early pressure. }
6. g3
{ It's also possible to reach this position with a different order of moves. This system is quite tricky - White positions his light-squared bishop to oppose Black's bishop on b7 and one of the most dangerous motifs that you will have to be aware of is the incoming e5 threat and the following intermezzo captures on f6 since the bishop on b7 will be under attack. }
6... Nf6
{ Black plays a little trick - you can start also with  6...Bb7  , it doesn't matter much. }
7. Bg2 Bb7
{ Now White has several continuations but all of them are more or less harmless. Black's idea is to avoid playing ...d6 as this would lead to some typical Sicilian Najdorf setups. That means - more lines to study and more unnecessary things to remember. Our task is not to overload your memory! }
8. Bg5
{ Not a very good idea, but still, you have to know what to do against it. White again offers to take the pawn on e4, but this time it doesn't work. }
8... Be7 9. O-O b4 10. Na4 Qa5
{ Here lies White's problem with the plan - he's forced to give up the dark-squared bishop.   10...Nxe4?  this time Black can't take the pawn either with the knight or the bishop.  11.Bxe7  Qxe7  12.Nb6  Ra7  13.Bxe4  Bxe4  14.Nc8  a pretty fork, so make sure you don't jump on it. }
11. Bxf6 Bxf6 12. c3
{ The knight on a4 is still under attack, so it's necessary to defend it. }
12... Nc6
{ Not the only good move in Black's arsenal, but the most consistent one. Alternatives are to castle short or to take the pawn on c3, all promising Black a good game. White will be missing the dark-squared bishop. }
13. cxb4 Qxb4 14. e5
{ White has to do something and try to make a draw, otherwise, he's simply worse with no counterplay. }
14... Bxe5 15. Nxc6 Bxc6 16. Bxc6 dxc6
{ This ends the forced sequence: Black has the extra pawn and a strong bishop, while White has a minor lead in development. }
17. a3 Qb5 18. Rc1 Rd8 19. Qc2 Bd4
{ To improve the position, Black lands the bishop on d4. Don't start to play passive in order just to keep the pawn, it's not worth it. }
20. Qxc6+ Ke7
{ The king is a piece as well! Due to the powerful bishop, White is still struggling, but if he manages to trade Black's powerful bishop on d4 and trade Black's a-pawn for both queenside pawns, he might escape in a rook endgame with 3 pawns vs. 4 on the kingside. }
