{ This is not very ambitious and most certainly not the reason why White played Nd5. }
11... Bxf6 12. O-O Qc7 { Black has a comfortable position. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "9) Open g3 With Nc3"]
[Black "Kan-Wing Attack 5.Nc3 b5 6.g3 #19"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3
{ Continuing to look at the setups with g3 and fianchettoing White's light-squared bishop to g2 - we will examine what to do if White plays Open Sicilian with the g3 setup, including Nc3. }
2... e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knights' potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways to pressure White's center. }
5. Nc3
{ It's time to move to the Open Sicilian Nc3 setups if White doesn't fianchetto the bishop on g2 but plays some central-based moves. We will examine some of the less-played moves before moving to the main continuation. }
5... b5
{ Black stays true to the spirit of the Kan - play ...b5 once the white knight stands on c3 so that the pawn on e4 is under early pressure. }
6. g3
{ It's also possible to reach this position with a different order of moves. This system is quite tricky - White positions his light-squared bishop to oppose Black's bishop on b7 and one of the most dangerous motifs that you will have to be aware of is the incoming e5 threat and the following intermezzo captures on f6 since the bishop on b7 will be under attack. }
6... Nf6
{ Black plays a little trick - you can start also with  6...Bb7  , it doesn't matter much. }
7. Bg2 Bb7
{ Now White has several continuations but all of them are more or less harmless. Black's idea is to avoid playing ...d6 as this would lead to some typical Sicilian Najdorf setups. That means - more lines to study and more unnecessary things to remember. Our task is not to overload your memory! }
8. Qe2
{ Since castling kingside and giving up the pawn is harmless, we'll treat this queen move as the main one. White is thinking about early Nd5 ideas, or at the right moment, pushing e5. }
8... Nc6
{ The simplest choice - again Black declines to play ...d6 which is not necessary. The arising variations might lead to drawish or at least peaceful lines, so if you are looking for something much sharper, we do have an alternative! }
9. Nxc6
{ White has to take, as the reasons are the same. If he tries to protect the knight with  9.Be3  , Black can immediately go bother the bishop with ...Ne5-c4 ideas. If White retreats with the knight to b3, it's really passive there and Black can safely switch to a perfect Sicilian Najdorf/Scheveningen structure, this time already not minding to play ...d6. }
9... Bxc6 10. Nd5
{ Nice way to complicate matters but Black doesn't have to take the knight. }
10... Be7 11. Nxe7 Qxe7
{ There was a time when reaching positions like this was treated as a success for White. However, time passes and it has been proven that Black organizes good counterplay using the light squares and that the dark-squared bishop has nothing better than a trade for the knight. }
12. O-O O-O 13. Bg5
{ White wants to trade his bishop for the knight and push forward the e-pawn, creating a weakness on d6. }
13... h6 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. e5 Qf5
{ White has a small edge, due to the weakened pawn on d7, but not enough to be something serious. }
16. Bxc6
{ This continuation, with the idea of seizing control of the d-file, also can't pose any problems for Black. }
16... dxc6 17. Rad1 Rad8 18. Rd6
{ The only idea that White can try to employ. } 18... Rxd6 19. exd6 Rd8 20. Rd1
Qc5 { The White pawn is not going anywhere. } 21. d7 Kf8
{ Black is about to bring the king to e7 and try to win the pawn. } *

