[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) Early 5.g3"]
[Black "5.g3 Qc7 6.Bg2 Nc6 | Informational 5...Qc7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. g3
{ This is a very interesting idea - White prepares the fianchettoing of the bishop on g2 while remaining flexible with the possible plans. White might try to set up the Maroczy Bind, but the queenside knight instead of the traditional c3-square might be developed on d2-c4, if necessary.   What makes it interesting is that in correspondence chess, the strongest players with White are not playing this at all but in over-the-board chess, it's been played by players like Carlsen, Anand, Giri, So, Vallejo, and a dozen good GMs.  In practice, Black is often surprised by this rare continuation as there are hidden practical problems that are difficult to solve over the board. That's why this chapter is so important! }
5... Qc7
{ This standard move allows White to be flexible with his plans, one of them involving a Marcozy Bind and a positional squeeze.   5...b5?!  this maneuver works best if the White knight already stands on c3.  6.Bg2  Bb7  7.O-O  White is significantly ahead in development and will immediately start active operations on the queenside. }
6. Bg2 Nc6 7. O-O
{ White has not decided yet where he will put his queenside knight. } 7... Nf6
{ 7...d6  this is a careful move, intending to bring the light-squared bishop to d7 first and thus keep an option to capture on c6 with the bishop and only then develop the kingside. However, due to the move order, White can now set up the strongest plan.  8.Nxc6  bxc6  9.c4!  Perks of still having the knight on b1.  9...Nf6  10.Nc3  White claimed a big opening advantage in Tari, A. @@StartBracket@@2635@@EndBracket@@ - Stachowiak, K. @@StartBracket@@2446@@EndBracket@@ Lisbon Portugal op 2020.  To understand the position better: White is often ready to get this Maroczy Bind setup even with something like 2 tempi less when the knight is already on c3, in front of the c2-pawn. White would take on c6, play Na4, c4, and eventually, return with the knight to c3. Here, it's done a lot faster. }
8. Re1
{ White is threatening Nxc6 and e5, so Black has to do something about it. }
8... d6 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10. e5 { A temporary pawn sacrifice. } 10... dxe5 11. Nd2
{ Because White did not commit to Nc3 earlier, this maneuver now becomes possible. Black is suffering. }
