[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) Early 5.g3"]
[Black "5.g3 Qc7 6.Bg2 Nc6 | Informational 5...d6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. g3
{ This is a very interesting idea - White prepares the fianchettoing of the bishop on g2 while remaining flexible with the possible plans. White might try to set up the Maroczy Bind, but the queenside knight instead of the traditional c3-square might be developed on d2-c4, if necessary.   What makes it interesting is that in correspondence chess, the strongest players with White are not playing this at all but in over-the-board chess, it's been played by players like Carlsen, Anand, Giri, So, Vallejo, and a dozen good GMs.  In practice, Black is often surprised by this rare continuation as there are hidden practical problems that are difficult to solve over the board. That's why this chapter is so important! }
5... d6
{ Of course, Black can do this and immediately aim for a Hedgehog setup, but this gives White a lot of freedom. }
6. Bg2 Nf6 7. c4
{ That's White's idea - to get the ideal Maroczy Bind structure  (pawns on  e4 and c4)  for a serious space advantage. }
7... Bd7 8. O-O Nc6 9. Nc3 Be7
{ This is a dream position for White. What we will be aiming for in the course, is to have more dynamics than a passive setup, which mainly works for unexpected counterstrikes. }
10. Nxc6 Bxc6 11. a4
{ One of the ideas in the Maroczy Bind is to take away from Black any options of making pawn breaks, and then slowly squeezing him to death. }
11... a5 12. Be3 O-O 13. Qe2 Nd7 14. Rfd1 Qb8 15. Nb5
{ Black's position wasn't great in Giri, A.  2782  - Carlsen, M.  2855  Paris GCT blitz 2016. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) Early 5.g3"]
[Black " 5.g3 d5 6.Nf3 Nf6 | Informational 6...Nf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. g3
{ This is a very interesting idea - White prepares the fianchettoing of the bishop on g2 while remaining flexible with the possible plans. White might try to set up the Maroczy Bind, but the queenside knight instead of the traditional c3-square might be developed on d2-c4, if necessary.   What makes it interesting is that in correspondence chess, the strongest players with White are not playing this at all but in over-the-board chess, it's been played by players like Carlsen, Anand, Giri, So, Vallejo, and a dozen good GMs.  In practice, Black is often surprised by this rare continuation as there are hidden practical problems that are difficult to solve over the board. That's why this chapter is so important! }
5... d5
{ This energetic move showcases the only minus of the g3 plan - slow play in the center. There's a reason why the main moves in the position are Nc3, Bd3, or c4 - for this very reason. White has several options on how to respond.   5...d6  Of course, Black can do this and immediately aim for a Hedgehog setup, but this gives White a lot of freedom.  6.Bg2  Nf6  7.c4!?  That's White's idea - to get the ideal Maroczy Bind structure @@StartBracket@@pawns on e4 and c4@@EndBracket@@ with a serious space advantage.  7...Bd7  8.O-O  Nc6  9.Nc3  Be7  . This is a dream position for White.  What we are aiming for in the course, is to have more dynamics than a passive setup which mainly works for unexpected counterstrikes.  10.Nxc6  Bxc6  11.a4  One of the ideas in the Maroczy Bind is to take away from Black any options of making pawn breaks and then slowly squeezing him to death.  11...a5  12.Be3  O-O  13.Qe2  Nd7  14.Rfd1  Qb8  15.Nb5  Black's position wasn't great in Giri, A. @@StartBracket@@2782@@EndBracket@@ - Carlsen, M. @@StartBracket@@2855@@EndBracket@@ Paris GCT blitz 2016. }
6. Nf3
{ One of White's ideas is to retreat the knight and so either force a queen trade with more active white pieces, or establish an isolated black pawn on d5. It's important to understand that the isolated pawn always has been the lesser evil, as long as your pieces are very active. Many players give the healthy pawn structure priority over piece activity.   6.exd5?  only creates problems for White.  6...Qxd5  and whatever White plays next, he's already on the defensive. }
6... Nf6
{ We would like to show you what could happen if Black focuses on the healthier pawn structure instead. }
7. exd5 Qxd5 { Capturing with the pawn is still fine. } 8. Qxd5 Nxd5 9. Bg2
{ This powerful bishop on g2 will resemble some of the most typical problems that Black faces in the Catalan, where the pawn structure is also fine. }
9... Bc5 { Perhaps not the best move, but seemingly it's active. } 10. O-O O-O
{ Anand, V. @@StartBracket@@2715@@EndBracket@@ - Lobron, E. @@StartBracket@@2570@@EndBracket@@ Munich Intel Express blitz '5 1994. }
11. c4
{ A standard idea to gain more space on the queenside and open the h1-a8 diagonal. }
11... Nb6 12. b3 Bd7 13. Rd1 Bc6
{ Black did manage to solve the problems of his Catalan bishop, but the Catalan mantle is given to the knight on b6. }
14. Nc3 N8d7 15. Bf4
{ White has a solid advantage: three pawns versus two on the queenside and better-positioned minor pieces. }
