6... Bc5
{ The most active continuation - Black shouldn't mind the isolated pawn. With the bishop move, Black also removes White's option to play an early Be3 and thus fight for the blockade on d4.   6...dxe4?!  this can be too much fun - White will win back the pawn by force, and the black king is walking in a semi-open position.  7.Qxd8+  Kxd8  8.Ng5  White is just better. }
7. exd5 exd5
{ For Black, the position is quite easy to play. Please note that White has already wasted a couple of tempi for the moves of the kingside knight. }
8. Nc3 Nf6 9. Bg2
{ If White continues with standard development, the absence of two tempi will soon be felt. }
9... O-O 10. O-O h6 11. Bf4 Nc6
{ Black is simply better as he has more active pieces. White is unable to make a quick blockade of Black's d-pawn, let alone start pressuring it. }
