[Black "5.g3 d5 6.e5 Qc7 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. g3
{ This is a very interesting idea - White prepares the fianchettoing of the bishop on g2 while remaining flexible with the possible plans. White might try to set up the Maroczy Bind, but the queenside knight instead of the traditional c3-square might be developed on d2-c4, if necessary.   What makes it interesting is that in correspondence chess, the strongest players with White are not playing this at all but in over-the-board chess, it's been played by players like Carlsen, Anand, Giri, So, Vallejo, and a dozen good GMs.  In practice, Black is often surprised by this rare continuation as there are hidden practical problems that are difficult to solve over the board. That's why this chapter is so important! }
5... d5
{ This energetic move showcases the only minus of the g3 plan - slow play in the center. There's a reason why the main moves in the position are Nc3, Bd3, or c4 - for this very reason. White has several options on how to respond.   5...d6  Of course, Black can do this and immediately aim for a Hedgehog setup, but this gives White a lot of freedom.  6.Bg2  Nf6  7.c4!?  That's White's idea - to get the ideal Maroczy Bind structure @@StartBracket@@pawns on e4 and c4@@EndBracket@@ with a serious space advantage.  7...Bd7  8.O-O  Nc6  9.Nc3  Be7  . This is a dream position for White.  What we are aiming for in the course, is to have more dynamics than a passive setup which mainly works for unexpected counterstrikes.  10.Nxc6  Bxc6  11.a4  One of the ideas in the Maroczy Bind is to take away from Black any options of making pawn breaks and then slowly squeezing him to death.  11...a5  12.Be3  O-O  13.Qe2  Nd7  14.Rfd1  Qb8  15.Nb5  Black's position wasn't great in Giri, A. @@StartBracket@@2782@@EndBracket@@ - Carlsen, M. @@StartBracket@@2855@@EndBracket@@ Paris GCT blitz 2016. }
6. e5
{ White may consider closing the center, but is this the position that White was aiming for? Since the structure resembles the French Defense, White's light-squared bishop belongs on d3 for a kingside attack, not g2, so the spent tempo for fianchettoing was a waste of time. Also, Black has not yet played ...Nf6 and after White's e5 has not retreated to d7. Here the knight can easily join the game via the e7-square and later go to either c6 or f5. Black can follow some typical French Defense ideas, which involve being active on the queenside. The next moves are just a sample line. }
6... Qc7
{ Black is provoking White to play f4, thus removing the dark-squared bishop from a potential kingside attack and also slightly weakening White's control of some of the central squares @@StartBracket@@for example, e4@@EndBracket@@. }
7. f4 Nc6 8. c3
{ White should probably not be allowed to bring the queenside knight to f3 - then White can perhaps claim some opening advantage due to better control of the central squares.   8.Be3  Qb6  creates some real problems for White to protect the b2-pawn. }
8... Bd7 9. Be3 Nge7 10. Nd2
{ Just before White is ready to bring reinforcements to d4, it's a good time to take on d4. It was possible to do it earlier as well. }
10... Nxd4 11. Bxd4
{ Taking with the bishop is a reasonable idea, but White is risking getting a worse position.   11.cxd4  Qb6  this is quite a comfortable French Defense position for Black. }
11... Nf5 12. Nf3 Nxd4 13. Nxd4
{ White may seem fine with a good blockade on d4, but actually, his position is a little static with no active plans. Black has a strong bishop pair, and then there's a way to complicate things a little. }
13... g5
{ Perhaps not even right away, but that's the idea - Black would like to create a weakness on f4 and, if possible, target it with either ...Bh6 or ...f6, opening the bishops. The king will go to the queenside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "10) Early 5.g3"]
[Black "5.g3 d5 6.Nb3 Nf6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. g3
{ This is a very interesting idea - White prepares the fianchettoing of the bishop on g2 while remaining flexible with the possible plans. White might try to set up the Maroczy Bind, but the queenside knight instead of the traditional c3-square might be developed on d2-c4, if necessary.   What makes it interesting is that in correspondence chess, the strongest players with White are not playing this at all but in over-the-board chess, it's been played by players like Carlsen, Anand, Giri, So, Vallejo, and a dozen good GMs.  In practice, Black is often surprised by this rare continuation as there are hidden practical problems that are difficult to solve over the board. That's why this chapter is so important! }
5... d5
{ This energetic move showcases the only minus of the g3 plan - slow play in the center. There's a reason why the main moves in the position are Nc3, Bd3, or c4 - for this very reason. White has several options on how to respond.   5...d6  Of course, Black can do this and immediately aim for a Hedgehog setup, but this gives White a lot of freedom.  6.Bg2  Nf6  7.c4!?  That's White's idea - to get the ideal Maroczy Bind structure @@StartBracket@@pawns on e4 and c4@@EndBracket@@ with a serious space advantage.  7...Bd7  8.O-O  Nc6  9.Nc3  Be7  . This is a dream position for White.  What we are aiming for in the course, is to have more dynamics than a passive setup which mainly works for unexpected counterstrikes.  10.Nxc6  Bxc6  11.a4  One of the ideas in the Maroczy Bind is to take away from Black any options of making pawn breaks and then slowly squeezing him to death.  11...a5  12.Be3  O-O  13.Qe2  Nd7  14.Rfd1  Qb8  15.Nb5  Black's position wasn't great in Giri, A. @@StartBracket@@2782@@EndBracket@@ - Carlsen, M. @@StartBracket@@2855@@EndBracket@@ Paris GCT blitz 2016. }
6. Nb3
{ The strongest idea that you should be ready for. White wants to take on d5 and create an isolated pawn and then pressure it with Bg2. The isolated pawn, as such, is not a big problem, but now Black can't choose the most active setup, which involves ...Bc5.   6.exd5?  only creates problems for White.  6...Qxd5  and whatever White plays next, he's already on the defensive. }
6... Nf6
{ Instead of grabbing pawns, Black focuses on development - this often makes a good strategy. We hope that after studying the following variations, you will have a pretty good idea of when to take on d5 with the pawn and settle for the isolated queen's pawn structure, or to keep your pawn structure intact. So far, White's been almost exclusively taking the pawn on d5, but let us examine other options as well. }
7. Bg5
{ A tricky move - White insists on taking the pawn on e4. With the inclusion of ...Nf6 and Bg5 this feels like a concession for Black. }
7... Be7 8. exd5 Qxd5
{ One of those moments when taking on d5 should be preferred! The reason is the upcoming dark-squared bishop trade, which makes Black's defense considerably easier. }
9. Qxd5 Nxd5 10. Bxe7 Kxe7 11. Bg2
{ White did manage to position his 'Catalan' bishop on g2 and slow down Black's development on the queenside, but due to the dark-squared bishop trade, now it's easier to untangle. }
11... Nb4 12. Na3 Ra7
{ Black has solved his opening problems. The absence of the dark-squared bishops makes the obvious difference - no one can bother the black rook. }
