8... Be7
{ This allows White to get exactly what he wants.   8...Bb4+  If you're thinking about provoking White to play c3 and then retreating to e7 to secure yourself from the potential Nc3 move, this time White has something better.  9.Bd2  Bxd2+  10.Qxd2  The dark-squared bishop trade favors White as Black is threatened to be left with the 'bad' bishop on  e6  in passive defense.  10...Qe7+  11.Qe2  Qxe2+  12.Kxe2  The fact that the white king is forced to walk early doesn't change the fact - White here has the opening advantage. }
9. O-O O-O 10. Nc3
{ Can you make a comparison with the main lines of Chapter 6 ? Also there we had a similar position but the white knight was on f3, the pawn on d5 was relatively safe, but here Black has included a useless ...a6 which doesn't help for the position. }
10... Be6 11. Bg5 { White is very fast with his threats. } 11... Nc6
{ Yang, W. - Andreikin, D. Belgrade Long Tire Cup 2019. Here White's game can be easily improved. }
12. Rb1
{ Prophylaxis: White defends the pawn on b2 and is very serious about winning the pawn on d5. }
12... Bg4
{ Black's only chance to salvage the game might be linked with pushing forward the d-pawn, but there's always the Bxc6 move. If Black pushes ...d4 right away, the arising position will be quite similar to this variation.   12.Bxf6?!  while the idea is there, this is too early.  12...Bxf6  13.Nxd5  Bxb2  Black wins back the pawn and is a happy person. }
13. Qd2 d4 14. Bxc6
{ White gives up the strong light-squared bishop but wins a pawn. Now starts a forced sequence. }
14... dxc3 15. Qxd8 Raxd8 16. Bxb7 cxb2 17. Rxb2 h6 18. Be3
{ Black has some compensation for the pawn, but he will have to work hard to achieve the draw - not the most pleasant of prospects for any chess player. }
