7. exd5 { The most popular move so far. } 7... exd5
{ This is the moment when Black doesn't have a choice but to go for the isolated queen's pawn structure and rely on his piece activity.   7...Qxd5  to illustrate, the following line is exactly what White wants.  8.Qxd5  Nxd5  9.Bg2  Nc6  10.O-O  White's plan is simple: c4, Nc3 and exploit the weakness on b6. If only Black had the light-squared bishops traded, it would be a great position. Here White has a solid advantage. }
8. Bg2
{ The obvious choice - White continues development and remains flexible with his plans. Now Black has to be a little aggressive, otherwise, the arising positions won't be fun to play. }
8... Bg4
{ This move, played early, is necessary as it forces the white queen to define its placement. White's f3 or Bf3 do not make much sense. }
9. Qd2
{ Here the white queen is blocking her own bishop's jump to g5 - we're not sure who would play this but it is still important to know what to do next. The queen can now be rearranged to f4. }
9... Nc6 10. O-O Qd7
{ A great move - not only does Black make sure that White can't play h3, thus preventing White from playing Rd1 and attacking the d5-pawn, but this also frees the d8-square for the rook. }
11. Nc3 Rd8 { Just in time. } 12. Qf4 Be7 13. Be3
{ If the white bishop can't make it to g5, it makes sense for White to seek other ways to contribute to the position. }
13... O-O 14. Bb6 Bd6 15. Qd2 {  } 15... Bc7
{ The black rook remains on d8. Even if White makes the dark-squared bishop trade, which,  in general, should be a small achievement for him, the problem is that he can't properly block the d5 pawn as the pieces are not coordinated for this. Black is very active and quite comfortable. }
