8... Bg4
{ This move, played early, is necessary as it forces the white queen to define its placement. White's f3 or Bf3 do not make much sense. }
9. Qd3
{ The standard retreat - the white queen feels good here, but now it will be subject to some tactical ideas. }
9... Nc6 10. O-O Be7
{ Rock solid and with a clear plan: Black continues development and keeps the option to play ...Nb4 later.   10...Nb4!  objectively, this move might be even stronger than  10...Be7  but there's one problem. The arising complications will be immense and simply impossible to remember, and the cost of making the correct move at a good level is so high that after the first mistake you might simply have to resign and go home to prepare for the next game.  Here is a sample line to enjoy! @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/1p3ppp/p4n2/3p4/1n4b1/1N1Q2P1/PPP2PBP/RNB2RK1 w kq - 6 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Qd2  Ne4!  12.Qf4  f5  everything is moving forward! The fork threat on c2 is still alive, and then there's the ...Bd6 threat.  13.Qe5+  Be7  14.c3  White happily sacrifices an exchange.  14...Nc2  15.Qxg7  Bf6  16.Qh6  Be2  Black wants to take the second exchange as well. The position, according to the engines, of course, is equal. }
11. Nc3 Nb4
{ Thanks to this maneuver, Black manages to rearrange his pieces.   11...Ne5?!  this maneuver is very tempting as Black now inevitably lands the knight on f3 and forces White to give up his precious light-squared bishop. However, this is where Black's achievements in the line end.  12.Qd4  Nf3+  13.Bxf3  Bxf3  14.Bg5  because of the static nature of the other pieces, Black's position is rather terrible.  14...O-O  15.Rae1  Re8  16.Re3  White pushes away the black bishop from f3 and dominates in the center. }
12. Qd2 Bf5 13. Nd4 Bg6
{ Here Black's light-squared bishop is contributing something to the queenside initiative and looks well-placed. Now the white knight on d4 is blocking the attack on the isolated pawn, while the white queen's awkward placement on d2 does not help. All Black now needs to do is quickly castle and seek counter-chances in the center. }
14. a3 Nc6
{ Black is again pressing at White's center and is indirectly threatening to win the pawn on c2. It definitely shouldn't be Black's focus but this absolutely will keep White busy. So far we've been following the game Bagi, M. @@StartBracket@@2470@@EndBracket@@ - Popovics, A. @@StartBracket@@2365@@EndBracket@@ HUN-chT 2020. White's game can be improved. }
15. Rd1
{ White could try to improve the Nde2 maneuver and make sure that Black can't respond to it with ...d4, but it's also very slow, plus Black has other ideas as well. }
15... O-O 16. Nde2 Bc5
{ Black wants to sacrifice the pawn on d5 and go for a counter-attack, pressing on the f2-pawn. }
17. Nf4
{ An alternate choice for White is to add more attackers. Don't focus on the d5-pawn too much, but think about Black's active prospects. }
17... Re8 18. Nxg6 hxg6 19. Nxd5
{ White wins the pawn, but now the initiative belongs to Black alone. } 19...
Ng4 20. Rf1 Nd4 21. Nc3 Rc8
{ Black is very active, while White is struggling to finish the development.   Just to illustrate, how quickly things can go wrong for White:  22.Qd1?  Ne2+  23.Nxe2  Qxd1  24.Rxd1  Rxe2  White has major problems with the 2nd rank and the f2 pawn.  25.Bf3  Rxf2  26.Bxg4  f5!  after this move, White's position collapses. }
*

