{ This energetic move showcases the only minus of the g3 plan - slow play in the center. There's a reason why the main moves in the position are Nc3, Bd3, or c4 - for this very reason. White has several options on how to respond.   5...d6  Of course, Black can do this and immediately aim for a Hedgehog setup, but this gives White a lot of freedom.  6.Bg2  Nf6  7.c4!?  That's White's idea - to get the ideal Maroczy Bind structure @@StartBracket@@pawns on e4 and c4@@EndBracket@@ with a serious space advantage.  7...Bd7  8.O-O  Nc6  9.Nc3  Be7  . This is a dream position for White.  What we are aiming for in the course, is to have more dynamics than a passive setup which mainly works for unexpected counterstrikes.  10.Nxc6  Bxc6  11.a4  One of the ideas in the Maroczy Bind is to take away from Black any options of making pawn breaks and then slowly squeezing him to death.  11...a5  12.Be3  O-O  13.Qe2  Nd7  14.Rfd1  Qb8  15.Nb5  Black's position wasn't great in Giri, A. @@StartBracket@@2782@@EndBracket@@ - Carlsen, M. @@StartBracket@@2855@@EndBracket@@ Paris GCT blitz 2016. }
6. Nb3
{ The strongest idea that you should be ready for. White wants to take on d5 and create an isolated pawn and then pressure it with Bg2. The isolated pawn, as such, is not a big problem, but now Black can't choose the most active setup, which involves ...Bc5.   6.exd5?  only creates problems for White.  6...Qxd5  and whatever White plays next, he's already on the defensive. }
6... Nf6
{ Instead of grabbing pawns, Black focuses on development - this often makes a good strategy. We hope that after studying the following variations, you will have a pretty good idea of when to take on d5 with the pawn and settle for the isolated queen's pawn structure, or to keep your pawn structure intact. So far, White's been almost exclusively taking the pawn on d5, but let us examine other options as well. }
7. exd5 { The most popular move so far. } 7... exd5
{ This is the moment when Black doesn't have a choice but to go for the isolated queen's pawn structure and rely on his piece activity.   7...Qxd5  to illustrate, the following line is exactly what White wants.  8.Qxd5  Nxd5  9.Bg2  Nc6  10.O-O  White's plan is simple: c4, Nc3 and exploit the weakness on b6. If only Black had the light-squared bishops traded, it would be a great position. Here White has a solid advantage. }
8. Bg2
{ The obvious choice - White continues development and remains flexible with his plans. Now Black has to be a little aggressive, otherwise, the arising positions won't be fun to play. }
8... Bg4
{ This move, played early, is necessary as it forces the white queen to define its placement. White's f3 or Bf3 do not make much sense. }
9. Qd3
{ The standard retreat - the white queen feels good here, but now it will be subject to some tactical ideas. }
9... Nc6 10. O-O Be7
{ Rock solid and with a clear plan: Black continues development and keeps the option to play ...Nb4 later.   10...Nb4!  objectively, this move might be even stronger than  10...Be7  but there's one problem. The arising complications will be immense and simply impossible to remember, and the cost of making the correct move at a good level is so high that after the first mistake you might simply have to resign and go home to prepare for the next game.  Here is a sample line to enjoy! @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/1p3ppp/p4n2/3p4/1n4b1/1N1Q2P1/PPP2PBP/RNB2RK1 w kq - 6 11@@EndFEN@@  11.Qd2  Ne4!  12.Qf4  f5  everything is moving forward! The fork threat on c2 is still alive, and then there's the ...Bd6 threat.  13.Qe5+  Be7  14.c3  White happily sacrifices an exchange.  14...Nc2  15.Qxg7  Bf6  16.Qh6  Be2  Black wants to take the second exchange as well. The position, according to the engines, of course, is equal. }
11. Nc3 Nb4
{ Thanks to this maneuver, Black manages to rearrange his pieces.   11...Ne5?!  this maneuver is very tempting as Black now inevitably lands the knight on f3 and forces White to give up his precious light-squared bishop. However, this is where Black's achievements in the line end.  12.Qd4  Nf3+  13.Bxf3  Bxf3  14.Bg5  because of the static nature of the other pieces, Black's position is rather terrible.  14...O-O  15.Rae1  Re8  16.Re3  White pushes away the black bishop from f3 and dominates in the center. }
12. Qd2 Bf5 13. Nd4 Bg6
{ Here Black's light-squared bishop is contributing something to the queenside initiative and looks well-placed. Now the white knight on d4 is blocking the attack on the isolated pawn, while the white queen's awkward placement on d2 does not help. All Black now needs to do is quickly castle and seek counter-chances in the center. }
14. a3 Nc6
{ Black is again pressing at White's center and is indirectly threatening to win the pawn on c2. It definitely shouldn't be Black's focus but this absolutely will keep White busy. So far we've been following the game Bagi, M. @@StartBracket@@2470@@EndBracket@@ - Popovics, A. @@StartBracket@@2365@@EndBracket@@ HUN-chT 2020. White's game can be improved. }
15. Nde2
{ This is the strongest move in the position, but we're not sure how human this choice is as the white queen is still clearly misplaced on d2. White should also properly evaluate if the attack on the d5-pawn is worth it, as the c2-pawn might be hanging in the end. }
15... d4 { This is a typical pawn sacrifice to gain a two-bishop advantage. }
16. Bxc6+
{ White has no choice, otherwise, the entire setup makes absolutely no sense. }
16... bxc6 17. Nxd4 Qc7
{ White has the extra pawn, but the bishop pair and the chronic weaknesses of the light squares give Black a long-term compensation. If Black manages to enter a position with just heavy pieces and opposite color bishops, the extra pawn there won't matter at all.   This is how the game could continue:  18.Qf4  Qd7  Of course, Black is not interested to trade queens. Also, the white pawn on c2 might be lost in a couple of moves.  19.Re1  O-O!  Black wants to make some active moves like ...Rfe8 and ...c5 next - what should White do about the c2-pawn?  20.Nxc6  there might be no choice for White.   20.Nf3  White would like to trade that powerful light-squared bishop but it's easier said than done.  20...Rfe8  21.Ne5??  Bd6!  There's room for tactical solutions - Black unexpectedly wins.  20...Qxc6  21.Rxe7  White wins a second pawn, but this mobilizes Black's resources.  21...Rfe8  22.Rxe8+  Rxe8  23.Be3  White is now up to two pawns, but the light-squared weaknesses are still there  23...Ne4!  Black is not counting the pawns but wants to control the initiative. After all, when you checkmate your opponent via the light squares, nobody will count the number of pawns on the other side of the board.  24.Qf3  Qc8  25.Nd5  Qxc2  . One pawn is regained, the second one might follow soon. White has still not solved the problems of his weakened light squares. }
