1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. g3
{ This is a very interesting idea - White prepares the fianchettoing of the bishop on g2 while remaining flexible with the possible plans. White might try to set up the Maroczy Bind, but the queenside knight instead of the traditional c3-square might be developed on d2-c4, if necessary.   What makes it interesting is that in correspondence chess, the strongest players with White are not playing this at all but in over-the-board chess, it's been played by players like Carlsen, Anand, Giri, So, Vallejo, and a dozen good GMs.  In practice, Black is often surprised by this rare continuation as there are hidden practical problems that are difficult to solve over the board. That's why this chapter is so important! }
5... d5
{ This energetic move showcases the only minus of the g3 plan - slow play in the center. There's a reason why the main moves in the position are Nc3, Bd3, or c4 - for this very reason. White has several options on how to respond.   5...d6  Of course, Black can do this and immediately aim for a Hedgehog setup, but this gives White a lot of freedom.  6.Bg2  Nf6  7.c4!?  That's White's idea - to get the ideal Maroczy Bind structure @@StartBracket@@pawns on e4 and c4@@EndBracket@@ with a serious space advantage.  7...Bd7  8.O-O  Nc6  9.Nc3  Be7  . This is a dream position for White.  What we are aiming for in the course, is to have more dynamics than a passive setup which mainly works for unexpected counterstrikes.  10.Nxc6  Bxc6  11.a4  One of the ideas in the Maroczy Bind is to take away from Black any options of making pawn breaks and then slowly squeezing him to death.  11...a5  12.Be3  O-O  13.Qe2  Nd7  14.Rfd1  Qb8  15.Nb5  Black's position wasn't great in Giri, A. @@StartBracket@@2782@@EndBracket@@ - Carlsen, M. @@StartBracket@@2855@@EndBracket@@ Paris GCT blitz 2016. }
6. Nb3
{ The strongest idea that you should be ready for. White wants to take on d5 and create an isolated pawn and then pressure it with Bg2. The isolated pawn, as such, is not a big problem, but now Black can't choose the most active setup, which involves ...Bc5.   6.exd5?  only creates problems for White.  6...Qxd5  and whatever White plays next, he's already on the defensive. }
6... dxe4
{ This is an alternative that leads straight to a complex endgame with chances for both players. The arising endgame is quite interesting and you can hope to outplay a less experienced opponent as White will face many choices and could get confused in the process. Against a strong player who knows how to handle the initiative, we'd think twice before going for this. }
7. Qxd8+ Kxd8
{ White has sacrificed a pawn, exposed Black's king, and has very interesting compensation. Let's have a look at several continuations at White's disposal. }
8. N1d2
{ Moving the knight on d2 seems to be the trickiest approach from White. Not only White is attacking the pawn on e4 but the knight can be moved to c4 to fight for the b6 and d6 weaknesses. In addition, it allows White to play f3 and recapture on f3 with the knight.   8.Nc3  should also be very much playable, but it feels to be less flexible - then Black probably should stick to ...f5 and hide the king on the kingside. }
8... b6
{ Black gives back the pawn to finish development.   8...f5?!  the idea of keeping the pawn is there, but White has not yet defined the placement of his dark-squared bishop, which makes this a dangerous choice.  9.f3  exf3  10.Nxf3  Bd6  11.Be3  White's initiative now develops very quickly.  11...Nf6  12.O-O-O  Kc7  moving the king to e7 and thus the epicenter of action does not seem wise.  13.a4!  A powerful idea - White wants to grab the b6-square, making sure that the black rook on a8 will never join the game. This probably also means that eventually, Black will lose. }
9. Nxe4
{ This seemingly careless move leads to a forced line after which White will have a pawn for the exchange and some initiative but the position will remain  dynamic equality. Judge yourself! }
9... Bb7 10. Bg2 f5 11. Bg5+
{ Only a prepared player will venture here with White as the pin of the h1-a8 diagonal looks deadly. }
11... Be7 12. O-O-O+ Nd7
{ All of this is forced and there are no alternatives. } 13. Nbc5
{ The order of the moves may change, but the outcome is the same - the forced line continues. }
13... bxc5 14. Bxe7+ Kxe7 15. Rxd7+ Kxd7 16. Nxc5+ Kc7
{ After many moves White finally has a small choice, how to capture the bishop on b7. }
17. Bxb7
{ 17.Nxb7  e5  Black quickly arranges some harmony in his position.  18.Nc5  Ra7  The rook on a7 indirectly defends the g7 pawn.  19.Rd1  Nf6  The position is quite difficult to evaluate so let's just say - the stronger player will win this. }
17... Ra7 18. Bf3
{ This is pretty much the same as taking with the knight, with the minor difference that White can choose the retreat square for the bishop. }
18... e5 19. Rd1 Nf6 20. Ne6+ Kc8
{ The position is still very unclear - technically, White is down the smallest margin of material. }
