[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) 5.Nc3 Rare Moves"]
[Black "Kan − Wing Attack 5.Nc3 b5 6.a3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. Nc3
{ It's time to move to the Open Sicilian Nc3 setups if White doesn't fianchetto the bishop on g2 but plays some central-based moves. We will examine some of the lesser-played moves before moving to the main continuation in the next chapter. }
5... b5
{ Black stays true to the spirit of the Kan - play ...b5 once the white knight stands on c3 so that the pawn on e4 is under early pressure. }
6. a3
{ This modest move can't pose any problems for Black. While White's idea is understandable and he stops the incoming ...b4 move, this comes at a cost of a tempo. }
6... Bb7 7. Be3
{ A normal developing move but it doesn't compute together with the 6.a3 move. White usually plays an early Be3 move with an idea to continue with Qd2, possibly long castle, and f3 to protect the e4-pawn. Here it begs the question, for what purpose then was a3 included, as it also protects the e4-pawn @@StartBracket@@from the ...b4 push@@EndBracket@@. It seems that White has twice insured himself from the same threat, but this is just a loss of time. }
7... Qc7 8. Bd3
{ Positioning the queen on d2 and the pawn on f3 with castle long would just fuel Black's initiative on the queenside with ...b4, thanks to White's included a3. }
8... Nf6
{ Black has a very flexible development in the center and is thinking of bothering both the white pawn on e4 and the knight on d4. }
9. f4
{ White wants to push e5 and invites Black to play ...d6 which would stop it. However, there's no real reason to do it as the e5 push itself here is not a problem. On the contrary, it activates Black's bishop on b7 and hands over the d5 square. }
9... Bc5 { Since Black already wants to play ...Qb6, White has to act fast. }
10. e5 Nd5 11. Nxd5 Bxd5
{ This position is perfectly alright for Black. You don't have to focus on pushing forward the d-pawn to d6 at all costs, just to trade the 'weak' pawn on d7. Instead, try to make as active moves as you can. }
12. c3 Nc6 13. Nc2
{ Never miss the idea of  13.Nxb5  . White wins a pawn due to a small trick. Here, Black has a satisfactory continuation but under different circumstances, this could prove deadly.  13...axb5  14.Bxc5  Nxe5!  Black has his tricks as well. }
13... Ne7 { With dynamic equality. } *

