[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) 5.Nc3 Rare Moves"]
[Black "5.Nc3 b5 6.Be3 Bb7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. Nc3
{ It's time to move to the Open Sicilian Nc3 setups if White doesn't fianchetto the bishop on g2 but plays some central-based moves. We will examine some of the lesser-played moves before moving to the main continuation in the next chapter. }
5... b5
{ Black stays true to the spirit of the Kan - play ...b5 once the white knight stands on c3 so that the pawn on e4 is under early pressure. }
6. Be3 Bb7 7. Bd3
{ White centralizes all of his pieces and extra protects the e4-pawn. In the meantime, Black's pieces are standing perfectly for the occasion - the black knight doesn't stand on c6 just yet, and the white pawn on e4 can be bothered very early. }
7... Qc7
{ Black first takes control of the e5-square and only then will play ...Nf6. }
8. f4 Nf6
{ Black already is threatening with ...b4 to win the pawn on e4. White's  9.e5  here is not such an obvious choice at all as Black can respond in numerous ways, starting with  9...Bxg2  and ...Nd5 next, where thanks to White's included f4, the bishop on e3 is under attack. Also  9...b4  as the classical intermezzo move, or perhaps just  9...Nd5  should work just fine. }
9. Qf3
{ This is a classic setup against the Sicilian Najdorf, but here Black is more dynamic in the center thanks to the open dark-squared bishop. Just continue playing this position as Sicilian Kan and keep the black pawn on d7. White most likely pushes forward the g-pawn either with or without castling long to gain some space. }
9... Nc6 10. g4
{ White may play this too early, and there's a very nice punishment. } 10... h5
{ This move is amazing for the reason that White simply doesn't have a good reply against it. If White takes the pawn, Black can just ignore it as White's initiative and the quest for the space advantage is over.   White can't protect the pawn with  11.h3  as after  11...hxg4  12.hxg4  Rxh1+  13.Qxh1  ,  the pawn is just hanging on g4 while  playing @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/1bqp1pp1/p1n1pn2/1p5p/3NPPP1/2NBBQ2/PPP4P/R3K2R w KQkq - 0 11@@EndFEN@@  11.g5  would hand Black the control of the g4-square. }
11. gxh5
{ Andriasian, Z.  @@StartBracket@@2585@@EndBracket@@ - Potkin, V. @@StartBracket@@2646@@EndBracket@@ RUS Cup final 2010. }
11... Na5
{ The strongest follow-up. Black continues with his active plans on the queenside while White's initiative on the kingside is dead. }
12. O-O-O Nc4
{ Black has many threats, starting with eliminating the important dark-squared bishop on e3. It's quite difficult to suggest something reasonable to White - Black has a very strong initiative, as long as you are not resorting to some standard moves like ...d5 @@StartBracket@@closing the bishop on b7@@EndBracket@@ or castling long. }
