1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. Nc3
{ It's time to move to the Open Sicilian Nc3 setups if White doesn't fianchetto the bishop on g2 but plays some central-based moves. We will examine some of the lesser-played moves before moving to the main continuation in the next chapter. }
5... b5
{ Black stays true to the spirit of the Kan - play ...b5 once the white knight stands on c3 so that the pawn on e4 is under early pressure. }
6. Be3 Bb7 7. f3
{ White is playing the English Attack - this is a very popular choice against the Najdorf, some time ago it was often used to meet the Sicilian Taimanov as well. Also against the Kan system, there's some considerable venom, although exactly here it poses the least of the problems. }
7... Nf6
{ Black's idea is to continue with ...Qc7, push away White's queenside knight with ...b4, and then take over the center. Your opponent might be playing the English Attack against the Taimanov Sicilian but here it's not the same. }
8. Be2 { This is too weak and too slow. } 8... Nc6 9. Nxc6 Bxc6 10. a3 Qc7
{ White's setup looks awkward and has no ambition - Black can easily take over the game, starting with the dark squares. }
