{ Black stays true to the spirit of the Kan - play ...b5 once the white knight stands on c3 so that the pawn on e4 is under early pressure. }
6. Be3 Bb7 7. f3
{ White is playing the English Attack - this is a very popular choice against the Najdorf, some time ago it was often used to meet the Sicilian Taimanov as well. Also against the Kan system, there's some considerable venom, although exactly here it poses the least of the problems. }
7... Nf6
{ Black's idea is to continue with ...Qc7, push away White's queenside knight with ...b4, and then take over the center. Your opponent might be playing the English Attack against the Taimanov Sicilian but here it's not the same. }
8. Qd2 d5
{ What you have to understand about this tempting pawn push, either here or in a similar variation, is that it allows White to close the center, so Black loses a lot of dynamics, which is so common in Sicilian Kan. }
9. e5
{ The standard response - White closes Black's bishop on b7 and establishes an excellent outpost on d4. }
9... Nfd7 10. f4
{ Black has got a French Defense with an extra tempo @@StartBracket@@moves f2-f3-f4@@EndBracket@@, but the problem is that the variation for White strategically is quite sound. If Black tries to seek counterplay on the queenside with ...b4, ...a5, and ...Ba6, he's given up the extra tempo as the bishop moves again. }
10... b4 11. Nce2 Nc5 12. Ng3 h5 13. Bd3
{ White's game is easy, with great control of the central squares. All factors combined, White's position should be preferred. }
