{ Before pushing the central pawns, Black kicks away the white knight. Now the question is, where will it go?   9...Bb4?!  It's very tempting to ruin White's pawn structure, but remember that in the list of priorities, the pawn structure is in the last place. Piece activity is way higher.  10.a3!  Bxc3  11.Qxc3  Qxc3  12.bxc3  The development, two bishops, and the weak dark squares is a high price for just doubling the pawns.  12...d5  13.e5  Nfd7  14.f4  White has a great position. }
10. Nce2
{ This is a more careful move - White feels that the knight on a4 might cause more problems, thus he's seeking an alternative placement. The next move is quite important. }
10... e5
{ A very important move, typical for the structure. Black takes away from White the e5-square and only then will push forward the d-pawn. Notice that this is possible if the white knight is not standing on a4, otherwise, the weakness of the b6-square will play a major role. }
11. Nf5 d5
{ The Black king is still in the center, thus Black should always be a little cautious about the tactical tricks, but White is unable to use this as his kingside is undeveloped. }
12. exd5 Nxd5 13. Bf2 Nd7 { Black is very active in the center. } 14. Kb1 g6
15. Ne3 N7b6 16. Nxd5 Nxd5
{ We can probably wrap up the variation here and evaluate that if anybody is better here, it's Black due to the strong central pawn and active pieces.   This is how the game could continue:  17.c4!  bxc3  18.Nxc3  White forces some trades  18...Nxc3  19.Qxc3  Qxc3  20.bxc3  Rc8  Not only is Black attacking the pawn on c3, but also defending the c5-square so that the dark-squared bishop can be fianchettoed to g7 and the black king can castle short. }
