{ White is playing the English Attack - this is a very popular choice against the Najdorf, some time ago it was often used to meet the Sicilian Taimanov as well. Also against the Kan system, there's some considerable venom, although exactly here it poses the least of the problems. }
7... Nf6
{ Black's idea is to continue with ...Qc7, push away White's queenside knight with ...b4, and then take over the center. Your opponent might be playing the English Attack against the Taimanov Sicilian but here it's not the same. }
8. Qd2 Qc7
{ Now the ball is in White's court. Of course, the question is whether White is even aware of Black's idea and that here the English attack will play out completely differently than in Sicilian Najdorf or Taimanov. }
9. a3
{ If White makes sure that Black's ...b4 is not happening, go for the central breakthrough. }
9... d5 10. Bf4
{ White might try to get more favorable circumstances for the incoming pawn trade on d5 as playing Bf4 and pushing e5 next looks rather strange but this taunts Black to push forward the e-pawn and some crazy complications. Since we're not sure who is going to play this very rare line, we decided to mark it as informational. }
10... e5
{ Challenge accepted. It's worth mentioning that Black's  10...Bd6  is impossible due to a piece sacrifice on b5 and the incoming fork:  11.Bxb5+  axb5  12.Ndxb5+-  . }
11. Bxb5+ { One of the two potential sacrifices that White might consider. }
11... axb5 12. Ncxb5 Qe7 13. O-O-O
{ White is going completely berserk and throwing pieces at Black - you will appreciate the next move! }
13... Kd8
{ This must be the most spectacular move of the entire course! Black voluntarily starts to walk with the king, but the idea is to escape from the e-file while taking some pieces on the way. The d-file will remain closed. }
14. Rhe1 exd4 15. Bxb8 Qd7
{ Keeping in mind that the white queen has access to the a5-square, this is the strongest move - Black in return attacks another white piece and leaves the dangerous e-file. }
16. Qf4 Nh5 { Final simplification - White is forced to trade queens. } 17.
Qc7+ Qxc7 18. Bxc7+ Kd7 19. Be5 Ra5
{ Black dodges final tricks and simplifies the position. } 20. Nxd4 dxe4
{ There is a discovered check, but it gives White nothing. } 21. Nb3+ Rd5 22.
fxe4 Rxd1+ 23. Rxd1+ Kc8
{ Move after a move and the reality for White is about to kick in - the piece is still missing, but those 3 pawns for the piece on the queenside are very static. }
24. Rd4 Nf6 25. Na5 Ba8
{ Black is better. Now judge for yourself how important it would be to study this rare line with a MoveTrainer. Our best guess - it's not, but keep the following tactical ideas in your mind so that you've at least seen them. }
