11. Nd1
{ A logical retreat - White wants to fight for control of the d5-square. The awkward knight can be rerouted to e3 or help to push c3. }
11... d5 12. exd5 h5
{ Sicilian Najdorf says hello! The inclusion of this move seems to be stronger than capturing the pawn on d5 right away - Black wants to push away the white knight from d4 before capturing the pawn back. Black is threatening to get rid of the bishop with ...h4, but the pawn on d5 at the moment is not going anywhere. Maybe at some point, Black is now ready to explore ideas with ...g6 and ...Bh6. }
13. Nf5 { Since White is threatening to push d6, it's time to take the pawn. }
13... Nxd5 14. Nde3 Nxe3 15. Nxe3 Nc6
{ Black's position looks pretty safe - the temporary control of the d5-square alone can't guarantee White better chances. }
16. O-O-O h4
{ Black wants to play ...Nd4 which is immediately impossible due to the pin. After the bishop leaves, the black knight is ready to land on d4. }
17. Nd5 O-O-O
{ Very strong, otherwise Black will start to experience some problems due to the weak b6-square. Now an almost forced sequence starts. }
18. Nxc7
{ 18.Bf2  Qa5  19.Bb6  Qxa2  White's king is about to get mated in  1. } 18...
Rxd2 19. Kxd2 hxg3 20. Nxa6
{ The obvious choice - the pawn on a6 seems to be for free. However, now the white knight on a6 is stuck.   20.Bxa6  We're not sure who would choose this continuation over the obvious choice, but we have to show it as well.  20...Kxc7  21.Bxb7  Kxb7  22.hxg3  Rg8!  It's very important to keep rooks on the board, otherwise Black has no counterplay against White's passed pawns on the queenside. The position is unclear. }
20... gxh2 21. Bd3 e4
{ A beautiful move - Black defends against the check on f5 and uses the fact that White can't capture with the bishop. }
22. Bxe4 Nd8 { Black is going after the knight. } 23. Bd3
{ 23.Bxb7?!  Kxb7  24.Kc1  Nc6  White drops the knight on a6. } 23... Rh6 24.
Bf5+ Ne6 25. Bd3 Nd8
{ Black can agree to a repetition or keep pushing as it's not very clear how White will bring the knight back to the game. Black's pawn on h2 can become lethal. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) 5.Nc3 Rare Moves"]
[Black "5.Nc3 b5 6.Be3 Bb7 #24"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. Nc3
{ It's time to move to the Open Sicilian Nc3 setups if White doesn't fianchetto the bishop on g2 but plays some central-based moves. We will examine some of the lesser-played moves before moving to the main continuation in the next chapter. }
5... b5
{ Black stays true to the spirit of the Kan - play ...b5 once the white knight stands on c3 so that the pawn on e4 is under early pressure. }
6. Be3 Bb7 7. f3
{ White is playing the English Attack - this is a very popular choice against the Najdorf, some time ago it was often used to meet the Sicilian Taimanov as well. Also against the Kan system, there's some considerable venom, although exactly here it poses the least of the problems. }
7... Nf6
{ Black's idea is to continue with ...Qc7, push away White's queenside knight with ...b4, and then take over the center. Your opponent might be playing the English Attack against the Taimanov Sicilian but here it's not the same. }
8. Qd2 Qc7
{ Now the ball is in White's court. Of course, the question is whether White is even aware of Black's idea and that here the English attack will play out completely differently than in Sicilian Najdorf or Taimanov. }
9. Bf4
{ This very rare move is a common idea in the Sicilian Taimanov when White plays the English Attack. This is the best that White can do in the position. }
9... e5
{ A very principled approach. It does not win a piece as White can keep the pin alive. }
10. Bg3
{ White's threats are to rearrange his d4-knight to e3 and take over the d5-square in comfort. Black has no choice but to react immediately. }
10... b4
{ Now White has three reasonable retreats with the knight as the b1 and e2-squares look very passive. }
11. Nd1
{ A logical retreat - White wants to fight for control of the d5-square. The awkward knight can be rerouted to e3 or help to push c3. }
11... d5 12. exd5 h5
{ Sicilian Najdorf says hello! The inclusion of this move seems to be stronger than capturing the pawn on d5 right away - Black wants to push away the white knight from d4 before capturing the pawn back. Black is threatening to get rid of the bishop with ...h4, but the pawn on d5 at the moment is not going anywhere. Maybe at some point, Black is now ready to explore ideas with ...g6 and ...Bh6. }
13. h4
{ Most likely, this will be the 'automatic' response from your opponent to keep the bishop on g3 but the pin - alive. }
13... Nxd5 14. Ne3
{ White is interested in keeping the knight on d4 as long as possible for more active options in the center. }
14... Nxe3 15. Qxe3 Nd7
{ The black knight now can't be developed to the more active c6-square as it would drop the pawn on e5. }
16. O-O-O
{ Including h4 and ...h5 gives Black some extra options, otherwise why go through all the hassle and not take the pawn on d5 right away? }
16... Rc8
{ As an alternative, Black can now play  16...g6  as well, with an idea to bring the bishop on h6. Without including the h-pawn push, this obviously would be impossible. }
17. Bd3 Bc5 18. Bf5 O-O
{ The game is sharp, but Black's chances are not worse. A potential way for the game to continue is  19.Qe2  Bd6  20.Nb3  Rcd8  21.Rhe1  Rfe8  Black's center is solid, the weakening of the kingside with ...h5 does not play a big role. Black is thinking about playing ...a5-a4 at some point. }
