[Round "?"]
[White "11) 5.Nc3 Rare Moves"]
[Black "5.Nc3 b5 6.Be2 Bb7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. Nc3
{ It's time to move to the Open Sicilian Nc3 setups if White doesn't fianchetto the bishop on g2 but plays some central-based moves. We will examine some of the lesser-played moves before moving to the main continuation in the next chapter. }
5... b5
{ Black stays true to the spirit of the Kan - play ...b5 once the white knight stands on c3 so that the pawn on e4 is under early pressure. }
6. Be2
{ A standard developing move, but it also somewhat ignores the 'potential problem' of the e4-pawn. Maybe White is preparing to sacrifice it? }
6... Bb7 7. Bf3
{ If White positions the bishop on f3 to defend the pawn, from a strategic point of view it's just wrong as it's passive and also blocks the advancement of the f-pawn shortly. White could have played g3 and Bg2 then. Perhaps White might play an early e5 to open the bishop and the e4-square for the knight, but then the pawn on e5 might become vulnerable. We already discussed that the e5 push is not always an achievement for White. }
7... Ne7
{ Black stays aware that White might push e5 - that's why the traditional f6 square for the development is out of the question. }
8. O-O Nbc6
{ When using this maneuver to trade a pair of knights, make sure that you never have the queen on c7 while executing it - then you will receive a very traditional @@StartFEN@@r3kb1r/1bqpnppp/p1n1p3/1p6/3NP3/2N2B2/PPP2PPP/R1BQ1RK1 w kq - 0 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Ndxb5  sacrifice and after  9...axb5  10.Nxb5  Qb6  ,  landing the white knight on d6 and a fork on f7 afterward.  11.Nd6+  Kd8  12.Nxf7++-  . }
9. Nxc6 Nxc6
{ Black is about to get nice control over the central squares. Indeed, the knight controls the d4 and e5-squares while the d5-square is protected. }
10. Bf4 Rc8
{ Black is very flexible with the plans. Since White might be thinking about an early Bd6, that's where ...Rc8 comes into play. Even if White takes over the d6-square, it's going to be temporary. Watch the following clickable line.   11.Bd6?  Bxd6  12.Qxd6  is seemingly an achievement for White, right? Well, no!  12...Qc7  13.Rad1  Qxd6  14.Rxd6  White has seemingly made the right moves, but his position is quite dangerous. The square on d6 alone doesn't do any good, but Black can establish quick counterplay on the queenside.   14...Ke7  , the e7-square for these types of positions is the perfect spot for the king, assuming that the queens are off the board!  15.Rfd1  Ne5  16.Be2  g5!  The d6-square is useless this time. The white bishop is already forced to guard the c4-square against the knight jump - another reason why the passive Bf3 earlier is not a great idea. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11) 5.Nc3 Rare Moves"]
[Black "5.Nc3 b5 6.Be2 Bb7 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. Nc3
{ It's time to move to the Open Sicilian Nc3 setups if White doesn't fianchetto the bishop on g2 but plays some central-based moves. We will examine some of the lesser-played moves before moving to the main continuation in the next chapter. }
5... b5
{ Black stays true to the spirit of the Kan - play ...b5 once the white knight stands on c3 so that the pawn on e4 is under early pressure. }
6. Be2
{ A standard developing move, but it also somewhat ignores the 'potential problem' of the e4-pawn. Maybe White is preparing to sacrifice it? }
6... Bb7 7. O-O
{ We already know this idea of sacrificing the central pawn from Chapter 9. }
7... b4
{ A principled approach - don't be afraid to take the pawn.   7...Qc7  this multi-purpose move here is too slow.  8.Re1  White is back with the Nd5 ideas.  8...Nc6  9.Nxc6  , an annoying precision from White! The black knight was heading to the e5-square.   9...dxc6  Necessary, otherwise White will include 10.a4 and then jump with the knight to d5. If only Black would be in time to play ...Bd6 and ...Ne7.  10.e5!  This is strong - White does not allow Black to block the e5-square with a minor piece and will launch an early kingside offensive.  10...Rd8  11.Bd3  c5  12.Qh5  White's advantage is obvious due to the lead in development. }
8. Nd5
{ This is something that after the ...b4 push you should be always expecting. Here, however, White is not ready for this kind of action. }
8... exd5 9. exd5 Bc5
{ If not for this move, maybe White's idea would be quite interesting. Now the black king gets access to the f8 square. }
10. Re1 Kf8
{ Doghri, N. @@StartBracket@@2342@@EndBracket@@ - Maiwald, J. @@StartBracket@@2529@@EndBracket@@ Tunis op 4th 2000. }
11. Nb3
{ If White tries to be smart and starts with  11.a3  to open the queenside, there's a very strong  11...Qb6  and the pin is very annoying. }
11... Bb6 12. a3
{ We already had this type of position in Chapter 9 where the light-squared bishop was on g2. The position is almost the same, except that Black has not managed to play ...Nf6 just yet due to the difference in tempo. }
12... bxa3
{ If you remember that variation, here White already had to commit himself to Nb3, thus he can't open the position any further with b4. That's why we can safely take the pawn, however,  12...a5  should also work. }
13. Rxa3 d6 14. Bf4 Ne7 { It doesn't look like White has a real attack. } *

