1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. Nc3
{ It's time to move to the Open Sicilian Nc3 setups if White doesn't fianchetto the bishop on g2 but plays some central-based moves. We will examine some of the lesser-played moves before moving to the main continuation in the next chapter. }
5... b5
{ Black stays true to the spirit of the Kan - play ...b5 once the white knight stands on c3 so that the pawn on e4 is under early pressure. }
6. Be2
{ A standard developing move, but it also somewhat ignores the 'potential problem' of the e4-pawn. Maybe White is preparing to sacrifice it? }
6... Bb7 7. O-O
{ We already know this idea of sacrificing the central pawn from Chapter 9. }
7... b4
{ A principled approach - don't be afraid to take the pawn.   7...Qc7  this multi-purpose move here is too slow.  8.Re1  White is back with the Nd5 ideas.  8...Nc6  9.Nxc6  , an annoying precision from White! The black knight was heading to the e5-square.   9...dxc6  Necessary, otherwise White will include 10.a4 and then jump with the knight to d5. If only Black would be in time to play ...Bd6 and ...Ne7.  10.e5!  This is strong - White does not allow Black to block the e5-square with a minor piece and will launch an early kingside offensive.  10...Rd8  11.Bd3  c5  12.Qh5  White's advantage is obvious due to the lead in development. }
8. Na4 Bxe4 9. Bf3
{ The biggest danger for Black here is to play with the same approach as in Chapter 9. In this case, it's not quite the same. }
9... Nf6 10. Bxe4 Nxe4 11. Re1
{ This is the same position as in Chapter 9 with fianchettoing the light-squared bishop on g2, only there the white pawn is standing on g3 - so where's the difference? While here White does not have additional extra control of the f4-square for the bishop @@StartBracket@@which might be important@@EndBracket@@, in return he gets access to the g3-square for the queen. This will prove to be a critical difference if Black tries to play in the same manner as in Chapter 9 and the fianchetto setup. }
11... d5
{ A necessary move, otherwise, White's attack becomes too strong.   11...Nc5?  Here this retreat is a huge mistake. Is it obvious? No, but try not to mix up the two lines.  12.Nxc5  Bxc5  13.Qf3  Ra7  , Black continues in the same manner, and seemingly nothing is wrong.  14.Nf5  O-O  15.Nxg7!  In Chapter 9 there was no such follow-up because it did not make any sense!  15...Kxg7  16.Qg3+!  But here it does! This check with the pawn on g3 is not possible.  16...Kh8  17.Qe5+  f6  18.Qxc5  The weak king, the shattered pawn structure, and the strong white bishop - this makes Black's defense very difficult. It might as well already be lost. }
12. Nxe6
{ This motif is common, but with or without the white pawn on g3, it's not dangerous for Black. }
12... fxe6 13. Qh5+ g6 14. Qe5 Qf6 { Black has to give up the extra piece. }
15. Rxe4 Qxe5 16. Rxe5 Kf7
{ Despite White's fireworks, Black is perfectly fine. } *

