14. Qh5 { Something is about to hit Black on e6. } 14... Ne4 15. Nxe6 g6 16.
Nc7+
{ The point of White's combination.  16.Qe5??  does not work for White.  16...fxe6  17.Qxh8  Qe7  and Black's two knights are superior to the white rook. }
16... Qxc7 17. Qxd5 { Black can't keep his extra material. } 17... f5 18. Qxa8
{ Compared with a very similar line in Chapter 9,  the white pawn here does not stand on g3, thus this line for Black is quite playable. }
18... Bb4
{ It seems to be stronger than  18...Bc5  , which allows White to trade the bishops and open the position for his rooks. }
19. Re2 O-O 20. Qd5+ { The queens are about to disappear from the board. }
20... Qf7 21. Qxf7+ Kxf7 22. Be3 Rd8
{ The game might continue like this:  23.a3  Bc5  Perhaps this is not mandatory - you can try to keep more pieces on the board and retreat with the bishop to e7. White is still pushing.  24.Bxc5  Nxc5  25.Rae1  Rd6  , Black gives up another pawn to activate his pieces.  26.Re7+  Kf6  27.Rxh7  Nc6  28.b4  Ne6  , even though Black is quite active and can make a draw, it's only White who can win this. Don't trade the rooks. }
