[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) 5.Nc3 Mainline"]
[Black "5.Nc3 b5 6.Bd3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. Nc3
{ It's time to move to the Open Sicilian Nc3 setups if White doesn't fianchetto the bishop on g2 but plays some central-based moves. We have examined some of the lesser-played moves in the previous chapter and now we're moving to the main continuation. }
5... b5
{ Black stays true to the spirit of the Kan - play ...b5 once the white knight stands on c3 so that the pawn on e4 is under early pressure. }
6. Bd3
{ By a big margin, this is the main move in the position, directed against Black's chosen setup. The bishop on d3 overprotects the pawn on e4 and this means that White most likely won't have to include a3, defending against the ...b4 push. White is quite flexible with his ideas on the kingside, but with the light-squared bishop standing on the b1-h7 diagonal, it's safe to assume that White will be thinking either about an e5 push or an Nd5 motif, using the open e-file. }
6... Bb7 7. O-O Nc6
{ You probably remember, we have mentioned this a couple of times already - trading a pair of knights usually favors Black. Black is also flexible with his ideas - there's no need to rush with ...d6 and thus close the dark-squared bishop. The kingside knight might be developed to f6, but an alternative is also ...Ne7-g6. }
8. Be3
{ Quite a rare move, giving Black plenty of choices - a creative mind would think about alternatives like ...Ne5 or ...Nb4 to capture the bishop on d3 and easily finish the development. The following moves make the most sense though. }
8... Qc7 { This is simple and good, keeping many options to improvise. } 9. Qe2
Nf6
{ Since White has committed himself to an early Be3, he is not ready to push e5 right away, thus this is the perfect square for the black knight. }
10. f4
{ Now Black gets to execute one of the most typical ideas of the Sicilian Kan. }
10... Nxd4 11. Bxd4 Bc5
{ Black first trades the dark-squared bishops before playing ...d6. } 12. Bxc5
Qxc5+ 13. Kh1
{ Don't miss White's e5 push with Ne4 next, thus Black's follow-up makes perfect sense. }
13... b4 14. Nd1 d6
{ Black has an easy game on the queenside and can already in earnest think about taking over the game. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12) 5.Nc3 Mainline"]
[Black "5.Nc3 b5 6.Bd3 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. Nc3
{ It's time to move to the Open Sicilian Nc3 setups if White doesn't fianchetto the bishop on g2 but plays some central-based moves. We have examined some of the lesser-played moves in the previous chapter and now we're moving to the main continuation. }
5... b5
{ Black stays true to the spirit of the Kan - play ...b5 once the white knight stands on c3 so that the pawn on e4 is under early pressure. }
6. Bd3
{ By a big margin, this is the main move in the position, directed against Black's chosen setup. The bishop on d3 overprotects the pawn on e4 and this means that White most likely won't have to include a3, defending against the ...b4 push. White is quite flexible with his ideas on the kingside, but with the light-squared bishop standing on the b1-h7 diagonal, it's safe to assume that White will be thinking either about an e5 push or an Nd5 motif, using the open e-file. }
6... Bb7 7. O-O Nc6
{ You probably remember, we have mentioned this a couple of times already - trading a pair of knights usually favors Black. Black is also flexible with his ideas - there's no need to rush with ...d6 and thus close the dark-squared bishop. The kingside knight might be developed to f6, but an alternative is also ...Ne7-g6. }
8. Nxc6
{ This move is usually played in a heartbeat - the alternatives look somewhat less appealing. If the knight retreats somewhere, then Black has nothing to worry about, so the only reasonable alternative seems to be to defend it. }
8... Bxc6 9. a3
{ White could try to include this rather useless move with an idea that it might be necessary at some point in the game. It is also an attempt by White to gain an idea of what setup Black will choose. Some of the lines might transpose to Chapter 11. }
9... Bd6
{ Typical to the Sicilian Kan! Black brings out the dark-squared bishop first, and then decides where to put the kingside knight. There's a good chance that it will jump to e7-g6 to fight for control of the dark squares. }
10. f4
{ White is starting active operations on the kingside, which makes perfect sense, but now, suddenly, Black can change the direction of the fight.   10.Be3  can transpose to one of the lines of Chapter 11.  10...Qc7  11.f4  Nh6  Black develops his pieces in a very creative way! }
10... Bc5+
{ Not the only move, but it's fun! Black gives up a tempo and positions the bishop on a more active diagonal before White can play Be3. An alternative is to play ...Ne7, castle short and push ...f5. }
11. Kh1 Qh4 12. Bd2 Nf6
{ Black has an unexpected early initiative on the kingside, threatening with the banal ...Ng4! }
13. Be1 Qh5 14. Be2
{ Quite principled - the queen trade can't cause Black any problems. } 14...
Qg6 15. f5 exf5 16. Rxf5 d6
{ Black is just in time to cover all of his weaknesses, and has a very dynamic game. }
17. Qd3 O-O 18. Bh4 Rfe8
{ Black equalizes and has prepared some tricks.   This is how the game could continue - the following tactical trick is quite important to know:  19.Bxf6  Bxe4!  20.Nxe4  Qxf5  21.Bf3  White doesn't have a choice, or he's risking himself.  21...gxf6  22.Nxc5  Qxc5  23.Bxa8  Rxa8  The position has been dramatically simplified. Black has an extra pawn, but due to the weak pawns, White keeps the balance.  24.Qg3+  Qg5  It is best to give up the pawn to consolidate the position.  25.Qxd6  Kg7  the position is balanced. }
