[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. Nc3
{ It's time to move to the Open Sicilian Nc3 setups if White doesn't fianchetto the bishop on g2 but plays some central-based moves. We have examined some of the lesser-played moves in the previous chapter and now we're moving to the main continuation. }
5... b5
{ Black stays true to the spirit of the Kan - play ...b5 once the white knight stands on c3 so that the pawn on e4 is under early pressure. }
6. Bd3
{ By a big margin, this is the main move in the position, directed against Black's chosen setup. The bishop on d3 overprotects the pawn on e4 and this means that White most likely won't have to include a3, defending against the ...b4 push. White is quite flexible with his ideas on the kingside, but with the light-squared bishop standing on the b1-h7 diagonal, it's safe to assume that White will be thinking either about an e5 push or an Nd5 motif, using the open e-file. }
6... Bb7 7. O-O Nc6
{ You probably remember, we have mentioned this a couple of times already - trading a pair of knights usually favors Black. Black is also flexible with his ideas - there's no need to rush with ...d6 and thus close the dark-squared bishop. The kingside knight might be developed to f6, but an alternative is also ...Ne7-g6. }
8. Nxc6
{ This move is usually played in a heartbeat - the alternatives look somewhat less appealing. If the knight retreats somewhere, then Black has nothing to worry about, so the only reasonable alternative seems to be to defend it. }
8... Bxc6 9. Qe2
{ Positioning the queen on e2 to do the job of the rook is not dangerous for Black. }
9... Bc5 { Black slows down White's f4 and wants to play ...Ne7 next. } 10. a4
b4 11. Nd5
{ As you will already have noticed, this is standard. White includes a4 first before jumping with the knight to d5, trying to initiate some hostilities, but the main problem with the plan is that Black doesn't have to take the knight or rush anywhere. There's a fair chance that the white knight will retreat in no time. }
11... Bb7
{ Black can afford to consolidate his position a little! The light-squared bishop stands much better on b7, not only defending the pawn on a6 but already threatening to take the knight on d5 for real. }
12. Be3
{ White would love to trade the dark-squared bishops first, before landing with the knight on e3. }
12... Qa5
{ If White wants to take on c5, this will activate the black queen. White has absolutely nothing here. }
13. Bxc5 Qxc5 14. Qe3 { The black queen on c5 is too active to tolerate it. }
14... Qxe3 15. Nxe3 Nf6
{ However, Black still has nothing to worry about and is enjoying a healthy development.   This is how the game could continue:  16.e5  Nd5  17.Nc4  Ke7  18.Nd6  .  Although White has occupied the d6-square, it's an irrelevant achievement. The knight on d6 might not hold for long.  18...Bc6  19.f4  However, if White tries to strengthen the position of the knight, Black has a nasty surprise.  19...f5!  Suddenly, Black has a very easy-going initiative on the kingside. The white knight on d6 looks great, but what exactly is it doing there? }
