12... Qa5
{ If White wants to take on c5, this will activate the black queen. White has absolutely nothing here. }
13. Qg4
{ This is one of the little drawbacks of developing the bishop early - White can make a queen jump, bothering the g7 pawn. }
13... Kf8
{ You don't have to castle at all costs - the black king feels perfectly safe on f8. Now Black is about to gain some important tempi. }
14. Bxc5+ Qxc5 15. Ne3 h5
{ Exactly this move, and not the tempting  15...Nf6!  You will understand the difference immediately. }
16. Qf4
{ White is still ambitious and thinking about pushing e5 next. If he retreated the queen to e2, Black would just bring out the knight to f6 and enjoy a good game. Here you have something better. }
16... g5 17. Qf3 f5
{ What a shocking way to fight for the initiative!   A potential follow-up from here:  18.Nc4  Nf6  19.Nd2  White is on the defensive already.  19...Ke7  20.Qe2  fxe4  Black would like to keep the knights on the board if possible.  21.Nxe4  Bxe4  22.Bxe4  Rag8  . Positioning the queen on e5 is also good, aiming for a good rook endgame. Here Black can develop a kingside attack. If you are forced to trade all minor pieces, make sure that the queens get traded as well, otherwise, the black king is too exposed. }
