8. Nxc6
{ This move is usually played in a heartbeat - the alternatives look somewhat less appealing. If the knight retreats somewhere, then Black has nothing to worry about, so the only reasonable alternative seems to be to defend it. }
8... Bxc6 9. Re1
{ This is the only move that gives White some hope for an opening advantage. }
9... Qb8
{ This is a classic multi-plan move. In addition to creating a counterplay on the b8-h2 diagonal, Black evades the Nd5 threat with a tempo, that's why here this move looks better than the traditional ...Qc7. White has many ways to continue here, but Black's response almost always remains the same. Let's have a look at them. }
10. Qe2 { White prepares to meet Black's ...Bd6 with the e5 push. } 10... Bd6
11. e5 Bc7
{ Black is ready to organize a serious pressure against the white pawn on e5 - it's so easy for White to go wrong. }
12. f4
{ It's difficult to believe, but after this inaccurate move White can get into trouble very fast! }
12... f5
{ After a couple of moves, Black will organize a ...g5 thrust with a powerful initiative. }
13. Be3 Ne7 14. a3 O-O 15. Qf2
{ White is already in trouble, and it's becoming difficult to come up with a good plan. What exactly is White supposed to do against the ...g5 push? }
15... g5
{ Black is happy to trade the g-pawn for the e-pawn, which would open the dark-squared bishop on c7. }
16. Qg3 Rf7 17. h4
{ All of this happened in Edouard, R. @@StartBracket@@2688@@EndBracket@@ - Dearing, E. @@StartBracket@@2418@@EndBracket@@ BCF-chT 1213 @@StartBracket@@4NCL@@EndBracket@@ 2013. Black could have continued with a logical plan to open the queenside and get a crushing attack. }
17... h6 18. hxg5 hxg5
{ Strategically, White is already lost as he can't trade off any of Black's attacking pieces to ease the pressure. }
