11... Ne7 { Black continues the development traditionally. } 12. Nxe7 Bxe7 13.
e5
{ White makes sure that for Black there's no easy way to hide the black king on the kingside, or it takes too much time. }
13... h6
{ To muddy the waters, Black can be quite creative and stop White from trading the dark-squared bishops and thus getting an easy game. At the same time, Black is also planning to do an expansion at the queenside with ...b4, ...a5-a4, and eventually ...Ra5.  The engines tend to overestimate this position in White's favor. Black's game is very straightforward, while White has to navigate through a million nuances. The immediate light-squared bishop trade poses Black no problems. }
14. Bd2
{ If White plays some normal developing moves, Black quickly sets up his perfect position. }
14... Qb7
{ Not only an aggressive move but targeted against the light-squared bishop trade. }
15. Qh3 { Or  15.Qg4  , Black would play the same. } 15... h5
{ A friendly reminder that Black can be very creative on the kingside. This move is also targeted against White's Qg3. }
16. Rad1
{ 16.Qg3?  White is careless.  16...h4!  17.Qxg7  O-O-O  Black's threats suddenly became huge! }
16... b4
{ White is still struggling to understand what exactly he's supposed to do here. }
