11... Kf8
{ If you are feeling bold and trust your defensive skills, or if the main continuation doesn't inspire you, you can consider gambling a little. Black is threatening to take the knight on d5. }
12. e5
{ White calls the bluff! We are not sure how obvious this move is for an average player. White sacrifices a pawn for a long-term initiative. }
12... Bxe5
{ Capturing on e5 first is stronger as it forces White to awkwardly position his rook. }
13. Rxe5
{ 13.Nb4  This is an alternative continuation, but still a less popular one.  13...Bf6  14.Nxc6  dxc6  15.a4  Ne7  Black will centralize the knight, strengthening the defense. }
13... Bxd5 14. Bf4
{ 14.Rxd5!?  Experienced players may find this to be a simpler move but the final position is not so clear.  14...Nf6!  15.Rxb5  Qxb5!  Avoiding unnecessary sidelines.  16.Qxb5  axb5  17.Bxb5  Ke7  Although White has two connected passed pawns on the queenside and two bishops, Black is pretty active, thus Black should be able to hold this. }
14... Nf6 15. Qh4 d6
{ This is where the almost forced line ends. Even though Black has an extra pawn, the position looks quite risky to play, but it depends against who you are playing and what his playing style is. White's compensation is obvious and maybe even more, but this also forces him to charge forward. Use with great caution! }
16. Rg5
{ 16.Ree1  the natural retreat might not be the best.  16...Ke7!  17.Rad1  h6  Anatoly Karpov would be proud of this idea! }
16... Ne8
{ Black wants to play ...Qd8 next and try to force the queen trade, but the general idea is to slowly untangle.   This is how the game could continue:  17.Rg3  e5  18.Bd2  h5  19.Re1  f6  . Black manages to rearrange his pieces, and White's advantage starts to dissipate.  20.f4  Qa7+  21.Be3  Qe7  This is already just unclear. }
