10. e5
{ If White pushes an early e5, this signals that he wants to lift either the knight or the bishop to e4. The best is to stop it before White has the chance to go for it. }
10... b4 11. Nb1
{ The white knight can't jump to e4 because the pawn on e5 would be lost. }
11... Ne7 { Black's setup is the same - the knight is heading to g6. } 12. Nd2
a5 13. Nc4 Ng6 14. Be4 Qb7
{ If White wants to trade the light-squared bishops, do it under your terms. The black queen on c6 will be very active. The weakness on d6 doesn't play an important role.   A potential follow-up from here:  15.Qd3  Be7  16.Bxg6  hxg6  17.Bg5  This idea is not to be missed. Probably even if White trades the dark-squared bishops and lands the knight on d6, it won't be anything dramatic, but if you want to be sure, just trade the knight.  17...Bd5  The simplest choice - Black can also pick up the gauntlet and capture the pawn on g2 for a very sharp position.  18.Bxe7  Intermezzo  18...Bxc4  19.Qxc4  Kxe7  20.Qc5  Ke8  The weak pawn on d7 is compensated by his cousin on c2 - the position is balanced. }
