{ This is a classic multi-plan move. In addition to creating a counterplay on the b8-h2 diagonal, Black evades the Nd5 threat with a tempo, that's why here this move looks better than the traditional ...Qc7. White has many ways to continue here, but Black's response almost always remains the same. Let's have a look at them. }
10. Qg4
{ White brings into action the heavy artillery. Now Black's ...Bd6 and ...Ne7 maneuver is not possible for obvious reasons. }
10... Nf6 11. Qh4
{ The white queen gets here also via the h5-square, it does not matter. } 11...
Bd6
{ The dark-squared bishop is still developed via d6, only the knight's route has changed. }
12. Ne2
{ It's very risky for White to play  12.f4  as it would expose the king too much, handing over to Black an immediate initiative  @@StartBracket@@...Bc5+ and ...h5 followed by ...Ng4 are legitimate ideas@@EndBracket@@. }
12... Be5 13. c3 b4
{ Black is very aggressive on the queenside and is trying to provoke White to start an action, like the f4 push. }
14. Nd4
{ 14.f4  this careless move can seriously backfire.  14...Qb6+  15.Kh1?  This standard retreat here is a mistake.  15...Nxe4  16.Bxe4  Bf6!  due to this intermezzo move, Black wins material. }
14... bxc3 15. bxc3 Bb5
{ Black sacrifices a pawn to activate his queenside pieces and finish development. }
16. Rb1 Qc8 17. Bxb5 axb5 18. Nxb5 O-O
{ White can't hold onto his extra pawn.   This is how the game could continue from here:  19.Ba3  d6  20.Bxd6  , necessary as taking with the knight is a mistake.   20.Nxd6?  Qc6  21.Nb5  White can't keep everything together - the entire queenside is hanging.  21...Rfb8  22.f4  Rxb5  23.Rxb5  is a nice idea.  23...Bc7!  24.Rb3  Rxa3!  25.Rxa3  Qc5+  26.Kh1  Qxa3  Black's two minor pieces should dominate the rook.  20...Bxd6  21.Nxd6  Qxc3  .  The white pawn on a2 won't survive, Black is too active.  22.e5  Nd7  23.Qg3  Qxg3  24.hxg3  Rxa2  . In the end, the position is just equal. }
