1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. Nc3
{ It's time to move to the Open Sicilian Nc3 setups if White doesn't fianchetto the bishop on g2 but plays some central-based moves. We have examined some of the lesser-played moves in the previous chapter and now we're moving to the main continuation. }
5... b5
{ Black stays true to the spirit of the Kan - play ...b5 once the white knight stands on c3 so that the pawn on e4 is under early pressure. }
6. Bd3
{ By a big margin, this is the main move in the position, directed against Black's chosen setup. The bishop on d3 overprotects the pawn on e4 and this means that White most likely won't have to include a3, defending against the ...b4 push. White is quite flexible with his ideas on the kingside, but with the light-squared bishop standing on the b1-h7 diagonal, it's safe to assume that White will be thinking either about an e5 push or an Nd5 motif, using the open e-file. }
6... Bb7 7. O-O Nc6
{ You probably remember, we have mentioned this a couple of times already - trading a pair of knights usually favors Black. Black is also flexible with his ideas - there's no need to rush with ...d6 and thus close the dark-squared bishop. The kingside knight might be developed to f6, but an alternative is also ...Ne7-g6. }
8. Nxc6
{ This move is usually played in a heartbeat - the alternatives look somewhat less appealing. If the knight retreats somewhere, then Black has nothing to worry about, so the only reasonable alternative seems to be to defend it. }
8... Bxc6 9. Re1
{ This is the only move that gives White some hope for an opening advantage. }
9... Qb8
{ This is a classic multi-plan move. In addition to creating a counterplay on the b8-h2 diagonal, Black evades the Nd5 threat with a tempo, that's why here this move looks better than the traditional ...Qc7. White has many ways to continue here, but Black's response almost always remains the same. Let's have a look at them. }
10. a4
{ White may want to include this move before shoving the queenside knight to d5 for better prospects - this continuation in practice has been White's top choice so far. }
10... bxa4 { Black diverts White's attention from the Nd5 maneuver. } 11. Nxa4
Bd6
{ Although the way of developing pieces is typical, the arising position is very fresh. Indian GM Pragganandhaa has played this position already twice. }
12. g3
{ This is suggested by the engines - White wants to execute the same Be3 and Nb6 idea but at the expense of the king's safety. For a human being to go here is quite difficult, especially taking into account that Black can push forward the h-pawn. }
12... h5 13. Be3 { Otherwise White has nothing much to fight for. } 13... h4
{ Black is threatening to take on g3 and sacrifice the bishop. } 14. Qg4
{ This is another semi-defensive move, but Black quickly gets a rich game. }
14... hxg3 15. hxg3 Nf6 16. Qxg7 Ke7
{ Suddenly, Black's attack on the kingside starts to look real - White has forgotten all about his plan to go after the a6-pawn. }
17. Bg5 Be5
{ The position is balanced and Black can at least repeat the position with ... Rg8-h8-g8.   A potential follow-up:  18.f4  Bd4+  19.Kf1  Qg8  Black keeps the game going! It's still possible to finish the game in a draw by attacking the queen with the rook.  20.Qxg8  Raxg8  21.Kg2  Rh5  Exchange sacrifice on g5 is imminent.  22.Nc3  Rhxg5  23.fxg5  Rxg5  24.Rxa6  Be5  Black has a lot of amazing dynamic opportunities, but the game remains equal if White makes no mistakes. }
