13. Be3 { White is aiming at Nb6 tricks, attacking the black rook on a8. }
13... Bh2+
{ Before playing ...Bf4 and thus trading off the dark-squared bishops, Black gives this intermezzo check to weaken the control of the f2-pawn. }
14. Kh1 Bf4 15. Bd4
{ If White is forced to trade the dark-squared bishops, Black easily holds together the queenside. Thus, it's understandable that White wants to dodge the trade, at least for the time being. However, now the game becomes highly tactical and it's easy to miss one shot if you are not careful. }
15... O-O
{ Don't forget about your development - hunting White's dark-squared bishop can wait. }
16. Nb6
{ This is tempting, but it tactically backfires. White's bishop on d4 is quite vulnerable. }
16... e5 17. Bc5 d6
{ White can't take on a8 because Black will capture the bishop first, getting two minor pieces for a rook. Thus, White has no choice. }
18. Bxd6 Qxd6 19. Nxa8 Bxa8 20. Rxa6 Qc7
{ Black's position should be preferred, but avoid trading any pieces as it will increase the power of the passed pawns on the queenside. }
