[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) 5.Be2"]
[Black " 5.Be2 Nf6 6.f3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. Be2
{ A very interesting move order - White is provoking the black knight to f6 and only then plays Nc3. This also means that Black will be unable to continue the traditional plan of ...b5, ...Bb7, and ...Nc6. Please note that even though Black has access to the early ...d5 move and can even capture with the queen, White is ahead in development thus such an approach to open the position could seriously backfire. }
5... Nf6 6. f3
{ White wants to set up a Maroczy Bind with c4 and Nc3. However, pretty much nobody plays like this as Black can immediately start active operations in the center.   6.e5?  Qa5+  this is one of the standard traps in the Sicilian - White loses the pawn on e5 for no compensation. }
6... d5
{ There are other good continuations like first  6...e5  and then  --  7...d5  as well but this one is the most straightforward. }
7. e5 Nfd7 8. f4
{ We have the French Defense with an extra tempo due to White's f-pawn movements. }
8... Nc6 9. c3 Qb6
{ Black is immediately pressing the white knight on d4 - it could be difficult for White to come up with a good follow-up. }
10. Be3 { Sort of necessary, but it costs a pawn. } 10... Nxd4 11. Bxd4 Qxb2
{ Black collects a free pawn. Now White has to show, what exactly he has for it. }
12. Nd2 Bc5 13. Nb3 Ba7
{ Black keeps White's pawn structure shattered and keeps a small trick. } 14.
O-O Qxc3 { There it is! The queen can't be taken due to the pin. } 15. Bxa7
Rxa7 16. Rc1 Qe3+ 17. Kh1 Ra8
{ White is down two pawns - that might be too much. Black will castle short in a moment but don't blunder the queen please. }
*

