[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. Be2
{ A very interesting move order - White is provoking the black knight to f6 and only then plays Nc3. This also means that Black will be unable to continue the traditional plan of ...b5, ...Bb7, and ...Nc6. Please note that even though Black has access to the early ...d5 move and can even capture with the queen, White is ahead in development thus such an approach to open the position could seriously backfire. }
5... Nf6 6. Qd3
{ A very modern idea that deserves serious attention. White once again is aiming for the Maroczy Bind setup. Actually, in many Sicilian Defense variations, an early Qd3 is becoming a trend. }
6... e5
{ Our proposition - be modern as well! Black makes sure that White can't walk past the e-pawn and prepares the d-pawn push. }
7. Nf3 d5
{ With the White knight on f3, this works right away - don't delay the solution for later. }
8. exd5
{ Apparently White can play it as the incoming ...e4 does not win a piece. }
8... e4 9. Qe3 Be7
{ Black closes the e-file and will capture the pawn on d5 later. Here, the White knight has three potential moves. }
10. Ng5
{ That's another way to attack the e4-pawn. However, if the pawn holds, the knight on g5 might feel quite clumsy. }
10... Bf5
{ Because the knight on g5, unlike on d2, does not hinder White's development, Black is no longer interested in trading the e4 pawn for the d5-pawn. }
11. Nc3 Nxd5
{ With the Nc3 and ...Bf5 moves included, White can't win the e4-pawn anymore. }
12. Qd4
{ The most critical move. If instead a trade of knights on d5, and the following f3 breakthrough, the position is just equal. }
12... Nxc3 13. Qxg7 Rf8 14. Qxc3
{ This would take quite a tactical player to spot, from afar, that the white knight on g5 can't be taken. }
14... Nc6
{ Black can castle long and has good compensation for the pawn.  14...Bxg5??  15.Qe5+  Black loses a piece. }
