1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. Be2
{ A very interesting move order - White is provoking the black knight to f6 and only then plays Nc3. This also means that Black will be unable to continue the traditional plan of ...b5, ...Bb7, and ...Nc6. Please note that even though Black has access to the early ...d5 move and can even capture with the queen, White is ahead in development thus such an approach to open the position could seriously backfire. }
5... Nf6 6. Qd3
{ A very modern idea that deserves serious attention. White once again is aiming for the Maroczy Bind setup. Actually, in many Sicilian Defense variations, an early Qd3 is becoming a trend. }
6... e5
{ Our proposition - be modern as well! Black makes sure that White can't walk past the e-pawn and prepares the d-pawn push. }
7. Nb3
{ White still wants to set up the Maroczy Bind with c4 and Nc3 and thus create a big hold on d5. The immediate d-pawn push here won't give Black the desired results but there's a good preparation move. }
7... Nc6
{ Black will play ...d5 next move but this time there will be better circumstances. There's some potential to play this position also like some sort of Najdorf which also has a similar setup with the black pawns on e5, d6, and against Maroczy Bind with the white pawn on c4, push ...a5-a4 for interesting complications. Here ...d6 might not be necessary.   7...d5?!  this is too early  8.exd5  Qxd5  9.Qg3!  The position is open and Black has problems finishing development. }
8. c4 { That's a nice idea but there's a flaw. } 8... Nb4 9. Qc3 Nxe4
{ White's aim to set up the Maroczy Bind has failed - Black is very active. }
10. Qxe5+ Qe7 11. Qxe7+ Bxe7 12. Na3 O-O
{ Black has a lot of active moves - if one side is worse, it's White. The knight on a3 is very passive, the black knights, on the contrary, are controlling many squares. }
