1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. Be2
{ A very interesting move order - White is provoking the black knight to f6 and only then plays Nc3. This also means that Black will be unable to continue the traditional plan of ...b5, ...Bb7, and ...Nc6. Please note that even though Black has access to the early ...d5 move and can even capture with the queen, White is ahead in development thus such an approach to open the position could seriously backfire. }
5... Nf6 6. Nc3
{ White is threatening to play e5 so Black should do something about it. Since this is not a Sicilian Scheveningen course, we won't advocate for  6...d6  . Instead, we'd like to keep the option for the dark-squared bishop to be flexible and participate in fighting for the center. }
6... Bb4
{ Doing this right away is not good, as now the white pawn marches forward.   6...b5?  @@StartBracket@@As with  6...Bb4  , this doesn't stop the e-pawn's advancement.@@EndBracket@@ @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/3p1ppp/p3pn2/1p6/3NP3/2N5/PPP1BPPP/R1BQK2R w KQkq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.e5  b4  the idea is typical, but the circumstances could have been better.  8.exf6  bxc3  9.fxg7  Bxg7  10.bxc3  White is up a pawn and the black king is exposed - don't go here. }
7. e5 Ne4 8. O-O
{ A common gambit idea that White can employ. Be sure - if he knows the tricky 5.Be2 setup, he is aware that this pawn has to be sacrificed. None of the pawn grabs will keep Black happy. }
8... Nxc3
{ 8...Bxc3  Black forces some trades but some of the critical the dark squares will be weakened forever.  9.bxc3  Nxc3  10.Qd3  Nxe2+  11.Qxe2  all of these weaknesses for just one pawn... }
9. bxc3 Bxc3 10. Ba3
{ Another common idea - that exchange doesn't matter much. The White bishop on a3 is a true monster. }
10... Qa5 11. Bd6 Nc6 { The best that Black can do in the position. } 12. Nxc6
dxc6 13. Qd3
{ Also  13.f4  looks great - it was played in Giri, A. @@StartBracket@@2714@@EndBracket@@ - Vitiugov, N. @@StartBracket@@2729@@EndBracket@@ Reggio Emilia 2012. The Dutch grandmaster scored a stunning victory, which is hardly surprising. }
13... Bxe5 14. Rad1 Bxd6 15. Qxd6
{ If Black will survive this for more than 5 moves, that already is a miracle. White has a huge threat Bf3-Bxc6. }
15... Qg5 16. Bf3 f5 17. Bxc6+ Kf7 18. Bf3 Qe7 19. Qe5
{ White's attack has not slowed down but at least Black is not lost immediately. Not a fun position to play! }
