[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13) 5.Be2"]
[Black "6.Nc3 Qc7 7.a3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. Be2
{ A very interesting move order - White is provoking the black knight to f6 and only then plays Nc3. This also means that Black will be unable to continue the traditional plan of ...b5, ...Bb7, and ...Nc6. Please note that even though Black has access to the early ...d5 move and can even capture with the queen, White is ahead in development thus such an approach to open the position could seriously backfire. }
5... Nf6 6. Nc3
{ White is threatening to play e5 so Black should do something about it. Since this is not a Sicilian Scheveningen course, we won't advocate for  6...d6  . Instead, we'd like to keep the option for the dark-squared bishop to be flexible and participate in fighting for the center. }
6... Qc7
{ This takes care of the incoming e5 push - now just wait and see, what White will choose. }
7. a3
{ If White is this slow and pays big attention to the incoming ... Bb4 threat, Black can resume the idea of the b-pawn push, now that the e5-square is protected. }
7... b5 8. f4 Bb7
{ Black has a very dynamic play in the center. You must understand - the incoming e5 push does not always have to be stopped as for White the d6-square is difficult to exploit. }
9. Bf3
{ White can also focus on further development, keeping in mind the e5 push for later. As we already mentioned, the push itself is not a problem as the black knight can retreat to g8 and enter the game either via e7 or h6-square. }
9... Nc6 10. Be3 Nxd4
{ Already a known motif - the white queen on d4 is not much of a threat, on the contrary - it can be used to gain some tempos. Black could also explore an option to push ...b4 and renew the treat to pressure the e4-pawn. }
11. Qxd4 h5
{ Black takes care of the g4 square as a potential retreat, should White consider pushing e5. If that doesn't happen, the next move that Black can include is ...Rc8 and then decide, how to bring into the game the dark-squared bishop. }
12. h3
{ It makes sense to stop the knight jump, but this now weakens the g3-square. }
12... h4 { At the right moment, now Black has an option to explore ...Nh5. }
13. O-O-O Rc8
{ Black is thinking about options like ...Bxa3 or ...Bc5, or perhaps just develop the bishop on e7, avoiding forcing an immediate crisis. }
14. Kb1 Be7
{ 14...Bxa3?  Although, this idea exists and it's one of the threats for this type of position, here it doesn't work.  15.e5!  Bxf3?  Technically a big mistake and  15...d5  is sort of better but it's important to illustrate where this line leads to. @@StartFEN@@2r1k2r/2qp1pp1/p3pn2/1p2P3/3Q1P1p/b1N1Bb1P/1PP3P1/1K1R3R w k - 0 16@@EndFEN@@  16.gxf3  Nh5  17.bxa3  Qxc3  18.Qxd7+  . There's one problem - Black loses control of the d7-square and the black king is weak.  18...Kf8  19.Rd3!  However, this is the biggest problem of them all - now Black doesn't have a satisfactory continuation, and the weakened back rank plays a crucial role.  19...Qxc2+  20.Ka1  White is winning material. From afar this is by no means obvious and under different circumstances, the line might work for Black. }
15. e5 Nh5
{ Or take on f3 first but this option might not always be available to you. The knight is heading to g3 and f5; the king at some point can find a shelter on g7. }
