{ White is threatening to play e5 so Black should do something about it. Since this is not a Sicilian Scheveningen course, we won't advocate for  6...d6  . Instead, we'd like to keep the option for the dark-squared bishop to be flexible and participate in fighting for the center. }
6... Qc7
{ This takes care of the incoming e5 push - now just wait and see, what White will choose. }
7. a3
{ If White is this slow and pays big attention to the incoming ... Bb4 threat, Black can resume the idea of the b-pawn push, now that the e5-square is protected. }
7... b5 8. f4 Bb7
{ Black has a very dynamic play in the center. You must understand - the incoming e5 push does not always have to be stopped as for White the d6-square is difficult to exploit. }
9. e5
{ White decides to clarify the situation in the center immediately. Now Black has a choice - play ...Nd5 for a simpler game or keep more pieces on the board and retreat. }
9... Ng8
{ Suddenly you might realize that the knight on c3 is the least flexible piece in White's position that you might want to avoid trading. }
10. Be3 Nc6 11. Bf3 Nxd4
{ Trading a pair of knights for the position is good for you as White has some space advantage. }
12. Bxd4 Ne7 13. O-O Nf5 { Black has a dynamic game. } *

