1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. Be2
{ A very interesting move order - White is provoking the black knight to f6 and only then plays Nc3. This also means that Black will be unable to continue the traditional plan of ...b5, ...Bb7, and ...Nc6. Please note that even though Black has access to the early ...d5 move and can even capture with the queen, White is ahead in development thus such an approach to open the position could seriously backfire. }
5... Nf6 6. Nc3
{ White is threatening to play e5 so Black should do something about it. Since this is not a Sicilian Scheveningen course, we won't advocate for  6...d6  . Instead, we'd like to keep the option for the dark-squared bishop to be flexible and participate in fighting for the center. }
6... Qc7
{ This takes care of the incoming e5 push - now just wait and see, what White will choose. }
7. f4
{ White could insist on pushing e5 - now we get slightly better circumstances than one of the previous informational lines. }
7... Bb4
{ Otherwise, you will have to enter the Scheveningen structures with  7...d6  . }
8. e5
{ Seems to be necessary, otherwise, White will either lose the e4-pawn or allow Black to push ...d5. }
8... Nd5 { Or  8...Ne4  , it does not matter. } 9. O-O Nxc3 10. bxc3 Bxc3 11.
Rb1
{ The difference here is that, because of the included  f4  , White can't afford himself to play  11.Ba3  -  the knight on d4 will be lost. }
11... b5
{ This comes with an idea to play ...b4 at some point, closing  White's dark-squared bishop on a3. }
12. Bf3
{ Sengupta, D.  2543  - Omar, N.  2377  Asian Continental op 15th 2016. } 12...
Bxd4+
{ Quite paradoxical but it's also the simplest choice for Black. Black can also gamble a little and keep the dark-squared bishop alive. }
13. Qxd4 Bb7
{ Now after any White's Ba3, Black will trade the light-squared bishops, play ...Nc6, and push ...b4. }
14. Ba3 Bxf3 15. Rxf3 Nc6 16. Qe4 Qa7+
{ Quite precise - the rook on a8 needs to be protected for the b4 push. } 17.
Kh1 b4
{ The simplest - Black can also explore  17...Qd4  and keep the pawn for the time being.   This is how the game could continue:  18.Rxb4  O-O!  Accepting the exchange is risky.  19.Rb1  Qd4!  20.Qe2  Rfe8  White has good control of the dark squares but has a lot of weaknesses on the light squares. }
