[White "13) 5.Be2"]
[Black "7.O-O Bb4 8.Qd3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. Be2
{ A very interesting move order - White is provoking the black knight to f6 and only then plays Nc3. This also means that Black will be unable to continue the traditional plan of ...b5, ...Bb7, and ...Nc6. Please note that even though Black has access to the early ...d5 move and can even capture with the queen, White is ahead in development thus such an approach to open the position could seriously backfire. }
5... Nf6 6. Nc3
{ White is threatening to play e5 so Black should do something about it. Since this is not a Sicilian Scheveningen course, we won't advocate for  6...d6  . Instead, we'd like to keep the option for the dark-squared bishop to be flexible and participate in fighting for the center. }
6... Qc7
{ This takes care of the incoming e5 push - now just wait and see, what White will choose. }
7. O-O
{ There are Grandmasters like Anand, MVL, and Azarov who are deliberately going for these continuations, because many Sicilian Kan players are not fans of Sicilian Scheveningen, which involves committing to ...d6, and neither are we. You must find your way, at the same time avoid getting suspicious positions. Let us explain, what choices you have. }
7... Bb4
{ This continuation is favored by such elite players like Caruana and Vitiugov. All other positions lead to hardly inspiring positions for Black. Not only does Black keep the option to play ...d6 later, we also try to cause White maximum discomfort with development as the White pawn on e4 is immediately under attack. White is forced to react and that means - developing the pieces more aggressively but not always harmoniously. There's a good chance that soon they might interfere with each other.   7...b5?  Unfortunately, here this is a mistake that can be punished right away. The black knight on f6 in this position is developed too early and will now backfire.  8.Bf3  Bb7  9.e5!  White opens the position and has a great lead in development.  9...Ng8  10.Re1  Nc6   There's no  10...Ne7  due to the typical Nxb5 trick.  11.Nxc6  dxc6  12.Bf4  White is up four tempi and should be already strategically winning. }
8. Qd3
{ One of the most popular continuations in the position - White brings the queen out early to protect both the knight on c3, the pawn on e4, and is also thinking to rearrange the queen to g3 at some point later. }
8... Nc6
{ This idea we already know - trading a pair of knights, in general, is good for Black but there might be some occasions when the black knight is heading to e5. White once again faces some choices. }
9. Rd1
{ White increases control of the d-file, takes away from Black the typical ...Bd6 maneuver, and is flexible with the next moves. }
9... O-O 10. Bg5 Bxc3
{ Since the d6 square is not available for the retreat of the dark-squared bishop, it's time to clarify the situation in the center. }
11. bxc3
{ This might be what the majority of players will choose but now White has some issues with the pawn on e4. }
11... Ne5 12. Qe3 Neg4
{ If not for this move, the entire approach would be very shady. Now there are interesting tactical elements in the position. }
13. Qg3
{ 13.Qh3??  Nxf2!  this is easy to miss  14.Kxf2  Nxe4+  White is suddenly down two pawns for nothing. }
13... Qxg3 14. hxg3 Nxf2
{ The same idea works again, although taking the pawn on e4 is fine as well. }
