{ Retreating with the king is one of the most popular moves in the position. White prepares the f4-pawn push which right away is impossible as the white knight on d4 hangs because of the ...Bc5 threat. }
9... Nxd4 10. Qxd4 Bc5
{ The bishop on b4 has done its job and now it's time to give it a new role. Black pushes away the white queen from controlling the d4-square and will fight for other central squares. }
11. Qd2
{ This strange retreat has gained some popularity - White wants to lift the white queen to the kingside. }
11... h6
{ It makes sense to stop White's plan right away, plus ...h6 seems to be a useful move to have for the position. }
12. f4 d6
{ Now that the dark-squared bishop is out on c5, Black doesn't mind playing ...d6, which stops White's e5 and Ne4 threat. White wants to build here the following setup - queen on g3, the light-squared bishop on d3, and at the right moment push e5 for an attack. Let's keep this in our mind. }
13. Qe1
{ Watch out for the order of the moves in which you should play out the position. }
13... Bd4
{ Castling short here would be early as White would position his bishop on d3 first and only then play Qg3. Then Black's ...Bd4 would be useless as the knight can retreat to e2, plus with tempo. }
14. Bd3
{ White is preparing to play Qg3 so it's a good idea not to castle into an attack as this time you won't have a satisfactory counterstrike in the center. }
14... Bd7
{ Black wants to bring the bishop to c6 and be flexible with his plans. Castling at the moment is postponed @@StartBracket@@could be both ways!@@EndBracket@@ as Black needs to wait to see where the game is heading. }
15. Qg3
{ Or  15.Ne2  Ba7  and only then Qg3 - this is an important moment. This is how the game could continue here but what's interesting - it's not very good for White! }
15... Bc6
{ Thanks to this shot, Black can take over the game. White can't take the pawn on g7. }
16. Ne2 Bb6 17. Qxg7 Ke7
{ Suddenly the Black king stands very well on e7 and there's the ...Rag8 threat! Of course, in this and any other similar positions, you need to make sure what happens if White tries to open the center to punish your strategy. }
18. e5 Nh5 19. Qg4 Rag8 20. Qh4+ Kd7
{ White can't defend the pawn on g2 and is losing. } *

