20. Bxh6 f6 { Black defends everything just in time. } 21. Bf4 Qf7
{ The position is equal, although Black needs to be a little careful with the control of the dark squares and the safety of the king. Trading queens would be great.   22.exf6  This is a very logical follow-up of how the game might continue:  22...Qxf6  23.Be5  Qh6  24.Rf4  White has some very annoying threats  24...g5  25.h4!  Kh7!  Black temporarily gives up a pawn.  26.Qxg5  Qxg5  27.hxg5  Kg6  28.Bf6  Be6  .  The position has normalized and White's extra pawn at the queenside plays no role. Watch out for White's Rh4-h6 threat but doing this immediately can backfire.  29.Rh4?!  Rxf6!  What a concept!  30.gxf6  Rd8  Even though Black is down an exchange and a pawn, it's probably White who is fighting for the draw here as Black is incredibly active and has a strong passed pawn, backed by the bishop. }
