f4 Bb7 13. Bf3 { White is threatening to push e5 . } 13... h5
{ For many years this used to be the main continuation in the position. The idea is to play ...Ng4 with some tactical tricks on the kingside. }
14. e5 Ng4
{ Not only is Black threatening the fork on f2,  but the knight often won't move from g4, and will cause long-term annoyance to White. Even if White plays h3, the knight can often remain on g4 because opening the h-file would be disastrous for White. }
15. Ne4
{ It seems to be more precise than the immediate capture on b7 and only then Ne4.   15.Bxb7  Qxb7  16.Ne4  Be7  White doesn't have anything as the d6-square alone is not enough. If White tries to open the queenside and the a-file with a4, the standard response is ...b4, keeping it closed. }
15... Bxe4
{ The dark-squared bishop is more important than the light-squared bishop, at least in this position. }
16. Qxe4 Rc8 17. Qe2
{ Since the knight on g4 this time is under attack for real, Black has to make a decision, whether to retreat or sacrifice a pawn. }
17... Nh6
{ This comes with an idea to deliver a nasty check on g3, which could end with a mate.   17...f5!?  A very common idea for the structure - the knight on g4 won't go anywhere as White's h3 comes with no threat. At the same time, White can't close the g1-a7 diagonal to escape with the king to g1.  18.exf6  gxf6  19.Bxg4  hxg4  20.Qxg4  Kf7  Probably Black has good compensation for the pawn, but it could be difficult to come up with real threats. }
18. Be4 Nf5 19. Bxf5 exf5
{ The position is closer to equal than White being better, but it's Black who has some weaknesses in the position. }
