8. Kh1
{ If White ever plays Kh1 or something similar, you can adopt the following plan which is quite important for the position. }
8... Bxc3 9. bxc3 d6
{ It's not advisable to take the pawn on c3 as White can very quickly get a dangerous initiative with the e5 push, even if it will involve sacrificing an exchange as well. Black's weak dark squares and the weak king can be too difficult problems to solve in practice. The same applies to the pawn on e4 - it opens more files, more diagonals for white pieces. Keep the idea to grab the pawn in your mind, but focus on your position's strategic strength first. }
10. f3 e5 11. Nb3 O-O 12. Qd3 Be6
{ Black wants to push ...d5 - the queenside knight in this structure often is developed to d7. }
13. Rd1 d5 14. exd5 Nxd5
