{ This continuation is favored by such elite players like Caruana and Vitiugov. All other positions lead to hardly inspiring positions for Black. Not only does Black keep the option to play ...d6 later, we also try to cause White maximum discomfort with development as the White pawn on e4 is immediately under attack. White is forced to react and that means - developing the pieces more aggressively but not always harmoniously. There's a good chance that soon they might interfere with each other.   7...b5?  Unfortunately, here this is a mistake that can be punished right away. The black knight on f6 in this position is developed too early and will now backfire.  8.Bf3  Bb7  9.e5!  White opens the position and has a great lead in development.  9...Ng8  10.Re1  Nc6   There's no  10...Ne7  due to the typical Nxb5 trick.  11.Nxc6  dxc6  12.Bf4  White is up four tempi and should be already strategically winning. }
8. Bg5
{ Currently the hottest move in the position which involves also some early tricks that you should be aware of. }
8... Bxc3
{ Winning the pawn on c3 right away is risky business - something we already learned in some of the previous variations.   8...d6??  it would be great if Black could play ...Nbd7 next, keeping a nice control of the center, the dark squares while the dark-squared bishop is out.  9.Nf5!  A cold shower!  9...O-O   Black can't salvage the game anymore but at least it's a good attempt.  9...exf5  the piece grab ends with a disaster right away.  10.Bxf6  gxf6  11.Nd5  Qc5  12.a3  White wins back the sacrificed piece while Black's position is completely shattered.  10.Nh6+  Kh8  11.Bxf6  gxf6  12.Qd4  The forced line continues - there's not much that Black can do.  12...Bxc3  13.bxc3  Nd7  14.Ng4  Qc5  15.Rfd1  Black has survived a direct mating attack but the pawn on d6 will be lost for nothing. }
9. Bxf6 { Typical intermezzo move for the variation. } 9... gxf6 10. bxc3 Qxc3
11. Rb1
{ White has a strong long-term initiative while the Black king is struggling to find a safe shelter. }
11... Nc6 12. Nxc6 dxc6 13. Rb3 Qc5 14. Qd2
{ White's game is quite straightforward - build an attack, there's no hurry. Black all the time needs to make difficult decisions. }
14... e5 15. Rd1 Qe7 16. Rd3 Be6 17. Qh6 Rg8
{ Vachier Lagrave, M. @@StartBracket@@2789@@EndBracket@@ - Lenderman, A. @@StartBracket@@2565@@EndBracket@@ FIDE World Cup 2017. }
18. Bh5
{ Black's position is divided in half and the king is in the middle of a strong attack. Black is already hopeless. }
