{ This continuation is favored by such elite players like Caruana and Vitiugov. All other positions lead to hardly inspiring positions for Black. Not only does Black keep the option to play ...d6 later, we also try to cause White maximum discomfort with development as the White pawn on e4 is immediately under attack. White is forced to react and that means - developing the pieces more aggressively but not always harmoniously. There's a good chance that soon they might interfere with each other.   7...b5?  Unfortunately, here this is a mistake that can be punished right away. The black knight on f6 in this position is developed too early and will now backfire.  8.Bf3  Bb7  9.e5!  White opens the position and has a great lead in development.  9...Ng8  10.Re1  Nc6   There's no  10...Ne7  due to the typical Nxb5 trick.  11.Nxc6  dxc6  12.Bf4  White is up four tempi and should be already strategically winning. }
8. Bg5
{ Currently the hottest move in the position which involves also some early tricks that you should be aware of. }
8... Nc6
{ The best move - Black focuses on development and doesn't mind if White takes on f6. After all, this is a big decision as it can hand Black on the platter many of the critical dark squares in the position. White once again is at a crossroads and has some choices. }
9. Nxc6
{ Quite a smart order of the moves, restricting Black of a choice. White removes some of Black's pressure from the center and keeps an option to play Qd4 next, attacking both the bishop on b4 and the knight on f6. }
9... dxc6
{ The correct recapture. At the moment, the white pawn on e4 is under attack, and White needs to act. If White takes on f6, Black will castle long and rely on the bishop's power.   9...bxc6?!  Unfortunately, with this move order, capturing with the b-pawn and fighting for a strong pawn center with ...d5 is not an option here.  10.Qd4  Not only is White attacking both the bishop on b4 and the knight on f6, but there's also the threat of e5.  10...Bd6  Black seemingly solves all problems as the lost pawn on f6 will be recaptured on h2 and then there's the ...Be5 trick, but White has more ideas.   11.f4  , because of the early knight trade on c6, ...Bc5 is not available for Black; hence, White is threatening an immediate e5.  11...e5  12.Qd2!  Black's position becomes shaky very fast.  12...exf4  13.Bxf4  Bxf4  14.Rxf4  d6  If only Black could have enough time to play ...Be6 and reroute the knight to e5 the position would be great.  15.Rd1  Ke7  16.Bc4  Be6  17.Bb3  and White has a big advantage. }
10. Qd4
{ A standard double-attack which comes together with the e5 threat. However, on d4 the white queen can become a target to win necessary tempi for the development. }
10... Bd6
{ This must be quite an unexpected reply for White who should be expecting either ...Bxc3 or ...Be7. Black goes on the offensive. }
11. h3 c5
{ Black pushes away the White queen from the center, intending to continue with ...h6, ...Bd7 and castling long. }
12. Qd2
{ This maneuver comes with a different plan from White's perspective - retreat with the bishop to e3 and push f4. }
12... h6 13. Be3
{ If White takes on f6, Black's plan will be just like in other lines - castle long. }
13... O-O 14. f4 Rd8
{ A nice intermezzo move to develop another piece - White needs to deal with the queen's placement. }
15. Qe1 e5 16. f5 c4
{ Black wants to trade the dark-squared bishops or gain some space at the queenside. Otherwise, if White is allowed to play a4 and Bc4, the loss of the d5-square and the lack of active plans could be seriously harmful. }
17. Qf2 b5 { If not for this move, Black's idea doesn't work! } 18. Bb6 Qc6
{ White can't take the rook due to ...Bc5 threat. Black can already think about taking over the game as the activity on the queenside is considerable. }
*

