10... Be7
{ There are some nuances in the position. Now that the white queen is on d3 and White can easily double the control over the d-file, Black's ...Bd6 looks much less appealing. Now instead, the white queen no longer controls the g4-square, giving Black access to some tactical tricks. For a sharper game, it's possible to consider playing  10...h6  with similar ideas like before. }
11. f4
{ If White tries to push e5 right away, there's an important intermezzo move to know. }
11... h6
{ This little move works like a charm, especially after White's f4. Now the white bishop can't retreat to the c1-h6 diagonal but if he takes on f6, White might regret including f4, which weakens many dark squares in the position. }
12. Bxf6
{ White can easily misplay this and the inclusion of f4 for White is a major setback - check out the following variation. }
12... gxf6
{ Black wants to castle long and exploit the freshly created weaknesses of the dark squares on the queenside. }
13. Rad1 Bd7 14. Bh5 { A typical maneuver to hold the king in the center. }
14... O-O-O
{ But Black castles long anyway - you could also play  14...Rf8  . Notice this minor little detail - the white pawn on f4 also stops the white queen from attacking the pawn on h6 via the e3-square, where it would compensate for the loss of the dark squares. }
15. Bxf7 { Not an obvious mistake, but it is. } 15... Rhf8 16. Bh5 Be8
{ White is forced to defend the bishop on h5, leaving the entire queenside up for grabs. }
17. Qe2 Bxh5 18. Qxh5 Qb6+ 19. Kh1 Qxb2
{ White is expected to lose even more. } *

