{ Against the Bd3 systems in particular, this move has always been one of the most popular continuations and the true drawback of White's plan. Otherwise, everybody would just play 5.Bd3 with all the flexibility perks and not bother learning the other sidelines. Due to the early bishop's placement on d3, the white knight on d4 is unprotected, so Black's goal is to push it away from the center. }
6. Be3
{ White can keep the knight in the center but the obvious ...Qb6 threat is looming in the air, attacking both the knight on d4 and the pawn on b2. However, be very careful! }
6... d6
{ Focus on your development but don't forget about the Qb6 idea which might work just fine later. Here the d-pawn belongs on d6 so that you can continue with ...Nf6. Playing  6...Qb6  immediately is a mistake. }
7. O-O Nf6
{ The rest is less forced but think about this - White will always have to be alert to the ...Qb6 threat and if White tries to be active in the center with the f4 push, there's always the ...e5 counterstrike, leading to the dark-squared bishop trade and most likely - again ...Qb6 as a follow-up. }
8. c3 O-O 9. Nd2 Nbd7
{ Black is flexible with his ideas - one plan might be to push ...b5 and ...Bb7, another ...Ne5-g6 and prepare ...e5. Another possibility - to push ...d5,  at the right time. White's setup is not very ambitious as his pieces are hardly fighting for control in the center. }
10. Bc2 Qc7 11. Qe2 b5
{ Black enjoys a great game, although White's position is not worse, it's just balanced. }
*

