[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. Bd3
{ One of the main continuations that has been around for decades. White develops the kingside first with a fast short castle and is very flexible with the ideas on the queenside where the knight not always is developed to c3. Thus the approach of ...b5 which worked so well against White's Nc3, won't be a good idea here as now it's not creating any threats, but only weaknesses. }
5... Bc5
{ Against the Bd3 systems in particular, this move has always been one of the most popular continuations and the true drawback of White's plan. Otherwise, everybody would just play 5.Bd3 with all the flexibility perks and not bother learning the other sidelines. Due to the early bishop's placement on d3, the white knight on d4 is unprotected, so Black's goal is to push it away from the center. }
6. c3
{ That's another way for White to keep the knight in the center, but it's just as 'ambitious' as  6.Be3  . Black's plan remains the same - first, secure the e5-square to play ...Nf6 later. }
6... d6
{ Black will continue the development just like after @@StartFEN@@rnbqk1nr/1p1p1ppp/p3p3/2b5/3NP3/3B4/PPP2PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 2 6@@EndFEN@@  6.Be3  . However, what happens if White pushes an early Qg4 before you have the chance to develop your kingside knight? This is something that you always have to be ready for. }
7. Qg4 Nf6
{ Once you are done studying this chapter, this maneuver will be a piece of cake for you as it's a standard reply in many lines. }
8. Qxg7 Rg8
{ Black wins back the pawn on g2 but with the white bishop still not on e3, there's something more. }
9. Qh6 e5
{ Here, this is stronger than just grabbing the pawn - you'll see, why. } 10.
Nf5 Bxf5 11. exf5 Bxf2+
{ Due to the fork threat on g4 White was already busted after the 11th move in the game Perez Rodriguez, L. @@StartBracket@@2370@@EndBracket@@ - Gonzalez Zamora, J. @@StartBracket@@2523@@EndBracket@@ Carlos Torre Memorial op 26th 2014. }
