{ With the bishop on a7, it's important to take care of the e5-square.   8...Nc6?  9.e5!  Now Black doesn't have a satisfactory continuation.  9...Nh5  10.Qh3  g6  11.g4  Ng7  12.Qh6  Black's position and the control of the dark squares, in general, is terrible. }
9. Nc3 Nc6
{ With the white king still in the center, the Qxg7 threat always is parried with the ...Rg8 and ...Bxf2+ idea. }
10. Bg5
{ White pins the knight and wants to castle long to apply some pressure on the d6-pawn. }
10... h6
{ Black has to act quickly, otherwise the position can become very unpleasant soon. }
11. Be3
{ White might be willing to kill two birds with one stone - castle long and trade-off Black's most active piece. However, Black unexpectedly takes over the game. }
11... Nh5 12. Qh3 Bxe3 13. Qxe3 Qg5
{ White essentially is left with a slightly worse light-squared bishop, whereas the black king is heading to e7 and preparing for the ensuing endgame. }
14. Qxg5 { Not the best move, but the best move to illustrate Black's plans. }
14... hxg5 15. O-O-O Nf4 16. g3 Ng6
{ Now White has an eternal weakness on h2. } 17. Bf1 Ke7 18. Bg2 Bd7
{ Black achieved a dream position in Roganovic, M. @@StartBracket@@2476@@EndBracket@@ - Grandelius, N. @@StartBracket@@2542@@EndBracket@@ Wch U20 50th 2011. White's kingside pawns are a lot more vulnerable than the black pawn on d6. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "14) 5.Bd3, Qg4 Ideas"]
[Black "6.Nb3 Ba7 7.Qg4 Nf6 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. Bd3
{ One of the main continuations that has been around for decades. White develops the kingside first with a fast short castle and is very flexible with the ideas on the queenside where the knight not always is developed to c3. Thus the approach of ...b5 which worked so well against White's Nc3, won't be a good idea here as now it's not creating any threats, but only weaknesses. }
5... Bc5
{ Against the Bd3 systems in particular, this move has always been one of the most popular continuations and the true drawback of White's plan. Otherwise, everybody would just play 5.Bd3 with all the flexibility perks and not bother learning the other sidelines. Due to the early bishop's placement on d3, the white knight on d4 is unprotected, so Black's goal is to push it away from the center. }
6. Nb3
{ White retreats with a tempo, thus logically this is the top choice for White. }
6... Ba7
{ There's an ongoing debate, what is stronger for Black - retreating with the bishop on a7 or e7, having accomplished that the white knight has been pushed away in the center. We think that on a7 the dark-squared bishop is more active and it applies more pressure on White. In other words - it's more fun! }
7. Qg4
{ One of the main ideas for White is to try to exploit the fact that Black's dark-squared bishop is no longer defending the g7-pawn, thus there are some dark-square weaknesses. }
7... Nf6 { Black solves the problems with a tactical solution. } 8. Qg3
{ White keeps the option of taking on g7 for later but at the moment the e5 push is a bigger threat to worry about. }
8... d6
{ With the bishop on a7, it's important to take care of the e5-square.   8...Nc6?  9.e5!  Now Black doesn't have a satisfactory continuation.  9...Nh5  10.Qh3  g6  11.g4  Ng7  12.Qh6  Black's position and the control of the dark squares, in general, is terrible. }
9. Nc3 Nc6
{ With the white king still in the center, the Qxg7 threat always is parried with the ...Rg8 and ...Bxf2+ idea. }
10. Bg5
{ White pins the knight and wants to castle long to apply some pressure on the d6-pawn. }
10... h6
{ Black has to act quickly, otherwise the position can become very unpleasant soon. }
11. Bd2
{ The best retreat square, albeit it closes the d-file in White's quest to go after the d6-pawn. }
11... Nh5
{ A silent draw offer - after the queen retreat the knight is heading back to f6. }
12. Qf3 Nf6 { The knight goes back. } 13. O-O-O { White sticks to the plan. }
13... Ne5
{ Black doesn't have any real alternatives in the position - castling short is very risky and ...b5 immediately is not available due to the e5 push. }
14. Qg3 b5 { Now this works just fine. } 15. Kb1
{ Now Black can already repeat the position with ...Nh5-f6, or continue to play on. This has happened already in the year 2021 between very high-level GMs. }
15... b4
{ The most principled approach - Black has to do something fast, otherwise, the question is, how long will the black king feel comfortable without castling. }
16. Ne2 Rb8
{ Black's idea is to be very aggressive on the queenside, at the same time offering the pawn on g7. The black king for the time being feels quite well in the center. }
17. Qxg7 { A silent draw offer. } 17... Rg8 18. Qxh6 Nfg4
{ Now starts a forced sequence. } 19. Qh7 Kd7 { This idea we already know! }
20. f4 Rh8 21. Qg7 Rg8
{ It was a draw by repetition in Motylev, A. @@StartBracket@@2624@@EndBracket@@ - Andreikin, D. @@StartBracket@@2728@@EndBracket@@ RUS-ch 74th 2021. }
*

