{ White eliminates Black's control of the e5-square but at a cost of a pawn.   24.fxg5?  Nd7  Black gains access to some very critical dark squares.  25.Rxd6  Be3+  26.Kb1  Bf4!  Black collects the h2-pawn and completely takes over the game. }
24... dxe5 25. fxg5 Nd5
{ Otherwise, White's Ne4 will be a big problem. The game continues and White has to find some not very obvious moves.   This is how the game could follow from here:  26.Nxd5+  exd5  27.Rxd5  Bd4!  ...Be6 is threatened.  28.Nb3  Be3+  .  Now that the white knight has committed itself to b3, the bishop is rerouted to f4.  29.Kb1  Bf4  30.h3  Be6  . Suddenly, it's not very clear where exactly White misplayed the position. White's game can be improved somewhere along the way but Black has some dynamic chances to trick the opponent. }
