[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. Bd3
{ One of the main continuations that has been around for decades. White develops the kingside first with a fast short castle and is very flexible with the ideas on the queenside where the knight not always is developed to c3. Thus the approach of ...b5 which worked so well against White's Nc3, won't be a good idea here as now it's not creating any threats, but only weaknesses. }
5... Bc5
{ Against the Bd3 systems in particular, this move has always been one of the most popular continuations and the true drawback of White's plan. Otherwise, everybody would just play 5.Bd3 with all the flexibility perks and not bother learning the other sidelines. Due to the early bishop's placement on d3, the white knight on d4 is unprotected, so Black's goal is to push it away from the center. }
6. Nb3
{ White retreats with a tempo, thus logically this is the top choice for White. }
6... Ba7
{ There's an ongoing debate, what is stronger for Black - retreating with the bishop on a7 or e7, having accomplished that the white knight has been pushed away in the center. We think that on a7 the dark-squared bishop is more active and it applies more pressure on White. In other words - it's more fun! }
7. O-O
{ White castling short immediately before committing to Qg4 has an important nuance.   7.Qe2  this is the main continuation in the position, preparing to play Be3 next. This will be analyzed in the next chapter. }
7... Nc6 { Black has to take care of the e5-square first. } 8. Qg4
{ 8.Qe2  Nge7  9.Be3  O-O  all of the Qe2 ideas are analyzed in the next chapter. }
8... Qf6
{ Some time ago the popular belief was that in this line White easily obtains the advantage in this line @@StartBracket@@ as published, for example, in Parimarjan Negi's acclaimed Sicilian opening books for White@@EndBracket@@. However, opening theory moves on and it is becoming apparent that not only does Black have good chances to equalize, he also has chances to take over the game; the fight will take place over the entire board. It was no accident that Georgian grandmasters were pushing for this line in some high-level official tournaments in 2018, getting excellent chances to play for the win with the black pieces.   8...Nf6?!  The difference of a tempo for Qg4-g3-g7 in another line should make a difference here - White captures on g7 in one go.  9.Qxg7  Rg8  10.Qh6  Ne5  11.Be2!  Black doesn't have sufficient compensation for the pawn.  11...d5?!  12.Nc3!  dxe4  13.Bg5  , with an aggressive game - White gets a much better position. }
9. Nc3 Nge7
{ Black keeps the option to play either ...d6 or ...d5, depending on the situation. White has several ways to fight for the initiative, but none leads to the goal. }
10. Bg5
{ The old studies show that exactly this move gives White an advantage. However, Black has a stunning new idea to prove that it is actually White who will be on the defensive here. }
10... Qg6 11. Qh4
{ White is threatening with the traditional Nd5 - don't miss it! Immediately it doesn't work for several reasons. }
11... f6 12. Bf4
{ Here a new idea has been discovered, giving Black excellent chances to fight for the initiative. }
12... h5
{ Black is threatening with some unexpected ideas at the queenside. It's important to mention that in his book, P. Negi mentions only  12...Ne5  13.Be2  with an advantage for White. }
13. Nd5 { First, we make sure that White's old threat doesn't work now. } 13...
exd5 14. exd5 Qf7 { Black wins a piece with ...g5. } *

