{ 8.Qe2  Nge7  9.Be3  O-O  all of the Qe2 ideas are analyzed in the next chapter. }
8... Qf6
{ Some time ago the popular belief was that in this line White easily obtains the advantage in this line @@StartBracket@@ as published, for example, in Parimarjan Negi's acclaimed Sicilian opening books for White@@EndBracket@@. However, opening theory moves on and it is becoming apparent that not only does Black have good chances to equalize, he also has chances to take over the game; the fight will take place over the entire board. It was no accident that Georgian grandmasters were pushing for this line in some high-level official tournaments in 2018, getting excellent chances to play for the win with the black pieces.   8...Nf6?!  The difference of a tempo for Qg4-g3-g7 in another line should make a difference here - White captures on g7 in one go.  9.Qxg7  Rg8  10.Qh6  Ne5  11.Be2!  Black doesn't have sufficient compensation for the pawn.  11...d5?!  12.Nc3!  dxe4  13.Bg5  , with an aggressive game - White gets a much better position. }
9. Nc3 Nge7
{ Black keeps the option to play either ...d6 or ...d5, depending on the situation. White has several ways to fight for the initiative, but none leads to the goal. }
10. a4
{ It's logical for White to start fighting for the b6-square - the black bishop on a7 is too active. }
10... Ng6
{ Black has to create immediate counterplay, leaving himself the option for some strategic choices later.   10...h5?!  It's interesting to play in the same spirit as with 10.Bg5, but the difference here is that the white queen is not committed to staying on the kingside.  11.Qe2  Ng6  12.Be3  Nf4  13.Qd2  White can cooly fend off any early attacks.  13...Bb8  14.Ne2  g5  15.f3  Although it looks fun, Black's game is too risky. Since Black is so far behind in development, he can't afford a single inaccuracy.  15...Qe5  16.Nxf4  gxf4  17.Bb6  Qxb2  . The attack is over so Black wins at least a pawn to justify the entire approach.  18.Rab1  Qf6  19.c4  White has a dominating position that entirely compensates for the pawn. }
11. a5 { White proceeds with his plan. } 11... Nce5
{ Black bids for the initiative on the kingside before White can close the dark-squared bishop with Nb6. }
12. Qg3
{ White can be also a little ambitious and why not - at the moment Bg5 is a big threat to worry about. }
12... h5
{ A nice counter-shot! Black intends to meet White's Bg5 with ...h4 and the white queen has nowhere to retreat to keep the bishop on g5 defended! }
13. Na4 { White can't ignore the threat of the black h-pawn moving forward. }
13... h4 14. Qg5 h3 15. Qxf6 gxf6
{ White is left with an ugly position and it's in his best interest to close the kingside as quickly as possible. }
16. g3 Nf3+ 17. Kh1 Nge5 18. Be2 d5 { Black is dominating the light squares. }
19. exd5 { A potential follow-up. } 19... exd5 20. Nb6 Bxb6 21. axb6 Bf5
{ Black's threats are very real. } *

