{ Slightly careless as Black can unexpectedly fight for the initiative. } 11...
Qh4 12. h3
{ The natural response. Now Black quickly gets an entertaining game. } 12... f5
{ If White now captures on f5, Black will take the bishop on d3 with one knight, and the pawn on f5 with the other. }
13. f4 Nxd3 14. cxd3 O-O
{ Black has decent chances to take over the game with a brilliant idea. } 15.
Be3
{ White wants to trade the dark-squared bishops to win the fight for the dark squares on the queenside. }
15... b6
{ The paradoxical idea behind imprisoning your own bishop on a7 is to avoid the bishop trade and eventually reroute it to b8 for attacking purposes! }
16. Nd2 Bb7 17. Kh2 Rad8 18. a4 Bb8
{ Black gives up the pawn on b6 for a very interesting initiative.   Here's how the game could continue:  19.g3  Qh6  20.Bxb6  Rc8  21.Be3  fxe4  22.dxe4  d5  Black is trying to open diagonals for his bishops and also expose the white king.  23.e5  Nf5  24.Nf3  Rc4  Black's dynamics compensate the missing pawn. }
