{ It's best to clarify White's intentions right away - Black simplifies the position while White has to make a big commital decision. }
12. cxd3
{ This is probably what most players will do - capture with the pawn and aim for a more solid pawn structure. Now Black has a choice. }
12... d5
{ Solid and good - Black eventually equalizes the game. Now White's Kh1 feels like a waste of time but the f4-pawn push is shooting in the empty air. }
13. exd5
{ This leads to mass trades, taking away any potential excitement of a potential glorious game for both players. }
13... Nxd5 14. Bg5 { Or capture on d5 right away, it changes nothing. } 14...
Qg6 15. Nxd5 exd5 16. Rfe1+ Be6
{ White is unable to exploit the fact that the black king is slightly stuck in the center.   This is how the game could continue from here:  17.Be3  White needs to trade the dark-squared bishops, otherwise, the bishop pair eventually will become a real force.  17...Qxg3  18.hxg3  Bxe3  19.Rxe3  Rc8  20.Nd4  Kd7  . The position is dead equal. }
