{ There's an ongoing debate, what is stronger for Black - retreating with the bishop on a7 or e7, having accomplished that the white knight has been pushed away in the center. We think that on a7 the dark-squared bishop is more active and it applies more pressure on White. In other words - it's more fun! }
7. O-O
{ White castling short immediately before committing to Qg4 has an important nuance.   7.Qe2  this is the main continuation in the position, preparing to play Be3 next. This will be analyzed in the next chapter. }
7... Nc6 { Black has to take care of the e5-square first. } 8. Qg4
{ 8.Qe2  Nge7  9.Be3  O-O  all of the Qe2 ideas are analyzed in the next chapter. }
8... Qf6
{ Some time ago the popular belief was that in this line White easily obtains the advantage in this line @@StartBracket@@ as published, for example, in Parimarjan Negi's acclaimed Sicilian opening books for White@@EndBracket@@. However, opening theory moves on and it is becoming apparent that not only does Black have good chances to equalize, he also has chances to take over the game; the fight will take place over the entire board. It was no accident that Georgian grandmasters were pushing for this line in some high-level official tournaments in 2018, getting excellent chances to play for the win with the black pieces.   8...Nf6?!  The difference of a tempo for Qg4-g3-g7 in another line should make a difference here - White captures on g7 in one go.  9.Qxg7  Rg8  10.Qh6  Ne5  11.Be2!  Black doesn't have sufficient compensation for the pawn.  11...d5?!  12.Nc3!  dxe4  13.Bg5  , with an aggressive game - White gets a much better position. }
9. Nc3 Nge7
{ Black keeps the option to play either ...d6 or ...d5, depending on the situation. White has several ways to fight for the initiative, but none leads to the goal. }
10. Kh1
{ A logical and popular move that prepares f4. However, Black has a good answer that has already been tested in practice. }
10... Ne5
{ Black switches from the extravagant ...h5 plans to a positional approach to equalize the game. Here the idea is to push away the white queen and most likely take the white bishop on d3.   10...h5?!  Please don't mix this up with the earlier ...h5  ideas - here circumstances are different and White will quickly push f4.  11.Qe2  h4  12.f4  and White has an advantage due to the better control of the center. }
11. Qg3
{ Normally, White wants to play either f4 or Be3 next, aiming for a positional game. If Black is not careful, then Bg5 can unexpectedly drop material. }
11... Nxd3
{ It's best to clarify White's intentions right away - Black simplifies the position while White has to make a big commital decision. }
12. cxd3
{ This is probably what most players will do - capture with the pawn and aim for a more solid pawn structure. Now Black has a choice. }
12... d5
{ Solid and good - Black eventually equalizes the game. Now White's Kh1 feels like a waste of time but the f4-pawn push is shooting in the empty air. }
13. Be3
{ White would like to trade the dark-squared bishops without opening Black's light-squared bishop but now starts a little tactical sequence. }
13... d4 { A blunder? } 14. e5 { Or perhaps it's Black who blundered? } 14...
Nf5 { Everything is still good! A funny line with several intermezzo moves. }
15. exf6 { This starts a forced line. } 15... Nxg3+ 16. hxg3 dxe3 17. fxe3 gxf6
{ Due to the potential power of the bishop pair, White needs to be accurate. }
18. Rxf6 Bxe3 19. Raf1 O-O 20. Ne4 b5
{ Black brings the remaining pieces into the game and is just in time to protect f7. Strategically, White is still not out of woods and needs to prove that he can hold off the bishops. }
