15. dxe4 f6
{ Black's idea is to find the right moment to play ...e5 and bring the light-squared bishop to life, but be careful with the execution of the idea. }
16. Bd6 Qf7 { First, protect the knight on e7. } 17. Rad1 O-O
{ The e5 pawn push can wait for the time being - get the king out of the center first. }
18. f3
{ Perhaps White can be a little more aggressive with  18.f4  , but this weakens the central e4-pawn and there's no direct attack on the kingside. After Black's tricky  18...b6  , Black brings out the light-squared bishop to b7 for good counterplay. The bishop on a7 will find a way back into the game. }
18... Ng6
{ Now the plan of ...b6 and ...Bb7 makes less sense as the white pawn on e4 is well protected. }
19. Qg3 Re8 { Black finally is threatening ...e5. } 20. e5 f5
{ Black has other ideas as well. The loss of the d6-square is not important, as long as White can't position a knight there. }
21. Rd3 Bd7 22. Rfd1 Bc6
{ Black has solved all of his opening problems and the position is dynamic enough to fight for more than just equality. }
