{ It's best to clarify White's intentions right away - Black simplifies the position while White has to make a big commital decision. }
12. cxd3
{ This is probably what most players will do - capture with the pawn and aim for a more solid pawn structure. Now Black has a choice. }
12... Qg6
{ If you are looking for some adventures and a simple position is not what you want, you can gamble a little. Black wants to trade the queens for some flexibility with the following plans. }
13. Qd6
{ The obvious choice - White wants to exploit the weakened dark squares and keep the black king in the center. }
13... Qh5 { Black has some unexpected tactical ideas. } 14. f4 b5
{ Without this move, it's difficult to imagine a serious plan for Black, otherwise the dark squares have been weakened for no reason. Black needs to be very dynamic. }
15. a4 bxa4 16. Rxa4 f5
{ A familiar motif - Black wants to defend the knight and castle short. White seems to be better but there are good practical chances to trick your opponent. At the right moment, Black's ...Bb8 and opening the center with ...fxe5 and ...d5 next can make waves. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15) 5.Bd3, Qe2 Ideas"]
[Black " 5.Bd3 Bc5 6.Nb3 Ba7 7.c4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. Bd3 Bc5 6. Nb3 Ba7 7. c4
{ White probably can set up the Maroczy Bind right away as well, but this quite early reveals the chosen setup and gives  Black some options. Black still has the breakthrough of ...d5 in the air, but immediately it might not work.   7.Nc3  is a normal developing move, just like the early 7.c4, and will transpose to one of the lines covered later.  7...Nc6  8.O-O  Nge7  9.Qe2  O-O  10.Be3  b5  . See the later part of the chapter. }
7... Ne7 8. Nc3 Nbc6 9. O-O O-O
{ Now White has many moves, but think about Black's perspective - you have three potential plans.  First, try to break through the center with ...d5, assuming that there are no immediate tactics that punish it. After all, reaching a symmetrical position is not always your dream. Second, close the center with ...d6-e5 and fight for the d4-square. And third - consider going for an inspired kingside attack with ...f5 and perhaps ...f4-Ne5. }
10. Bf4
{ White can't be allowed to position his dark-squared bishop on d6. White might be thinking about Qd2-Be3 next, so it's a good idea to push away the bishop right now.   10.Qe2  White wants to play Be3 and fight for control of the dark squares.  10...d5  transposes to a later line. }
10... e5 11. Be3
{ Engines like this move but it's a very committal choice for a human being - now the white pawns in the center are quite static. }
11... Bxe3 12. fxe3 d6 13. Qe2 Be6
{ Black is doing just fine and should concentrate on his counterplay on the queenside with moves like ...Rc8 and ...Na5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15) 5.Bd3, Qe2 Ideas"]
[Black "5.Bd3 − 7.Qe2 Ne7 8.O-O #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. Bd3 Bc5 6. Nb3 Ba7 7. Qe2
{ Instead of the more aggressive Qg4, White tries to play more positionally and immediately trade the dark-squared bishops. White keeps the option to castle either way, thus we're interested to have a setup as flexible as possible. }
7... Ne7
{ Black wants to castle short as quickly as possible and prepare against a potential Maroczy Bind setup.   7...Nc6  is the most played move in the position but we're not convinced it is the most accurate way to play the variation.  8.Be3  d6  is traditionally one of the most popular moves for Black who wants to trade the dark-squared bishops and at some point later consider playing ...e5, opening the light-squared bishop and at the same time reducing the efficiency of its counterpart on d3.  However, if Black immediately defines his pawn structure in the center, White can choose the most deadly setup against it. We have the utmost respect for the Maroczy Bind if Black doesn't have any active breakthroughs. There's a good reason why we devoted several chapters for c4 setups against the Sicilian Kan.  9.O-O  Nf6  10.c4!  Of course! White has not committed himself to an early Nc3 and is now fighting for a considerable space advantage, leaving Black in a cramped position.  10...O-O  11.Nc3  White has an easy plan. If Black has no active pawn breakthroughs, this is not going to be fun. }
8. O-O
{ White defines his setup very early on - there's nothing wrong with the plan but now White is a little more predictable. }
8... O-O
{ Black has made the most flexible moves and waits for White to further define his setup. }
9. c4
{ White goes for the Maroczy Bind but Black has played the perfect move order to meet it. If White instead plays  9.Nc3  , Black could resume the traditional  9...b5  and ...Nc6 ideas later. }
9... Nbc6 10. Rd1
{ If White includes this move either now or a move earlier to meet Black's incoming ...d5 threat, you can use this as an extra tempo for an alternate plan. }
10... e5 { Black takes control over the d4-square. } 11. Be3
{ As soon as White's dark-squared bishop lands on e3, reject the bishop trade to be able to fight for control of the dark squares. }
11... Nd4 12. Nxd4 exd4 13. Bf4 d6
{ Despite the doubled d-pawns, Black has easy development and good control over the central squares. }
