{ If White includes this move either now or a move earlier to meet Black's incoming ...d5 threat, you can use this as an extra tempo for an alternate plan. }
10... e5 { Black takes control over the d4-square. } 11. Nc3 d6 12. Be3
{ White can't improve the idea - after  12.Bc2  to reinforce control of the d4 square, Black can play  12...Be6  , and this time, after the dark-squared bishop trade on e3, because of the hanging pawn on c4, White will be forced to recapture with the f-pawn, ruining his pawn structure. }
12... Nd4 { Again, the same idea. } 13. Bxd4 exd4 14. Nd5 Nxd5 15. exd5 a5
{ White can't take the pawn on d4 for free without suffering consequences - Black will get excellent counterplay.   This is how the game could continue:  16.Bc2  Re8  17.Qd2  d3!  a typical pawn sacrifice to dislocate White's pieces.  18.Bxd3  a4  19.Nc1  Bg4  20.Rf1  Qf6  Black holds the initiative. }
