{ Black wants to castle short as quickly as possible and prepare against a potential Maroczy Bind setup.   7...Nc6  is the most played move in the position but we're not convinced it is the most accurate way to play the variation.  8.Be3  d6  is traditionally one of the most popular moves for Black who wants to trade the dark-squared bishops and at some point later consider playing ...e5, opening the light-squared bishop and at the same time reducing the efficiency of its counterpart on d3.  However, if Black immediately defines his pawn structure in the center, White can choose the most deadly setup against it. We have the utmost respect for the Maroczy Bind if Black doesn't have any active breakthroughs. There's a good reason why we devoted several chapters for c4 setups against the Sicilian Kan.  9.O-O  Nf6  10.c4!  Of course! White has not committed himself to an early Nc3 and is now fighting for a considerable space advantage, leaving Black in a cramped position.  10...O-O  11.Nc3  White has an easy plan. If Black has no active pawn breakthroughs, this is not going to be fun. }
8. Be3
{ A multi-purpose move as White doesn't reveal anything yet. Thus, we want to be as flexible as possible and be able to react to White's chosen setups in the best possible way. As a general rule of thumb, Black seldom takes on e3 himself, unless there's something immediately right after it. After all, why would you want to take it and give up the g1-a7 diagonal? The black rook on a7 stands just fine.  If White is looking for a big fight and is an aggressive player, he should castle long and focus on the kingside attack with a quick pawn push.  This, however, will give Black enough counter-chances on the queenside, thus, it's all about the order of the moves. If White is a positional player and prefers to castle short, Black is quite flexible with his development on the queenside. }
8... O-O
{ It's strange but this is quite a rare move order. Black wants to save time on ...Nbc6 and ...d6 so that it's possible to meet the Maroczy Bind with ...d5.   8...Nbc6  If Black includes this standard move here, there will be some practical problems with the d-pawn push.  9.Bxa7  Rxa7  10.c4  d5  Otherwise, you might never get a second chance.  11.exd5  exd5  12.cxd5  Qxd5  Black is forced to recapture with the queen and the Black rook in the open position feels weird on a7.  13.O-O  O-O  14.Nc3  Qe5  . Probably Black can hold this, but White is pushing. }
9. f4
{ A very tricky move order - White keeps the option of castling either way and, under the right circumstances, is ready to set up the Maroczy Bind again. }
9... Nbc6 10. Bxa7 { After  10.N1d2  we simply transpose to a later line. }
10... Rxa7 11. Nc3
{ White has no time for the Maroczy Bind since Black is ready to push ...d5. Once the white knight lands on c3, Black plays ...b5 for the typical counterplay ideas at the queenside. }
11... b5 12. O-O-O
{ The most challenging way to continue but now the game gets pretty sharp. }
12... b4 13. Na4
{ This is already necessary, otherwise Black will push forward the a-pawn with a great effect. White uses the fact that Black has already committed himself to ...Nbc6 earlier and can't immediately attack the knight on a4. Smart choice! }
13... d6
{ Black's plan is simple - go after the stranded knight on a4. Check the following variations and see for yourself how difficult it can be for White to find the best moves. }
14. Qe3
{ The best move - White prepares a potential escape route for the knight via the b6 square. }
14... Bd7 15. Nb6
{ Black's ...Nc8 and ...N6e7 look like a dangerous threat, thus it makes sense to escape with the knight, while it's not too late. Engines like the white h-pawn push as far as h6, finding some tactical tricks to keep the White knight alive. However, White's attack on the kingside is not guaranteed to succeed, and White will always have to look over his shoulder to take care of the knight on a4. Black can improve his threats with a well-timed ...Qc7 to better meet White's counter-strikes in the center to aid the knight.   15.Qb6??  this would directly fall into Black's trap  15...Nc8  16.Qxd8  Nxd8  White loses the knight. }
15... a5 { Now that the blockade is gone, Black charges forward. } 16. Bb5 a4
17. Bxa4 Be8 { Black's threats start to look very real. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15) 5.Bd3, Qe2 Ideas"]
[Black "5.Bd3 − 7.Qe2 Ne7 8.Be3 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. Bd3 Bc5 6. Nb3 Ba7 7. Qe2
{ Instead of the more aggressive Qg4, White tries to play more positionally and immediately trade the dark-squared bishops. White keeps the option to castle either way, thus we're interested to have a setup as flexible as possible. }
7... Ne7
{ Black wants to castle short as quickly as possible and prepare against a potential Maroczy Bind setup.   7...Nc6  is the most played move in the position but we're not convinced it is the most accurate way to play the variation.  8.Be3  d6  is traditionally one of the most popular moves for Black who wants to trade the dark-squared bishops and at some point later consider playing ...e5, opening the light-squared bishop and at the same time reducing the efficiency of its counterpart on d3.  However, if Black immediately defines his pawn structure in the center, White can choose the most deadly setup against it. We have the utmost respect for the Maroczy Bind if Black doesn't have any active breakthroughs. There's a good reason why we devoted several chapters for c4 setups against the Sicilian Kan.  9.O-O  Nf6  10.c4!  Of course! White has not committed himself to an early Nc3 and is now fighting for a considerable space advantage, leaving Black in a cramped position.  10...O-O  11.Nc3  White has an easy plan. If Black has no active pawn breakthroughs, this is not going to be fun. }
8. Be3
{ A multi-purpose move as White doesn't reveal anything yet. Thus, we want to be as flexible as possible and be able to react to White's chosen setups in the best possible way. As a general rule of thumb, Black seldom takes on e3 himself, unless there's something immediately right after it. After all, why would you want to take it and give up the g1-a7 diagonal? The black rook on a7 stands just fine.  If White is looking for a big fight and is an aggressive player, he should castle long and focus on the kingside attack with a quick pawn push.  This, however, will give Black enough counter-chances on the queenside, thus, it's all about the order of the moves. If White is a positional player and prefers to castle short, Black is quite flexible with his development on the queenside. }
8... O-O
{ It's strange but this is quite a rare move order. Black wants to save time on ...Nbc6 and ...d6 so that it's possible to meet the Maroczy Bind with ...d5.   8...Nbc6  If Black includes this standard move here, there will be some practical problems with the d-pawn push.  9.Bxa7  Rxa7  10.c4  d5  Otherwise, you might never get a second chance.  11.exd5  exd5  12.cxd5  Qxd5  Black is forced to recapture with the queen and the Black rook in the open position feels weird on a7.  13.O-O  O-O  14.Nc3  Qe5  . Probably Black can hold this, but White is pushing. }
9. N1d2
{ This setup is directed against Black's potential b-pawn and d-pawn pushes. Remember - you should push the b-pawn only when the black knight stands on c3. In other scenarios, the pawn on b5 becomes a weakness that White can target with a4. }
9... Nbc6 10. f4
{ White kindly invites you to push ...d5, so that he can switch to a good French Defense setup. }
10... Bxe3
{ A small exception to the rule but it's possible to play  10...Nb4  right away as well, with the same idea.  10...d5  11.Bxa7  Rxa7  12.e5!  this is White's goal - have a better light-squared bishop and establish a perfect blockade on d4. }
11. Qxe3 Nb4
{ Black eliminates White's potentially strong light-squared bishop. } 12. a3
Nxd3+ 13. Qxd3
{ Capturing with the pawn can't cause Black any problems - just continue with ...d6 and ...Bd7, carefully keeping control of the dark squares. }
13... Qc7
{ Black's goal should be to give his light-squared bishop a good role.   13...d5  The most aggressive pawn push is not always the best move: Black has many dark square weaknesses.  14.e5!  Bd7  15.Nd4  Rc8  16.O-O-O  Anand - Artemiev, Bucharest blitz 2019. White will always have the easier game - Black's light-squared bishop is a little useless. }
14. g3 b5 15. Nf3 Bb7 16. O-O-O Rac8
{ Black has an interesting initiative. Don't move the d-pawn to d5, unless you are ready to continue to push it further to d4. Maybe a well-timed ...f5 push could make all the difference. }
