{ Instead of the more aggressive Qg4, White tries to play more positionally and immediately trade the dark-squared bishops. White keeps the option to castle either way, thus we're interested to have a setup as flexible as possible. }
7... Ne7
{ Black wants to castle short as quickly as possible and prepare against a potential Maroczy Bind setup.   7...Nc6  is the most played move in the position but we're not convinced it is the most accurate way to play the variation.  8.Be3  d6  is traditionally one of the most popular moves for Black who wants to trade the dark-squared bishops and at some point later consider playing ...e5, opening the light-squared bishop and at the same time reducing the efficiency of its counterpart on d3.  However, if Black immediately defines his pawn structure in the center, White can choose the most deadly setup against it. We have the utmost respect for the Maroczy Bind if Black doesn't have any active breakthroughs. There's a good reason why we devoted several chapters for c4 setups against the Sicilian Kan.  9.O-O  Nf6  10.c4!  Of course! White has not committed himself to an early Nc3 and is now fighting for a considerable space advantage, leaving Black in a cramped position.  10...O-O  11.Nc3  White has an easy plan. If Black has no active pawn breakthroughs, this is not going to be fun. }
8. Be3
{ A multi-purpose move as White doesn't reveal anything yet. Thus, we want to be as flexible as possible and be able to react to White's chosen setups in the best possible way. As a general rule of thumb, Black seldom takes on e3 himself, unless there's something immediately right after it. After all, why would you want to take it and give up the g1-a7 diagonal? The black rook on a7 stands just fine.  If White is looking for a big fight and is an aggressive player, he should castle long and focus on the kingside attack with a quick pawn push.  This, however, will give Black enough counter-chances on the queenside, thus, it's all about the order of the moves. If White is a positional player and prefers to castle short, Black is quite flexible with his development on the queenside. }
8... O-O
{ It's strange but this is quite a rare move order. Black wants to save time on ...Nbc6 and ...d6 so that it's possible to meet the Maroczy Bind with ...d5.   8...Nbc6  If Black includes this standard move here, there will be some practical problems with the d-pawn push.  9.Bxa7  Rxa7  10.c4  d5  Otherwise, you might never get a second chance.  11.exd5  exd5  12.cxd5  Qxd5  Black is forced to recapture with the queen and the Black rook in the open position feels weird on a7.  13.O-O  O-O  14.Nc3  Qe5  . Probably Black can hold this, but White is pushing. }
9. O-O
{ Castling short seems to be the critical idea, as casting long and marching on the kingside pawns does not look so menacing with the black kingside knight positioned on e7 instead of the traditional f6-square - thus White can't win any tempi with the g4-g5 push. }
9... Nbc6
{ Black plays the most useful move before making any big committal decisions, and now, White needs to decide which direction he is going to take the game. }
10. Rd1
{ Engines really like early Rd1 maneuvers. White doesn't allow Black to push ...d5 but at the same time, he loses some of the flexibility with plans. }
10... Nb4
{ Again, a crucial element fighting against a potential Maroczy Bind setup. With White's light-squared bishop gone, it will be much easier to organize counterplay against White's c4-pawn or breakthroughs with either ...b5 or ...d5. }
11. c4 Ng6 12. Nc3 Nxd3
{ Black eliminates White's light-squared bishop before it can retreat to b1. To make things worse for White, there are some immediate problems with the c4-pawn. }
13. Rxd3 Ne5
{ Black is threatening to take on e3 and either win the c4 pawn or seriously ruin White's pawn structure. White can keep the position balanced, but from afar it could be not very obvious. After all, it costs an exchange! }
14. Bxa7 Nxd3 15. Be3 Ne5 16. c5
{ Because of the weak squares, Black's best choice is to give up the exchange and finish development. }
16... d5 17. cxd6 Qxd6 18. Bc5 Qc7 19. Bxf8 Kxf8 { The position is equal. } *

