{ From the elite players, this setup has been favored many times by the former World Champion Vishy Anand. In contrast to the typical lines, here, Black has not wasted time on ...d6 and thus gets a good dynamic game. }
10... Ne5
{ Black goes after White's light-squared bishop again with an idea to trade it and then position his light-squared bishop on b7 with familiar motifs. However, this time the maneuver is executed not via the b4-square - on e5, the knight is simply more active! }
11. Bxa7
{ You will see that many times White will capture on a7 himself. The difference is that after the eventual Qe3 maneuver, you are not forced to retreat with the rook but can defend it with ...b6, bringing the queenside pieces into the game. }
11... Rxa7 12. f4
{ White forces the bishop trade for some clarity. If he plays something else, Black wants to play ...b5, ...Bb7 and look for the right moment to take White's light-squared bishop. Who knows - maybe later you might even change your mind - circumstances can be different. }
12... Nxd3 13. cxd3 a5
{ An amazing concept - Black avoids committing to the ...b6 maneuver to protect the rook and activates his pieces. Black also increases control of the dark squares and eventually will find a way to activate the light-squared bishop. Make sure you understand, when pushing ...d5 is good, and when - not so much. }
14. Qf2 Ra6
{ Anand - Caruana, Leuven GCT rapid 2018. White's f5 can be stopped with ...f6. }
