9... Nbc6
{ Black plays the most useful move before making any big committal decisions, and now, White needs to decide which direction he is going to take the game. }
10. Nc3
{ There's a fair chance that this move will transpose to similar setups with f4. Black's approach doesn't change - meet White's Nc3 with ...b5. }
10... b5 11. Rad1
{ 11.a4  b4  12.Nd1  d5  this can't cause any problems for Black. } 11... Ne5
{ Black follows the proven values - go for the light-squared bishop trade. Keep in your mind the following plan. }
12. f4 Nxd3 13. cxd3
{ It feels safer, otherwise Black will always have enough counterplay against White's e4-pawn. }
13... Bxe3+ 14. Qxe3 b4 15. Ne2 a5
{ Black is very active on the queenside and already has found more than one way to bring the light-squared bishop to life. Remember that White is waiting for your ...d5 push so that he can close the center with e5 and establish an outpost on d4. The black pawn stands quite well on d7 at the moment. }
