{ It's strange but this is quite a rare move order. Black wants to save time on ...Nbc6 and ...d6 so that it's possible to meet the Maroczy Bind with ...d5.   8...Nbc6  If Black includes this standard move here, there will be some practical problems with the d-pawn push.  9.Bxa7  Rxa7  10.c4  d5  Otherwise, you might never get a second chance.  11.exd5  exd5  12.cxd5  Qxd5  Black is forced to recapture with the queen and the Black rook in the open position feels weird on a7.  13.O-O  O-O  14.Nc3  Qe5  . Probably Black can hold this, but White is pushing. }
9. O-O
{ Castling short seems to be the critical idea, as casting long and marching on the kingside pawns does not look so menacing with the black kingside knight positioned on e7 instead of the traditional f6-square - thus White can't win any tempi with the g4-g5 push. }
9... Nbc6
{ Black plays the most useful move before making any big committal decisions, and now, White needs to decide which direction he is going to take the game. }
10. Bxa7
{ This trade is typical thus the only question is - when White will include it. The black rook on a7 stands pretty well. }
10... Rxa7 11. c4 { The last attempt to set up the Maroczy Bind. } 11... d5
{ Black's response doesn't change. } 12. exd5 exd5 13. Rd1
{ The best practical choice for White - preventing Black's ...dxc4. There is a similar position but the white queen standing on e3, for some better circumstances. Here, Black's approach remains the same - close the center, although things are still not quite simple. }
13... d4
{ Black has to push the d-pawn forward - better sooner than later. Now White has numerous ways to challenge the d4-pawn, but Black should have enough resources to equalize.   13...Re8?!  14.Nc3  d4  this was played in another high-level GM game Sethuraman, S. @@StartBracket@@2657@@EndBracket@@ - Yu, Y. @@StartBracket@@2760@@EndBracket@@ CHN-chT 2018. Here White had a stronger continuation, forcing Black into a long defense.  15.Qc2!  Black did not equalize as the d4-pawn is too weak.  15...h6  16.Be4  b6  17.Bxc6  Nxc6  18.Nd5   The d4-pawn is about to fall - Black won't have sufficient compensation. }
14. Na3
{ White can apply pressure on the d4-pawn with the queenside knight but now Black has quite an unexpected helper to defend the pawn. }
14... b6 { It's the rook! } 15. Nc2 Rd7 16. Rd2
{ White brings his entire army to get the pawn. } 16... Ng6 17. Bxg6
{ A bit unclear and clumsy - even if the d4-pawn eventually falls, Black will always have good counterplay due to the powerful light-squared bishop. }
17... hxg6 18. Rad1 Re8
{ Black starts to make the preparations to give up the d4-pawn under the best circumstances. And they are - activate your pieces! }
19. Qf1 Qf6 20. Ncxd4 Ne5
{ Finally, White has achieved what he wanted but Black is incredibly active. }
*

