{ A multi-purpose move as White doesn't reveal anything yet. Thus, we want to be as flexible as possible and be able to react to White's chosen setups in the best possible way. As a general rule of thumb, Black seldom takes on e3 himself, unless there's something immediately right after it. After all, why would you want to take it and give up the g1-a7 diagonal? The black rook on a7 stands just fine.  If White is looking for a big fight and is an aggressive player, he should castle long and focus on the kingside attack with a quick pawn push.  This, however, will give Black enough counter-chances on the queenside, thus, it's all about the order of the moves. If White is a positional player and prefers to castle short, Black is quite flexible with his development on the queenside. }
8... O-O
{ It's strange but this is quite a rare move order. Black wants to save time on ...Nbc6 and ...d6 so that it's possible to meet the Maroczy Bind with ...d5.   8...Nbc6  If Black includes this standard move here, there will be some practical problems with the d-pawn push.  9.Bxa7  Rxa7  10.c4  d5  Otherwise, you might never get a second chance.  11.exd5  exd5  12.cxd5  Qxd5  Black is forced to recapture with the queen and the Black rook in the open position feels weird on a7.  13.O-O  O-O  14.Nc3  Qe5  . Probably Black can hold this, but White is pushing. }
9. O-O
{ Castling short seems to be the critical idea, as casting long and marching on the kingside pawns does not look so menacing with the black kingside knight positioned on e7 instead of the traditional f6-square - thus White can't win any tempi with the g4-g5 push. }
9... Nbc6
{ Black plays the most useful move before making any big committal decisions, and now, White needs to decide which direction he is going to take the game. }
10. Bxa7
{ This trade is typical thus the only question is - when White will include it. The black rook on a7 stands pretty well. }
10... Rxa7 11. c4 { The last attempt to set up the Maroczy Bind. } 11... d5
{ Black's response doesn't change. } 12. exd5 exd5 13. Rd1
{ The best practical choice for White - preventing Black's ...dxc4. There is a similar position but the white queen standing on e3, for some better circumstances. Here, Black's approach remains the same - close the center, although things are still not quite simple. }
13... d4
{ Black has to push the d-pawn forward - better sooner than later. Now White has numerous ways to challenge the d4-pawn, but Black should have enough resources to equalize.   13...Re8?!  14.Nc3  d4  this was played in another high-level GM game Sethuraman, S. @@StartBracket@@2657@@EndBracket@@ - Yu, Y. @@StartBracket@@2760@@EndBracket@@ CHN-chT 2018. Here White had a stronger continuation, forcing Black into a long defense.  15.Qc2!  Black did not equalize as the d4-pawn is too weak.  15...h6  16.Be4  b6  17.Bxc6  Nxc6  18.Nd5   The d4-pawn is about to fall - Black won't have sufficient compensation. }
14. N1d2
{ White finishes development but hasn't given up on attacking the d4-pawn. }
14... Ng6
{ Black keeps the option to remove one of the attackers with the a-pawn push, thus White doesn't have a lot of time. }
15. Nf3 Bg4 16. Qe4 h5 { Black wins a critical tempo to equalize the game. }
17. h3 { 17.Qd5  Nf4  White makes no progress. } 17... Re8 18. Qd5 Bxf3 19.
Qxf3 Nce5
{ The pawn on h5 can't be taken due to a simple fork on f4 - thus, it's important to play Nce5 rather than Nge5, Black has equalized the game, but there's still room for some sharp lines. }
20. Qf5 b5
{ Black's tactical options here are admirable. If White is not alert and makes one mistake, Black is ready to take over. }
21. cxb5 Nxd3 22. Rxd3 Rd7 23. Rad1 Re5 24. Qf3 Red5 25. Rxd4
{ White gives up a piece and pins hopes on the passed a-pawn. } 25... Rxd4 26.
Rxd4 Rxd4 27. Nxd4 Qxd4 28. bxa6 Qc4
{ The simplest - Black makes sure the white pawn is not going anywhere.   29.Qa3  Qc1+  30.Kh2  Qc7+  31.Qg3  Qb6  . White can't make progress as there's always the perpetual check idea.  32.Qd3  Qc7+  33.Kg1  Qc1+  34.Qf1  Qxb2  . With perfect play from both sides, the game will end in a draw. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16) Early c4 Rare Moves"]
[Black "2.c4 Nc6 3.Nc3 g6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ The remaining chapters of the course will be devoted to c4 pushes if White tries to set up something similar to the Maroczy Bind. This system at the moment is considered to be the most dangerous weapon against the Sicilian Kan but first - let's pay attention to early c4 pushes and rare continuations, which shouldn't pose any problems. }
2. c4
{ This is a little too early but you never know - maybe you're playing an English opening fanatic who for some reason wanted to start with 1.e4 and then switch to the English? It sounds very unlikely. If we don't allow White to set up the Maroczy Bind, we will immediately equalize with chances to take over the initiative. Drop the Sicilian Kan involving ...a6 and fight for the central squares. }
2... Nc6 3. Nc3
{ White can switch to the English opening Botvinnik system - just make sure you are not tricked into a worse version of the Maroczy Bind, which involves White pushing d4. }
3... g6
{ Since White is not threatening with the immediate d4 pawn push, Black can afford to put the dark-squared bishop on the much more active g7-square to directly fight for the central squares. }
4. g3 Bg7
{ This is just a start of the Botvinnik system but Black's plan is very straightforward - ...e6, ...d6, ...Nge7 and position the queenside knight on d4, which is backed by the other knight on c6. Here is a sample line - the theory is really easy. }
5. Bg2 d6
{ Or  5...e6  first, it does not matter. In this move order, it might be a little tricky as you are not yet revealing your chosen setup to White. Your kingside knight might go to f6 as well, but ...e6 signals to ...Nge7 setup. }
6. d3 e6 7. Nge2 Nge7
{ There is just one rule - as soon as White plays Be3, be ready to play ...Nd4 to block White's attempt to switch to the Maroczy Bind by pushing d3-d4. }
8. O-O O-O 9. Rb1
{ The most played plan - typical to the English opening, White tries to expand at the queenside. Make sure you manage to position your light-squared bishop to b7 - the move order may vary. }
9... b6 10. a3 Bb7 11. b4 Qd7
{ Black is thinking about active plans in the center. If White starts to become very aggressive at the kingside with f4 and g4 pushes, typically it's answered with ...f5, but perhaps you can just ignore it. }
12. Be3 Nd4
{ If White captures on d4 with the knight, take with the pawn. You are ready to lift your second knight to c6 to increase control of the central squares. Maybe an inspired ...f5 push will allow you to fight for the initiative on the kingside. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16) Early c4 Rare Moves"]
[Black " 2.c4 Nc6 3.Ne2 Nf6 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ The remaining chapters of the course will be devoted to c4 pushes if White tries to set up something similar to the Maroczy Bind. This system at the moment is considered to be the most dangerous weapon against the Sicilian Kan but first - let's pay attention to early c4 pushes and rare continuations, which shouldn't pose any problems. }
2. c4
{ This is a little too early but you never know - maybe you're playing an English opening fanatic who for some reason wanted to start with 1.e4 and then switch to the English? It sounds very unlikely. If we don't allow White to set up the Maroczy Bind, we will immediately equalize with chances to take over the initiative. Drop the Sicilian Kan involving ...a6 and fight for the central squares. }
2... Nc6 3. Ne2
{ This move itself does not reveal much yet of White's chosen plan but there's a good chance that the d4 push is planned. This means that Black has no time to play ...g6.   3.Nf3  e5!  the white knight on f3 stands poorly as White's pawn structure is less flexible now. Black has all the chances to take over the game with the plan ...g6, ...d6, ...f5 and ...Be6. }
3... Nf6 4. Nbc3 e6
{ Black goes for the immediate d-pawn push in the center. Most likely White already has to push d4 and transpose to a line covered later. }
5. g3
{ White tries to set up something similar to the English Botvinnik system, but the move order was wrong.   5.d4  transposes to a line, had White started with 2.Nf3 and then 3.c4.  5...cxd4  6.Nxd4  Bc5  this position is covered later in the course. }
5... d5
{ To allow this breakthrough so easily, something has gone wrong with White's plan. If you're not happy with the equalizing approach, consider some alternatives like  5...Ne5  with plans to play ...a6-b5 next. }
6. cxd5 exd5 7. exd5 Nb4 { The simplest. } 8. Nf4 a6
{ Black has some aggressive ideas so White needs to push away the intruder. }
9. a3 Nbxd5 { Black has solved all opening problems. } *

