1. e4 c5
{ The remaining chapters of the course will be devoted to c4 pushes if White tries to set up something similar to the Maroczy Bind. This system at the moment is considered to be the most dangerous weapon against the Sicilian Kan but first - let's pay attention to early c4 pushes and rare continuations, which shouldn't pose any problems. }
2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 { Another attempt to switch to the Maroczy Bind setup. } 3...
Nc6 4. Nc3
{ White might include a standard developing move, inviting Black to play the natural  4...Nf6  and only then push d4 but you don't need it as there's a far simpler continuation. }
4... Nd4
{ Black thwarts White's plan to push d4 and will position his kingside knight to c6 for better control of the central squares. }
5. Be2
{ White might delay the trade but now there are coming reinforcements in the fight for the central squares. }
5... Ne7 6. Nxd4 cxd4 7. Nb5 Nc6
{ Black manages to position the knight on c6, and steers clear of any embarrassing mate ideas on d6. }
8. O-O a6 9. Na3 Be7
{ Black's game is very simple and there are excellent chances to take over the game. There's no need to commit to ...d6. }
10. d3 O-O 11. f4 Rb8
{ Black's initiative at the queenside looks much more real than what White is preparing on the kingside. }
