1. e4 c5
{ The remaining chapters of the course will be devoted to c4 pushes if White tries to set up something similar to the Maroczy Bind. This system at the moment is considered to be the most dangerous weapon against the Sicilian Kan but first - let's pay attention to early c4 pushes and rare continuations, which shouldn't pose any problems. }
2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 { Another attempt to switch to the Maroczy Bind setup. } 3...
Nc6 4. Be2
{ If White tries to be tricky with the move order, Black can close the center for a simple plan. However, there's a very nice alternative idea that you should know! }
4... g5
{ The spirit of the Grob is alive! Here, this is a great move as it does not allow White to push d4. The black bishop will be fianchettoed on g7 for great control of the central squares. This might be a little more exciting to play. }
5. d3
{ All of the positions more or less lead to the same. White is not interested to give up the central d-pawn to win Black's g-pawn. }
5... h6 6. Nc3 Bg7 { Black is keeping an eye for the d4 push. } 7. Be3 d6 8. h3
{ As soon as White is ready to finally play d4, it's a good moment to land the knight on d4 - this motif we already know. Besides, there are other interesting moves as well, like  8...f5  . }
8... Nd4 { Black has no problems whatsoever. } 9. Qd2
{ One game continued the following way. } 9... Ne7 10. h4
{ The idea is there but the execution could have been better. } 10... g4 11.
Nh2 h5 12. Nf1 Nec6
{ Black had a large advantage after the opening in Bernotas, A. @@StartBracket@@2430@@EndBracket@@ - Ganguly, S.  @@StartBracket@@2650@@EndBracket@@ chess.com PRO League Stage 2018. White's game can definitely be improved earlier and you can probably say as far as committing to 8.h3. The d4 push doesn't work anyway. }
