{ What else?  9.Bd2  Covering with the bishop is even worse - after Black's  9...Bb4  , White's position falls apart. }
9... Bxd4
{ Black wins the pawn on e4 but be a little careful with the execution. } 10.
Bxd4 e5 11. Be3 Nxe4
{ White does not have sufficient compensation for the missing pawn. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16) Early c4 Rare Moves"]
[Black "2.Nf3 e6 3.c4 Nc6 4.d4 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ The remaining chapters of the course will be devoted to c4 pushes if White tries to set up something similar to the Maroczy Bind. This system at the moment is considered to be the most dangerous weapon against the Sicilian Kan but first - let's pay attention to early c4 pushes and rare continuations, which shouldn't pose any problems. }
2. Nf3 e6 3. c4 { Another attempt to switch to the Maroczy Bind setup. } 3...
Nc6 4. d4
{ If White wants to push d4, it has to be done right now, otherwise later there might be no chance. }
4... cxd4 5. Nxd4 Nf6 6. Nc3
{ White has set up the Maroczy Bind but the pawn structure is still quite shaky and Black is very dynamic. Notice that Black didn't include ...a6 which is characteristic for the Kan, and now there's no reason to do it. The battle for the center commences. }
6... Bc5
{ This rare move is the simplest way to solve any opening problems - Black forces White to clarify what to do with the central knight.   6...Bb4  is the most played move in the position - not everything is so clear.  7.Nxc6  bxc6  8.Bd3  e5  , Black tries to exploit control over the central dark squares, White is usually expanding on the queenside. The theory here only begins. }
7. Nb3
{ The logical retreat with the knight to b3 might draw some comparisons with the previous chapters. White retreats with a tempo but now the knight on b3 isn't doing much. }
7... Bb4
{ Black switches to the main idea to pressure White's center. The difference is that Black keeps the knight on c6. }
8. Bd3 O-O
{ 8...d5?!  going for the pawn breakthrough in the center is one of the core ideas to combat the Maroczy Bind but don't take it for granted. It depends on the moment.  9.exd5  exd5  10.cxd5  Nxd5  11.O-O!  White is very fast with development, the position is open and the Black king is still in the center. Black needs to be very careful.   11...Nxc3?!  12.bxc3  Be7  accepting the pawn on c3 would be too much but the position still is quite dangerous.  13.Bf4  Be6  14.Re1  Although Black seemingly has no weaknesses, White is more active. White very quickly developed a dangerous initiative against the Black king in Eljanov, P. @@StartBracket@@2663@@EndBracket@@ - Abasov, N. @@StartBracket@@2632@@EndBracket@@ FIDE chess.com Grand Swiss 2019. }
9. O-O Ne5
{ Black has many dynamic ideas here to fight for the center. If White is a little slow, Black can consider playing ...b6 and ...Bb7, and the knight on e5 repositioned to g6. }
10. f4
{ White forces the matter and wants to push e5 next - Black has to react fast. }
10... Qb6+ { Good intermezzo move. } 11. Kh1 Nxd3 12. Qxd3 d5
{ The only way to question White's chosen setup. Black sacrifices a pawn for the initiative. }
13. cxd5 exd5
{ While the first trade seems to be quite automatic, now White has some choices, both good and bad. }
14. exd5 Re8
{ Keeping the knights on the board and just grabbing the pawn looks reasonable but now Black has a lasting initiative. }
