[Round "?"]
[White "16) Early c4 Rare Moves"]
[Black "2.Nf3 e6 3.d4 − 6.Nc3 Qc7 7.f3 #1 | Informational 7...Bc5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ The remaining chapters of the course will be devoted to c4 pushes if White tries to set up something similar to the Maroczy Bind. This system at the moment is considered to be the most dangerous weapon against the Sicilian Kan but first - let's pay attention to early c4 pushes and rare continuations, which shouldn't pose any problems. }
2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. c4
{ This is it - White goes for the Maroczy Bind once again, this time with more favorable circumstances. We will continue to examine the less played lines before moving to the top-notch theory. Black's strategy, in general, is to avoid playing ...d6 and the arising Hedgehog structure @@StartBracket@@pawns on d6, e6, knights of f6, d7, and light-squared bishop on b7@@EndBracket@@ as long as you can, and go for much more dynamic lines instead.  If White is ready to invest a lot of energy to force Black to play ...d6 and switch to the Hedgehog, you can do it as White will have lost time. We will explain this concept in more detail later. }
5... Nf6
{ Let's start with challenging the center and see, how well exactly is White prepared. The white pawn on e4 is under attack. }
6. Nc3
{ This is White's main response, also renewing the e5 threat.   6.e5?  is a typical mistake - there's almost no chance that your opponent will miss it, otherwise he would never go for this aggressive setup.  6...Qa5+  . }
6... Qc7
{ Black deals with the e5 threat - the Maroczy Bind setup against the Sicilian Kan here is a huge crossroads. White can seek some off-beat continuations to catch the opponent off-guard, or play the classical a3 to prevent Black from playing ...Bb4. Before the age of Stockfish and the likes, it was unanimously considered as 'the only way to fight for the advantage'.  Time passed and practice proved that Black has many practical options, and the position is not so simple to give conclusions about. Then came the modern Be2 and, with the help of modern engines, it became clear that White can allow the ...Bb4 maneuver - focusing on development, with plans to grab space advantage or go for a direct attack is much more important than the integrity of the pawn structure. But let's not get ahead of ourselves.   The biggest reason why we have decided to avoid playing the immediate  6...Bb4  with a pin on the e4-pawn is the following setup.  7.Qd3  Qc7  8.Nc2  White has not committed to Be2 yet and very early retreats Nc2, attacking the dark-squared bishop. The capture on c3 is a bad strategic choice as White will recapture with the queen and the pawn on e4 can't be taken since the black pawn on g7 hangs.  The Nc2 setups, in general, are one of the most dangerous approaches that White can take, and the circumstances here could have been better. We will keep the idea of ...Bb4 but look for a better moment to execute it. }
7. f3
{ White can go for the classical pawn structure of the Maroczy Bind once again. }
7... Bc5
{ Unfortunately, the idea to push away the knight from the d4-square does not work.   7...Be7  Black can play it out as classical Hedgehog but judge the consequences yourself.  8.Be3  O-O  9.Be2  b6  10.O-O  Bb7  All of this is done in the best traditions of the Hedgehog system.  11.Qd2  d6  12.Rfd1  White has saved a tempo for the necessary a3 move for the system, thus he is better. }
8. Be3 d6
{ 8...Nc6??  does not work either.  9.Nxe6!  and Black loses material. } 9. Qd2
{ Black might regret that he brought out the dark-squared bishop so early - the d6-pawn is very vulnerable. }
*

