8. Be2
{ White can also focus on development and pretty much ignore Black's last move, but now you will have the possibility for a successful breakthrough in the center. }
8... O-O 9. O-O d5
{ The dark-squared bishop will remove the knight that fights for the d5-square. }
10. cxd5 Bxc3 11. bxc3 exd5 12. Bg5 Nbd7
{ Black's position is in perfect order. Due to the nature of the open position, Black needs to be careful in the next few moves.   An aggressive continuation to the variation:  13.Nf5  dxe4  14.Qd4  Qe5  it's best to offer a queen trade.  15.Bxf6  Qxf6  16.fxe4  Ne5  .  The knight on e5 makes a wonderful blockade. Any immediate retreats from the white knight are not dangerous, but keep them on your radar.  17.Rad1  Be6  Black is looking for the right moment to play ...Nd7. }
