2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. c4
{ This is it - White goes for the Maroczy Bind once again, this time with more favorable circumstances. We will continue to examine the less played lines before moving to the top-notch theory. Black's strategy, in general, is to avoid playing ...d6 and the arising Hedgehog structure @@StartBracket@@pawns on d6, e6, knights of f6, d7, and light-squared bishop on b7@@EndBracket@@ as long as you can, and go for much more dynamic lines instead.  If White is ready to invest a lot of energy to force Black to play ...d6 and switch to the Hedgehog, you can do it as White will have lost time. We will explain this concept in more detail later. }
5... Nf6
{ Let's start with challenging the center and see, how well exactly is White prepared. The white pawn on e4 is under attack. }
6. Nc3
{ This is White's main response, also renewing the e5 threat.   6.e5?  is a typical mistake - there's almost no chance that your opponent will miss it, otherwise he would never go for this aggressive setup.  6...Qa5+  . }
6... Qc7
{ Black deals with the e5 threat - the Maroczy Bind setup against the Sicilian Kan here is a huge crossroads. White can seek some off-beat continuations to catch the opponent off-guard or play the classical a3 to prevent Black from playing ...Bb4. Before the age of Stockfish and the likes, it was unanimously considered as 'the only way to fight for the advantage'.  Time passed and the practice proved that Black has many practical options, and the position itself is not so simple to give conclusions. Then came the modern Be2 and with the help of modern engines, it became clear that White can allow the ...Bb4 maneuver and that focusing on the development with the plans to grab space advantage or go for a direct attack is much more important than the integrity of the pawn structure. However, let's do step by step. }
7. f4
{ This is an interesting idea and, once again, it's important to understand what White is aiming for - it's not only the e5 push. If you quickly close the center with ...d6 and go for the Hedgehog, White will be able to build up the perfect system against it and take the space advantage. Every variation which requires aggressive measures is of paramount importance. }
7... Bb4 8. e5 Ne4
{ Black wants to take on c3 with the knight, retreat with the dark-squared bishop to e7, and, depending on the situation, either push ...d6 or ...d5. }
9. Qf3
{ Most logical way to defend the knight on c3 - an alternative square is d3. }
9... Nxc3 10. bxc3 Be7 11. Bd3 d5
{ Since the white pawn on c3 is vulnerable, Black can explore the options to go after the c4-pawn. Please notice that after ...d6, White is not obliged to take the pawn and could opt to sacrifice it. }
12. O-O dxc4 13. Bc2 g6 14. Rb1
{ White most certainly has compensation for the pawn, but it's not very obvious how to capitalize on it because the position is closed. }
14... Nd7 15. f5
{ The typical breakthrough, with all the potential sacrifices, leads nowhere, at least right away. }
15... Nxe5 16. Ba4+ Bd7 17. Bxd7+ Qxd7 { The position simplifies too much. }
18. Qe4 Qd5 19. Qxd5 exd5 20. Re1 f6
{ Maybe White will win back the sacrificed pawns but that was not the point of the attack, was it? }
