{ This is White's main response, also renewing the e5 threat.   6.e5?  is a typical mistake - there's almost no chance that your opponent will miss it, otherwise he would never go for this aggressive setup.  6...Qa5+  . }
6... Qc7
{ Black deals with the e5 threat - the Maroczy Bind setup against the Sicilian Kan here is a huge crossroads. White can seek some off-beat continuations to catch the opponent off-guard or play the classical a3 to prevent Black from playing ...Bb4. Before the age of Stockfish and the likes, it was unanimously considered as 'the only way to fight for the advantage'.  Time passed and the practice proved that Black has many practical options, and the position itself is not so simple to give conclusions. Then came the modern Be2 and with the help of modern engines, it became clear that White can allow the ...Bb4 maneuver and that focusing on the development with the plans to grab space advantage or go for a direct attack is much more important than the integrity of the pawn structure. However, let's do step by step. }
7. Be3
{ Another tricky move @@StartBracket@@there are many of them, surprise, surprise@@EndBracket@@ - White remains flexible with the potential follow-ups thus it's a good idea to force matters in the center immediately. }
7... Bb4
{ One of the most thematic ideas that Black always considers, is to take on c3, continue with ...d6 and ...Nbd7, and effectively use the dark squares. }
8. Qb3
{ Very energetic - White stops Black's idea and is ready to sacrifice a pawn. }
8... Bc5
{ Since the white queen is no longer fighting for the d4-square, Black starts to fight for it.   8...Bxc3+?!  Taking the pawn looks like a risky choice.  9.Qxc3  Nxe4  10.Qa3   Even the typical  10.Nb5  may work as well which is a known idea from another line where White has played a3 instead of Be3.  10...b6  11.f3  Nc5  12.b4  Nb7  13.Nb5  White's initiative is spreading like wildfire. Black may temporarily keep the pawn but the queenside will be very difficult to develop. The b-pawn is very weak. }
9. Be2
{ Now Black needs to identify the weakness of White's setup. Against the classical Hedgehog, White is ready, but with the active dark-squared bishop on c5 fighting for the d4-square - not so much. }
9... d6
{ Before Black is ready to play ...Nc6, it's necessary to include ...d6 to protect the dark-squared bishop. }
10. Rd1 Bd7 11. O-O Nc6 12. Qc2 O-O
{ Black plans to twice take on d4, push e5 and establish a counterplay against White's c4-pawn. Try to provoke White to include a3 as this will make your counterplay against the c4-pawn more real. If White doesn't rush anywhere, also Black can make some preparation moves. The weakness of the d4-square may play a role later. }
13. a3 { White forces matters. } 13... Nxd4 { Now starts a mass of trades. }
14. Bxd4 Bxd4 15. Rxd4 e5 16. Rd2 Be6 17. Rfd1 Rfd8
{ Engines give here some advantage for White but this is a classical position where Black has enough counterplay at the queenside. It might be simply impossible for White to get to the d6 pawn - there's always the ...Ne8. Black would like to keep the knight on the board, if possible. }
