{ White's concerns are understandable - Black wants to play ...Ne5, ...Bc5 and many dynamic ideas and, from White's perspective, it could be difficult to navigate through all the nuances - thus the trade simplifies the position. At the same time, the trade also creates a considerable weakness on d4. If White is not accurate, it's easy to misplay this position. }
8... dxc6 9. Be3 Bd6
{ Black's idea is to fight for the d4-square but you can't underestimate White's chances. Go for the more careful approach and trade the dark-squared bishop via the f4-square. Then you want to continue with ...e5 and ...Be6, bringing out your light-squared bishop. If White manages to keep the light-squared bishop imprisoned on c8, Black will be in big trouble.   9...e5  One of the most typical ideas that Black usually has in these positions is to trade the dark-squared bishops via the c5-square. This would allow Black to fight for control of the d4-square and leave White with a bad light-squared bishop. The problem is the number of moves to make this maneuver work. Besides, Black also has a weakness on b6.   10.h3  Be6  11.O-O  Nd7?!  One of the most common mistakes in chess is focusing too much on one's own ideas and forgetting to pay attention to the opponent.  12.Nd5!  Black can't take the knight as the bishop on e6 will be trapped, plus the position opens while Black is seriously underdeveloped.  12...Qd8  13.b4!  f6?!  If Black insists on his idea to get rid of the bishop, things can get ugly soon.  14.Qf3!  a5  15.a3  cxd5  16.exd5  Bf7  17.c5  White unexpectedly has a crushing attack. }
10. Qd2
{ This would be a careless way to prepare c5 as Black can trade off White's dark-squared bishop now. Focusing too much on your ideas - remember? }
10... Ng4
{ Black now either trades off the strong dark-squared bishop or will take full control over the dark squares. }
