[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "16) Early c4 Rare Moves"]
[Black "2.Nf3 e6 3.d4 − 6.Nc3 Qc7 7.Bd3 #8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ The remaining chapters of the course will be devoted to c4 pushes if White tries to set up something similar to the Maroczy Bind. This system at the moment is considered to be the most dangerous weapon against the Sicilian Kan but first - let's pay attention to early c4 pushes and rare continuations, which shouldn't pose any problems. }
2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. c4
{ This is it - White goes for the Maroczy Bind once again, this time with more favorable circumstances. We will continue to examine the less played lines before moving to the top-notch theory. Black's strategy, in general, is to avoid playing ...d6 and the arising Hedgehog structure @@StartBracket@@pawns on d6, e6, knights of f6, d7, and light-squared bishop on b7@@EndBracket@@ as long as you can, and go for much more dynamic lines instead.  If White is ready to invest a lot of energy to force Black to play ...d6 and switch to the Hedgehog, you can do it as White will have lost time. We will explain this concept in more detail later. }
5... Nf6
{ Let's start with challenging the center and see, how well exactly is White prepared. The white pawn on e4 is under attack. }
6. Nc3
{ This is White's main response, also renewing the e5 threat.   6.e5?  is a typical mistake - there's almost no chance that your opponent will miss it, otherwise he would never go for this aggressive setup.  6...Qa5+  . }
6... Qc7
{ Black deals with the e5 threat - the Maroczy Bind setup against the Sicilian Kan here is a huge crossroads. White can seek some off-beat continuations to catch the opponent off-guard or play the classical a3 to prevent Black from playing ...Bb4. Before the age of Stockfish and the likes, it was unanimously considered as 'the only way to fight for the advantage'.  Time passed and the practice proved that Black has many practical options, and the position itself is not so simple to give conclusions. Then came the modern Be2 and with the help of modern engines, it became clear that White can allow the ...Bb4 maneuver and that focusing on the development with the plans to grab space advantage or go for a direct attack is much more important than the integrity of the pawn structure. However, let's do step by step. }
7. Bd3
{ White protects the pawn on e4 in advance but also weakens the control of the d4-square, thus Black's continuation is quite obvious. }
7... Nc6
{ Not only does Black lay eyes on the d4-quare but also keeps an option to reroute the knight to e5 for some active perspectives. }
8. Nxc6
{ White's concerns are understandable - Black wants to play ...Ne5, ...Bc5 and many dynamic ideas and, from White's perspective, it could be difficult to navigate through all the nuances - thus the trade simplifies the position. At the same time, the trade also creates a considerable weakness on d4. If White is not accurate, it's easy to misplay this position. }
8... dxc6 9. Be3 Bd6
{ Black's idea is to fight for the d4-square but you can't underestimate White's chances. Go for the more careful approach and trade the dark-squared bishop via the f4-square. Then you want to continue with ...e5 and ...Be6, bringing out your light-squared bishop. If White manages to keep the light-squared bishop imprisoned on c8, Black will be in big trouble.   9...e5  One of the most typical ideas that Black usually has in these positions is to trade the dark-squared bishops via the c5-square. This would allow Black to fight for control of the d4-square and leave White with a bad light-squared bishop. The problem is the number of moves to make this maneuver work. Besides, Black also has a weakness on b6.   10.h3  Be6  11.O-O  Nd7?!  One of the most common mistakes in chess is focusing too much on one's own ideas and forgetting to pay attention to the opponent.  12.Nd5!  Black can't take the knight as the bishop on e6 will be trapped, plus the position opens while Black is seriously underdeveloped.  12...Qd8  13.b4!  f6?!  If Black insists on his idea to get rid of the bishop, things can get ugly soon.  14.Qf3!  a5  15.a3  cxd5  16.exd5  Bf7  17.c5  White unexpectedly has a crushing attack. }
10. h3 { White prepares Qd2 to push c5 and f4 next. } 10... Bf4 11. Bxf4 Qxf4
{ Black has fully equalized the game and wants to play ...e5 and ...Be6 next. The weakness of the b6-square is irrelevant. }
12. Qd2 { One game continued the following way. } 12... Qxd2+ 13. Kxd2 e5 14.
Ke3 Be6 15. Be2 Ke7
{ There's no need to castle anymore - the Black king controls a lot of important squares in the center. }
16. Rad1 b5 { Black finds more targets to pressure at the queenside. } 17. cxb5
axb5 18. a3 Rhb8 19. Rd2 b4 20. axb4 Rxb4
{ Black completely took over the game in Lukovic, V. @@StartBracket@@2234@@EndBracket@@ - Miladinovic, I. @@StartBracket@@2556@@EndBracket@@ SRB-ch 2011. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17) 5.c4, 7.a3, Na4"]
[Black "5.c4 Nf6 6.Nc3 − 10.Qd2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7
{ Black deals with the e5 threat - the Maroczy Bind setup against the Sicilian Kan here is a huge crossroads. White can seek some off-beat continuations to catch the opponent off-guard or play the classical a3 to prevent Black from playing ...Bb4. Before the age of Stockfish and the likes, it was unanimously considered as 'the only way to fight for the advantage'.  Time passed and the practice proved that Black has many practical options, and the position itself is not so simple to give conclusions. Then came the modern Be2 and with the help of modern engines, it became clear that White can allow the ...Bb4 maneuver and that focusing on the development with the plans to grab space advantage or go for a direct attack is much more important than the integrity of the pawn structure. However, let's do step by step. }
7. a3
{ This 'old continuation' remains popular even today. White's game feels to be more positional and harmonious while  7.Be2  is very aggressive, ignoring some positional concepts but fast charging forward.  7...Bb4  the ideas of allowing Black to play ...Bb4 we will examine in the final chapters of the course. }
7... b6
{ First, Black fianchettoes the bishop on b7 and keeps eyes open, what White will choose next. }
8. Be3 Bb7 9. f3
{ So, White has set up the Maroczy Bind - the position which has been tested for decades. Where to go? There are two plans. The first one is to commit to ...d6, aiming for the traditional Hedgehog, however, today it's considered to be very dangerous because White has several perspective plans. Among them: either push the a-pawn as far as a5 or push forward the kingside pawns @@StartBracket@@and it does not matter, where the white king stands@@EndBracket@@.  The second plan for Black at the end of the 90's resurrected one of the most creative players in the chess circuit Alexander Morozevich - Black plays ...Nc6 with mainly two ideas. First, trade the knights on d4 and continue with ...Bd6 and ...h5, enjoying good counterplay because of the dark squares. The second, reposition the knight on g6 via e5-square, push the h-pawn as far as h4 and continue with either ...Bd6 or ...d5. The only minus - lack of flexibility and the weak pawn on b6. }
9... Nc6
{ With this move Black's idea is to escape the aforementioned two dangerous plans. Let us remind you, what they are - White either pushing forward the a-pawn as far as a5 or storming forward with the pawns on the kingside @@StartBracket@@g4-g5 and h4@@EndBracket@@ when Black will be dreaming about getting a draw.  With the knight on c6, these plans are impossible. Black's task is to get as complex Hedgehog as possible, delaying the ...d6 move as long as possible since you might want to include your dark-squared bishop in the game via the d6-square. With pushing forward the h-pawn Black will be able to create his counterplay. }
10. Qd2
{ White can include something before switching to the Na4 maneuver a move or two later - it does not matter. }
10... Be7 11. Na4 O-O { Black keeps the option to include ...Rb8 later. } 12.
Nxc6 { It makes perfect sense to take the pawn, otherwise, why attack it? }
12... Bxc6 13. Nxb6 Rab8 14. c5 { Everything makes perfect sense so far. }
14... d5
{ A very powerful counterstrike - White can't open the position as his development state has seen better days. }
15. e5 { The best practical choice. } 15... Qxe5 16. Be2 Rbd8
{ Black has a very rich game. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17) 5.c4, 7.a3, Na4"]
[Black "5.c4 Nf6 6.Nc3 − 10.Be2 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7
{ Black deals with the e5 threat - the Maroczy Bind setup against the Sicilian Kan here is a huge crossroads. White can seek some off-beat continuations to catch the opponent off-guard or play the classical a3 to prevent Black from playing ...Bb4. Before the age of Stockfish and the likes, it was unanimously considered as 'the only way to fight for the advantage'.  Time passed and the practice proved that Black has many practical options, and the position itself is not so simple to give conclusions. Then came the modern Be2 and with the help of modern engines, it became clear that White can allow the ...Bb4 maneuver and that focusing on the development with the plans to grab space advantage or go for a direct attack is much more important than the integrity of the pawn structure. However, let's do step by step. }
7. a3
{ This 'old continuation' remains popular even today. White's game feels to be more positional and harmonious while  7.Be2  is very aggressive, ignoring some positional concepts but fast charging forward.  7...Bb4  the ideas of allowing Black to play ...Bb4 we will examine in the final chapters of the course. }
7... b6
{ First, Black fianchettoes the bishop on b7 and keeps eyes open, what White will choose next. }
8. Be3 Bb7 9. f3
{ So, White has set up the Maroczy Bind - the position which has been tested for decades. Where to go? There are two plans. The first one is to commit to ...d6, aiming for the traditional Hedgehog, however, today it's considered to be very dangerous because White has several perspective plans. Among them: either push the a-pawn as far as a5 or push forward the kingside pawns @@StartBracket@@and it does not matter, where the white king stands@@EndBracket@@.  The second plan for Black at the end of the 90's resurrected one of the most creative players in the chess circuit Alexander Morozevich - Black plays ...Nc6 with mainly two ideas. First, trade the knights on d4 and continue with ...Bd6 and ...h5, enjoying good counterplay because of the dark squares. The second, reposition the knight on g6 via e5-square, push the h-pawn as far as h4 and continue with either ...Bd6 or ...d5. The only minus - lack of flexibility and the weak pawn on b6. }
9... Nc6
{ With this move Black's idea is to escape the aforementioned two dangerous plans. Let us remind you, what they are - White either pushing forward the a-pawn as far as a5 or storming forward with the pawns on the kingside @@StartBracket@@g4-g5 and h4@@EndBracket@@ when Black will be dreaming about getting a draw.  With the knight on c6, these plans are impossible. Black's task is to get as complex Hedgehog as possible, delaying the ...d6 move as long as possible since you might want to include your dark-squared bishop in the game via the d6-square. With pushing forward the h-pawn Black will be able to create his counterplay. }
10. Be2
{ White may want to postpone the idea of Na4, pressing the b6-pawn for later - either knowingly or randomly. Then Black's plan of ...Nxd4 will only bring problems but to play ...Rb8 with the plan of ...Nh5-f5 is not very practical - an infinite number of difficult variations simply don't fit in an average human's mind. However, if Black avoids playing ...Rb8, the variations are less and they are more forced, with everything moving forward! It's easy to understand and calculate. But one step at a time... }
10... Be7 11. Rc1
{ White saves a tempo for the standard Qd2 so that it's possible to immediately build up a battery with Qe1-f2 later. }
11... O-O 12. Na4
{ The order of the moves, how White can execute Na4 can be tricky. } 12... Nh5
{ We were considering this to be our main approach against anything Na4 but then we decided that the Nxd4 plan, whenever possible, is simpler. Black here wants to push ...f5 for a rich counterplay on the kingside. The knight might be heading to f4.   12...Rab8  Black, unfortunately, can't switch to the main line.  13.b4  Nxd4?  14.Qxd4  Bc6  It may seem the same but here the white pawn stands on b4, which makes a huge difference.  15.b5!  Bxa3  16.O-O!  Very strong - on top of the pawn, White sacrifices also exchange to dominate the dark squares.  16...Bxc1  17.Rxc1  Bb7  18.e5  Ne8  19.Nxb6  Black is paralyzed. }
13. g3
{ Not an obvious move for White to make - that's a potential target in Black's attack. This stops ...Nf4, but not ...f5. }
13... f5 14. exf5
{ If White retreats  14.Nb3  , we transpose to a later line with  14...Ne5  . }
14... exf5 15. Nxc6
{ White goes for the b-pawn immediately.   15.Nc2  now Black will have another piece to improve the attack  15...Ne5  Black's threats look very real and all of it - for just a pawn. }
15... Bxc6 16. Nxb6 Rae8 17. Nd5 Qb8
{ Notice that the white king can't safely castle - among all threats there's also ...Nxg3. }
18. f4 Nf6 19. Bd4
{ To normalize the position, White may want to give up the extra pawn and quickly castle. }
19... Nxd5 20. cxd5 Bxd5 21. O-O Qb7
{ The position is double-edged. Black has a weaker pawn structure but the white king is quite vulnerable. }
*

