{ With this move Black's idea is to escape the aforementioned two dangerous plans. Let us remind you, what they are - White either pushing forward the a-pawn as far as a5 or storming forward with the pawns on the kingside @@StartBracket@@g4-g5 and h4@@EndBracket@@ when Black will be dreaming about getting a draw.  With the knight on c6, these plans are impossible. Black's task is to get as complex Hedgehog as possible, delaying the ...d6 move as long as possible since you might want to include your dark-squared bishop in the game via the d6-square. With pushing forward the h-pawn Black will be able to create his counterplay. }
10. Be2
{ White may want to postpone the idea of Na4, pressing the b6-pawn for later - either knowingly or randomly. Then Black's plan of ...Nxd4 will only bring problems but to play ...Rb8 with the plan of ...Nh5-f5 is not very practical - an infinite number of difficult variations simply don't fit in an average human's mind. However, if Black avoids playing ...Rb8, the variations are less and they are more forced, with everything moving forward! It's easy to understand and calculate. But one step at a time... }
10... Be7 11. Rc1
{ White saves a tempo for the standard Qd2 so that it's possible to immediately build up a battery with Qe1-f2 later. }
11... O-O 12. Na4
{ The order of the moves, how White can execute Na4 can be tricky. } 12... Nh5
{ We were considering this to be our main approach against anything Na4 but then we decided that the Nxd4 plan, whenever possible, is simpler. Black here wants to push ...f5 for a rich counterplay on the kingside. The knight might be heading to f4.   12...Rab8  Black, unfortunately, can't switch to the main line.  13.b4  Nxd4?  14.Qxd4  Bc6  It may seem the same but here the white pawn stands on b4, which makes a huge difference.  15.b5!  Bxa3  16.O-O!  Very strong - on top of the pawn, White sacrifices also exchange to dominate the dark squares.  16...Bxc1  17.Rxc1  Bb7  18.e5  Ne8  19.Nxb6  Black is paralyzed. }
13. Nb3
{ If White wants to brutally grab the pawn, Black quickly seizes the initiative. }
13... f5
{ Now White will have to navigate through some uneasy choices while for Black it's very simple - everything forward! Make sure you get some popcorn before looking at the following lines. }
14. Bxb6
{ Taking the pawn with the bishop catapults the Black queen closer to the epicenter of the action. }
14... Qe5 15. Nac5
{ Here Black has two very appealing ways to continue the attack. } 15... fxe4
{ This is probably a simpler choice which is also easier to remember. It also offers White a way out of the complications. Will he gather the courage? }
16. Nxb7 { Another way to grab material, leaving the king's fate to luck. }
16... exf3
{ It's also possible to explore  16...Rab8  with similar ideas if White retreats on c5 and once again delivers the fork on d7. This move is more straightforward. }
17. gxf3 Rxf3
{ Due to the multiple threats, the white king doesn't stand a chance - the extra piece does not matter. }
18. N7c5 Nf4 19. Nxd7 Ng2+
{ Positioning the queen on e4 with many threats works just fine as well - this is more forcing. }
20. Kd2 Qxb2+ 21. Qc2 Bg5+
{ White's position collapses like a house of cards. } *

