14. g3 { Smart defense. } 14... Ne5
{ Black doesn't rush with taking the pawn but focuses on the threats. Now ...fxe4 is a threat as White won't have f4 move because of ...Nf3+.   14...fxe4  15.f4  this is White's idea - to solidify the kingside. The b6-pawn is still weak but the white king can safely castle short. It doesn't mean that it's not playable though. }
15. f4
{ The best move - White keeps the position as closed as possible and at the same time targets two Black's minor pieces. }
15... Bxe4
{ Black keeps the initiative going - the white rook on h1 is under attack but the black knight wants to jump to g4 to avoid the loss of a piece. We will learn the most critical line but make sure to check the clickable variations for a better understanding, of what happens if White does something else. }
16. O-O
{ This might be a choice of a pragmatic player - keep things under some control and avoid gambling.   16.Bxb6  A very tempting move, however, if White does this, he already has to give up the rook on h1, otherwise, Black's ...Bc6-a4 could be a major problem to White.  16...Qb8  17.fxe5  Bxh1  18.Qxd7  Otherwise Black plays ...Bc6 and White's queenside is starting to fall apart  18...Rf7!  With a trick, Black defends both of his hanging minor pieces.   19.Qxe6  g6  20.Bxh5  gxh5  21.Nac5!  Qe8  It's material equality on the board. Both players have their strengths and weaknesses, thus the position is about balanced.  22.Rd1  Bc6  23.Nd4  Bxc5  Black has to start to eliminate some of White's active pieces.  24.Bxc5  Ba4  25.Rd3  Qxe6  26.Nxe6  Re8  Black eliminates the strongly passed e-pawn.  27.Nf4  Rxe5+  28.Kd2  Rd7  the chances are still equal. }
16... Ng4 17. Bxb6 Qc6 18. Nd4 Qb7
{ Black's initiative is still going but this time the piece count is even. }
19. Bxg4 fxg4 20. Qxg4 Nf6 21. Qe2 a5
{ Black is down a pawn but it's greatly compensated by the powerful light-squared bishop and the weakened white king. }
