12. Qxd4
{ If White takes with the queen, there's a major difference with a position, that could have occurred before, when White pushed @@StartFEN@@1r2kb1r/1bqp1ppp/ppn1pn2/8/N1PNP3/P3BP2/1P4PP/R2QKB1R w KQk - 3 11@@EndFEN@@  11.b4  . }
12... Bc6
{ With the white pawn on b2 White doesn't have access to b5 push and only then wins the pawn. }
13. c5 b5
{ Black follows the pattern and closes the queenside. No matter where the white knight goes next, Black plays ...d6 and gets a fine game. }
14. Nb6
{ A little bit more ambitious than  14.Nc3  but this also can be a little scary as the white knight on  b6  might also be lost. }
14... d6 15. cxd6 Bxd6 16. Rc1 O-O
{ Black has finished the development and now needs to deal with the pin at the c-file. }
17. Be2 Rb7 18. Qc3 Qb8
{ Due to a tactical trick, Black escapes the pin but White has nothing better than to accept it. }
19. Qxc6 Rc7 20. Nd7 Nxd7 21. Qxa6 Rxc1+ 22. Bxc1 Bxh2
{ Black sacrifices a pawn but White's king is too weak to call this a success. }
23. Qxb5 Qc7 24. Qc4 Qb8 25. Qb5 { A smart player will repeat the position. } *

