14. Qg5 e5
{ Black deals with both of White's threats and wants to reposition the bishop on c5. }
15. Bf2
{ Once again, the strongest reply - on f2 the bishop won't be needing the protection of the queen.   15.Qxg7??  White is on the wrong side of tactics - the knight on c3 is under attack as well.  15...exd4  16.Qxf6  Be5  Black wins. }
15... O-O
{ The position is double-edged. Black wants to play ...Bc5 to control all the dark squares in the center but the move ...a5 is necessary to keep the square, otherwise White will play b4 as soon as the black bishop will land on c5. }
16. b4
{ If White tries to stop the maneuver before it's happening, it allows Black to open the queenside. }
16... b5
{ And not the tempting  16...a5  as then after  17.b5  and Na4 next White would close the queenside and seriously pressure the b6-pawn. }
17. cxb5
{ Necessary, otherwise after  17.c5  Black will just retreat and play ...d6 next, equalizing the game. }
17... axb5 18. Qd2 Be7
{ Black is ahead in the development thus it's in his best interest to open the center as quickly as possible. }
19. Bd3 d5
{ This thrust seems to be coming in either way, even if involving a piece sacrifice - notice the ... Qc3+ check idea. }
20. exd5 Nxd5 21. Bxh7+ Kh8
{ Quite precise, otherwise, White's next move Qc2+ and Nxd5 next could be a little annoying. }
22. Nxd5 Bxd5 23. Qxd5 Qc3+
{ There's the idea again - Black is threatening to win the rook. } 24. Ke2 Rbd8
25. Qa2
{ White covers from the ...Rd2+ threat but now Black takes back the piece and enjoys a very good compensation for the missing pawn. }
25... Kxh7 26. Rhd1 e4 27. fxe4 f5
{ If someone is risking here, it's White - it's difficult to play with such an exposed king. }
