{ If you can bring out the dark-squared bishop to d6, do it but mind the tactical possibilities. Please mind that ...Bd6 maneuver as such might not always be available, if White had included Rc1, not going after the b6-pawn right away - watch out for the incoming tactical shots on the b6-pawn. Then Black can just continue development with ...Be7 and try not to play ...d6 as long as possible.  For White, such a slower choice is also not very obvious because at any moment a counterstrike with ...b5 might turn the tables. However, don't do this when unprepared. Now Black is threatening ...Bxh2 but don't miss White's potential counterstrike of Rxh2 and Bf4 next. }
13. O-O-O
{ Castling long to attack the bishop on d6 with a tempo and the following kingside pawn march is interesting but at the same time not a very obvious choice for White as it jumps under the direct ...b5 push. White's queenside is quite vulnerable. }
13... Be7
{ 13...Bxh2??  unfortunately, White is prepared against it.  14.Rxh2!  Qxh2  15.Bf4  Qh4  16.Bxb8  Nxb8  17.Qd6  Nc6  18.Nxb6  White is crashing through on the queenside. }
14. Kb1
{ White quickly tries to hide the king before the b-file is about to open. }
14... O-O 15. Bf4
{ White could slow down the incoming ...b5 push with  15.Nc3  but Black doesn't have to hurry with it.  The threats can be improved with slower maneuvers like ...d6, ...Nd7-c5 and then at some point go for ...b5. }
15... e5 16. Bg5 b5 { The moment to strike feels right. } 17. cxb5 axb5 18. Nc3
b4
{ Black got a powerful queenside attack in Velicka, P. @@StartBracket@@2441@@EndBracket@@ - Manolache, M. @@StartBracket@@2462@@EndBracket@@ Ortigueira op 4th 2005. }
