{ Another idea to bother the darks-squared bishop on d6, inviting to send it back to e7. }
13... Bxh2
{ And now this idea works! You must understand the moments and differences when Black can take the pawn, when it's not possible and when the tactical shots of taking on b6 don't go through. These lines are very tactical. }
14. Rxh2 Qxh2 15. Bf4
{ White employs the same idea as with castling long but now the major difference is that the white king is still in the center. }
15... Qh4+ { That's a check! } 16. g3 Qh5
{ The game is a complete mess but chances are equal. } 17. Nd4
{ White wants to dominate the dark squares, not rushing to take the black rook.   17.Bxb8  Qxf3!  a very important intermezzo move, otherwise Black is in trouble.  18.Bc7  Qxb3  19.Nxb6  O-O  with balanced dynamics. }
17... Ne5 18. Qb4 Rb7
{ Black removes the rook from the pin and wants to play ... Nc6 next. } 19.
Nxb6 Nxf3+ 20. Nxf3 Qxf3 21. Qc5
{ Black has an escape with a perpetual check. } 21... Qxe4+ 22. Be2 Qh1+ 23.
Bf1 Qe4+ { If both players got this far, congratulations! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17) 5.c4, 7.a3, Na4"]
[Black "5.c4 Nf6 6.Nc3 − 10.Na4 #15"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7
{ Black deals with the e5 threat - the Maroczy Bind setup against the Sicilian Kan here is a huge crossroads. White can seek some off-beat continuations to catch the opponent off-guard or play the classical a3 to prevent Black from playing ...Bb4. Before the age of Stockfish and the likes, it was unanimously considered as 'the only way to fight for the advantage'.  Time passed and the practice proved that Black has many practical options, and the position itself is not so simple to give conclusions. Then came the modern Be2 and with the help of modern engines, it became clear that White can allow the ...Bb4 maneuver and that focusing on the development with the plans to grab space advantage or go for a direct attack is much more important than the integrity of the pawn structure. However, let's do step by step. }
7. a3
{ This 'old continuation' remains popular even today. White's game feels to be more positional and harmonious while  7.Be2  is very aggressive, ignoring some positional concepts but fast charging forward.  7...Bb4  the ideas of allowing Black to play ...Bb4 we will examine in the final chapters of the course. }
7... b6
{ First, Black fianchettoes the bishop on b7 and keeps eyes open, what White will choose next. }
8. Be3 Bb7 9. f3
{ So, White has set up the Maroczy Bind - the position which has been tested for decades. Where to go? There are two plans. The first one is to commit to ...d6, aiming for the traditional Hedgehog, however, today it's considered to be very dangerous because White has several perspective plans. Among them: either push the a-pawn as far as a5 or push forward the kingside pawns @@StartBracket@@and it does not matter, where the white king stands@@EndBracket@@.  The second plan for Black at the end of the 90's resurrected one of the most creative players in the chess circuit Alexander Morozevich - Black plays ...Nc6 with mainly two ideas. First, trade the knights on d4 and continue with ...Bd6 and ...h5, enjoying good counterplay because of the dark squares. The second, reposition the knight on g6 via e5-square, push the h-pawn as far as h4 and continue with either ...Bd6 or ...d5. The only minus - lack of flexibility and the weak pawn on b6. }
9... Nc6
{ With this move Black's idea is to escape the aforementioned two dangerous plans. Let us remind you, what they are - White either pushing forward the a-pawn as far as a5 or storming forward with the pawns on the kingside @@StartBracket@@g4-g5 and h4@@EndBracket@@ when Black will be dreaming about getting a draw.  With the knight on c6, these plans are impossible. Black's task is to get as complex Hedgehog as possible, delaying the ...d6 move as long as possible since you might want to include your dark-squared bishop in the game via the d6-square. With pushing forward the h-pawn Black will be able to create his counterplay. }
10. Na4
{ First, we need to familiarize ourselves with this simple move - White goes after the b6-pawn and tries to exploit the obvious drawback of Black's last move. Although it's not the most popular move at the moment, it feels like a stand-alone continuation, which can't be put into the same basket as other a3 continuations.  The other continuations like b4, Qd2, Rc1, or Be2 look very similar and on most occasions will just transpose from one line to another. This plan is one of the favorites of Stockfish and it makes sense. }
10... Rb8
{ Everything so far is logical. We are attacked and there comes the defense. Now White faces some of the first choices.   10...Ne5?!  Unfortunately, this typical maneuver here is not so great.  11.Nb3  Bc6  12.Nxb6  Rb8  13.c5  d5  . This idea we've seen before but White emerges on top of the complications.  14.Na5  dxe4  15.Nxc6  Qxc6  16.Qd4  White's domination of the queenside, backed with two bishops seems to be too strong. }
11. Rc1
{ A multi-purpose move that might be the favorite choice of an experienced player. }
11... Nxd4
{ Black forces matters in the center and is more practical.  11...Be7  also is very interesting but we decided that it requires Black to remember too many computerized lines and calculate a lot while White has several interesting continuations.   11...Bd6?  12.Ne2!  now Black suddenly has real problems defending the b6-pawn as the dark-squared bishop is hanging as well.  12...Ba8  13.Nxb6  White wins something. }
12. Bxd4 { Capturing with the bishop feels just too shy. } 12... Bc6
{ Black defends the pawn on b6 and prepares to play ...Bxa4 and ...Bc5 next, continuing the fight for the dark squares. }
13. e5
{ White could go for a more radical choice but this opens Black's light-squared bishop. }
13... Nh5 14. c5 b5 { Naturally, Black should close the queenside. } 15. Nb6
Nf4 16. g3 Nd5
{ The intruding knight is eliminated and Black will get a comfortable game. }
17. Nxd5 Bxd5 18. b4 Be7 19. Bd3 h5
{ The chances are equal. White has problems dealing with the light-squared bishop on d5. Even if he would prepare the Be4 maneuver to trade it, Black can always step back to c6, offering a trade with ...dxc6 and thus leaving White with a bad dark-squared bishop and an open d-file. }
*

