{ The best move that White can do - it could be quite challenging for White to pick it up.   A@@EndBracket@@  17.Qb4  If White declines accepting the material, Black equalizes comfortably.  17...Qxb4  18.axb4  Ra8  19.Bd3  .  White can't stop the ...a5 push as Black has an alternate idea of ...Rfc8, ...Ne8 and ...d6 as well.  19...a5  20.bxa5  Bxc5  21.Nxb5  .  Now the position simplifies quite fast.  21...Bxb5  22.Bxb5  Bb4+  23.Ke2  Rxa5  24.Bd3  d6  .  The white b-pawn is not going anywhere.   B@@EndBracket@@  17.b4  White would love to, but the black queen escapes from the capture attempt.  17...Qxa3  18.Rb1  18...e5!  The only move but it's enough - Black deflects the white bishop from attacking the queen on c1.  19.Bxe5   19.Qxe5??  Ng4!  20.fxg4  Bf6  Black is crashing through.  19...a5  .  The game becomes razor sharp and it's not even clear if White is interested to pick up the exchange on b8.  20.Kf2  Rbc8  21.Bd6  Bxd6  22.cxd6  The peaceful approach. Now, this leads to some kind of a perpetual check.  22...Ba8  23.Nxb5  Rc2+  24.Be2  Qa2  25.Nc3   25.Qe3?  Bxe4!  26.Ra1?  Qd5  27.Nc3  Qf5  White completely loses the game thread.  25...Qa3  26.Nb5  Qa2  Draw by repetition.   C@@EndBracket@@  17.Bxb8?!  Accepting the exchange right away in terms of the best approach for White is a little too early.  17...Rxb8  Now, in all variations, Black gets access to the c7-square for the queen and good counterplay.  18.Bd3  Finally, White can continue development and try to close the action on the queenside with a pawn sacrifice.   18.Qb4  White would love to trade queens but Black doesn't have to.  18...Qc7  19.Be2?  a5  20.Qd4  Qa7  .  This trick is fairly common for the position.  21.Nd1  d6  22.O-O  dxc5  23.Qe3  Nd7  Black's compensation for the sacrificed exchange is more than enough.   18.Qd2  This retreat is clearly directed against Black's ...b4 threat.  18...b4  19.Na2  19...Bxc5  20.axb4  White is looking for simplifications but, instead, there are even more complications.  20...Qxa2!  21.Rxc5  Bxe4!  This idea we've seen already in other lines.  22.Qf4  e5  23.Rxe5  Rxb4  Black once again will be down a full rook but enjoying complete compensation for it.  24.fxe4  Qb1+  25.Kf2  Rxb2+  26.Kg1  Qd1  White seems safe, but there's no easy way to untangle the kingside and bring the extra rook into the game!  27.Qe3  g6  28.Rc5  Rb1  29.Kg2  Rb2+  White has to accept the draw!  18...b4  19.Na2  bxa3+  20.b4  Qc7  White is up an exchange but Black's game is very simple.  21.Bxa6  Qa7  22.Qd3  h5  23.b5  The human choice - White forces the matter. Now Black revisits a familiar motif - sacrifice even more material.  23...Bxc5  24.bxc6  Rb2  25.Bc4  White once again is up a whole rook but must walk a tightrope not to get mated right away.  25...d5  26.exd5  Nxd5  27.Bxd5  exd5  White's extra rook on the kingside seems to be irrelevant thus White has no choice but to repeat the position.  28.Rc2  Rb1+  29.Rc1  Rb2  Draw! }
