{ 20.Bxa6  h5  21.O-O  h4  will most likely transpose to the later line. }
20... Qxb8 21. Bxa6 h5
{ The game is still an incredible mess and White has to make a lot of uneasy moves. For Black is pretty simple - throw at White everything you've got. }
22. Bd3
{ White prepares to push b5, escaping a queen sacrifice from Black.   A@@EndBracket@@  22.O-O  Castling short can be a difficult choice as it's not clear if the white king is even feeling safe there.  22...h4  23.gxh4  Qf4  24.Nc3  Qxh4  25.Kh1  Nh5  Black is exploiting all the dark square weaknesses.  26.Qf2  Qg5  27.Rc2  Qe5  .  We have to stop at some point. The engine gives an advantage for White and it's understandable @@StartBracket@@exchange up@@EndBracket@@, however, the position itself is very difficult and anything can happen here. This entire variation for White already is very difficult to pick up - he keeps advantage by finding a series of only moves or intermezzos.   B@@EndBracket@@  22.b5?  Bxb5  23.Rb1  Bxa6  24.Rxb8  Rxb8  Black is taking over. }
22... h4 23. b5 Bxb5 { More sacrifices are incoming. } 24. Rb1 hxg3 25. e5
{ Very precise!   25.Rxb5  Accepting the extra material right away leads to a very unclear position.  25...g2!  26.Rg1  Qxh2  27.Qf2  Nd5!  Black is having too much fun here.  28.Rxg2   28.Qxg2??  One slip and White is done.  28...Bh4+  29.Kd2  Qf4+  White loses his queen.  28...Qe5  29.Qd2  f5  30.Kd1  Nf4  .  The engines confirm that the position is equal - all we understand is that the position is much easier to play for Black. }
25... Ng4
{ Probably one of the craziest maneuvers of the entire course! Black can't take the knight with the queen or the pawn. }
26. Rxb5
{ Again, the best in the pool of complications.   A@@EndBracket@@  26.fxg4??  This loses stunningly.  26...Qa8!!  Suddenly White can't keep together the position, despite being up a whole rook!  27.Be4  Bc6  28.Nc3  Bxc5  .  Black crashes through.   B@@EndBracket@@  26.Qxg4?  While White doesn't lose here on the spot, the variation is too pretty not to show it.  26...Qxe5+  27.Qe4  ,  the only move.  27...Qxe4+  28.Bxe4  Bc4  .  Black trades the queens and plays a position game, down a full rook.  29.Nc1  g2  30.Rg1  Bf1!  Black will reclaim something of the sacrificed material soon. }
26... Nxe5 { Black is down a rook but now offers a queen sacrifice as well. }
27. Rxb8 Nxf3+ 28. Kf1 Nxd4 29. Rxf8+
{ Finally, the position simplifies a little. } 29... Bxf8 30. hxg3 Bxc5 31. Kg2
f5
{ This position is quite difficult to evaluate - Black has four pawns for the rook, a far advanced pawn on a3, and opposite-colored bishops. The engines give here almost winning advantage for White but for a human being, this might be a little too much. White did have to walk a long road to get here. }
