[White "18) 5.c4, 7.a3 Classical Ideas"]
[Black " 5.c4 − 9.f3 Nc6 10.b4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7
{ Black deals with the e5 threat - the Maroczy Bind setup against the Sicilian Kan here is a huge crossroads. White can seek some off-beat continuations to catch the opponent off-guard or play the classical a3 to prevent Black from playing ...Bb4. Before the age of Stockfish and the likes, it was unanimously considered as 'the only way to fight for the advantage'.  Time passed and the practice proved that Black has many practical options, and the position itself is not so simple to give conclusions. Then came the modern Be2 and with the help of modern engines, it became clear that White can allow the ...Bb4 maneuver and that focusing on the development with the plans to grab space advantage or go for a direct attack is much more important than the integrity of the pawn structure. However, let's do step by step. }
7. a3
{ This 'old continuation' remains popular even today. White's game feels to be more positional and harmonious while  7.Be2  is very aggressive, ignoring some positional concepts but fast charging forward. }
7... b6
{ First, Black fianchettoes the bishop on b7 and keeps eyes open, what White will choose next. }
8. Be3 Bb7 9. f3
{ So, White has set up the Maroczy Bind - the position which has been tested for decades. Where to go? There are two plans. The first one is to commit to ...d6, aiming for the traditional Hedgehog, however, today it's considered to be very dangerous because White has several perspective plans. Among them: either push the a-pawn as far as a5 or push forward the kingside pawns @@StartBracket@@and it does not matter, where the white king stands@@EndBracket@@.  The second plan for Black at the end of the 90's resurrected one of the most creative players in the chess circuit Alexander Morozevich - Black plays ...Nc6 with mainly two ideas. First, trade the knights on d4 and continue with ...Bd6 and ...h5, enjoying good counterplay because of the dark squares. The second, reposition the knight on g6 via the e5-square, push the h-pawn as far as h4 and continue with either ...Bd6 or ...d5. The only minus is the lack of flexibility and the weak pawn on b6. }
9... Nc6
{ Before we move on to the classical system of 7.a3 and the Maroczy Bind, let's refresh the main principles of studying theory: 1.@@EndBracket@@ Since there are so many variations that often switch from one line to another, there's a considerable risk that as the result the size of your brains will increase 5 times and you won't want to have a look into the mirror! That's why we prefer to focus on plans, typical structures, and standard tactical shots, making your life considerably easier @@StartBracket@@and the brain - normal size@@EndBracket@@. 2.@@EndBracket@@ In order to remember the plans, you need to know answers to three questions - which pieces are important, which are the key squares, and what you can't allow to happen. }
10. b4
{ One of the common motifs for Black is to trade knights on d4 and play ...Bc5 next, fighting for the control of the dark squares. With this move, White makes sure that this is not going to happen. Also, White has ideas including Na4 and pushing c5. }
10... Be7
{ 10...Bd6??  is standard mistake - don't ever fall into it.  11.Ndb5  axb5  12.Nxb5  Black is already lost. }
11. Rc1
{ Once the white rook lands on c1, you're always expecting Nd5. It won't always be dangerous, but it can never be missed or underestimated. }
11... Ne5
{ Black doesn't dodge White's threats but instead sticks to the plan. } 12. Be2
O-O
{ Black must remember exactly this setup. White can change the move order @@StartBracket@@except bothering the b6-pawn@@EndBracket@@ but Black's maneuvers always are the same. }
13. O-O Ng6
{ Remove the knight from the center before White can play f4! Now White's center is a little static thus Black can focus on his plans. Black wants to play ...Bd6 and fight for the dark squares thus White's next move will be directed against it.   13...Rab8?  after this standard move we transpose to a known game where Black got a lost position after the opening.  14.f4!  Ng6  The pawn on c4 obviously can't be taken - that's why the White rook stands on c1.  15.Bd3  White got a decisive space advantage in Kasparov, G. - Vallejo Pons, F. Linares 19th 2002. }
14. Qe1
{ The white queen on e1 gives access to the defensive g3 move, so that after ...Bd6 Black doesn't have the option to force a perpetual check with the sacrifice on g3. }
14... Bd6 15. g3
{ With the black bishop controlling the h2-b8 diagonal, White never, ever wants to play h3 - this would completely hand over the control of the dark squares to Black.   15.h3??  Nh5  White is already losing something. }
15... h5
{ Notice that White's Nb5 threat has lost the power - the white queen no longer stands on d1. Don't get carried away - never forget this threat! }
16. Na4 h4 { Black's initiative looks menacing. } 17. c5 bxc5 18. Nxc5
{ Now Black crashes through. } 18... hxg3 19. Ncxe6 gxh2+ 20. Kh1 fxe6
{ A positional queen sacrifice! } 21. Rxc7 Bxc7
{ Even though the queen has departed the board, Black's attack is still going very strong. }
