11... Ne5
{ Black doesn't dodge White's threats but instead sticks to the plan. } 12. Be2
O-O
{ Black must remember exactly this setup. White can change the move order @@StartBracket@@except bothering the b6-pawn@@EndBracket@@ but Black's maneuvers always are the same. }
13. O-O Ng6
{ Remove the knight from the center before White can play f4! Now White's center is a little static thus Black can focus on his plans. Black wants to play ...Bd6 and fight for the dark squares thus White's next move will be directed against it.   13...Rab8?  after this standard move we transpose to a known game where Black got a lost position after the opening.  14.f4!  Ng6  The pawn on c4 obviously can't be taken - that's why the White rook stands on c1.  15.Bd3  White got a decisive space advantage in Kasparov, G. - Vallejo Pons, F. Linares 19th 2002. }
14. Kh1
{ Now Black's ...Bd6 is impossible - there will be an Nb5 trick and the pawn on h2 can't be taken with a check. Also, White wants to play Na4 and attack the b6-pawn, perhaps linked together with the c5 push. }
14... d6
{ It's time to switch to the classical Hedgehog - this is one of the rare moments in the entire course that we have to do this. }
15. Qe1 { White is going after the b6-pawn. } 15... Rab8 16. Qf2 Rfc8
{ Black is looking for ways to attack the c4-pawn but doesn't have to hurry. }
17. Rfd1 Ba8 18. Nb3 h6
{ There's no need to rush anywhere - wait for White to define his structure first. Black is thinking about ...Ne5 and ...g5 ideas in the distant future but a lot can happen on the road.   The more impatient players can push  18...h5  and as far as it goes, but don't forget that you will need to pay some attention to the b6-pawn and your early kingside campaign can turn against you. After all, the dark-squared bishop is packed away on e7 and won't be able to assist. }
19. Na4 { White goes after the b6-pawn as planned. } 19... Nd7
{ Black defends it - what should White do next? Typical for the classical Hedgehog, there's a lot of maneuvering and provocations. }
20. Bf1 Qd8 21. Nb2 Nge5
{ The perfect position of the black knights - the knight on d7 protects the b6-pawn and the queenside, while the e5-knight has its own ambitions. All the time, Black is trying to provoke White to push one of his kingside pawns to establish targets. An idea of pushing ...g5 appears under the horizon, starting active operations on the kingside. }
22. a4 { White has to do something, the question is: what and when? } 22... a5
23. b5 Bh4 { Black continues the provocations. } 24. Qd2 Nc5 25. Nxc5 dxc5
{ If Black achieves this, the position is equal. } *

