{ First, Black fianchettoes the bishop on b7 and keeps eyes open, what White will choose next. }
8. Be3 Bb7 9. f3
{ So, White has set up the Maroczy Bind - the position which has been tested for decades. Where to go? There are two plans. The first one is to commit to ...d6, aiming for the traditional Hedgehog, however, today it's considered to be very dangerous because White has several perspective plans. Among them: either push the a-pawn as far as a5 or push forward the kingside pawns @@StartBracket@@and it does not matter, where the white king stands@@EndBracket@@.  The second plan for Black at the end of the 90's resurrected one of the most creative players in the chess circuit Alexander Morozevich - Black plays ...Nc6 with mainly two ideas. First, trade the knights on d4 and continue with ...Bd6 and ...h5, enjoying good counterplay because of the dark squares. The second, reposition the knight on g6 via the e5-square, push the h-pawn as far as h4 and continue with either ...Bd6 or ...d5. The only minus is the lack of flexibility and the weak pawn on b6. }
9... Nc6
{ Before we move on to the classical system of 7.a3 and the Maroczy Bind, let's refresh the main principles of studying theory: 1.@@EndBracket@@ Since there are so many variations that often switch from one line to another, there's a considerable risk that as the result the size of your brains will increase 5 times and you won't want to have a look into the mirror! That's why we prefer to focus on plans, typical structures, and standard tactical shots, making your life considerably easier @@StartBracket@@and the brain - normal size@@EndBracket@@. 2.@@EndBracket@@ In order to remember the plans, you need to know answers to three questions - which pieces are important, which are the key squares, and what you can't allow to happen. }
10. Be2 Be7 11. Qd2 O-O 12. O-O
{ Another interesting setup from White - he doesn't play the 'automatic' Rac1 and instead keeps the c1 square available for the kingside rook. Then, depending on Black's reaction, White wants to push the pawns at the queenside with either b4-c5, or a4-a5. }
12... Bd6 { Black uses the opportunity to activate the dark-squared bishop. }
13. Kh1
{ This maneuver we've seen in another sideline before Black got the chance to play ...Bd6. Here things are different. Don't forget White's Ndb5 threat which now becomes real. }
13... Nxd4
{ Before taking the pawn on h2, Black makes sure that the dark-squared bishop will be able to escape the kingside and not get trapped. }
14. Bxd4 Bf4 { An important intermezzo move before taking the h2-pawn. } 15.
Bxb6
{ Nice trick but you don't have to take the bishop.   15.Be3  White could insist on trapping the bishop. The idea is there, but the difference is a whole pawn.  15...Bxh2  16.f4?  Bg3  The major difference here is that White didn't take the pawn on b6 for the same position. The black bishop can't be trapped.  17.Rf3?  Nh5  Not only does Black hold the bishop but is ready to start the decisive assault. }
15... Qb8 16. Be3 Bxh2 17. f4 Bg3
{ White can't get to the bishop on g3 as his dark-squared bishop on e3 is blocking the queen's way. }
18. Bf3 Qd8 19. Kg1 { That's quite a bold defense! } 19... Nh5 20. Bxh5 Qh4 21.
Rf3 { The only move. } 21... Qh2+ 22. Kf1 Qh1+ 23. Bg1 Bh2
{ Black inevitably wins back the sacrificed piece. } 24. Qd4 Bxg1 25. Qxg1
{ Taking the pawn on f7 with an intermezzo check opens the f-file for the black rook and great compensation. }
25... Qxh5 26. Rh3 Qa5 { The position has normalized and is about equal. } *

