19... Rad8 20. Rd4 Rfe8 21. Rfd1 Kf8
{ Black defends the pawn on d6 with a tactical trick, which could be useful to know. In addition, Black eliminates the back rank weakness.   21...Re6  this might be a little early.  22.e5  Ne8  . Unfortunately, you can't take on e5 due to the back rank weakness.  23.exd6  Rdxd6  24.Rxd6  Rxd6  25.Rxd6  Nxd6  . Although there have been mass trades, Black looks solid, White does have a chance to organize a passed pawn on the queenside.  26.Bf3  Bxf3  27.gxf3  White has an advantage in the endgame which could be dangerous. }
22. Rxd6 Nd5
{ Nice shot! Black wins an exchange for a pawn but White's passed pawns on the queenside could become dangerous. Black will have to be a little careful but also for White there are risks. }
23. exd5 Qxd6 24. Qxd6+ Rxd6
{ The position is dynamically balanced - White's pawns look scary, but if Black is active enough, they can't easily move forward. Check the following moves for a reference on how the game could continue.   25.Bf3  The immediate c-pawn push is no good - Black will happily sacrifice the exchange back on d5  25...Re3  26.Rc1  Rf6  27.Kf2  Re5  The pawns are moving!  28.Rd1  Rf4!?  29.Na4  Rxc4  30.d6  Probably the best attempt for White.  30...Rc2+  31.Kg3  Rg5+  32.Kf4  Rc4+!  The rook can't be taken.  33.Kxg5??   33.Ke3  Re5+  34.Kf2  Rc2+  Draw by a perpetual check - White can't play any further.  33...f6+  34.Kf5  Kf7  The drama ends with a lovely checkmate. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18) 5.c4, 7.a3 Classical Ideas"]
[Black " 5.c4 − 9.f3 Nc6 10.Rc1 #1 | Informational 10...Nxd4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7
{ Black deals with the e5 threat - the Maroczy Bind setup against the Sicilian Kan here is a huge crossroads. White can seek some off-beat continuations to catch the opponent off-guard or play the classical a3 to prevent Black from playing ...Bb4. Before the age of Stockfish and the likes, it was unanimously considered as 'the only way to fight for the advantage'.  Time passed and the practice proved that Black has many practical options, and the position itself is not so simple to give conclusions. Then came the modern Be2 and with the help of modern engines, it became clear that White can allow the ...Bb4 maneuver and that focusing on the development with the plans to grab space advantage or go for a direct attack is much more important than the integrity of the pawn structure. However, let's do step by step. }
7. a3
{ This 'old continuation' remains popular even today. White's game feels to be more positional and harmonious while  7.Be2  is very aggressive, ignoring some positional concepts but fast charging forward. }
7... b6
{ First, Black fianchettoes the bishop on b7 and keeps eyes open, what White will choose next. }
8. Be3 Bb7 9. f3
{ So, White has set up the Maroczy Bind - the position which has been tested for decades. Where to go? There are two plans. The first one is to commit to ...d6, aiming for the traditional Hedgehog, however, today it's considered to be very dangerous because White has several perspective plans. Among them: either push the a-pawn as far as a5 or push forward the kingside pawns @@StartBracket@@and it does not matter, where the white king stands@@EndBracket@@.  The second plan for Black at the end of the 90's resurrected one of the most creative players in the chess circuit Alexander Morozevich - Black plays ...Nc6 with mainly two ideas. First, trade the knights on d4 and continue with ...Bd6 and ...h5, enjoying good counterplay because of the dark squares. The second, reposition the knight on g6 via the e5-square, push the h-pawn as far as h4 and continue with either ...Bd6 or ...d5. The only minus is the lack of flexibility and the weak pawn on b6. }
9... Nc6
{ Before we move on to the classical system of 7.a3 and the Maroczy Bind, let's refresh the main principles of studying theory: 1.@@EndBracket@@ Since there are so many variations that often switch from one line to another, there's a considerable risk that as the result the size of your brains will increase 5 times and you won't want to have a look into the mirror! That's why we prefer to focus on plans, typical structures, and standard tactical shots, making your life considerably easier @@StartBracket@@and the brain - normal size@@EndBracket@@. 2.@@EndBracket@@ In order to remember the plans, you need to know answers to three questions - which pieces are important, which are the key squares, and what you can't allow to happen. }
10. Rc1
{ Think from White's point of view - the plan of a4-a5 now makes no sense but the classical development of Qd2, Be2, O-O, Rfd1 is not dangerous because in many lines Black has the dangerous idea of ...h5-h4 and ...Bd6, targeting the h2-pawn. Thus White might seriously want to consider punishing Black for the early ...Nc6. }
10... Nxd4
{ In the era of the yet weak chess engines, this was several times played by Morozevich. }
11. Qxd4
{ Quite logical and thus the strongest - White is targeting the b6-pawn.   11.Bxd4  If White is a little slow with his decisions, Black gets to execute his typical idea.  11...Bd6  12.g3  h5!  13.Qd2  White already needs to be quite careful. Going for the b6-pawn will backfire as Black won't protect it and will simply push forward the h-pawn.  13...h4  14.g4  Carlsen, M. @@StartBracket@@2881@@EndBracket@@ - Morozevich, A. @@StartBracket@@2731@@EndBracket@@ World Blitz championship 2014. Black's game here can be easily improved.  14...O-O!?  Black keeps many of his dynamic options alive. }
11... Bc5 12. Qd2 Bxe3
{ Black has to take, otherwise White would push b4 and avoid the queen trade. Retreating to d6 here does not make a lot of sense as Black has lost a tempo and the b6 pawn remains weak. }
13. Qxe3 Qc5
{ Black's idea is to trade queens, play ...d6-Ke7, and have a solid position while White has a passive light-squared bishop. }
14. Qxc5
{ If White knows the following few precise moves, he will get the advantage.   14.Qf2?!  This is a little slow - now Black gets a nice control over the dark squares.  14...d6?!  The immediate queen trade might have been better.  15.Be2?!  White could have voluntarily 'lost' another tempo with 15.Qd2 - the black pawn on d6 is more vulnerable than on d7.  15...a5  16.Nb5  Ke7!  17.Nd4  g6  18.O-O  e5  . Black is executing a textbook plan of grabbing all the dark squares. White is left with a passive bishop.   19.Nc2  Qxf2+  20.Kxf2  a4  . The position is already equal. In the game, White tried to be active but it backfired.  21.Rb1?!  Wrong idea - this only creates weaknesses.  21...Nd7  22.b4?!  axb3  23.Rxb3  Ra5  Black was already better in Ganguly, S. @@StartBracket@@2583@@EndBracket@@ - Kamsky, G. @@StartBracket@@2700@@EndBracket@@ World op 33rd 2005. }
14... bxc5 15. e5 { Otherwise Black plays ...d6. } 15... Nh5 16. Na4 Rc8 17. b4
cxb4 18. axb4
{ White has a better pawn structure while Black's pawn on a6 is chronically weak. }
18... f6 19. exf6 Nxf6 20. Bd3
{ In front of Black lies a long defense - White is slightly pushing, with chances to create an outside passed pawn. On the other hand - maybe it's not so terrible? The line is rather simple and White needs to know all of this and the final result is just a better endgame. }
*

