10. Rc1
{ Think from White's point of view - the plan of a4-a5 now makes no sense but the classical development of Qd2, Be2, O-O, Rfd1 is not dangerous because in many lines Black has the dangerous idea of ...h5-h4 and ...Bd6, targeting the h2-pawn. Thus White might seriously want to consider punishing Black for the early ...Nc6. }
10... Ne5
{ We would like to switch to one of our favorite setups but it might be a little too early.   10...Bc5?!  this is not great, White forces quickly some favorable trades.  11.b4  Bxd4  12.Bxd4  Nxd4  13.Qxd4  Black has spent several tempi to trade minor pieces and now he doesn't have enough time to cover the d6 and b6 squares. }
11. Na4 Rb8 12. b4 Be7 13. Be2 O-O 14. c5
{ White is very fast with the breakthrough. } 14... b5 15. Nb6 d5 16. cxd6
{ No choice for White but ultimately he's the one with better control of the queenside squares. }
16... Qxd6 17. Nb3 Qxd1+ 18. Rxd1 Bd8 19. Bd4
{ Quite precise, otherwise Black is thinking about ...Bxe4 and the white knight on b6 hangs. }
19... Nc6 20. Bc5 Re8 21. Na5 { White has a solid advantage. } *

