{ This move is typical but from a practical point of view, it could cause White a lot of headaches. }
14... Ng6
{ Once again Black wants to play ...Bd6 and exploit the fact that the d-pawn still stands on d7. }
15. Kh1 { A necessary prophylactic move. } 15... Bd6 16. g3
{ This should be treated as a success - Black has provoked White to make a move that he normally doesn't want to include. More targets! Now Black has a fine choice.   16.Bg1  Bf4  Unfortunately for White, he's about to lose something. }
16... Be5
{ Perhaps this is more dynamic - Black returns to the idea of pushing forward the h-pawn. The bishop on e5 stands well so that you're not missing any c5 or Nb5 ideas from White. }
17. b4 h5 18. Nb3 Bc6 19. b5 Ba8
{ Black is attacking - nobody cares about the extra pawn on a6. } *

