{ Since White has no direct threats yet, Black can afford to include this move and keep the b-pawn alive. We hope you didn't get the wrong idea that you are sacrificing the b-pawn, whenever the chance! }
14. b4
{ From one point of view, White is making a standard pawn push, from another - this forces Black to react against the incoming c5 threat, thus taking away the precious d6-square for the dark-squared bishop. }
14... d6
{ We treat the switching to the classical Hedgehog as a concession, plus, White has a typical tactical shot at his disposal. }
15. Nxb6 Bxe4
{ The tactical fight is about to start!   15...Qxb6  this is not the same as before - make sure you understand the difference.  16.Nxe6  Qc6  17.Nxf8  Bxf8  18.O-O  Unlike a very similar variation before, here White has not committed any weaknesses at the kingside. Rook and two pawns are much stronger than two knights and White is ready to push forward the queenside pawns. In the meantime, Black hasn't created anything yet on the kingside. }
16. c5
{ Stronger than the cowardly  16.Na4  .   16.fxe4  is easily met with  16...Rxb6  17.Nf3  Rbb8  18.Nxe5  dxe5  19.c5  Nxe4  Black can manage. }
16... dxc5
{ Unfortunately, the bishop can't retreat to b7 as White will have a powerful c6 thrust and Black loses something due to the terrible pins. }
17. Na4 Qd8 18. Nxc5 Ba8 19. O-O
{ White is much better - Black's weak pawn on a6 looks terrible while the counterplay on the kingside has not yet started. }
