15. b5
{ Logical - White's priority is to open the queenside and keep pressing on the b6-pawn. }
15... Bb7
{ Quite precise.   15...Ba8?!  Black can't completely ignore White's ideas at the queenside.  16.bxa6  Qa7  17.c5!  White is very fast.  17...bxc5  18.Nb5  Qxa6  19.Nxc5  Qc6  The only moves for Black.  20.Na7  Qd6  21.Qxd6  Bxd6  22.a4  White has achieved a lot more than Black - passed pawn at the queenside and no attack threats for Black on the kingside since queens have been traded. }
16. O-O { If White castles, Black continues with his traditional plan. } 16...
Ng6 17. Kh1 { White gives up the a3-pawn. } 17... Bxa3 18. Ra1 Bc5
{ Black remains careful and gives up the extra pawn. The standard  18...Bd6?!  doesn't work.  19.bxa6  Bxa6  20.Nc3  ,  remember the Ndb5 trick? It's back.  20...Bxh2  21.f4!  White will win a piece by force.  21...Bxc4  22.Kxh2  Bxe2  23.Ndxe2  b5  . Black has three pawns for the minor piece but with so many pieces on the board, White's chances are higher. }
19. Nxc5 { Engines pick up this move but the idea might be a little too deep. }
19... bxc5 20. Nb3 d6
{ If White will take the pawn on a6 since the knight on b3 is under attack. }
21. Rfd1 Rfd8
{ White has a typical compensation for the pawn but not more. A pawn is a pawn, plus Black can still use the dark squares for his knights. }
