{ Black stops the white pawn on c4 and creates more outposts for his knights. }
18. Nc3 Qa7 19. O-O Nfd7
{ Don't rush with taking the pawn.   19...Qxa6  Taking the pawn is a little early.  20.c5!  Qxa3  21.cxb6!  White temporarily sacrifices a knight.  21...Qxb3  22.Rb1  Nc4  No choice for Black, otherwise the White rooks will hunt down the queen.  23.Rxb3  Nxd2  24.Bxd2  We had a similar position before but there were more pieces on the board, plus queens. Here White's b-pawn looks strong. }
20. Nd4 Nc5
{ Black first makes sure that White won't push c5 and only then collects the a-pawn. White has enough weaknesses at the queenside to give Black enough counterplay, leading to a double-edged game. Here's a potential follow-up from here. }
21. Ndb5
{ If White won't gather the courage to push forward the f-pawn, attacking the d-pawn alone is not enough. }
21... Qxa6 22. Rb1 Rfd8 23. Rfd1 Bc6 24. a4 Qb7
{ The white f-pawn is no longer moving and Black can resume his idea to fight for the dark squares. }
