{ From one point of view, White is making a standard pawn push, from another - this forces Black to react against the incoming c5 threat, thus taking away the precious d6-square for the dark-squared bishop. }
14... Rfc8 { This might be a very deep alternative. } 15. c5
{ It makes sense for White to go for the push as it might not be available later. }
15... b5
{ Here the White knight has two good jumps - either on b6 or back to c3. } 16.
Nb6
{ This jump comes with a tempo but this comes with some risk that the knight on d6 might get lost.   16.Nc3  If White retreats back, then it's time to strike in the center.  16...d5  Black would like to take on e4, retreat with the knight to g6 and pressure the e4-pawn while still eyeing for the white king. Thus it seems very logical to capture en passant. If White doesn't take it, it's a double-edged game where engines slightly prefer White.  17.cxd6  Bxd6!  Now you understand the importance of ...Rfc8 - Black can recapture with the bishop.  18.Nb3  Nc6  Black has nothing to worry about. }
16... Rd8
{ Black has lost a tempo, but the white knight on b6 instead of a potential strength can become a weakness. White has to react somehow to Black's ...d5 push threat. }
17. Qc3 { A nice move but Black equalizes due to a very nice trick. } 17... d5
18. cxd6 Qxc3+ 19. Rxc3 Rxd6 20. Bf4
{ A strong idea but Black's response is even better. } 20... Nxe4 21. fxe4 f6
{ Black wins back the knight on b6 with an equal game. Here's how the game could continue:  22.Nf3  Rxb6  23.Nxe5  fxe5  24.Bxe5  Bh4+  ,  a nice intermezzo check to provoke White to include g3.  25.g3  Bf6  26.Bxf6  gxf6  27.Bf3  Rc8  . The position is just equal. }
