{ From one point of view, White is making a standard pawn push, from another - this forces Black to react against the incoming c5 threat, thus taking away the precious d6-square for the dark-squared bishop. }
14... Rfc8 { This might be a very deep alternative. } 15. c5
{ It makes sense for White to go for the push as it might not be available later. }
15... b5
{ Here the White knight has two good jumps - either on b6 or back to c3. } 16.
Nb6
{ This jump comes with a tempo but this comes with some risk that the knight on d6 might get lost.   16.Nc3  If White retreats back, then it's time to strike in the center.  16...d5  Black would like to take on e4, retreat with the knight to g6 and pressure the e4-pawn while still eyeing for the white king. Thus it seems very logical to capture en passant. If White doesn't take it, it's a double-edged game where engines slightly prefer White.  17.cxd6  Bxd6!  Now you understand the importance of ...Rfc8 - Black can recapture with the bishop.  18.Nb3  Nc6  Black has nothing to worry about. }
16... Rd8
{ Black has lost a tempo, but the white knight on b6 instead of a potential strength can become a weakness. White has to react somehow to Black's ...d5 push threat. }
17. Nb3
{ White extra protects the knight on b6 and wants to move his knight to a5. }
17... Nc6
{ Black is about to push ...d6. Check the potential follow-ups from here. } 18.
Qc3
{ White wants to stop Black from pushing the d-pawn.   18.O-O  Another logical way to continue.  18...d6  19.Qc3!  d5!?  The queen on c3 is under a tempo!  20.e5  A strong idea but now the White queen on c3 is slightly misplaced.  20...Nxe5  21.Bf4  d4  Remember 'wasting' the tempo? Here's the difference.  22.Nxd4  Nh5!  Black gets rid of the annoying pin. There will be a forced line that will end with complete equality. }
18... d5 19. cxd6 Bxd6 20. Na5
{ The pin looks strong but the white king in the center makes it possible to play a gambit. }
20... Be5 21. Qc2 Bf4 22. Bxf4 Qxf4 { Now starts a forced series of moves. }
23. Nxc6 Bxc6 24. Qxc6 Rxb6 { The white rook on c1 now is undefended. } 25.
Qxb6 Qxc1+ 26. Kf2 Nxe4+ { Because of this check, Black is alright. } 27. fxe4
Qf4+ 28. Kg1 Rc8 { The black rook is ready to join the attack. } 29. Qd4 Rc1+
30. Bd1 h6
{ White can't make any progress or will lose a few pawns in the process. } 31.
Qd8+ Kh7 32. Qd3 Qe5 { Nothing is over yet! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19) 5.c4, 7.Be2"]
[Black " 5.c4 − 7.Qf3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7
{ Black deals with the e5 threat - the Maroczy Bind setup against the Sicilian Kan here is a huge crossroads. White can seek some off-beat continuations to catch the opponent off-guard or play the classical a3 to prevent Black from playing ...Bb4. Before the age of Stockfish and the likes, it was unanimously considered as 'the only way to fight for the advantage'.  Time passed and the practice proved that Black has many practical options, and the position itself is not so simple to give conclusions. Then came the modern Be2 and with the help of modern engines, it became clear that White can allow the ...Bb4 maneuver and that focusing on the development with the plans to grab space advantage or go for a direct attack is much more important than the integrity of the pawn structure. However, let's do step by step. }
7. Qf3
{ This early queen maneuver has gained popularity in other Sicilian variations like Taimanov but here it's harmless. }
7... Bd6 8. Be2 O-O 9. Bg5 Be5
{ Black is doing just fine, controlling the central dark squares. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19) 5.c4, 7.Be2"]
[Black " 5.c4 − 7.Qd3 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7
{ Black deals with the e5 threat - the Maroczy Bind setup against the Sicilian Kan here is a huge crossroads. White can seek some off-beat continuations to catch the opponent off-guard or play the classical a3 to prevent Black from playing ...Bb4. Before the age of Stockfish and the likes, it was unanimously considered as 'the only way to fight for the advantage'.  Time passed and the practice proved that Black has many practical options, and the position itself is not so simple to give conclusions. Then came the modern Be2 and with the help of modern engines, it became clear that White can allow the ...Bb4 maneuver and that focusing on the development with the plans to grab space advantage or go for a direct attack is much more important than the integrity of the pawn structure. However, let's do step by step. }
7. Qd3
{ However, this is an interesting attempt to lead Black to variations that favor White. }
7... Nc6
{ It's necessary to fight for the central squares as quickly as possible.   7...b6?!  One of the World's strongest Grandmasters, Vladislav Artemiev played this a couple of times against Ian Nepomniatchtchi and Vladimir Fedoseev, and lost both games.  8.Qg3!  This early queen lift Black should be aware of - trading queens and opening the h-file favors White.  8...d6  9.Be3  Bb7  10.f3  Nbd7  11.Be2  The White queen on g3 performs many functions. In addition, White has saved time for the a3 tempo and Black is experiencing a long-term discomfort with the dark squares. }
8. Nxc6
{ This trade is interesting - White voluntarily creates a weakness on d4 to counter it with the weak b6 -square. }
8... dxc6 9. Be2 e5
{ The simplest choice - Black fights for the control of the dark squares. } 10.
O-O { If White allows Black to occupy the c5-square, go for it. } 10... Bc5 11.
Qg3 O-O 12. Bh6 Ne8
{ White's initial threats are easily parried, leaving the question - what exactly does White have for the weak d4-square? }
*

