7. Qd3
{ However, this is an interesting attempt to lead Black to variations that favor White. }
7... Nc6
{ It's necessary to fight for the central squares as quickly as possible.   7...b6?!  One of the World's strongest Grandmasters, Vladislav Artemiev played this a couple of times against Ian Nepomniatchtchi and Vladimir Fedoseev, and lost both games.  8.Qg3!  This early queen lift Black should be aware of - trading queens and opening the h-file favors White.  8...d6  9.Be3  Bb7  10.f3  Nbd7  11.Be2  The White queen on g3 performs many functions. In addition, White has saved time for the a3 tempo and Black is experiencing a long-term discomfort with the dark squares. }
8. Be2 { White is continuing to play tricky. } 8... Bd6
{ In the spirit of the entire course - Black is fighting for the dark squares.  8...Bb4  is too early as White once again could retreat with the knight on c2 and there's no trade on c3 as the g7-pawn is not protected. }
