1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7
{ Black deals with the e5 threat - the Maroczy Bind setup against the Sicilian Kan here is a huge crossroads. White can seek some off-beat continuations to catch the opponent off-guard or play the classical a3 to prevent Black from playing ...Bb4. Before the age of Stockfish and the likes, it was unanimously considered as 'the only way to fight for the advantage'.  Time passed and the practice proved that Black has many practical options, and the position itself is not so simple to give conclusions. Then came the modern Be2 and with the help of modern engines, it became clear that White can allow the ...Bb4 maneuver and that focusing on the development with the plans to grab space advantage or go for a direct attack is much more important than the integrity of the pawn structure. However, let's do step by step. }
7. Be2
{ White is aiming for fast development, underlining that the ...Bb4 threat does not concern him. If Black doesn't play ...Bb4, then White has simply won a tempo by not committing to a3. In addition, White has two chances to fool his opponent, but both of these have their weak sides as well. }
7... Bb4
{ Black should bring out the bishop only after the inclusion of moves ...Qc7/Be2. The ...Bb4 move itself is just developing a piece and nothing else while ...Qc7 starts creating the battery Qc7-Bd6, attacks the pawn on c4, and also dodges a potential pin with Bg5. We will examine positions if White goes for fast development, often not minding to sacrifice a pawn. Anything related to the very popular Nc2 retreat in all possible scenarios we will examine in the final chapter of the course. }
8. O-O
{ White offers the pawn on e4 'for free', but it's too dangerous to take it, at least right away. }
8... O-O { However, the pawn on e4 could be under attack a move or two later. }
9. Bg5
{ Quite an important and independent variation that will require some accuracy of Black. }
9... Bxc3
{ This forces matters.   9...Be7?!  Check, how the game quickly can head the wrong way, if you are not careful.  10.Be3!?  b6  11.f4  d6  12.Rc1  White has forced Black to early enter the classical Hedgehog and on top of it already grabbed a considerable space advantage. This is the type of position that we're always trying to avoid. }
10. Bxf6 Bb4
{ Black should resume the fight for the d4-square.   10...Bxb2?!  As practice has proven, taking the pawn is dangerous.  11.Qd2!  gxf6  12.Qxb2  d6  13.Qd2  Black holds on to the extra pawn, but not for long.  The pawn on d6 is fatally weak and the king is not very safe.  After  13...Nd7  14.Rad1  Kh8  15.Nb3  White had a solid advantage in Cornette, M. @@StartBracket@@2586@@EndBracket@@ - Shchekachev, A. @@StartBracket@@2555@@EndBracket@@ FRA-ch 90th 2015. }
11. Bh4
{ White has an idea to position the dark-squared bishop on g3 and fight for the d6-square, but at the same time he has given up on the d4-square. }
11... Nc6 12. Bg3
{ This provokes Black to play ...e5, but that was your plan all along. } 12...
e5 { Black continues with his plan to control the d4-square. } 13. Nf5 Bc5 14.
a3 a5 { So far these are easy moves. } 15. Qd2 h6
{ There's no need to allow the perpetual check with the incoming knight sacrifice on g7 and Qg5 next. }
16. Rfd1 Ra6
{ White is already risking getting worse, since his bishops are not very active. Of course, it's a good idea not to blunder a piece on d4 due to a pin on the h2-b8 diagonal. }
