{ It makes sense to position the bishop on the most active square first and properly meet one of the most typical Black's ideas. Kollars, D. @@StartBracket@@2534@@EndBracket@@ - Gordievsky, D. @@StartBracket@@2630@@EndBracket@@ Karlsruhe Grenke op 2018. }
12... d6
{ Black does not take on d4 just yet and prepares to fight for the d4-square. Now White won't have access to the useful Rd1 move since the queen still stands there. }
13. Nxc6 { Probably White is interested to simplify the position a bit. } 13...
Qxc6 14. Qd3 e5 { Black builds the same setup. } 15. Rfd1 Be6 16. Rac1 Bc5
{ If White will ever take on c5, Black will recapture with the d-pawn. Black himself does not want to take on e3 unless forced with b4 which creates counterplay on the c4-pawn. The b4 push itself not always will happen as Black can slow it down with ...a5. If White eventually will trade both bishops and leave Black with weakness on d6, it's not enough as such heavy-piece endgame tend to be drawn. }
