7... Bb4
{ Black should bring out the bishop only after the inclusion of moves ...Qc7/Be2. The ...Bb4 move itself is just developing a piece and nothing else while ...Qc7 starts creating the battery Qc7-Bd6, attacks the pawn on c4, and also dodges a potential pin with Bg5. We will examine positions if White goes for fast development, often not minding to sacrifice a pawn. Anything related to the very popular Nc2 retreat in all possible scenarios we will examine in the final chapter of the course. }
8. Qd3
{ In most cases, White can't ignore what's happening with the e4-pawn and has to respond in some way. The white queen feels awkward on d3 but, it covers many important squares and can be rerouted to g3. }
8... O-O 9. O-O
{ 9.Bg5?!  While this maneuver is one of the main ideas, including  9.O-O  and  9...Nc6  , here it's too early. @@StartFEN@@rnb2rk1/1pqp1ppp/p3pn2/6B1/1bPNP3/2NQ4/PP2BPPP/R3K2R b KQ - 8 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Qe5  Because White has not castled short, the pawn on e4 now is under attack.  10.Bxf6  If White has to commit to this trade, that's a clear concession.  10...Qxf6  11.O-O  Nc6  12.Rad1  The position is equal but White has excellent chances to get a worse position as Black's dark-squared bishop eventually will become even stronger. }
9... d6
{ This continuation is quite popular and perhaps Black is looking for a better version of ...Bxc3 and the blockade via the dark squares but because of the stranded bishop on b4 Black is not in time to set up a comfortable Hedgehog. To give it up for no good reason is not great. }
10. Bd2
{ White defends against Black's ...Bxc3 threat so that he can recapture with the bishop. Now Black has two choices, how to continue the development. }
10... Nbd7
{ Seemingly the least of the evil.   10...Nc6  Black has too early committed to ...d6.  11.Nxc6!  Qxc6  Capturing with the pawn allows White to push a3-b4 and target the d6-pawn.  12.Rfd1  White has a large advantage with multiple threats. He's threatening with Rac1 and a3-b4 next, going after the d6 pawn. After Black's early ...Bc5 there will be the very annoying Bg5 and the Black knight has hardly anywhere to go. Then there's the Nd5 jump with various tricks. Mind you, Black still has not finished his development.  12...Bxc3  13.Bxc3  Nxe4  Black temporarily wins a pawn but not for long.  14.Bf3  d5  15.cxd5  exd5  16.Bb4!  White keeps the two bishop advantage alive.  16...Re8  17.Qxd5  Qxd5  18.Rxd5  Black is in the world of hurt - those White bishops are dominating the board. }
11. Nb3
{ White makes sure that the black bishop is not going anywhere and wants to trade it off for the knight. }
11... Ne5
{ 11...b6  another game continued, Black trying to build up some sort of Hedgehog.  12.a3  Bxc3  Seems to be necessary. If the bishop would retreat to c5, White could select the best possible moment to take it. Think about moves like Rad1 and Bf4 first and only then trade the bishop on c5 as it's not going anywhere.  13.Bxc3  Bb7  14.f3  Ne5  15.Qd4  Rac8  16.Rac1  White had the perfect Maroczy Bind setup in Cornette, M. @@StartBracket@@2558@@EndBracket@@ -Hapala, E. @@StartBracket@@2154@@EndBracket@@ Sitges Sunway 7th 2020. Black is missing the dark-squared bishop. }
12. Qd4 Nc6 13. Qe3
{ Unfortunately, White doesn't have to agree to repeat the position. } 13...
Bd7 14. Rac1
{ White can afford to choose the right moment for a3 and force White to take on c3. }
14... Rac8 15. a3 Na5
{ Black committed another inaccuracy in Naiditsch, A. @@StartBracket@@2712@@EndBracket@@ - Ivanchuk, V. @@StartBracket@@2729@@EndBracket@@ Danzhou 8th 2017. It was better to take on c3, push ...e5, and suffer for a long time anyway. }
16. Nxa5 Bxa5 17. b4 Bb6 18. Qd3
{ It's already very difficult for Black to parry all threats - White's advantage is close to decisive. You should be able to see the difference that compared to similar variations, Black did not manage to keep his dark-squared bishop on c5 and push ...e5 with ...Be6. }
