{ The strongest move - you'll see that the alternatives don't even come close. Black is once again fighting for the d4-square, but might also consider the ...Ne5 jump if the circumstances are right. White has quite a few choices here. }
10. Nxc6
{ This motif we already recognize - White takes away some flexibility from Black with the knight maneuvers. You might remember - the weakness on b6 is not enough for White to claim an advantage. }
10... dxc6
{ If you can establish a weakness on d4, take with the d-pawn. Capturing with the b-pawn does not make any sense here as with the white pawn on c4 Black is not even close to pushing...d5 and could experience some problems with the d-pawn later. }
11. f4
{ Quite a standard plan from White but it's harmless. Just don't allow White to push e5. }
11... Rd8 12. Qf3 e5 { Black is just in time to play it. } 13. f5 b5 14. Bg5
{ Shubin, K. @@StartBracket@@2338@@EndBracket@@ - Kovalev, A. @@StartBracket@@2517@@EndBracket@@ Panevezys 2017. Black's game can be improved with simple moves. }
14... Qe7 15. Kh1
{ White is thinking about g4-g5 so make sure you are establishing your counterplay on the queenside or center. }
15... h6 16. Bh4 Rd2 { Black is doing great. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19) 5.c4, 7.Be2"]
[Black " 5.c4 − 7.Be2 Bb4 8.Qd3 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7
{ Black deals with the e5 threat - the Maroczy Bind setup against the Sicilian Kan here is a huge crossroads. White can seek some off-beat continuations to catch the opponent off-guard or play the classical a3 to prevent Black from playing ...Bb4. Before the age of Stockfish and the likes, it was unanimously considered as 'the only way to fight for the advantage'.  Time passed and the practice proved that Black has many practical options, and the position itself is not so simple to give conclusions. Then came the modern Be2 and with the help of modern engines, it became clear that White can allow the ...Bb4 maneuver and that focusing on the development with the plans to grab space advantage or go for a direct attack is much more important than the integrity of the pawn structure. However, let's do step by step. }
7. Be2
{ White is aiming for fast development, underlining that the ...Bb4 threat does not concern him. If Black doesn't play ...Bb4, then White has simply won a tempo by not committing to a3. In addition, White has two chances to fool his opponent, but both of these have their weak sides as well. }
7... Bb4
{ Black should bring out the bishop only after the inclusion of moves ...Qc7/Be2. The ...Bb4 move itself is just developing a piece and nothing else while ...Qc7 starts creating the battery Qc7-Bd6, attacks the pawn on c4, and also dodges a potential pin with Bg5. We will examine positions if White goes for fast development, often not minding to sacrifice a pawn. Anything related to the very popular Nc2 retreat in all possible scenarios we will examine in the final chapter of the course. }
8. Qd3
{ In most cases, White can't ignore what's happening with the e4-pawn and has to respond in some way. The white queen feels awkward on d3 but, it covers many important squares and can be rerouted to g3. }
8... O-O 9. O-O
{ 9.Bg5?!  While this maneuver is one of the main ideas, including  9.O-O  and  9...Nc6  , here it's too early. @@StartFEN@@rnb2rk1/1pqp1ppp/p3pn2/6B1/1bPNP3/2NQ4/PP2BPPP/R3K2R b KQ - 8 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Qe5  Because White has not castled short, the pawn on e4 now is under attack.  10.Bxf6  If White has to commit to this trade, that's a clear concession.  10...Qxf6  11.O-O  Nc6  12.Rad1  The position is equal but White has excellent chances to get a worse position as Black's dark-squared bishop eventually will become even stronger. }
9... Nc6
{ The strongest move - you'll see that the alternatives don't even come close. Black is once again fighting for the d4-square, but might also consider the ...Ne5 jump if the circumstances are right. White has quite a few choices here. }
10. Nxc6
{ This motif we already recognize - White takes away some flexibility from Black with the knight maneuvers. You might remember - the weakness on b6 is not enough for White to claim an advantage. }
10... dxc6
{ If you can establish a weakness on d4, take with the d-pawn. Capturing with the b-pawn does not make any sense here as with the white pawn on c4 Black is not even close to pushing...d5 and could experience some problems with the d-pawn later. }
11. Bg5
{ White is threatening to expose the black king but the inclusion of Nxc6 feels early. }
11... Bxc3
{ Good enough to equalize and is simple enough. If you are looking for a greater fight, check the alternative. }
12. bxc3 Qe5 13. Bxf6 Qxf6
{ Black has some dark square weaknesses but White is unable to exploit them. }
14. f4 { Black's ...e5 is inevitable, no matter what White does. } 14... e5 15.
f5 Rd8 16. Qe3 c5
{ It's important to activate the light-squared bishop at all costs. } 17. Qxc5
Bd7 { White's extra pawn means nothing. } *

