{ This idea is borrowed from the Sicilian Taimanov - White wants to push c5 and imprison the black bishop on b4. }
10... b5
{ Black goes on the offensive very early - with the hanging white knight on a4 this thrust looks very logical. }
11. cxb5 axb5 12. Nxb5 Qb8
{ Because of Black's activity, White probably should give up the pawn right away. }
13. Nac3 Ba6 14. f3
{ White could try to hold onto the pawn but now Black can fight for the initiative. Just don't focus on winning back the pawn at all costs. }
14... Rd8 { Pushing ...d5 right away and then ...Rd8 also looks interesting. }
15. Kh1
{ If White would include  15.Bg5  then after  15...Be7  Black has an additional trick of ...Ng4. }
15... d5 16. exd5 exd5 { White already needs to be very careful. } 17. Bg5 Be7
18. Bxf6 Bxf6 19. Nxd5 Nd4
{ This is a forced line that inevitably leads to the following outcome. } 20.
Nxf6+ gxf6 21. Qxd4 { White doesn't have anything better. } 21... Rxd4 22. Nxd4
Bxe2 23. Nxe2 Qxb2 { Despite winning the queen, the position looks drawish. } *

