{ Black should bring out the bishop only after the inclusion of moves ...Qc7/Be2. The ...Bb4 move itself is just developing a piece and nothing else while ...Qc7 starts creating the battery Qc7-Bd6, attacks the pawn on c4, and also dodges a potential pin with Bg5. We will examine positions if White goes for fast development, often not minding to sacrifice a pawn. Anything related to the very popular Nc2 retreat in all possible scenarios we will examine in the final chapter of the course. }
8. Qd3
{ In most cases, White can't ignore what's happening with the e4-pawn and has to respond in some way. The white queen feels awkward on d3 but, it covers many important squares and can be rerouted to g3. }
8... O-O 9. O-O
{ 9.Bg5?!  While this maneuver is one of the main ideas, including  9.O-O  and  9...Nc6  , here it's too early. @@StartFEN@@rnb2rk1/1pqp1ppp/p3pn2/6B1/1bPNP3/2NQ4/PP2BPPP/R3K2R b KQ - 8 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Qe5  Because White has not castled short, the pawn on e4 now is under attack.  10.Bxf6  If White has to commit to this trade, that's a clear concession.  10...Qxf6  11.O-O  Nc6  12.Rad1  The position is equal but White has excellent chances to get a worse position as Black's dark-squared bishop eventually will become even stronger. }
9... Nc6
{ The strongest move - you'll see that the alternatives don't even come close. Black is once again fighting for the d4-square, but might also consider the ...Ne5 jump if the circumstances are right. White has quite a few choices here. }
10. Bg5
{ If we were to move the white pawn from c4 to c2, we would likely reach similar positions to the ones seen in Chapter 13, where White plays the very tricky 5.Be2. On the one hand, White has more space and he can try to squeeze Black. On the other, the weakness on d4 will be a key element for Black to get a good game in some variations, and the 'lost' tempo for c4 could also be important. }
10... Be7
{ Black retreats with the bishop to consolidate the position, and once again threatens the typical ...Ng4, forcing White to give up the dark-squared bishop. }
11. Nxc6 dxc6
{ With the white pawn on c4 it makes the most sense to take with the d-pawn and fight for the d4-square. An alternate plan is to push ...b5 - it depends, on what White will play here. }
12. f4 h6
{ An important accuracy.   12...e5?!  13.Qg3  Black has unexpected problems with the e5 pawn as taking on f4 would fuel White's attack with Bxf4 and e5 next. }
13. Bxf6
{ White has to take, otherwise after retreating to h4 Black's ...e5 this time works like a charm. The reason is - White won't be able to recapture on f4 with the bishop from g5. }
13... Bxf6 14. e5 Be7
{ Here the game is less forced. White needs to figure out if he's ready to play a gambit and allow Black to play ...Qb6+ and take the b2-pawn. Black inevitably will bring out his light-squared bishop in the game, either via b7 or c6-square. }
15. Qe3
{ It makes sense to give the white queen some functions of the missing dark-squared bishop. }
15... b6 16. Ne4 c5 17. Rad1 Bb7 { Black is solid enough. } *

