{ 9.Bg5?!  While this maneuver is one of the main ideas, including  9.O-O  and  9...Nc6  , here it's too early. @@StartFEN@@rnb2rk1/1pqp1ppp/p3pn2/6B1/1bPNP3/2NQ4/PP2BPPP/R3K2R b KQ - 8 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Qe5  Because White has not castled short, the pawn on e4 now is under attack.  10.Bxf6  If White has to commit to this trade, that's a clear concession.  10...Qxf6  11.O-O  Nc6  12.Rad1  The position is equal but White has excellent chances to get a worse position as Black's dark-squared bishop eventually will become even stronger. }
9... Nc6
{ The strongest move - you'll see that the alternatives don't even come close. Black is once again fighting for the d4-square, but might also consider the ...Ne5 jump if the circumstances are right. White has quite a few choices here. }
10. Bg5
{ If we were to move the white pawn from c4 to c2, we would likely reach similar positions to the ones seen in Chapter 13, where White plays the very tricky 5.Be2. On the one hand, White has more space and he can try to squeeze Black. On the other, the weakness on d4 will be a key element for Black to get a good game in some variations, and the 'lost' tempo for c4 could also be important. }
10... Be7
{ Black retreats with the bishop to consolidate the position, and once again threatens the typical ...Ng4, forcing White to give up the dark-squared bishop. }
11. Rac1
{ We find it to be incredible that the most played move in this position so far is such a simple positional mistake! This is what happens when people play standard moves 'on autopilot'. }
11... Ng4 12. Bxg4 Bxg5
{ In this structure Black's dark-squared bishop is a powerful piece. } 13. Nxc6
{ White already has to acknowledge that things are bad and fight his way to escape the trouble. }
13... dxc6 14. Rcd1 c5
{ Black fixes an outpost on d4 for the bishop. The rest is not so important.   15.g3  Bf6  White can't stop the Black bishop from reaching the d4-square.  16.f4  Rd8  17.Qc2  Bd4+  18.Kg2  Rb8  and White has a very long defense ahead - Black is better. }
