12... Bb4
{ This move underlines the retreat of the queen to d2 - you should remember a sideline if White plays 11.Be3 - the idea is the same. }
13. Nxc6
{ White recognizes Black's threat and acts before the pawn breakthrough happens. }
13... bxc6
{ Black has not given up the fight for the d4-square, or any other central squares. Compared with other moments when Black had the chance to capture with the b-pawn, here White has already committed himself to position the dark-squared bishop on e3.   13...dxc6  this used to be our standard capture with the white pawns on c4 and e4 but here the circumstances are somewhat different. White controls the g1-a7 diagonally already thus it will be very difficult to fight for the d4-square.  14.f3  b5  Black is looking for counterplay on the queenside and tries to eliminate the b6-square weakness.  15.Rfd1  e5  16.a3  White is a little faster on the queenside.  16...Be7  17.cxb5  axb5  18.Rac1  Qb7  . White is pushing, but with an accurate defense, Black should hold this. }
14. c5
{ Not the only move but it's a very interesting idea. Otherwise Black is pretty flexible with his ideas at the queenside, starting with capturing on c3 and pushing ...d5, or ...a5 with ...Ba6, in the spirit of the Scotch opening. }
14... d5
{ Black acknowledges the strong idea from White.   14...Nxe4?!  taking the pawn can be a risky strategic decision.  15.Qd4  Nxc3  16.bxc3  Ba5  17.f4  Black's position looks extremely unpleasant - White has free hands to start a kingside assault. }
15. cxd6 Bxd6 16. f4 Rd8
{ White has a weak pawn on c6 and should compensate it with a very active play. }
17. Qc2 e5 18. f5 a5 19. Na4 c5
{ It's important not to allow White to fix the position by landing a minor piece on c5 and then and start to squeeze. If necessary, sacrifice a pawn but always focus on having active pieces. }
20. Bc4
{ This is how an experienced player could continue - instead of hunting the weak pawn on c5, White tries to exploit the weak light squares. }
20... Bb7 21. Nc3 Bf8 22. Bf2 Rd4 { Long live Petrosian! } 23. b3 Bc6 24. Rfe1
Qb7
{ Black has a very rich game - sacrificing the exchange feels very natural as it hands over to Black the control of all the dark squares and the center. }
