{ 9.Bg5?!  While this maneuver is one of the main ideas, including  9.O-O  and  9...Nc6  , here it's too early. @@StartFEN@@rnb2rk1/1pqp1ppp/p3pn2/6B1/1bPNP3/2NQ4/PP2BPPP/R3K2R b KQ - 8 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Qe5  Because White has not castled short, the pawn on e4 now is under attack.  10.Bxf6  If White has to commit to this trade, that's a clear concession.  10...Qxf6  11.O-O  Nc6  12.Rad1  The position is equal but White has excellent chances to get a worse position as Black's dark-squared bishop eventually will become even stronger. }
9... Nc6
{ The strongest move - you'll see that the alternatives don't even come close. Black is once again fighting for the d4-square, but might also consider the ...Ne5 jump if the circumstances are right. White has quite a few choices here. }
10. Bg5
{ If we were to move the white pawn from c4 to c2, we would likely reach similar positions to the ones seen in Chapter 13, where White plays the very tricky 5.Be2. On the one hand, White has more space and he can try to squeeze Black. On the other, the weakness on d4 will be a key element for Black to get a good game in some variations, and the 'lost' tempo for c4 could also be important. }
10... Be7
{ Black retreats with the bishop to consolidate the position, and once again threatens the typical ...Ng4, forcing White to give up the dark-squared bishop. }
11. Bh4
{ The most logical move, which also serves as prophylaxis against Black's ...Ng4 maneuver. }
11... Ne5
{ Black dodges the potential knight trade in the foreseeable future and pressures the white pawn on c4. White still needs to understand, try to keep it or not. There are three queen retreats that make sense. }
12. Qg3
{ White protects the pawn on c4 by pinning the black knight, but this makes the bishop on h4 rather awkward. If Black is very slow and tries to do something else like fianchettoing the light-squared bishop on b7, there's a fancy-looking Nd5 shot. }
12... d6 { Simple and good - Black renews the threat to win the c4-pawn. } 13.
Bg5
{ White returns the bishop to a better square - it's not doing anything on h4. }
13... Kh8
{ A very useful move as Black removes the king from the g-file. You will need it very soon in all lines to counter White's attack. }
14. Rac1 Bd7 15. b3 Rac8
{ Black is looking for ways to create counterplay on the queenside with ...b5. }
16. f4 { The direct attack doesn't do White any good. } 16... Nc6 17. Nf3 Nh5
{ Watch out for the unexpected trick at Black's disposal! } 18. Qh3
{ Or  18.Qg4  - it's the same.  18.Qh4?  this is so easy to blunder!  18...Nxf4!  19.Qxf4  f6  20.Bh4  g5  Not only does Black regain the piece, he dominates the dark squares. }
18... Nxf4 19. Bxf4 e5 { The entire point of the combination. } 20. Qg3 exf4
21. Qxf4 Qa5
{ There's no more attack and White is left with some dark square weaknesses. }
