{ White once again stops Black's plan to play ...Qa5 and ...b5 and prepares himself to push f4. }
17... Qc5
{ Black accepts the loss of tempo and provokes the white bishop to e3.   17...b5?  The difference between White's 16.Kh1 and 16.h3 is that here this move does not work!  18.cxb5  Qb6  19.Qe3  the white pawn on h3 protects the queen from the Ng4 jump. Deep! }
18. Be3 Qa5
{ If White is ready to repeat the position, there might be nothing better than to accept it or risk further complications. }
19. f4
{ This thrust is tempting and sort of what White is aiming for but the consequences are far from clear.   19.a4  Bd8!  The game is only starting - the position is double-edged and there will be a lot of maneuvering. White's f4-f5 plan is not obvious while White constantly needs to guard the ...b5 push. Have fun! }
19... Ng6 20. f5 Ne5 21. Qe1 Bd8
{ White's attack is finished but Black controls many of the important dark squares. }
