[White "20) 5.c4,  Nc2 Setups"]
[Black "5.c4 − 8.Nc2 #1 | Informational 8...Be7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7
{ Black deals with the e5 threat - the Maroczy Bind setup against the Sicilian Kan here is a huge crossroads. White can seek some off-beat continuations to catch the opponent off-guard or play the classical a3 to prevent Black from playing ...Bb4. Before the age of Stockfish and the likes, it was unanimously considered as 'the only way to fight for the advantage'.  Time passed and the practice proved that Black has many practical options, and the position itself is not so simple to give conclusions. Then came the modern Be2 and with the help of modern engines, it became clear that White can allow the ...Bb4 maneuver and that focusing on the development with the plans to grab space advantage or go for a direct attack is much more important than the integrity of the pawn structure. However, let's do step by step. }
7. Be2 Bb4
{ In the final chapter of the course we are going to examine the Nc2 setups if White retreats with the d4-knight to challenge Black's dark-squared bishop. Sometimes the arising positions will seem similar to previous chapters, but not always. }
8. Nc2
{ A strong move that has recently gained popularity, especially among young players who are working with modern engines. White immediately tries to clarify the situation with the pinned knight. }
8... Be7
{ It seems normal but now Black loses a lot of dynamics and White can quickly claim a lot of space advantage  @@StartBracket@@which is something that we recommend to avoid@@EndBracket@@. }
9. Be3
{ Not only is White preparing an aggressive pawn push at the kingside with the knight on c2, but White is also immediately applying pressure on the b6-square. Black does not have that many options. }
9... O-O
{ Black castles short and pins hope on an early ...b5 counterstrike.   9...d6  Black too early switches to the classical Hedgehog and allows White to gain space.  10.g4!?  Nc6  11.g5  Nd7  12.Qd2  Black does not have many active options and a cramped position - White is much better. }
10. Rc1
{ White makes sure that there is no ...b5 push. Also  10.f4  works great, threatening with e5, thus inviting Black to close the center with ...d6 and all the passiveness, that comes with it. }
10... b6 11. Na4 Bc5 12. Nxc5 bxc5 13. f3 d6
{ Unfortunately Black is not in time to position his knight on d4 - there are a bit too many preparation moves. }
14. Qd2 Nc6 15. Rd1 Rd8 16. Bg5 { White just doesn't give Black any rest. }
16... Qe7 17. Ne3
{ And now ...e5 is never happening, plus the pin on the f6 knight is still there. }
17... h6 18. Bh4
{ White was much better in Elyoseph, H. @@StartBracket@@2379@@EndBracket@@ - Zeihen, P. @@StartBracket@@2285@@EndBracket@@/ICCF email 2017. }
