[White "20) 5.c4,  Nc2 Setups"]
[Black "5.c4 − 8.Nc2 #2 | Informational 8...Bxc3+"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7
{ Black deals with the e5 threat - the Maroczy Bind setup against the Sicilian Kan here is a huge crossroads. White can seek some off-beat continuations to catch the opponent off-guard or play the classical a3 to prevent Black from playing ...Bb4. Before the age of Stockfish and the likes, it was unanimously considered as 'the only way to fight for the advantage'.  Time passed and the practice proved that Black has many practical options, and the position itself is not so simple to give conclusions. Then came the modern Be2 and with the help of modern engines, it became clear that White can allow the ...Bb4 maneuver and that focusing on the development with the plans to grab space advantage or go for a direct attack is much more important than the integrity of the pawn structure. However, let's do step by step. }
7. Be2 Bb4
{ In the final chapter of the course we are going to examine the Nc2 setups if White retreats with the d4-knight to challenge Black's dark-squared bishop. Sometimes the arising positions will seem similar to previous chapters, but not always. }
8. Nc2
{ A strong move that has recently gained popularity, especially among young players who are working with modern engines. White immediately tries to clarify the situation with the pinned knight. }
8... Bxc3+
{ Taking on c3 is very risky - as sometimes seen in the previous chapters, this time you won't be able to block the dark-squares as the d6-square is already under fire, but the pawn on e4 is Greek's gift. }
9. bxc3 d6
{ Black would like to block the dark squares with the knight but White is lightning fast.   9...Nxe4?  this mistake would probably cost Black the entire game.  10.Qd4  Nf6  11.Bf4  Once White's dark-squared bishop lands on d6, Black's position is paralyzed. }
10. Ba3 Nxe4 11. Qd4 f5
{ Luckily, Black has this resource to keep the pawn on d6 and at least some hold of the dark squares. }
12. Bh5+ Kf8 13. f3
{ Not the only move for White as there are others that also keep the initiative going but this one forces Black to pick up many only moves next. }
13... Nc6 14. Qe3 Nc5 15. O-O-O b6
{ This line is pretty much forced which leads to a very complex position where the Black king is under a constant attack. Even if the final variations to all White's responses will lead Black to a draw, this is simply not practical, and playing such positions regularly is almost a suicidal approach. Players with a brilliant memory might disagree! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20) 5.c4,  Nc2 Setups"]
[Black "5.c4 − 8.Nc2 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7
{ Black deals with the e5 threat - the Maroczy Bind setup against the Sicilian Kan here is a huge crossroads. White can seek some off-beat continuations to catch the opponent off-guard or play the classical a3 to prevent Black from playing ...Bb4. Before the age of Stockfish and the likes, it was unanimously considered as 'the only way to fight for the advantage'.  Time passed and the practice proved that Black has many practical options, and the position itself is not so simple to give conclusions. Then came the modern Be2 and with the help of modern engines, it became clear that White can allow the ...Bb4 maneuver and that focusing on the development with the plans to grab space advantage or go for a direct attack is much more important than the integrity of the pawn structure. However, let's do step by step. }
7. Be2 Bb4
{ In the final chapter of the course we are going to examine the Nc2 setups if White retreats with the d4-knight to challenge Black's dark-squared bishop. Sometimes the arising positions will seem similar to previous chapters, but not always. }
8. Nc2
{ A strong move that has recently gained popularity, especially among young players who are working with modern engines. White immediately tries to clarify the situation with the pinned knight. }
8... Bd6
{ This seems to be a more solid continuation and a safer alternative to  8...Bxc3  and is also in the spirit of the Sicilian Kan. Black slows down White's short castle and wants to reposition the dark-squared bishop on e5. }
9. Be3
{ A serious move - White plans to play Qd2 next and bother the black bishop on d6. After all, White can play h3 later, if he wants, right? }
9... O-O 10. Qd2 Be5
{ Solak, D. @@StartBracket@@2593@@EndBracket@@ - Sadikhov, U. @@StartBracket@@2500@@EndBracket@@ TUR-chT 1st League 2019. Black is back to the idea of bothering the white pawn on e4, this time via the e5-square. White has a few ways to deal with the threat. }
11. Nd4
{ Since the Black bishop no longer stands on b4, pinning the queenside knight, this is very natural as it solves all problems with the e4-pawn. }
11... Nc6
{ Suddenly, it's not so easy for White to make a move. White can't castle short as the h2-pawn is under attack, the d4-knight can't retreat as it might cost the e4-pawn. Black is preparing either ...Rb8 and ...b5 or ...Rd8 with an analog idea ...d5. }
12. Rd1
{ White solidifies his control over the center, improving his defense odds against an immediate ...d5 push.   12.f4?  drops a pawn for no good reason.  12...Bxd4  13.Bxd4  Nxd4  14.Qxd4  Qxf4  and White doesn't have enough compensation for the lost pawn. }
12... Rb8
{ Black is very flexible with his ideas. Start thinking about an immediate ...b5 but the alternative ...Rd8 and ...d5 still might work. It depends, on what White is going to do. }
13. g4
{ There's a rule in chess - an attack in a flank should be answered with a counterstrike in the center. White included Rd1 earlier so that ...d5 is less likely to happen @@StartBracket@@which would have been your response if White had rushed with g4 a move earlier@@EndBracket@@. We're going to slightly modify it - a counterstrike on the queenside. }
13... b5
{ Activity above all! Black is ready to meet White's g5 with ...b4 - one of the most typical Sicilian counterstrikes. }
14. cxb5 Nxd4 15. Bxd4 d5
{ There comes another counterstrike - Black rips White's center apart. Black is very dynamic and it should be quite obvious that White's approach with g4 can seriously backfire as the white king will never be safe.   Just to illustrate where the game might be heading,  16.b6  is the most forcing move.  16...Rxb6!  17.Bxb6  Qxb6  18.exd5  Bb7  . The white king is wide open and White will have to carefully navigate through a minefield. }
