1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7
{ Black deals with the e5 threat - the Maroczy Bind setup against the Sicilian Kan here is a huge crossroads. White can seek some off-beat continuations to catch the opponent off-guard or play the classical a3 to prevent Black from playing ...Bb4. Before the age of Stockfish and the likes, it was unanimously considered as 'the only way to fight for the advantage'.  Time passed and the practice proved that Black has many practical options, and the position itself is not so simple to give conclusions. Then came the modern Be2 and with the help of modern engines, it became clear that White can allow the ...Bb4 maneuver and that focusing on the development with the plans to grab space advantage or go for a direct attack is much more important than the integrity of the pawn structure. However, let's do step by step. }
7. Be2 Bb4
{ In the final chapter of the course we are going to examine the Nc2 setups if White retreats with the d4-knight to challenge Black's dark-squared bishop. Sometimes the arising positions will seem similar to previous chapters, but not always. }
8. Nc2
{ A strong move that has recently gained popularity, especially among young players who are working with modern engines. White immediately tries to clarify the situation with the pinned knight. }
8... Bd6
{ This seems to be a more solid continuation and a safer alternative to  8...Bxc3  and is also in the spirit of the Sicilian Kan. Black slows down White's short castle and wants to reposition the dark-squared bishop on e5. }
9. h3
{ A very natural response - White protects the pawn so that he can castle short. }
9... b6
{ Before White can castle short and push f4, it's important to apply extra pressure on the e4-pawn. }
10. O-O Bb7 11. Bd3 Be7
{ Black switches to the Hedgehog. Yes, we lost a tempo for Bd6-e7 but also White played not the most successful moves h3 and Be2-d3. We're entering positions that the engines give White some advantage due to space advantage. However, there's one thing that the computers don't understand - the maneuvering game of the Hedgehog. }
12. f4
{ Because earlier committing to h3, White doesn't want to play f3 anymore, thus protecting the e4-pawn - that would seriously weaken the dark squares around the king. Since it's difficult to imagine what else can White do if not push f4, Black will always have some counterplay on the e4-pawn. }
12... d6 13. Be3 O-O
{ We've reached a traditional Hedgehog setup when White's setup is not ideal. }
14. Rc1 Nbd7 { Black wants to play ...Nc5 and start pressing the center. } 15.
b4 b5
{ This breakthrough might not always be there but if you can execute it, it makes sense to go for it as it clarifies the situation and gives you more to work with. The alternative is to maneuver the rooks to e8, c8, and position the dark-squared bishop to f8, waiting for a better moment.   Assuming that there might be a tricky move order and, for some reason, you don't get to execute the ...b5 push, you can always aim for the following setup:  15...Rac8  16.Nd4  Rfe8  17.a3  Qb8  18.Nde2  Bf8  .  Black would like to fianchetto the bishop on g7 and look for active options in the center. White risks overstretching the position as both pawns on e4 and c4 need to be constantly guarded. }
16. Na3 bxc4 17. Nxc4 d5
{ And there's the other breakthrough which springs all Black's pieces to life. White's remains very active thus such pushes need to be carried out carefully. }
18. exd5 { Not the strongest. } 18... exd5 19. Ne5 Qd6 20. Nxd7 Nxd7
{ The position remains double-edged with mutual weaknesses. Black has an isolated pawn on d5 while White has a more vulnerable king. }
