{ White forces the bishop to retreat to e7. It might seem like a loss of time and that White has managed to include a useful developing move but the white rook on d1 allows Black to easier make the counterstrike ...b5! }
11... Be7
{ Now White has to make a big decision, where to turn the game: positional squeeze or fight to the death? White's current setup is not ideal. }
12. O-O
{ White might be completely oblivious of Black's plan or estimate it to be not a big threat. }
12... b5 13. cxb5 axb5 14. Nxb5 Qb8
{ Thanks to the White rook on d1, Black wins a very important tempo. } 15. a3
Ne5 16. Qd4 Neg4
{ It is already possible to repeat the position with  16...Nc6  but there's no need. }
17. g3 Ba6 18. a4 h5
{ Black has full compensation for the pawn.   Here's one scenario of how the game could continue:  19.h3  Rc8!  20.hxg4  Rxc2  Black is about to win back the sacrificed pawn.  21.Rd2  Bc5  22.Qd3  Bxe3  Black has other choices as well.  23.Qxe3  White cannot capture on e3 with the pawn as g3 would be hanging  23...Rxd2  24.Qxd2  Nxe4  25.Qxd7  White allows a perpetual check.  25...Nxg3  26.fxg3  Qxg3+  A beautiful draw. }
