14... Ne8 15. Nxb5
{ White won't take the pawn, Black will just push it forward. } 15... Qb8
{ It's in Black's best interest to keep the position as complex as possible. Black didn't enter a gambit just to win back the pawn - we're looking for ways to take over the game. At the moment the a2-pawn is under attack and Black wants to play a quick ...f6 to bring the knight to d5 square as quickly as possible. Check out some of the scenarios, how the game could continue from here.   15...Qa5+  It's tempting to win back the pawn right away but White will keep the better chances.  16.Qd2!  Qxd2+  17.Kxd2  Rxa2   If Black seeks a positional compensation with  17...f6  , it's not very clear why the queen trade was necessary.  18.Ra1  Rxa1  19.Rxa1  Due to more active pieces and the potential of the outside passed pawn, White seems to be better. }
16. Qc4
{ White not only protects the a2-pawn but prepares a counterstrike with f5. }
16... f6 17. O-O fxe5 18. f5 { Now the game will get  sharp. } 18... Na5
{ Otherwise ...d5 push is impossible. } 19. Qc3 d5 20. b4 Nb7 21. fxe6 Bxe6
{ Black has won back the sacrificed pawn and enjoys a strong pawn center. However, White's pieces are very active. }
22. Rxf8+ Bxf8 23. Bf3 d4 24. Qc6 Qc8
{ The position looks messy but it's about to simplify. } 25. Ncxd4 exd4 26.
Rxd4
{ Unfortunately Black can't keep the extra piece due to multiple threats. }
26... Qxc6 27. Bxc6 Bxa2 28. Bxb7 Rb8 29. Bc6 Nf6
{ White can't keep the b4-pawn. } *

