{ Again!   13...d6?!  We'd like to show you one little nuance.  14.O-O  Ned7  15.b4  a5  16.a3  Here you see the difference if the white pawns stand on a2 or a4 - White can keep the b4-pawn and the control of the c5-square. }
14. Bf4 { An interesting idea - White goes for a counterstrike. } 14... Nd3+
15. Rxd3 Qxf4 16. e5 { The point of White's idea. } 16... Qxd4 17. Nxd4 Ne8
{ Black is about to open the center and activate the bishops so don't worry too much about the b5-pawn.   17...bxc4?  It's interesting, it's fun but it might be too much.  18.exf6  Bxf6  19.Rd1  d5  Black has two central pawns and a pair of bishops but it might not be enough for full compensation if White is accurate.  20.Na4!  Ra7  21.b3  Bd7  22.Nc5  White badly wants to trade one of the black bishops.  22...Bc8  23.bxc4  Rc7  24.Na4  dxc4  25.O-O  c3  Maybe Black has some practical chances, but it feels like a one-sided game. }
18. cxb5 axb5 19. Ndxb5 f6
{ Black inevitably will activate his pieces, claiming the compensation for the pawn. }
20. exf6
{ The most logical continuation.   20.Nd6  Not a very obvious alternative but also possible - White is seeking some simplifications.  20...Ba6  21.Rd2  fxe5  22.Nxe8  Rfxe8  23.Rxd7  Bb4  White is still up a pawn but the position is about to reach a rook endgame.  24.Bxa6  Rxa6  25.Rd2  Bxc3  26.bxc3  Rea8  White's extra pawn is falling.  27.Ke2  Rxa2  28.Rd1  Kf7  White is still better but such positions normally are not winning if Black leads an active defense. }
20... Nxf6 21. O-O d5
{ The game can easily go either way. White has the extra pawn but Black has a pawn center and two bishops. }
22. Nd4 Ne4
{ Black forces matters - it's possible to play a little conservative as  22...Bd7  and later ...Kf7. }
23. Nc6 Bf6 24. Nxe4 dxe4 25. Rd2 Rxa2
{ Black has equalized the game but it could be difficult to have any real winning chances. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "20) 5.c4,  Nc2 Setups"]
[Black "5.c4 − 8.Qd3 O-O 9.Nc2 #16 | Informational 12...b6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ The Sicilian Kan! Black has placed the pawns on e6 and a6 to limit the white knight's potential jumps to d5, b5, or f5 and will be looking for ways how to pressure White's center. }
5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7
{ Black deals with the e5 threat - the Maroczy Bind setup against the Sicilian Kan here is a huge crossroads. White can seek some off-beat continuations to catch the opponent off-guard or play the classical a3 to prevent Black from playing ...Bb4. Before the age of Stockfish and the likes, it was unanimously considered as 'the only way to fight for the advantage'.  Time passed and the practice proved that Black has many practical options, and the position itself is not so simple to give conclusions. Then came the modern Be2 and with the help of modern engines, it became clear that White can allow the ...Bb4 maneuver and that focusing on the development with the plans to grab space advantage or go for a direct attack is much more important than the integrity of the pawn structure. However, let's do step by step. }
7. Be2 Bb4
{ In the final chapter of the course we are going to examine the Nc2 setups if White retreats with the d4-knight to challenge Black's dark-squared bishop. Sometimes the arising positions will seem similar to previous chapters, but not always. }
8. Qd3
{ As already explained in the previous chapter, the White queen on d3 feels awkward but it does cover many important squares and can be rerouted to g3. This is the main move. }
8... O-O 9. Nc2
{ While not so popular, this continuation is quite a dangerous weapon. Black will have to precisely know, based on what he can create a good enough counterplay. The only choice here is really between the typical Kan's ...Bd6 or take on c3 as after ...Be7 Black is forced to enter the classical Hedgehog when White's position is close to optimal, grabbing a lot of space advantage.   9.O-O  Nc6!  This transposes to the lines with 8.O-O in the previous chapter. }
9... Bd6
{ As you have already learned so far, here the dark-squared bishop stands almost perfectly, at least temporarily. It slows down White's intentions to castle short and also stops the f4 push. This will give enough time for Black to prepare for what's coming next. }
10. Be3
{ The most natural move that White has, improving the control of the dark squares. Castling for the moment can wait, plus theoretically, it still can happen both ways. Of course, castling long carries an extra risk due to ...b5 push. }
10... Nc6
{ Black continues according to the general plan of the Sicilian Kan. Now White has some choices. }
11. Rd1
{ White forces the bishop to retreat to e7. It might seem like a loss of time and that White has managed to include a useful developing move but the white rook on d1 allows Black to easier make the counterstrike ...b5! }
11... Be7
{ Now White has to make a big decision, where to turn the game: positional squeeze or fight to the death? White's current setup is not ideal. }
12. a4
{ A standard prophylactic move that starts a positional fight. Apart from the extra protection against the ...b5 push, it has some downsides as well - the weakness of the b3-pawn and the b4-square could play a role later. }
12... b6
{ For a long time engines like to convince us that here this plan for Black works. However, they are wrong.   12...b5?!  Pushing ...b5 here is too much - with the white pawn on a4 it loses any purpose.  13.axb5  axb5  14.cxb5  Quite precise - if White captures the pawn with the knight, Black retreats with the queen to b8 and prepares the ...d5 push.  14...Ne5  15.Qd4  Bb7  Black has some activity but no real targets to pressure. White's extra pawn should mean something.  16.Bf4  Nd3+  17.Rxd3  Qxf4  18.O-O  White is much better. }
13. f4 Rd8 14. O-O Bb7 { Black's setup does look quite dynamic. } 15. Kh1
{ 15.e5  this is too early  15...Ne8  Black will push ...d6 next. } 15... Rac8
16. Bg1 { White prepares the queen lift to h3. } 16... g6
{ If not ...Na5, then what? This might be a way to muddy the waters but White's attack keeps going strong.   A@@EndBracket@@  16...Bc5  17.e5  Ne8  18.Ne4  Bxg1  19.Rxg1±  .   B@@EndBracket@@  16...Na5?  after some long thought engines do find a very strong plan for White.  17.e5!  Ne8  18.Qg3  f5  19.Ne3  . As it happens, there's no satisfactory defense against White's threats. Black is just losing!  19...Bc5  20.Ncd5!  exd5  21.Nxf5  After a long work with Stockfish, we were unable to find, how Black can escape - White's attack is decisive. The black king is left alone. }
17. Qh3 Nb4 18. Nd4 { White sacrifices a pawn on e4 and is about to push f5. }
18... Bxe4 19. Nxe4 Nxe4 20. f5 Qe5
{ Taking on f5 is too much - White will happily sacrifice the knight and start to hunt down the black king while Black's entire army is somewhere else. }
21. fxg6 fxg6 22. Nf3
{ White has a strong attack with many tactical motifs and the hanging pawn on b6 is just an extra. }
*

