[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ It is impossible to walk past one of the greatest experts and true defenders of the Kan variation - grandmaster Ilia Smirin. The fact that he wasn't afraid to play it against the strongest chess players in the world like Garry Kasparov and Vladimir Kramnik, already delivers big respect. }
2. Nf3 e6 3. g3 d5
{ We chose this game for the reason that Black used the setup that we advise in the course. Also, Black's interesting approach in the middlegame allows us to show you some practical decisions, made by chess professionals. }
4. exd5 exd5 5. d4 Nc6
{ Not the most accurate order of the moves.   5...Nf6  Remember one of the principles? Wait for White's queenside knight to develop first before jumping with the knight to c6.  6.Bg2  Be7  7.O-O  O-O  8.Nc3  Nc6  And only now the black knight comes out. }
6. Bg2 Nf6 7. O-O Be7 8. dxc5
{ One of the typical ideas: White forces the black bishop to move twice in a row and establishes an isolated pawn on d5. }
8... Bxc5 9. a3 O-O 10. Nc3
{ This logical move is an inaccuracy.   10.b4!  This was stronger.  10...Be7  11.Bb2  Now Black doesn't have the typical counterstrike with ...d4 as White's queenside knight is still on b1. }
10... Re8 { Now we transpose to familiar lines we have already looked at. } 11.
b4 d4
{ This counterstrike in the center is quite an important theme for the line. }
12. Na4
{ 12.bxc5  Tempting but it doesn't pose Black any problems.  12...dxc3  13.Qxd8  Rxd8  14.Rb1  Bf5!  15.Rxb7  Rac8!  Actually, it's White who can land into trouble as the black pawn on c3 is quite far advanced. }
12... Bf8 13. c4
{ White offers some simplifications while aiming for a position with slightly more active pieces.   13.Bb2  In the theoretical chapter we analyze this move, which is stronger. }
13... dxc3
{ Black forgives his opponent - now we get a symmetrical-looking position. It also seems that simplifications and a draw are just around the corner, but not everything is so simple.   13...Bg4  That's one way to seek hostilities.   13...d3  Black could have also opted for an aggressive pawn push forward. }
14. Nxc3 Bg4 15. Be3 Qc8
{ Black goes for a fight and keeps queens on the board.  15...Rc8  would be just equal. }
16. Qb3
{ White escapes the annoying pin.   16.Nd5!?  White could have insisted on simplifications.  16...Qf5   16...Qd8!?  17.Nd4!  Qxd5!  Nice shot but it's only a start of mass trades.  18.Bxd5  Bxd1  19.Bxc6  bxc6  20.Rfxd1  Ng4!  First, push away the bishop.  21.Bd2  c5  And only now the c-pawn goes forward. }
16... Be6
{ Black pushes away the white queen to improve control over the central squares.   16...Qf5  Black could have insisted on the same maneuver but now the White queen is gone from the pin.  17.Nd4  Nxd4  18.Bxd4  18...Rad8  19.Bxf6  Qxf6  It's quite interesting - Black gives up the b7-pawn for a lot of activity. }
17. Qb2 Bh3
{ Now it's time to trade one of White's most important pieces, thus weakening his control of the light squares. }
18. Rfd1 Bxg2 19. Kxg2 Qf5
{ Despite the symmetrical nature of the position, Black can organize something interesting on the kingside. }
20. h3 Rac8 21. Qb3 { The position is equal. } 21... Rxe3
{ A classic decision by a true chess practitioner. The white king now becomes so weak that, from a practical point of view, the game can be very difficult to play for White. Engines aren't impressed though.   21...a5  This would have been the standard continuation, which would lead to mass trades on the queenside and an inevitable draw. }
22. fxe3 Ne5 23. Nxe5
{ White is interested in trading off as many pieces as he can. } 23... Qxe5
{ And now White needs to show some remarkable accuracy and composure in order to push back the opponent's initiative. In the game, the strong English grandmaster did not succeed. }
24. Rac1
{ 24.Rd3!  White could have kept the better position with a series of very precise moves.  24...Bd6   24...h5  was another option for Black.  25.Rf1  h4  26.e4!  To find such variations over the board, you need not only good calculation skills but also composure.  25.e4!  White needs to protect the g3-pawn at all costs - the white knight can't move due to the rook on a1.  25...Nxe4  26.Nxe4  Qxe4+  27.Kg1  Nice shot - Black has two pawns for the exchange and the king is exposed. It's very easy for White to stop the calculation right here.  27...Bxg3!  28.Qd5!  It could be quite difficult to spot this move from afar. White wants to trade queens because then Black's 7th rank would be quite weak.   28.Rf1?  This safe would move would have been a mistake.  28...Bf4  29.Qc3  29...Re8  30.Rd7  Qe6  31.Qd3  g5  Black holds the initiative.  28...Qh4  29.Rf1  29...Rf8  30.Rd4!  Very strong - Black can't take on h3 due to a very typical queen sacrifice on f7 and make to follow.  30...Qe7  31.Re4!  Qc7  32.Kg2  Bd6  33.Rd1  Bh2  34.Rd3+-  White's rook is so strong that the position should be winning, even if we have material equality on the board.   24.Ne2  This move gives the feeling that the white king is left defenseless.  24...Qe4+  25.Kg1  a5!?  26.Qd3  Of course, White wants to trade queens, even if it costs a pawn.  26...Qe5  27.bxa5  Rc5  Black lifts the rook to join the initiative on the kingside.  28.a4  Rxa5  29.Kh2  h5  Although Black doesn't have full compensation for the missing exchange, it's much easier to play with Black. Plus, if we reach a position where the queenside pawns are eliminated, there are a lot of drawish tendencies. }
24... Qxe3 { Black should already not be risking anything. } 25. Qb2
{ 25.Qc2!  Engines don't really care about self-created pins.  25...a5  26.Qd3  Qe6  27.Qe2  White is pushing very hard to trade queens.  27...Qb3  28.Rd3  Re8  29.Qd1  Qxd1  Now it's alright to trade the queens - Black eliminates White's queenside pawns.  30.Nxd1  axb4  31.axb4  Bxb4  32.Rb1  Bc5  33.Rxb7  g6  The position is drawish - Black will easily hold the position with the pawn for the exchange. }
25... Nh5 26. Ne2 Re8
{ Black has minimal material losses but the initiative is still going. } 27.
Rd2 Qe4+ 28. Kh2 g6 29. Rf1 Bh6 { The perfect diagonal for the black bishop. }
30. Rc2
{ Another inaccuracy.   30.Nc3  Qe3  31.Rg2  Qd3  32.Qf2!  Finding such moves, especially in time trouble, can be very challenging, if not impossible.  32...Nf4!  33.gxf4  Qxc3  The position remains unclear. }
30... Qd3 31. Qa2
{ White errs in the time trouble but it was already difficult to pick up the right move.   31.Rg1  Ng7  Black's attack is going strong. }
31... Rxe2+ 32. Rxe2 Qxg3+ 33. Kh1 Qxh3+
{ Black has three pawns for two sacrificed exchanges but the weak white king means only one thing - Black should be winning. }
34. Kg1 Qg3+ 35. Kh1 Qh3+
{ A practical decision in time trouble - repeat moves to gain some valuable time. }
36. Kg1 Be3+
{ Despite the fact that this check is so tempting, Black collects the wrong white rook!   36...Qg4+!  Black should go for the white rook on f1. In time trouble - not obvious!  37.Kh2   37.Kf2  Qg3   37.Rg2  This allows Black to execute a very nice mating pattern.  37...Be3+  38.Rff2  Qf3!  39.Kh2  Bf4+  40.Kg1  Qd1+  41.Rf1  Be3+  42.Rgf2  Qg4+  Black is not in a hurry to take the white rook.  43.Kh2  Qg3+  44.Kh1  Qh3+  45.Kg1  Nf4  Mate on g2 is inevitable.  Bf4+  38.Rxf4  Nxf4  The difference to what happened in the game is that Black wins the exchange and keeps his attack going.  39.Re8+  Kg7  40.Qb2+  Kh6  41.Qd2  41...g5  Black has enough pawns on the kingside to close any pins.  42.Re3  Kg6  43.Qd6+  f6  There's no perpetual check and Black's attack on the kingside is decisive. }
37. Rxe3 Qxe3+ 38. Qf2
{ Suddenly White is back in the game! Black is not only ready to start the kingside attack, but also trading the queens is very risky as the White rook will easily penetrate the 7th rank, making Black's queenside pawns an easy target. }
38... Qg5+ 39. Kh2 Qe7 40. Qxa7 { White wins one pawn. } 40... Qe5+ 41. Kg1 Nf4
{ Black goes for the kingside attack again but the circumstances have changed. }
42. Rxf4
{ This brilliant idea Black had missed. White inevitably will push forward one of the queenside pawns thus Black will have to force a perpetual check. }
42... Qxf4 43. Qxb7 h5
{ Despite the material advantage, essentially it's one passed pawn vs another as two or three passed pawns run together much slower than one. }
44. b5 h4 45. b6 Qe3+ 46. Kh2 Qf2+ 47. Kh1 Qf1+ 48. Kh2
{ White managed to save the game but Black's approach truly impresses. } *

