1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Bd3 Bc5
{ Black takes the opportunity to push back the white knight from the center. }
6. Nb3 Ba7 7. O-O Nc6 8. Qg4 Nf6
{ Although this maneuver is standard, with the current move order it's a strategically dangerous choice. Still, it might be interesting to try it in some rapid or blitz games to surprise an opponent who doesn't know all the fine details of the variation.   8...Qf6  is the strongest move, analyzed in the course. }
9. Qxg7 Rg8 10. Qh6 Ne5 11. Be2
{ Very accurate - White defends the f3 and g4-squares.   11.Nc3?!  This standard developing move allows Black to grab the initiative.  11...Nfg4!  12.Qxh7  Rf8  Suddenly for White, it's difficult to parry Black's ...Qf6-Rh8 threat.  13.Nd1   13.Qh3?!  Qf6  Qf6  14.Qh5  14...Qg7  Black dodges the queen trade.  15.Be2  Rg8  16.g3  b5  Black has a powerful attack - it doesn't even seem that two pawns are missing.   11.Qh3  White could try to retreat and force the dark-squared bishop trade to extinguish Black's initiative.  11...Nfg4  12.Be2  Qf6  This maneuver for the system is standard.  13.Bxg4  Nxg4  14.Be3  Nxe3  15.fxe3  Qxb2  Black has won back the pawn but at least White finishes his development. Due to the power of the bishop, Black's position should still be slightly preferred. }
11... d5
{ Black aims to activate the queen.   11...b5!?  This is an interesting alternative try, aiming to activate the light-squared bishop.  12.Bg5   12.Be3  White's desire to trade off one of Black's most active pieces is understandable.  12...Rg6!  Don't focus on the e4-pawn!   12...Nxe4?!  It's tempting to grab the pawn but now White gets exactly what he wanted.  13.Bxa7  Rxa7  14.N1d2!  Black's attack is over but the weaknesses remain.  14...Qg5  15.Qxg5  Nxg5  16.Kh1  Bb7  17.f3  White solidifies the kingside first.  17...f5  18.a4  bxa4  19.Rxa4  Black's pieces are stuck on the kingside but the weakness on a6 remains - White is much better.  13.Qf4  Bb8  This bishop retreat is good to know.  14.Qh4  Neg4  15.Bxg4  Nxg4  16.Qxd8+  Kxd8  Despite the fact that the queens are off the board, Black's initiative continues.  17.Bb6+  Ke8  18.g3  e5!  Black has more than sufficient compensation for the missing pawn.  Rg6  13.Qh4  Bb7  14.N1d2!  h6  Black has to play very energetically to prove he has something for the missing pawn.  15.Bxf6  Rxf6  16.Qg3  16...Ng6  17.a4  Nf4!  A logical improvement over one Smirin's game.   17...Bb8?  Although this is a common trick, it doesn't work in this specific line.  18.Qc3  Be5  19.Qe3  Nf4  20.axb5  Sacrificing two pawns for unclear initiative was a little too much for Black in Aravindh, C. @@StartBracket@@2566@@EndBracket@@ - Smirin, I. @@StartBracket@@2669@@EndBracket@@ London Classic op 8th 2016.  18.Bf3  Kf8!  19.axb5   19.e5?  White would love to simplify the position but there's a cute trick.  19...Ne2+!  20.Bxe2  Rg6  21.Bg4  h5  Black holds the initiative.  19...e5!  Here lies Black's idea - hold onto the dark squares to get good counterplay.  20.Na5  Bc8  21.Qh4  axb5  22.b4  Qe7  The game is very unclear - here's how it could continue.  23.c4  Kg7  24.cxb5  Qxb4  Black's dynamimism compensates for the missing pawn.  25.Nac4  Qxb5  26.Rab1  Qc5  27.Ne3  d6  28.Rfc1  Qa5  29.Ndc4  Qd8  The hostilities are not over yet. }
12. Bg5
{ Not the best move.   12.Nc3!  If there's a move that can create problems for Black, it's this one, but only if White 'knows' it as over the board it can be quite difficult to find.  12...d4  13.Rd1  Neg4  14.Bxg4  Rg6  A nice intermezzo before Black recaptures on g4.  15.Qg5!  To spot this move from afar can be very difficult, even for a Grandmaster. Anything else is much less clear.  15...Rxg5  16.Bxg5  h6  17.Bh4  Qc7  Black initiates a semi-forced sequence of moves.  18.Bxf6  dxc3  19.Rd8+  It makes sense to win back the queen before Black can close the d-file with ...Bd7.  19...Qxd8  20.Bxd8  cxb2  21.Rd1  b1=Q  22.Rxb1  Kxd8  23.Na5  White has an extra pawn but the two bishops and White's weaknesses on the queenside give Black good hopes to hold the game to a draw. }
12... Neg4
{ Now the game is complex with about balanced chances - typical sacrifice ideas on f2 start to emerge. }
13. Bxf6 Nxf6 14. exd5
{ 14.Nc3  b5  The game is very sharp. As an alternative Black can consider the  14...Rg6  and ...Bb8 plan. }
14... Qxd5 15. g3
{ White's strategy seems to be sound - somehow position the light-squared bishop on g2 and survive the storm. }
15... Qe5
{ Very tempting but still - this move is more characteristic for a blitz game.   15...Qf5!  This was stronger, not allowing the White bishop to land on f3.  16.N1d2  Ng4  17.Qh4  It could take some composure to make this move!   17.Bxg4  Giving up the light-squared bishop is not better.  17...Rxg4  18.c3  Bd7  19.Nd4  Bxd4  20.cxd4  Bc6  Black is better due to the powerful light-squared bishop.  17...Bxf2+  18.Kg2  Ne3+  19.Kh1  Rg4!  Black is attacking with everything he's got and once the light-squared bishop lands on the h1-a8 diagonal, things can get ugly for White. Black is not focused on winning the exchange.  20.Qh6  Bd7  21.Bf3  Nxf1  22.Rxf1  Bxg3  23.Qh3  A cold-blooded defense!  23...Rg6  24.Qxf5  exf5  25.hxg3  O-O-O  The arising position is anything but clear. }
16. Nc3
{ 16.Bf3  White could have protected his king first.  16...Bd7  17.N1d2  O-O-O  18.Qh4  Black doesn't have enough compensation for the missing pawn - grabbing the b2-pawn would only fuel White's attack on the b-file. }
16... Bd7 17. Bf3
{ White doesn't sense the danger.   17.Qh4  It was important to extra protect the g3-pawn.  17...O-O-O  18.Rae1  White is in time to protect everything. }
17... O-O-O
{ Now the game once again is wide open and White immediately errs. } 18. Rad1
{ This must have been a hallucination. } 18... Rxg3+ 19. hxg3 Qxg3+ 20. Bg2 Rg8
21. Qh2 Bc6
{ Perhaps White simply missed this move - White's position collapses very fast. The remaining moves don't require annotation. }
22. Qxg3 Rxg3 23. Nd5 Bxd5 24. Rxd5 Nxd5 25. Kh1 Rg5 26. Nd2 Nf4 27. Bf3 f5 28.
Nc4 Nh3 29. Nd6+ Kc7 30. Nxb7 Nxf2+ 31. Kh2 e5 32. Na5 e4 33. Be2 f4
{ Even if White knew the correct setup, in practice it can feel different. } *

