[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Vladimir Onischuk vs. Igor Kovalenko, Bastia 2015"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ A memorable game for Igor Kovalenko. The tournament situation was demanding to play for the win - if you're looking for a fight, Sicilian Kan is a great choice. }
1... c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. b3
{ Igor's opponent was grandmaster Vladimir Onischuk, who is a strong practitioner. His expertise does not lie in long and theoretical lines, so playing something off-beat this early was to be expected. }
3... b6 4. Bb2 Bb7 5. Nc3 Be7
{ A move, with a touch of blitz.   5...Nf6  If Black immediately challenges the e4-pawn, you have to reckon with the following plan.  6.e5  Ne4  7.Qe2  Nxc3  8.dxc3  Nc6  9.O-O-O  White has the initiative. }
6. g3
{ The trick worked!   6.d4!  It was best to show ambition in the center.  6...cxd4  7.Qxd4  Nf6  8.O-O-O  White is better but still it feels like an Open Sicilian. }
6... Nf6 7. Bg2
{ The pawn on e4 is indirectly defended.   7.e5  With the inclusion of 6. g3 this is not so clear.  7...Ng4  8.Nb5  Nc6  9.Bg2  O-O  10.O-O  a6  Black forces White to do something about the e5-pawn.  11.Nd6  Bxd6  12.exd6  Nh6  White will need to be careful. }
7... Nxe4
{ Black picks up the gauntlet.   7...O-O  Objectively this is stronger, but there's one problem.  8.e5  Ne8  9.O-O  d6  10.d4  The position may be equal but how Black can win this? }
8. Nxe4 Bxe4 9. Bxg7 Rg8 10. Bb2
{ 10.Bh6!?  This was also possible.  10...Nc6  11.O-O  d5  12.c3  With a complex game - White is better but the position is anything but a dry draw. }
10... Bf6 11. Bxf6
{ 11.c3!  Apparently, this was better but voluntarily closing the dark-squared bishop is anything but obvious. }
11... Qxf6 { Now Black is doing just fine. } 12. O-O Nc6 13. Re1 Bd5
{ 13...d5!?  is a more active way to proceed. } 14. c4
{ White forces a lot of trades. } 14... Bxf3 15. Qxf3 Qxf3 16. Bxf3 Rc8 17.
Bxc6 Rxc6
{ Black enters a complex rook endgame and seeks his chances to win the game. }
18. Re4 Rd6 19. Rd1 h5 20. Rh4
{ The first step in the wrong direction.   20.Kf1  Ke7  21.Ke2  a6  The position is equal but White has no plan - he has to sit and wait for Black to do something.  22.d4?  White can't simplify matters, at least not right away.  22...f5  23.Rf4  Rg4  24.Rxg4?  Here's how White can completely misplay it.  24...hxg4  25.dxc5  Rxd1  26.Kxd1  bxc5  Despite material balance, White loses in the pawn endgame, mainly due to the h2-pawn. }
20... Rg5 21. Kf1 a6 22. f4 { A nervous decision. } 22... Rf5
{ Now it's going to be quite difficult for White to activate the stranded rook on h4. }
23. Ke2 Rd4
{ It will take forever for White to make the h3-g4 plan work. The black rook on d4 also stops any of White's d4-pawn push plans. }
24. d3 d5
{ The black rook on d4 is also attacking the white pawn on c4, but probably the d-pawn push was a little too early.  24...b5!  would have been preferable. }
25. a4 Kd7 26. Ke3 Kc6 27. Rc1 b5
{ White is forced to sit and wait - not the most pleasant situation to be in. }
28. axb5+ axb5 29. h3 Kb6
{ The black king is also a piece! Black is looking for ways to create an outside passed pawn on the queenside, but  29...e5!?  was also interesting. }
30. Rb1 { Intending to meet ...Ka5 with b4+. } 30... e5 31. cxd5 Rxd5
{ 31...exf4+  would help the white rook to escape its prison.  32.Rxf4  Rfxf4  33.gxf4  Ka5  34.b4+!  That's why White positioned the rook on b1 several moves ago.  34...Rxb4  35.Ra1+  Ra4  36.d6  Kb6  37.Rg1  Rd4  38.Rg7  White should draw the game. }
32. Ke4
{ In the time scramble, White is tempted to deliver a cute fork, but it only dooms the rook on h4.   32.b4!  White had to try to activate the queenside rook, although it allows Black to create an outside passed pawn.  32...exf4+   32...Rd4  This does not change anything.  33.bxc5+  Kxc5  34.Rc1+  Kb4  35.fxe5  Rxh4  36.gxh4  Rxe5+  37.Kd4  White should comfortably draw the game.  33.Rxf4  Rxf4  34.bxc5+  Kxc5  35.gxf4  b4  36.Rc1+  Kb5  37.d4  Black is still pushing but the draw is close. }
32... exf4 33. gxf4
{ 33.Rxf4  The problem is that now White can't bring out the rook.  33...Rfe5+  34.Kf3  Rxd3+  White's position collapses. }
33... Ka5
{ With the White rook forever stuck on h4, Black was able to win the game in mutual time trouble. }
34. b4+ cxb4 35. Ra1+ Kb6 36. Rb1 Kc5 37. Rc1+ Kd6 38. Rb1 Rf6 39. d4 Re6+ 40.
Kd3 Rg6 41. Rxb4 Rg3+ 42. Ke2 Rf5 43. Kf2 Rc3 44. Rb1 Kc6 45. Ke2 Kb6 46. Rd1
