[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6
{ As soon as we began our work on the Sicilian Kan course, Igor started several correspondence games against formidable opponents. This is the best game as it perfectly highlights some of the tactical options at Black's disposal. This is also the reason why we decided to investigate the setups with 9...Nc6 much closer, essentially offering them in the course. }
5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7 7. a3
{ The Maroczy Bind system with a3 against the Sicilian Kan has been around forever. White stops the ...Bb4 pin and aims for the classical Hedgehog. }
7... b6 8. Be3 Bb7 9. f3 Nc6
{ By now you should already remember the typical plans for Black. } 10. Na4
{ White immediately tries to underline the biggest weakness in Black's setup - the pawn on b6. This is also one of Stockfish's top choices, so this is where you will have to work the hardest. Although this plan is not the most popular, it has its own standalone importance. }
10... Rb8 { Everything is logical - White is attacking us, we are defending. }
11. Rc1 Be7
{ We were considering to offer this as your choice for study but discarded it due to the crazy amount of variations. Judge for yourself!   11...Nxd4  12.Qxd4  Bc6  This is what we're recommending in the course as it's simpler and easier to understand. Still, we felt that we have to show some of the alternative ideas to broaden your understanding of the arising positions. }
12. b4
{ Multi-purpose move - often White will want to push c5.   12.Nb3!?  White could attack the b6-pawn right away.  12...Bc8!?  13.Be2  O-O  14.O-O  Bd6  This is one of the ideas why we're advising to keep the d-pawn still on d7 - the dark-squared bishop can become very active on the b8-h2 diagonal.  15.Kh1!  Bf4  Black trades off the strongest piece in White's arsenal.  16.Bxf4  Qxf4  17.Rc2  Rd8  18.Qd2  Qc7  .  Trading the queens and quickly bringing the king to e7 also is interesting.    19.Rd1  d6  Black is back to the classical Hedgehog ideas, but there's a major difference - the dark-squared bishops have been traded. Since Black's position is always a little cramped, this should be good for you.  20.Nc3  Ne5  21.Nd4  h6  22.Bf1  Bb7  A long maneuvering game begins. }
12... O-O
{ Here Black has many tricky ideas and it really depends on what White will play next. }
13. Be2
{ A solid developing move.   A@@EndBracket@@  13.Qd2  Nxd4  14.Bxd4  Bc6  Black pushes away the White knight and remains flexible with his plans.  15.b5?!  Tempting, but here it's not good.  15...axb5  16.cxb5  Qa7!  Black starts to take over the game.   B@@EndBracket@@  13.Nb3  d5!  If White is very stubborn and insists on winning the b6 pawn, at some point you can simply drop it and go for an attack.  14.Bxb6  Qe5  White's lack of development starts to be felt. }
13... Nh5
{ This is one of Igor's greatest discoveries in the Sicilian Kan. It's difficult to find a real advantage for White even with engines, but it should be much more difficult over the board. White is at a big crossroads. }
14. g3
{ According to the engines, this is the strongest move but for a human it's not easy to make. After all, the white king now will never feel safe and White will always have to watch out for potential sacrifices on g3.   A@@EndBracket@@  14.Qd2  Covering the f4-square with the queen is sensible.  14...f5!  15.exf5  Nxd4  16.Qxd4  Rxf5  However, White will soon find himself on the defensive side.   B@@EndBracket@@  14.Nb3!?  If White goes after the b-pawn, Black can just ignore it.  14...f5!  15.g3  Taking the pawn looks very scary for White.   15.Bxb6?!  Qe5  16.Nac5  fxe4!  17.Nxd7  Qg5  18.Nxb8  Nf4!  Black's initiative is very powerful.  15...Ba8  16.exf5  Rxf5  The white king will never find a safe place to hide.   C@@EndBracket@@  14.Nxc6  White could also focus on the queenside, generating some quick targets.  14...Bxc6  15.b5!  Ba8  16.c5  This is now a race, but the White king is still in the center.  16...axb5  17.cxb6  Qd8  18.Bxb5  Bxa3  19.Rb1  d5!  Despite White's best efforts, the game is just unclear. }
14... f5 15. exf5 exf5 { Black's plan is simple - everything charges forward. }
16. Nb3
{ The most ambitious move.   16.Nc2  This slightly careful move to have the knight closer to the king starts an almost forced sequence.  16...f4  17.Qd5+  For White, it's a necessary tempo.   17.Bxb6?!  Qe5  18.g4  Nf6  Black has the initiative.  17...Rf7  18.Bxb6  Qe5  Since Black's piece activity is enormous, trading queens may be just fine.  19.g4  Bh4+  20.Kd2   20.Bf2  This 'automatic' defense meets a little shocker.  20...Bxf2+  21.Kxf2  Ng3!!  Suddenly, White realizes that he can't take the knight as the bishop on e2 is poorly defended.  22.Qxe5  Nxh1+  23.Rxh1  Nxe5  24.Rd1  The position is still unclear.  20...Nf6  21.Qxe5  Nxe5  Black has an interesting compensation for the missing pawn - the white king is in the middle of the tactical skirmishes. }
16... Rbe8 17. Bxb6 Qb8
{ Black is down a pawn, but the white king is within shooting range. } 18. Nbc5
{ They say the best defense is a good offense. } 18... Bxc5 19. Bxc5
{ 19.Nxc5  This will transpose to the game.  19...Bc8!  20.Na4  Rf6!  21.Bc5  Bb7  This is exactly the same as in the game but with a different move order. }
19... Rf6 20. Nc3 Rfe6
{ White once again is at a crossroads, but even to the naked eye it should be obvious that Black holds the initiative. Note that White can't castle short due to the ...Nxg3 threat. }
21. Rc2
{ A multi-purpose move to defend the bishop on e2.   A@@EndBracket@@  21.Kd2  White could try to escape to the queenside.  21...Nf6!  Since the white king is heading the other way, the black knight on h5 has nothing to do, so it's assigned a new role.  22.Rf1  a5!?  Black does everything to make sure that the white king will never feel safe on the queenside.  23.b5  Qe5!  24.bxc6  Ba6  With incredible willpower, Black is crashing through and it could be difficult for White to stay in the game.  25.Na4  Almost the only move for White.  25...Qxe2+  26.Qxe2  Rxe2+  27.Kc3  Rc8!  It's equal!   B@@EndBracket@@  21.f4  White stops Black's ideas to sacrifice on g3 or push f4, but it also opens the long diagonal for the black bishop.  21...Nxb4!  22.O-O  Na2!  What a move to make! Black wants to win the light-squared bishop on e2.  23.Bxh5  Nxc1  24.Bxe8   24.Qxc1?  Qc7  24...Qxe8  25.Qxc1  Qc8!  Despite the fact that Black is down a full piece, it's White who needs to be careful here.  26.Be3  Qxc4  It's not clear how White should deal with Black's ...Qc6 threat.  27.Rd1   27.Kf2  Qc6  28.Ke2  Qc4+  29.Kf2  Qc6  This leads to a position repetition.  27...Qc6  28.Nd5  White closes the long diagonal, but this loses the extra piece.  28...Qxc1  29.Bxc1  Bxd5  30.Rxd5  Re1+  31.Kg2  Rxc1  32.Rxf5  With an equal endgame. }
21... a5
{ This appears to be a very crucial move in the upcoming tactical skirmishes. In some variations either the white bishop on c5 hangs or the b-pawn is weak. Just check out several continuations at White's disposal.   21...Nxg3?!  Being impatient is never good, although this sacrifice will always be in the air.  22.hxg3  Qxg3+  23.Bf2  Qxf3  24.Rg1  Black might run out of attacking pieces - if only ...Ne5-f3 was working here, but it's not. }
22. b5
{ A@@EndBracket@@  22.Kf1  The white king tries to escape to g2.  22...axb4  23.axb4  f4  24.g4  Nf6  25.Rg1  Ne5  Black's initiative is long-lasting.   B@@EndBracket@@  22.Kf2  An alternate plan - White will keep the king on f2.  22...axb4  23.axb4  f4  24.Rg1  d6!  25.Bd4  Qd8  Now White can never touch the g-pawn due to ...Qh4+.  26.Nd5  Nxd4  27.Qxd4  Re5  There's no doubt that Black has full compensation for the pawn.   C@@EndBracket@@  22.Nb5  22...Nxg3!  At some point this sacrifice can go through!  23.hxg3  Qxg3+  24.Bf2  Qxf3  25.Rg1?!  Qh3  26.Nc7?  Ne5  Black is crashing though. }
22... Ne5 23. O-O Rg6
{ The white king has run away but not for long. We will provide you the remaining moves with very limited annotations - enjoy the spectacle and hopefully pick up some unorthodox ideas! }
24. Rf2
{ A@@EndBracket@@  24.Bf2  f4  25.g4  Nf6  26.Bd4   26.Nd5  h5  26...h5  27.Bd3  Rg5  28.h4  Nxf3+  29.Rxf3  Rxg4+  30.Rg2  Qd6!  31.Bf2  Bxf3  32.Qxf3  Re3!  33.Bxe3  Qxd3  34.Rxg4  hxg4  35.Qxf4  Qxc3  36.b6  Qe1+  37.Kg2  Nh5!  38.Qf2   38.Qxg4  Qxe3  39.Qxh5  Qxb6  38...Qb1  39.c5  Qe4+  With perpetual check.   B@@EndBracket@@  24.f4  24...Qc7!  Remember 21...a5?  25.Bxh5  Qxc5+  26.Rcf2  Nxc4  27.Qxd7  Nd6  28.Bxg6  hxg6  29.Rd1  Qxc3  30.Qxd6  Re1+  31.Rxe1  Qxe1+  Again, it ends with a perpetual check. }
24... f4
{ 24...Nxg3!?  25.hxg3  Rxg3+  26.Kf1   26.Rg2??  Nxf3+  26...Rh3  27.Rg2  Nxf3  The game is an incredible mess. }
25. g4 Ng3 { There are more acrobatic tricks coming. } 26. Bd4
{ A@@EndBracket@@  26.Nd5?!  Nxe2+  27.Rcxe2  Rge6  28.Qb3!  Qc8  29.Bd4  Nxg4  30.Rxe6  dxe6  31.Rg2  h5   B@@EndBracket@@  26.hxg3  fxg3  27.Rf1   27.Rg2  Nxf3+  28.Bxf3  Bxf3  29.Rce2  Rge6  30.Qxd7  Bxe2  31.Rxe2  Rxe2  32.Nxe2  Rxe2  33.b6  Re1+  It's equal!  27...Qd8!  28.Kg2  Rh6  29.Rh1  Rxh1  30.Qxh1  Ng6  31.Kg1  Qc7  32.Ba7  Ba8  33.Bd4  Qf4  34.Ba7  Qc7  Engines treat this as equal - we won't argue.   34...Re6!? }
26... Rd6
{ A@@EndBracket@@  26...Nxe2+?  This tempting move is an odd way in which Black can lose the game.  27.Rcxe2  Bxf3  28.Bxe5  Rxg4+  29.Kf1!  Bxe2+  30.Rxe2  Rxe5  31.Rxe5!  Qxe5  32.Qd5+!  Qxd5  33.Nxd5   B@@EndBracket@@  26...h5!? }
27. hxg3
{ A@@EndBracket@@  27.c5  Nxe2+  28.Rcxe2  Nxf3+  29.Rxf3  Bxf3  30.cxd6  Bxe2  31.Qb3+  Kf8  32.Qc2  Qxd6  33.Nxe2  Rxe2  34.Bxg7+  Kxg7  35.Qxe2   B@@EndBracket@@  27.Nd5  Bxd5  28.Bc5  Nxe2+  29.Rcxe2  Nxf3+  30.Rxf3  Rxe2  31.Bxd6  Qxd6  32.Qxe2  Bxf3  33.Qxf3  Kf8  . }
27... fxg3 28. Rf1 g2 29. Rf2 Qd8 30. Rxg2 { 30.c5??  Qh4! } 30... Qh4 31. Rc1
Rxd4 32. Qxd4 Nxf3+ 33. Bxf3 Re1+
{ There's a perpetual check incoming. This game is of very high theoretical value and discovers a new type of position that can arise in the Sicilian Kan, should White set up the Maroczy Bind pawn structure. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Vahe Danielyan vs. Levan Pantsulaia, Tbilisi 2017"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Nc3 b5
{ If White develops the queenside knight to c3, one of Black's typical ideas is to challenge the e4-pawn early. }
6. g3 Bb7 7. Bg2 Nf6 8. a3 d6
{ Black stops the white pawn at e4, which is logical. This used to be quite popular in the past, however, the consequences can be severe - from now on Black can't afford to make a single inaccuracy.   8...Qc7!  This is much simpler - all the details are in Chapter 9.  9.Qe2  Nc6!  10.Nxc6  Qxc6  11.O-O  Be7  Once again we're witnessing that trading a pair of knights favors Black. The remaining pieces are very well positioned. }
9. O-O Nbd7
{ A@@EndBracket@@  9...Be7?  Either here or in similar positions, Black often blunders the following trick.  10.e5!  dxe5   10...Bxg2  This is not really better.  11.exf6  Bxf1  12.fxe7  Qxe7  13.Qxf1  White is technically winning.  11.Bxb7  Ra7  Black's last hope - two of White's minor pieces are hanging.  12.Bc6+  Kf8  13.Ndxb5  axb5  14.Bxb5  White has an extra pawn, two bishops, and the black king is weak.   B@@EndBracket@@  9...Qc7  This is more careful, but now Black will suffer due to the advanced b-pawn.  10.Re1  Be7  11.a4!  b4  12.Na2  White was better in Topalov, V. @@StartBracket@@2745@@EndBracket@@ - Short, N. @@StartBracket@@2660@@EndBracket@@ Dortmund SuperGM 25th 1997. }
10. Re1 Qc7
{ Once again, Black needs to be careful to dodge the e5-push - that's why the development of the dark-squared bishop is delayed. }
11. a4
{ Quite typical for the structure, before sacrificing the knight on d5, White might want to open the queenside first. }
11... b4
{ Black keeps the queenside closed, but now the b-pawn becomes a target.   11...bxa4?  This loses immediately.  12.Nd5!  exd5  13.exd5+  Ne5  14.c4!  White first protects the d5-pawn and only then is threatening to win back the sacrificed piece with f4.  14...Nfd7  15.f4  Be7  16.fxe5  dxe5  17.Nc6  Black is strategically lost. }
12. Na2 Nc5
{ A common theme in Sicilian - Black trades the b-pawn for the e-pawn. However, the black king is still in the center. }
13. Nxb4 Ncxe4 14. Bf4
{ Exactly this move puts Black into a very difficult position with various tactical motifs that are easy to miss. }
14... g6
{ Now Black is close to lost.   A@@EndBracket@@  14...e5  N  This brave move is the best reply but it will force Black to walk a tightrope to survive.  15.Rxe4!?  Nxe4  The only move.  16.Qe2  Now Black has to show some engine-like composure.  16...Nf6   16...f5  Black could give back one pawn to divert the white knight.  17.Nxf5  Nf6  18.Bf3!  18...Kf7  19.Bg5  e4!  Strictly the only move.  20.Bg2  d5  21.c3  White holds the initiative.   16...d5  Tempting but might not be the best.  17.Nxd5!  Bxd5  18.Bxe4  Rd8  19.Re1  White is attacking with big forces.  19...f6  The safe move.   19...Bxe4  Black is suffering also here.  20.Qxe4  Bd6  21.Bg5!  Rd7  22.Qa8+  Qb8  23.Qxa6  O-O  24.Nf5  White has two pawns for the exchange and is still pushing.  24...Qc7  25.Qe2  25...f6  26.Be3  Rb8  27.c3  Once those queenside pawns start to roll forwards, they might become unstoppable.  20.Qxa6  Once again, White has two pawns for the exchange, but the black king is still not safe.  20...Bxe4  21.Rxe4  Be7  22.Bxe5!  fxe5  23.Ne6  White is continuing the attack without a full rook.  23...Rd1+  24.Kg2  Qd6  The human choice.  25.Qc8+  Kf7  26.Qxh8  Qxe6  27.Qxh7  If Black manages to draw here, it will be quite an achievement.  17.Bxb7  Qxb7  18.Nbc6  Kd7!  Almost the only move!   18...Rc8?  This allows White to rip apart the center.  19.Bxe5  dxe5  20.Qxe5+  Kd7  21.Rd1  White still has enough pieces to deliver a checkmate.  21...Rxc6  22.Ne6+!  Bd6  23.Nc5+  Kc8  24.Qf5+  Kb8  25.Nxb7  Kxb7  26.Qf3  White is winning.   18...Be7?  Black can't run away from the attack.  19.Nxe7  Qxe7  20.Nf5  Qd7  A sad necessity, otherwise the sacrifice on e5 will end the game on the spot.  21.Nxg7+  Kf8  22.Bh6  Ng4  23.Qd2  Black's position is terrible.  19.Nxe5+  dxe5  20.Bxe5  White's attack continues. Mind you, this is just a taste of what White can prepare - voluntarily venturing in this line is not very practical for Black.   B@@EndBracket@@  14...Be7?!  15.f3  Nc5  16.Nf5!  This looks scary enough - Black can neither take the knight nor castle short. }
15. Qd3 Nc5 16. Qc3
{ A very unfortunate retreat - White lets slip all of his advantage.   16.Qc4!  White could have started a desicive attack with a more precise move.  16...Bxg2  17.Kxg2  Black simply doesn't have a satisfactory defense against White's multiple threats.  17...Nh5  The best attempt to trick White.   17...Bg7  18.Nbc6  Unfortunately, Black doesn't have the time to castle.  18...Rc8  19.b4  19...Nh5  20.bxc5  White is winning.  18.Nbc6  Nxf4+  19.gxf4  a5  20.c3!  White wants to play b4 and then sacrifice on e6.  20...Bg7  21.b4!  Bxd4   21...axb4  22.cxb4  Qb7!  23.Kg1  Qa6!  A very resourceful approach doesn't save Black.  24.b5  Qb7  25.a5  O-O  26.Ra2  White's passed pawns on the queenside seal the game in favor for White.  22.Nxd4  Na6  23.Qb5+  Kf8  24.Qg5!?   24.Nxe6+!?  24...Kg8  25.b5  Nc5  26.f5  White's monstrous attack continues. }
16... Bxg2 17. Kxg2 Bg7 { Suddenly, Black is doing just fine! } 18. Ndc6
{ They say mistakes come in pairs.   18.Rad1  This was a better continuation, threatening to sacrifice on d6 and on e6 later.  18...e5  19.Ndc6  O-O  20.Bxe5  20...Nxa4  After several stormy moves, the position calms down.  21.Qa3  dxe5  22.Qxa4  a5  23.Nd5  Nxd5  24.Rxd5  Rac8  25.Rc5  Rfe8  This should be equal, although White is still hoping for something due to the possibility of organizing an outside passed pawn on the queenside. }
18... Nh5 { One of the major reasons why the white queen on c3 is misplaced! }
19. Bxd6
{ 19.Be5  dxe5  20.Qxc5  a5  This also gives White no reason to cheer. } 19...
Bxc3
{ A strange mistake - Black must have wrongly evaluated the importance of the extra exchange.   19...Qxd6!  There was nothing wrong with accepting the free piece!  20.Qc4  a5  21.Rad1  Qc7  22.Qxc5  axb4  White's attack will evaporate, leaving Black with extra material. }
20. Bxc7 Bxe1 21. Rxe1 Nxa4
{ Despite the fact that Black is up an exchange for nothing, White dominates the dark squares and has more active pieces. So, it's Black who is trying to survive here. }
22. g4 Ng7 23. b3 Nc5 24. Be5 Rg8 25. Bd4 Nd7 26. Nd5 Kf8
{ Black is trying to hold on. } 27. Bb2 f6 28. Nc7
{ White miscalculates and everything starts to go wrong from here.   28.Ne3  While taking on f6 was also possible, the simple retreat would have secured White an advantage with no risk, while Black is left with a very difficult defense.  28...e5  29.Rd1  Nc5  30.Ba3  30...Nge6  31.g5!  White crashes through - Black simply does not have the time to rearrange his pieces.  31...Kg7  32.gxf6+  Kxf6  33.Rd6  Kg7  34.b4  Nf4+  35.Kf3  Nce6  36.Rd7+  Kf6  37.Ng4+  Kg5  38.Ngxe5  White has won a pawn and still holds the initiative. Black will have to work very hard to earn a draw. }
28... Rc8 29. Nxe6+ Kf7
{ Apparently White simply missed that Black is not obliged to take on e6. From here Black took over the game and never looked back. }
30. Ned4 Rge8 31. Ra1 Ra8 32. c4 Ne6 33. Nxe6 Rxe6 34. Rd1 Ke8
{ Now White is fighting for the draw. } 35. Nd4 Re4 36. f3 Re5 37. f4 Ra5 38.
Nc6 { A colossal waste of time - this must have been time trouble. } 38... Ra2
39. Rd2 a5 40. Nd4 a4 41. Re2+ Kf7 42. bxa4 R8xa4 43. Nb5 Rb4 44. Nd6+ Kg8
{ Black won the game but the chosen approach in the opening raises questions if this is the way you want to go. }
