[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Rustam Kasimdzhanov vs. Sergei Rublevsky, Moscow 2007"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ Sometimes rare lines emerge so that they can disappear forever. Let us show you one of them. }
2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Nc3 Qc7
{ This standard move was advocated some 150 years ago by Paulsen but with the current move order there's an issue. }
6. Bd3 Nf6 7. Qe2
{ Because of this move, we decided not to recommend @@StartFEN@@rnbqkbnr/1p1p1ppp/p3p3/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R b KQkq - 1 5@@EndFEN@@  5...Qc7  . }
7... Bd6
{ This idea is quite common in similar positions of Sicilian Kan and we spent a great deal of time to make it work in the course, but here, this move is a big mistake.   7...d6  8.f4  This variation is not very practical at any level. }
8. Ndb5
{ This shot effectively closes the variation. We find it strange that after this game there were many more of them and even some strong analytical players were unable to see the mating pattern that can be found in some very old books. }
8... axb5 9. Nxb5 Qa5+
{ Black doesn't have a choice - allowing White to take on d6 and push e5 next looks like a strategic disaster. }
10. Bd2 Bb4 { That's the trick - Black keeps his extra piece. For now... } 11.
Bxb4 Qxb4+ 12. c3
{ All of this is forced - now Black needs to guard the c7-square against the fork. }
12... Qc5 13. e5 Nd5
{ 13...Ng4  Black could try to trade back the knight for the e5-pawn but White doesn't have to accept it.  14.O-O !  Taking the knight is also fine.  14...h5  Black can't take on e5 with the knight, otherwise after White's b4 the black queen will be overloaded to defend the knight on e5 and the incoming fork on c7.  15.h3  Qxe5  16.hxg4  Qxe2  17.Bxe2  17...Ke7  18.gxh5  White has an extra pawn, plus solid lead in development. }
14. Nd6+ Kf8
{ 14...Ke7?  This leads to the end faster.  15.Qh5  15...g6   15...Nc6  16.Qxf7+  Kd8  17.Qxg7  Black lost the entire arsenal of the kingside in Sulskis, S. @@StartBracket@@2555@@EndBracket@@ - Kveinys, A. @@StartBracket@@2534@@EndBracket@@ Vilnius 2009.  16.Qh4+  Kf8  17.Bxg6!!  Perhaps this variation stayed during the era of weak chess engines as this move was missed.  17...fxg6  18.O-O-O  White is crashing through and the absence of two minor pieces is only temporary. }
15. Qh5 g6 16. Qh6+ { Rustam chooses the right way. } 16... Kg8
{ And so, the black king is in the mating net - we just need to find the right idea. We're going to use some old ideas from Accelerated Dragon - also there, sometimes the defending king is squeezing his own rook, which in turn takes away space from the king. They are just not good company. }
17. h4
{ Too weak, too slow.   17.O-O !  White's idea is to play b4 to divert the black queen and at the right moment play Ne8 and end the game.  17...Nc6   17...f5  Nice attempt to escape but the result doesn't change.  18.b4  Qc7  19.Bc4  White prepares the Ne8 threat and wants to open the position even more.  19...Qd8  20.Bxd5  exd5  21.b5  One can get the feeling that the game was played in 17th century. Black is simply paralyzed.  18.b4!  White continues with the plan.  18...Qxc3   18...Qb6??  19.Ne8  This is an immediate mate.   18...Ndxb4  Another attempt to survive.  19.cxb4  Qxe5  20.Ne8  White's idea is to push away the black queen from the long h8-a1 diagonal and checkmate on g7.  20...d5  21.Rae1  Qd4  22.Rd1  Bd7  23.Bb5  The black queen sooner or later will run out of squares.  23...Qc3  24.Rc1  Qd4  25.Rfd1  Qe5  26.Re1  Qd4  27.Rcd1  And that's it.  27...Bxe8   27...Qc3  This could have been a little more stubborn.  28.Re3  Qb2  29.Rb3  Qe5  30.f4  The black queen has run out of available squares.  28.Rxd4  Nxd4  29.Bxe8  Rxe8  30.Qd2  White has achieved a material advantage, so it's fine to retreat and organize a passed pawn on the queenside.  19.Ne8  Black doesn't stand a chance to escape from the squeeze. All that's left is to push away the black queen from the long diagonal.  19...Qxe5  20.Rae1  Qc3  21.Rc1  Qb2  22.Rc2  Qd4  23.Rc4  Qb2  24.Rb1  Eventually the black queen will run out of squares.  24...Qe5  25.Re4  Qc3  26.Rc1  Qb2  27.Rce1  After a series of moves the black queen occupies the worst possible square and White is threatening to close the diagonal with Re4-e5.  27...Nc7  The only move to continue the game.   27...Rxa2  Nice attempt but it's easily dealt with.  28.R4e2  Qc3  29.Re5  28.Nxc7  Rxa2  29.R4e2  White is not done yet - the attack continues.  29...Qc3  30.Rxa2!  Qxe1+  31.Bf1  Qe5  32.Ne8  The annoying knight is back! This is the kind of position which doesn't even require a forced continuation - Black is paralyzed.  32...f5  33.b5  Kf7  34.Re2  Qd4  35.Rd2  Qe5  36.Nd6+  It's time for Black to resign. }
17... Nc6 18. h5 Nxe5
{ Instead of a spectacular attack White now has to resign. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Sergey Karjakin vs. Ilia Smirin, St. Petersburg 2018"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ Once again, we're following a game of the ever-resourceful Ilia Smirin, one of the greatest experts of the Sicilian Kan. Instead of paying a lot of attention to the opening phase, we will focus on some interesting middlegame ideas. The topic of this game - why the h-pawn is dangerous for White. }
2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7 7. a3 b6 8. Be3 Bb7 9. f3
d6
{ The classical Hedgehog - you should remember the reasons why we're advising to avoid setting it up early. }
10. Rc1 Nbd7 11. Be2 Rc8 12. O-O Be7 13. b4 Qb8
{ This move is useful in many plans - by playing it early Black also underlines that he can also play without castling short! }
14. Qd2
{ This is a standard Hedgehog setup from White's part - let's pay attention to the critical moments.   14.Kh1  14...h5!?  The push of the h-pawn is one of the tricks of the Kan system but ideally we prefer to have the option to include ...Bd6 as well. Notice that Black pushes the h-pawn as soon as the white king is on the same diagonal as Black's light-squared bishop.  15.Na4  h4  16.Nb3  In this game, White was playing an ambitious young player who at the time, unfortunately, had a poor understanding of strategic prophylaxis. Now arises an equal position but it's easier to play with Black.  16...Bd8  17.c5  Too direct.  17...b5   17...h3!?  It was interesting to include this move first.  18.g4  dxc5  18.Nd4  If you say A, be ready to say B as well.  18...Ba8  White's position becomes quite shaky, so he has no choice but to enter even greater complications.   18...bxa4?  19.c6   18...Qa8!?  19.Bf4  h3!  20.g4  e5  White has three minor pieces under attack!  21.Nf5  Nxe4!  A nice counter-shot, which must have been missed from afar by White.  22.Nc3?  That's a mistake.   22.Be3!  This was the best that White could have done, but the entire line is far from obvious.  22...g6  23.Ng7+  Kf8  24.Ne6+  fxe6  25.fxe4+  Ke8  The white knight on a4 is still hanging.  26.Kg1!?  bxa4  27.Bc4  Be7  28.Bxe6  Rc6  Although White is attacking with great imagination, he doesn't have sufficient compensation for the missing piece.  22...Nxc3  The position simplifies pretty fast.  23.Nxd6+  Kf8  24.Rxc3  exf4  25.Nxc8  Qxc8  Black confidently converted his advantage into a win. Sevian, S. @@StartBracket@@2600@@EndBracket@@ - Smirin, I. @@StartBracket@@2687@@EndBracket@@ Washington op 5th 2016. }
14... Bd8
{ Not only is Black slowing down with castling short - perhaps there might be an option to push forward the kingside pawns and keep the king in the center. }
15. Kh1 { Standard prophylaxis. } 15... h5
{ But Black doesn't want to castle short! } 16. Nb3
{ A logical move - White prepares the c5-push and wants to create some real targets on the queenside.   A@@EndBracket@@  16.Nd1!?  Stockfish often likes to reroute the knight to f2, where it protects many critical squares on the kingside. There's a drawback - the white knight no longer participates in any breakthroughs.   B@@EndBracket@@  16.Bg1!  It will be difficult for a human being to follow the recommendation of chess engines.  16...h4  17.h3  Nh5  18.Bh2  White is sort of better, but he typically avoids weakening so many dark squares around the king. 'You must unlearn, what you have learned'.  18...Ng3+  19.Bxg3  hxg3  20.f4  Nf6  21.Qe3  O-O  The black king can't stay in the center forever.   21...b5?!  Unfortunately, here it's a little too creative but perhaps this idea can work for you under different circumstances.  22.cxb5  Rxc3  23.Rxc3  Nxe4  24.Rc6!  This precise move kills all the excitement.  24...Nf2+  25.Rxf2  gxf2  26.bxa6  White's passed pawns on the queenside are too dangerous.  26...Bxc6  27.Nxc6  Bb6  28.Qf3  Qc7  29.a4  White should win.  22.Bd3  Qa8  At some point, White will collect the g3-pawn, leaving Black with questionable compensation in view of the dark-squared bishop. }
16... h4 17. Rfd1 Bc7 18. Bf4 { Karjakin is making all the logical moves. }
18... Ne5 19. c5
{ White is not ready for the breakthrough but the will to punish Black for keeping the king in the center for so long is understandable.   19.Bxe5!  White had to close the center.  19...dxe5  20.c5  Now White is slightly better but still the position remains quite complex. Here's how the game could continue.  20...h3  21.g3  O-O  22.Bf1  Rfd8  23.Qe2  Rxd1  24.Qxd1  Bc6  As long as Black is looking for dynamic options, he should be fine.  25.Bxh3  bxc5  26.Nxc5  Bb6  27.Nxa6  Qa8  Black is temporarily down two pawns.  28.Bf1  Be3  29.Rc2  Bb7  30.Qd3  Bd4  31.Nc5  Bxc5  32.bxc5  Rxc5  There goes one pawn.  33.Ra2  Bc6  34.Kg2  Nd7  White still has the extra pawn but will constantly have to look over his shoulder and worry about the king's safety. }
19... dxc5 20. Bg5
{ 20.bxc5  Nxf3  White must have forgotten about this tactical shot. } 20... h3
21. g3 c4 22. Nd4 b5
{ Black is obviously winning, so the question is - how did he manage to lose such a position? Blitz... }
23. a4 bxa4
{ Not accurate.   23...Rd8  This was stronger and more logical.  24.axb5  Bb6  25.Be3  axb5  . }
24. Nxa4 Nxe4 { Adrenaline! } 25. fxe4 Bxe4+ 26. Kg1 Ba8 27. Nc5 Bb6 28. Qe3
Rxc5 29. bxc5 Bxc5
{ If Black manages to create the battery of the queen and the light-squared bishop, it will be curtains for White. }
30. Rb1 Qd6 31. Kf1 Qd5
{ In the time scramble and rush to create the desired battery, Black completely forgot about castling.   31...O-O !  32.Bf4  f6  The position is an incredible mess but Black at least is attacking.  33.Bxc4  Bd5  34.Be2  g5  35.Bxe5  fxe5+  36.Ke1  Bxd4  37.Qxg5+  White is happy to deliver a perpetual check. }
32. Rb8+ Kd7 33. Nf3 { And that's how an exciting game sometimes can end. }
33... Qxd1+ 34. Bxd1 Bxe3 35. Nxe5+ Kc7 36. Rxh8 { Black resigned. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Janos Percze vs. Ian Brooks, ICCF 2018"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5
{ To better understand the Sicilian Kan, it's also important to know other middlegame plans. As in previous model games, we will skip discussing the details of the opening. }
2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7 7. a3 b6 8. Be3 Bb7 9. f3
d6 10. Be2 Be7 11. O-O
{ This is not the most dangerous plan that White can employ, but for all the details you can check the course. This is the classical and most known plan for White. }
11... Nbd7 12. Qd2 Rc8 13. Rfd1 Qb8
{ Once again, Black postpones castling short. } 14. Rac1
{ In correspondence chess, there's no place for bluffing or weird ideas but there's one interesting plan that you should definitely know. }
14... O-O 15. Bf2 h6
{ Very interesting move - Black is thinking about ...g5 push to improve the control of the e5-square for the knight. At the same time, the plan of aggressively pushing forward the h-pawn remains. }
16. b4 Ba8 17. Bf1 Ne5 18. Qa2
{ With the white queen on a2 some tactical motifs of c5 and Nxe6 start to appear. }
18... Rfd8 19. Na4 Nfd7
{ This chosen setup is typical for the classical Hedgehog - one black knight is very active in the center while the other holds together the queenside. }
20. Bg3 { White might be threatening to push c5. } 20... Rc7
{ Quiet maneuvering moves, trying to provoke the opponent into something radical, is a common strategy in the Hedgehog. }
21. Kh1
{ A standard retreat of the white king to dodge any potential checks.   21.c5!?  This does not quite work but still - should never be missed.  21...b5  22.Nxe6!  fxe6  23.Qxe6+  Kh7  24.Qxe7  Nxc5!  Black has got enough counterplay.  25.Qh4  Nxa4  26.Rxc7  Qxc7  27.Bxe5  27...g5  28.Qf2  dxe5  Black is temporarily up a piece but White will get many pawns.  29.Rxd8  Qxd8  30.Qa7+  Kg6  31.Qxa6+  Kg7  White will get 3 pawns for the minor piece so normally the game should end with a draw. }
21... Bf6 22. Qd2 Rcc8
{ Now that the c5 threat no longer is there, the black rook goes back. } 23.
Qe1 g5
{ Black is fighting for the e5 and f4-square. Engines give White some advantage but without a clear plan. This usually means that any activity from White's part will lead to simplifications. }
24. Qd2 Kh7 25. Nb3 Be7 26. h3 Bc6 27. Nc3
{ White is thinking about pushing forward either the c-pawn or b-pawn. } 27...
Ba8 28. Na4 Bc6
{ Probably it's best to push away the knight from attacking the b-pawn or preparing the c5 push. }
29. Nc3 Ba8 30. Na4
{ Both players decided not to risk it. Black can't really charge forward and break through White's solid position without seriously risking losing the game. Smart players will try to provoke White into some committal choices that can be exploited later - think about cat and mouse. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Veselin Topalov vs. Rustam Kasimdzhanov, Tripoli 2004"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6
{ In this game we will witness how the Hedgehog was too tough a nut to crack for FIDE World Champion Veselin Topalov. }
3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. c4 Nf6 6. Nc3 Qc7 7. a3 b6 8. Be3 Bb7 9. f3 d6 10. Be2
Be7 11. O-O O-O { This time Black castles short quickly. } 12. Qd2 Nbd7 13.
Rac1 Rac8 14. Rfd1 Qb8
{ This maneuver you will already recognize - it's a standard maneuver for many plans. }
15. Bf1 Rfe8 16. Kh1 Bd8
{ Black's idea is to position the dark-squared bishop on c7 and push ... d5. That's why White plays Kh1 and is ready to position the dark-squared bishop on g1 to stop the idea. }
17. Bg1 h5 { A good moment to push forward the h-pawn. } 18. Qf2 Ne5 19. b3 Ng6
{ Black's setup is very interesting - the knights on the kingside prepare to push forward the h-pawn while the bishop on d8 protects the weakness on b6.   19...h4!?  This was an interesting alternative for Black to consider. The plan is simple - push the h-pawn as far as it goes and if necessary, sacrifice it.  20.h3  Nh5  21.Bh2  Nd7  Black is very tricky and prepares ...Ng3+.  22.Nc2  22...Ng3+  23.Bxg3  hxg3  24.Qxg3  Bc7  Black is ready to make a breakthrough with either ...d5 or ...b5, getting excellent control of the dark squares in return. }
20. b4
{ A standard idea to play Nb3 and Na4 next but specifically here it might be the start of all White's problems.   20.h3  Making more dark-squared weaknesses is a very committal choice.  20...Bc7  21.b4  h4  22.Bh2  Nh5  Black is back with the ideas to play ...Ng3+ and break the center with ...d5. }
20... h4
{ White is facing a huge dilemma - allow the black pawn to be pushed to h3 and expose the white king, or weaken the dark squares. Not a pleasant choice! }
21. Nb3 { Topalov decides to continue with the plan. } 21... h3 22. g3 Ne5
{ Black is taking over the game - for White, it might not be obvious where the mistake was made! }
23. Rd4 { White can't play  23.Na4  due to a cute knight sacrifice on e4. }
23... Nc6
{ 23...Qa8!  Black should have continued the fight.  24.Qe2  d5  The standard breakthrough in the center is comfortable.  25.exd5  exd5  26.c5  White should desperately try to keep the long diagonal closed.  26...bxc5  27.Nxc5  Ned7  28.Qd2  Nxc5  29.bxc5  Rxc5  30.Bxh3  Rc4  Black has a huge, perhaps already decisive positional advantage. White has way too many weaknesses to hold everything together. }
24. Rdd1 Ne5 25. Rd4 Nc6
{ Topalov was officially pardoned. Why did Black agree to a draw and allow his opponent to slip away when the long diagonal is catastrophically weak? Black had already done everything. }
*

